1. Z0 ({Welcome to this course based on the Colle System! It is a complete} 1. d4 {repertoire. We intend to play} Z0 2. Nf3 {and} Z0 3. e3 {next. If Black plays ...[d5] then the white setup is called the Colle, but in fact, you can play the moves 2. [Nf3] and 3. [e3] against all Black's major openings and it is surprisingly good. OK, the word surprisingly is perhaps wrong, because there can't be anything wrong with playing 1. [d4], 2. [Nf3] and 3. [e3] followed by developing the light-squared bishop and castling short. These are all sound and natural moves. I have made a repertoire for Black based on the Queen's Gambit Declined, so it is pretty nice to play the same thing but with an extra move. Actually, in some lines the extra move is almost decisive, in other lines it is just pleasant. Does this give White an advantage, you might ask? Well, objectively speaking the answer is no. But which mainline openings lead to a better game for White these days? None! In a practical game, the story is different. When I have played the Colle setup my opponents have clearly been somewhat surprised. They have quickly made a few natural moves, but then they have started spending a lot of time on the follow-up. This surprise value is worth a lot in modern-day chess, where everybody knows their main openings extremely well. If you already are a 1. [d4]-player, adding the Colle to your repertoire means that you can choose what to play against a particular opponent making you more unpredictable and making you the one that decides what should be played. If you are new to 1. [d4], but want to learn it, this course is optimal. The lines are pretty easy - at least the starting moves! - and based much more on understanding than memorizing a lot of sharp stuff. Furthermore, this is a complete repertoire after 1. [d4], so all moves are covered, and we don't play the Colle setup against it all! I try to keep the repertoire coherent and as simple as possible without compromising the chess because we want a nice battle with a playable position after the opening. The repertoire is really for everyone. I have found a lot of novelties and interesting ideas, that professional players can use to ask a lot of difficult questions to their opponents. Everybody else can do the same and as a nice benefit get a deep, positionally sound opening repertoire.}) *

