1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 {Also a very natural active development move. Black plays a London reversed!} 4. Bd3 {We challenge the strong black bishop. This is also known to be good in the traditional London!} ({White could also strike with} 4. c4 {but then you must be prepared to play one of the biggest Slav mainlines after} c6 {.}) 4... Bxd3 5. Qxd3 ({You could consider} 5. cxd3 $5 {to get a more original position. Objectively it is probably balanced, but White has nice control over the central squares.}) 5... Nbd7 6. O-O e6 {Played in nearly all games.} 7. Nbd2 c5 {An aggressive approach.} 8. e4 {Going for complications.} ({It is possible to start with the subtle} 8. Re1 $5 {Next, we will go [e3]-[e4]. Of course, Black has an extra option:} cxd4 9. exd4 {. This is the typical Carlsbad structure with reversed colours. The knight seems somewhat misplaced on [d7] - it would rather be on [c6], but the position is basically balanced.}) 8... dxe4 9. Nxe4 cxd4 10. Qxd4 {White has some initiative, yet Black is very solid.} Qc7 11. Nxf6+ Nxf6 12. Bf4 (12. Bf4 {Black is under pressure. With some precise moves, it may be possible to keep the balance, but it will be hard on the board. Taking the bait is risky as this sample line shows:} Qxc2 13. Be5 $1 Be7 14. Rac1 Qe2 {(14...Qe4? loses to 15.Bxf6 . )} 15. Qa4+ b5 16. Qd4 {, and White is threatening [Rfe1].}) *

