1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose as an alternative against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... Nc6 {This natural move is played a lot. The question is if White is threatening to take on [c5]? I think the answer is yes!} 5. dxc5 $1 {Here White can really use the extra move compared to a normal Semi-Slav.} a5 {A move well-known from the Slav. Black tries to prevent [b2]-[b4].} 6. Bb5 $1 {[%cal Gb5e8,Gb2b4] By pinning the knight we are ready to play [b2]-[b4] after all.} e6 7. b4 Bd7 8. Qb3 {Protecting the [b4]-pawn.} (8. Bxc6 {is also good.}) 8... Be7 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. O-O $16 {Black doesn't have anything for the pawn. We will strengthen our position on the queenside with [a2]-[a4] and [Ba3]. If Black sooner or later plays ...[e6]-[e5], then it makes sense to play [h2]-[h3] to protect the [g4]-square.} *

