1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose as an alternative against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... cxd4 {A popular exchange.} 5. exd4 {This position could come from a Caro-Kann. The way to approach it is that what we have on the board is the so-called Carlsbad structure from the Queen's Gambit with colours reversed. If you already - and why shouldn't you? - play the QGD with Black you will immediately realize that this is a very pleasant version of the line. There is no real pressure on White's position and the bishop will get to [f4] with easy play. That said, of course, the psychology is different whether you play White or Black. Here it is important to play the position, not the result! By that, I mean that usually when playing White, you are educated to search for an advantage in all lines. In this case, however, you should be happy that you have an easy game. Maybe Black can equalize theoretically, but from a practical point of view, we have nothing to complain about.} Nc6 {The most natural. Black could also start with [Bf5], it doesn't really matter that much. We need to check the move...} 6. Bf4 ({Following the strategy. Other good moves were:} 6. Bd3 {or even 6.Ne5!?}) 6... Bg4 ({The most natural and the most popular move. Black has many other options like} 6... Bf5 {, 6...g6 , 6...e6 , 6...Qb6 and 6...a6 . They are all covered in depth in the 1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 c5 chapter, where I give a full repertoire for White against the Caro-Kann via the moves 3.e3 Nc6 4.c3 cxd4 5.exd4 . Here we will just focus on the main move 6...Bg4 .}) 7. Qb3 $1 {Breaking the pin and threatening the [b7]-pawn. Black doesn't have time to take on [f3].} Na5 8. Qa4+ {A disturbing check.} Bd7 9. Qc2 {White is slightly better. Black didn't manage to get the light-squared bishop out on [g4] or [f5] and still needs to find a good setup.} e6 {Black finishes development in classical fashion with [Be7] and [O-O].} 10. Bd3 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8]} Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Nbd2 Rc8 13. Ne5 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6b4] Threatening [Nb4].} 14. Qd1 {White regroups the queen with good play. White will slowly but surely build up on the kingside, while it is hard for Black to come up with some real counterplay.} *

