1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... e6 {The safest move and also the most played. Black simply protects the [c5]-pawn.} 5. Bd3 {The natural move.} (5. Nbd2 {will probably transpose after} Nc6 {.}) (5. Be2 {contains a small finesse. In certain lines, the bishop won't be exposed} Nc6 6. O-O {(played several times by Keymer. The idea is still to meet)} Bd6 {with} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 Bd6 {, and now either} 9. Nbd2 {or 9.Bb2 , I prefer the bishop on the more active [d3]-square.}) 5... Nc6 {Black also plays the most natural.} 6. O-O ({I like to get the king to safety before we start real action. Possible is} 6. Nbd2 {intending to meet} Bd6 {with the immediate} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 {, but I prefer castling first.}) 6... Qc7 7. Nbd2 Be7 8. dxc5 {The thematic move.} (8. e4 {is probably too forcing, but 8.Qe2 like in the mainline is interesting 8...O-O 9.dxc5 Bxc5 10.e4 here, Black should know the move 10...h6 with a complex fight.}) 8... Bxc5 9. b4 ({Much more popular is} 9. e4 {. The idea is known from the Anti-Meran of course. However, I think this is a good time to push [b2]-[b4]!}) 9... Bd6 10. Bb2 O-O 11. b5 {Forcing play. You can also say strong play!} ({White can also play} 11. a3 {, intending [c3]-[c4].}) 11... Ne5 ({If} 11... Na5 {, then White can play} 12. c4 $1 {anyway, because after} dxc4 13. Rc1 {White regains the pawn with good play.}) 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. f4 $1 Bd6 ({Of course,} 13... Bxc3 $2 14. Rc1 {wins for White. The black bishop is lost.}) 14. c4 {[%cal Gb2g7,Gd3h7] White is having a nice positional initiative. The two bishops look scary.} *

