1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... e6 {The safest move and also the most played. Black simply protects the [c5]-pawn.} 5. Bd3 {The natural move.} (5. Nbd2 {will probably transpose after} Nc6 {.}) (5. Be2 {contains a small finesse. In certain lines, the bishop won't be exposed} Nc6 6. O-O {(played several times by Keymer. The idea is still to meet)} Bd6 {with} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 Bd6 {, and now either} 9. Nbd2 {or 9.Bb2 , I prefer the bishop on the more active [d3]-square.}) 5... Nc6 {Black also plays the most natural.} 6. O-O ({I like to get the king to safety before we start real action. Possible is} 6. Nbd2 {intending to meet} Bd6 {with the immediate} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 {, but I prefer castling first.}) 6... Bd6 {Now it will be a Meran with an extra tempo for White. Usually, the position comes from the Semi-Slav: 1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 e6 5.e3 Nbd7 6.Bd3 . Also the so-called Anti-Meran move 6.Qc2 is very popular, so let's check the equivalent move here as well.} 7. Nbd2 O-O {The obvious move. Delaying castling is possible, but risky.} ({The move} 7... Qc7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 {transposes to 6...Qc7 .}) 8. dxc5 {The standard move in the Meran. White can also keep the tension with the interesting 8. [Qe2].} (8. Qe2 {, intending [e3]-[e4]. After the flexible response} Qc7 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. e4 {which leads to a position I have already mentioned. Black has several decent moves, but the most precise is} h6 {with a very complicated game with chances for both sides.}) (8. dxc5 {Even against c4!? Bc2} e5 $1 {I couldn't find any real advantage for White.}) 8... Bxc5 9. b4 {White continues with the normal Semi-Slav play.} ({Both,} 9. e4 Qc7 {, and 9.Qe2 Qc7 have also been played a lot.}) 9... Bd6 {The Meran move.} 10. Bb2 {The natural follow-up to [dxc5] and [b2]-[b4], but as we have seen already the direct [b4]-[b5] is always worth a thought or two.} ({The position after} 10. b5 Na5 {(10...Ne5 11.Nxe5 Bxe5 12.Bb2 Qe7 is also ok for Black. )} 11. c4 dxc4 12. Nxc4 Nxc4 13. Bxc4 e5 {has been tested in some email games, but White could maybe try the new move} 14. h3 {N. If} e4 {, then} 15. Nd2 $1 {with an exciting position. The white bishop will be superb on [b2]. Still, the game seems balanced to me.}) {14...Qe7 15.Bb2 is maybe a tad better for White.} 10... e5 {Always an important candidate move.} 11. e4 {With a lot of tension in the centre. In general I think that these kind of positions are quite dangerous for Black, because White has some tricky piece play in many lines.} Bg4 {The typical active move.} (11... Be6 12. Re1 {Black can hardly keep the tension for much longer. If} dxe4 13. Nxe4 {, it transposes to 11...dxe4 .}) (11... d4 12. cxd4 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 exd4 14. e5 {White wins a piece.}) {Or 12...exd4 13.b5 .} 12. h3 {Not forced, by any means, but I like to flick it in.} Bh5 ({If Black takes on f3 we should be happy:} 12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 d4 14. a3 $1 {protecting [b4].} dxc3 15. Bxc3 Rc8 16. Rac1 {White is better with the bishops.}) 13. Re1 $1 {A very precise move.} ({Tempting is} 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Qc2 {Here Black has a powerful novelty. •} Bg6 $2 {This obvious move is the only move that has been played. In fact, it loses by force! ( • 14...Nf4! N This pawn sacrifice almost refutes the line. 15.Bxh7+ Kh8 16.Be4? (16.g3! saves the day according to the machine: 16...f5! 17.Bxf5 Rxf5! 18.Qxf5 Bg6! 19.Qg4 Bh5 20.Qf5 with a repetition. ) 16...Rc8!  Black threatens [Nxb4] and also [f7]-[f5] is on the agenda. )} 15. Bxg6 hxg6 16. Rfd1 {Black won't get out of the pressure on the d-file.} Qc7 17. Nc4 Nce7 18. Nxd6 Qxd6 19. c4 Nxb4 20. Qc3 Qc5 21. Nxe5 {, and White was completely winning in Koellner-Javakhishvili, blitz 2022. The German talent, Ruben Koellner, plays this Colle system a lot with good results.}) 13... Bc7 ({On} 13... Re8 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Qc2 {is good.}) 14. a3 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Ga3b4,Gc3c4] Protecting [b4] and intending [c3]-[c4].} ({On} 14. exd5 {Black has} Qxd5 {, that was the point of [Bc7].}) (14. b5 {is possible as usual, but the text move is simpler.}) 14... Re8 ({Simplifying with} 14... dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Qxd1 17. Raxd1 f6 {held for Black in some email games, but White looks better after:} 18. c4 {.}) 15. Rc1 {[%cal Gc3c4] White is ready to play [c3]-[c4] next with some advantage.} *

