the king to safety before we start real action. Possible is} 6. Nbd2 {intending to meet} Bd6 {with the immediate} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 {, but I prefer castling first.}) 6... Bd6 {Now it will be a Meran with an extra tempo for White. Usually, the position comes from the Semi-Slav: 1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 e6 5.e3 Nbd7 6.Bd3 . Also the so-called Anti-Meran move 6.Qc2 is very popular, so let's check the equivalent move here as well.} 7. Nbd2 O-O {The obvious move. Delaying castling is possible, but risky.} ({The move} 7... Qc7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 {transposes to 6...Qc7 .}) 8. dxc5 {The standard move in the Meran. White can also keep the tension with the interesting 8. [Qe2].} (8. Qe2 {, intending [e3]-[e4]. After the flexible response} Qc7 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. e4 {which leads to a position I have already mentioned. Black has several decent moves, but the most precise is} h6 {with a very complicated game with chances for both sides.}) (8. dxc5 {Even against c4!? Bc2} e5 $1 {I couldn't find any real advantage for White.}) 8... Bxc5 9. b4 {White continues with the normal Semi-Slav play.} ({Both,} 9. e4 Qc7 {, and 9.Qe2 Qc7 have also been played a lot.}) 9... Bd6 {The Meran move.} 10. Bb2 {The natural follow-up to [dxc5] and [b2]-[b4], but as we have seen already the direct [b4]-[b5] is always worth a thought or two.} ({The position after} 10. b5 Na5 {(10...Ne5 11.Nxe5 Bxe5 12.Bb2 Qe7 is also ok for Black. )} 11. c4 dxc4 12. Nxc4 Nxc4 13. Bxc4 e5 {has been tested in some email games, but White could maybe try the new move} 14. h3 {N. If} e4 {, then} 15. Nd2 $1 {with an exciting position. The white bishop will be superb on [b2]. Still, the game seems balanced to me.}) {14...Qe7 15.Bb2 is maybe a tad better for White.} 10... a6 {Preventing [b4]-[b5] for the time being.} 11. a3 {[%cal Gc3c4] Preparing [c3]-[c4].} ({The active} 11. a4 {can be met by} e5 {N} 12. e4 dxe4 {(12...Be6!?)} 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 h6 {, a good prophylactic move.} 15. b5 Na5 16. Bd5 Qe7 17. c4 Be6 {, and Black equalizes.}) 11... b5 {Black stops White's [c4]-plan, but the [b5]-pawn will be a target.} 12. a4 $1 {[%csl Gb5] Hitting [b5].} Rb8 (12... bxa4 13. Rxa4 {leaves Black with a very weak [a6]-pawn.}) 13. axb5 {Fixing the weakness on [b5].} ({White can also play without taking on b5 first:} 13. Qe2 $5 Qb6 14. e4 {with similar play as we will see in the mainline.}) 13... axb5 14. Qe2 {[%csl Gb5]} ({Hitting the target one more time and forcing the black queen to take up a defensive role. White could also change the pawn structure completely with} 14. Nd4 {, leading to some strategically complex middlegames. I will give Nd4 as an alternative.}) 14... Qb6 15. e4 $1 {[%cal Ge4e5] White starts playing in the centre while still putting pressure on [b5].} Nd7 {[%csl Ge5] This has been played in three email games. Black keeps control over the [e5]-square.} ({The line after} 15... Ng4 16. Rad1 Nge5 17. Bb1 {is similar to the mainline.}) 16. Rad1 {A new move, but a very natural one. White adds extra power to the pressure in the centre.} Nde5 {The most natural response. We are taught that we often take the wrong rook, but what about the knights? Maybe Black should prefer [Nce5].} 17. Bb1 {Securing the bishop.} ({After} 17. exd5 exd5 {Black is much better coordinated than after Nce5 . Still, you can play like this with White. Play might continue:} 18. h3 Re8 19. Nb3 Nxf3+ 20. Qxf3 Ne5 21. Qe2 Bd7 22. Bc1 {with a balanced position.}) 17... Qc7 {Strenghtening the control over [e5].} 18. Rfe1 Re8 19. h4 $5 {It is hard to improve the pieces so this modern AlphaZero way of playing comes in handy.} Bd7 20. h5 (20. h5 {White has the initiative and the somewhat easier position. It may not be a real advantage, but it is hard for Black to devise a plan. Simplifying makes sense:} Nxf3+ 21. Nxf3 Ne5 {still, White can keep the game going with} 22. g3 {or 22.h6 .}) *

