1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {This is by far the most played move and the significance even raises when you add 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 to the list, when it is also very common for Black to play [d5] in one of the following moves. Black focuses on sound development and intends to move the dark-squared bishop and castle.} 4. Bd3 {Other moves are possible, but this is what we do. The bishop is good here.} Bd6 {Imitating White. In general [d6] is a more active post for the bishop than [e7].} 5. Nbd2 Nbd7 6. O-O e5 {This is too hasty.} 7. e4 $1 {[%csl Ge8] A typical counterstrike in the centre. The black king would wish it was already on [g8].} O-O (7... exd4 $2 8. e5 $1 {wins a piece for White.}) 8. Re1 {Improving the position and keeping the tension at the same time.} dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Rxe4 $5 {This is pretty dangerous for Black.} exd4 11. Bg5 ({Taking the pawn back with} 11. Rxd4 {is also fine.}) 11... f6 {A forced weakness.} ({After,} 11... Nf6 12. Rh4 {, it is too dangerous for Black.}) 12. Bf4 Bxf4 13. Rxf4 {[%csl Gd4]} c5 14. Qe2 (14. Qe2 {Intending Re1. White has good compensation for the pawn. A sample line goes:} Re8 15. Re4 Rxe4 16. Qxe4 Nf8 17. Re1 {, the control over the open e-file gives White a great game.}) *

