1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {This is by far the most played move and the significance even raises when you add 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 to the list, when it is also very common for Black to play [d5] in one of the following moves. Black focuses on sound development and intends to move the dark-squared bishop and castle.} 4. Bd3 {Other moves are possible, but this is what we do. The bishop is good here.} Bd6 {Imitating White. In general [d6] is a more active post for the bishop than [e7].} 5. Nbd2 Nbd7 6. O-O O-O {Keeping the symmetry.} (6... c5 {can be met with either} 7. c3 {or 7.b3 , with a transposition to other lines.}) 7. e4 {Now, finally White breaks the symmetry.} dxe4 (7... e5 {transposes to 6...e5 7.e4 O-O .}) 8. Nxe4 Nxe4 9. Bxe4 {White has extra space and nice piece play in an open position.} h6 {This subtle move is probably Black's best chance to equalize. It covers the [g5]-square and removes any pressure against [h7].} 10. c4 {Using the majority on the queenside.} ({After} 10. c3 Nf6 11. Bc2 b6 {, followed by [Bb7] looks ok for Black.}) 10... Nf6 11. Qe2 $5 {Playing for initiative demands active pieces!} ({The move} 11. Bc2 {allows} c5 {or 11...b6 .}) 11... Nxe4 12. Qxe4 {Black got the bishop pair, we got good play!} c5 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Bf4 {[%cal Ga1d1] White is more active. Next comes [Rad1] with some initiative.} *

