1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {This is by far the most played move and the significance even raises when you add 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 to the list, when it is also very common for Black to play [d5] in one of the following moves. Black focuses on sound development and intends to move the dark-squared bishop and castle.} 4. Bd3 {Other moves are possible, but this is what we do. The bishop is good here.} Be7 {Black plays a solid developing move in the spirit of the Queen's Gambit Declined.} 5. O-O ({White could also start with} 5. Nbd2 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Nbd2 ({The flexible} 6. b3 b6 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 {is very symmetrical, but, of course, it is possible to play like that.}) 6... Nbd7 {A flexible move, waiting to see which setup White goes for.} 7. Qe2 {[%cal Ge3e4] Preparing [e3]-[e4]. White has many other good options; basically, it is often just a matter of taste. • In general in this repertoire, I have tried to get the central break [e3]-[e4] in to open the position and get active piece play.} ({• You could also play more quietly with} 7. b3 {. • Another option is to go for the original Zukertort plan with} Ne5 {, followed by 8. [f4].}) 7... c5 8. c3 b6 {The most precise.} (8... Qc7 9. e4 dxe4 10. Nxe4 {or 8...c4 9.Bc2 b5 10.e4 gives White more chances to come out of the opening with a real edge.}) 9. e4 dxe4 10. Nxe4 Bb7 {A critical position. Black has managed to get both [Bb7] and [c7]-[c5] in. In many of the previous lines, Black only managed one of them! So is everything then fine for Black? Yeah, the position is probably balanced, but White can ask the usual questions.} 11. Rd1 Nxe4 {Simplifying is also ok.} 12. Bxe4 Bxe4 13. Qxe4 Nf6 14. Qe2 Qc7 {Basically Black has equalized. However I would like to play the position after:} 15. dxc5 Bxc5 16. Be3 {[%csl Ga2,Ga7,Gb2,Gb6,Gc3] The pawn majority on the queenside gives some chances, especially in endings.} *

