1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3 c5 {[%cal Gg7a1] Using the power of the strong King's Indian bishop on [g7] to put pressure on the white centre.} 7. Bb2 cxd4 {The critical continuation.} (7... Nc6 8. c4 {(8.d5 also looks strong. )} cxd4 9. Nxd4 {transposes to the mainline.}) (7... Nbd7 8. c4 {( also here 8.d5 looks good, but let's keep it simple. )} b6 {can transpose to 7...b6 .}) 8. Nxd4 $1 {[%csl Gb2]} ({An important move. White shouldn't block the bishop on b2. After} 8. exd4 d5 {the position is fine for Black, [Bb2] is passive, just shooting into its own d-pawn while [Bg7] is much more active.}) 8... d5 {Losing a tempo, but trying to fight for the [c4]-square. This might be Black's best chance to equalize.} 9. c4 {We need this break.} ({It is possible to start with} 9. Nd2 {but it gives Black time to strike back in the centre.} Re8 {( Not 9...e5 10.N4f3 and Black is forced to play 10...e4 when 11.Nd4 is nice for White. )} 10. c4 e5 11. N4f3 Nc6 {Black protects [e5].} 12. cxd5 Nxd5 13. Ne4 Bf5 {this has been tested. After} 14. Nc5 b6 15. Bb5 $1 Nde7 $1 16. Na6 Qxd1 17. Rfxd1 Red8 {Black defended in Hamitevici-Kulaots, Norway 2023.}) 9... dxc4 {The best.} ({The move} 9... e5 {is premature. After} 10. Nf3 e4 11. Nd4 {White has a nice edge.}) 10. Bxc4 {Black should find a good way to develop the queenside. There are two decent tries.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Intending [b7]-[b5] and [Bb7].} 11. Be2 {[%cal Ge2f3,Gf3a8] A clever move. White will be the first to take the long diagonal with [Bf3].} b5 12. a4 (12. a4 {Hitting b5. White is slightly better.} b4 {( Or 12...bxa4 13.Rxa4 and [a6] is weak. )} 13. Nd2 Bb7 14. Bf3 {, preparing to exchange the bishops. Later there is a nice square on [c4] for a knight.}) *

