1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3 Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5]} ({This is similar to} 6... Nbd7 {in that Black wants to play ...[e7]-[e5]. And again we can't prevent it, but we still get a fine position.}) 7. Bb2 e5 8. dxe5 Ng4 ({After} 8... Nd7 {the position should come to the same.}) 9. c4 Ngxe5 {If we compare this position to the one after 6...Nbd7 it seems that Black is more active here with the knight on [c6] and an open diagonal for [Bc8]. That might be true, but White is still better!} 10. Nc3 $1 {The most precise.} ({In this version} 10. Nxe5 dxe5 $1 11. Nc3 {might still give White a slight pull, though Black has} Qxd1 12. Raxd1 f5 {.}) (10. Nc3 {Playing with the knight, Nxe5 , transposes to the Nbd7-line.}) 10... Re8 {Also very natural.} 11. Qd2 Bg4 {Black develops the bishop. Nxf3+ is similar to 10...Nxf3+} 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. f3 {It was also possible to take on [g4], but this is clearly stronger.} Be6 14. e4 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4] White creates the Maroczy-structure with pawns on [c4] and [e4]. The extra space gives White a plesant middlegame.} *

