1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3 e5 {Probably Black can get away with this without any preperation.} 7. dxe5 dxe5 {The pawn can't be taken because of problems on the long diagonal. The open d-file means that the queens most likely will come off.} 8. Ba3 {[%cal Ga3f8] Gaining a tempo by attacking the black rook.} Re8 9. Qxd8 ({White could start with the tricky} 9. Nc3 {hoping for} e4 10. Qxd8 Rxd8 11. Rad1 $1) 9... Rxd8 10. Nc3 {White has the initiative.} Nc6 ({Black is not ready for} 10... e4 {because of} 11. Rad1 $1 {The rook leaves the [a1]-[h8] diagonal with tempo and after} Re8 {comes} 12. Ng5 {The e-pawn is weak. Actually, White threatens to take it at once!}) 11. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] Intending to cripple Black's structure.} Bf5 {Active defending.} ({The move,} 11... Bd7 12. Rad1 {is uncomfortable for Black.}) 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Bb2 ({White could also try} 13. Be7 {, the idea is to take on [f6] and play [e3]-[e4]. Then it is knights vs. bishops. The position is closed and Black's structure is bad, so an interesting option.}) 13... Bxc2 {Grabbing the pawn is tempting. But here it is also bad!} ({Black's best is probably} 13... Re8 {to protect the e-pawn. White can meet it with} 14. Rfe1 {when} Bxc2 15. Rac1 Bd3 16. Na4 {keeps some advantage.}) 14. Nxe5 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Ga1c1] White is better. [Rac1] is coming and [c6] is also hanging.} *

