1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 ({Black can play} 3... c5 {in every move, and here it sends us to the Benoni 2...c5 chapter.}) 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O c5 {A natural move. This is a Reti with colours reversed. Since we have no intention of entering the regular Benoni territory we don't play [d4]-[d5]. Fortunately there is another direct route to take.} 6. dxc5 {A standard reaction, also in the English/Reti.} Na6 {Black wants to take on [c5] with the knight and tries to lure us to take on [a6].} 7. c4 ({We go for some fluid positional play. Actually, it is also fine to take on a6:} 7. Bxa6 bxa6 8. b3 {the bishop will be good on [b2]} Qc7 {(8...Ne4 9.Nd4)} 9. Bb2 Bb7 {(9...Qxc5?! 10.Ba3)} 10. Nbd2 Qxc5 11. c4 d6 12. Qe2 {(1–0 Markowski,T 2548-Nguyen,P 2422 POL-chT Ekstraliga Warsaw 2020 4.5 with a complex strategic game ahead. The position is balanced. In general. I am not too keen to give my bishop with [Bxa6] in such positions. Also here, we see that Black's [Bb7] is really strong. But we have the best pawn structure, so clearly there is also potential in White's position.)}) 7... Nxc5 8. b4 $1 {White fights for the initiative. The black knight must go to [e4], but which knight?} Nce4 ({Black shouldn't play} 8... Ne6 9. Bb2 { the knight is clumsy on [e6].}) 9. Bb2 b6 ({Including} 9... a5 10. a3 {doesn't help Black.}) 10. Nbd2 Nxd2 ({Black could also play} 10... Bb7 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 {White keeps a small positional edge after} 12. Nd4 {the extra space matters.}) 11. Qxd2 Bb7 12. Rfd1 Rc8 13. Rac1 {[%cal Gf3d4] Next White can play [Nd4] with some advantage due to the extra space.} *

