1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 ({Black can play} 3... c5 {in every move, and here it sends us to the Benoni 2...c5 chapter.}) 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O c5 {A natural move. This is a Reti with colours reversed. Since we have no intention of entering the regular Benoni territory we don't play [d4]-[d5]. Fortunately there is another direct route to take.} 6. dxc5 {A standard reaction, also in the English/Reti.} Qa5 {Black should forcus on winning the pawn back.} 7. c4 ({This has a very specific idea. Also fine is the well-known} 7. a3 Qxc5 8. b4 Qc7 9. Bb2 {which we will see more of in the 2...[c5] chapter.}) 7... Qxc5 8. Nc3 d6 9. e4 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4] This was the idea. White gets a good Maroczy with pawns on [c4] and [e4] that secures extra space and makes it hard for Black to get active play.} Bg4 ({The quieter} 9... Nc6 10. Be3 Qa5 11. h3 { leads to a very pleasant position for White, where the Maroczy pawns on [c4] and [e4] prevent any active counterplay.}) 10. Be3 Qa5 {Probably the best square for the queen. Retreating down the c-file is more passive.} ({After} 10... Qc8 11. Rc1 $1 {Black can't take the c-pawn anyway.} Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Qxc4 $2 13. e5 $1 {and White wins material.}) 11. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Intending [b2]-[b4] to push the annoying black queen back.} ({White could also go for} 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 {we have the bishops, and the plan with [a2]-[a3] and [b2]-[b4] can follow.}) 11... Nc6 ({Black has tried} 11... Rc8 12. b4 Qd8 {but after the simple} 13. Qb3 {White is much better due to the extra space.}) 12. b4 Qd8 {This is almost universally played.} 13. Qb3 {So far White has played [Rc1].} Nd7 14. Rad1 $16 (14. Rad1 {The rook is much better here than on c1. White is clearly better because of the extra space. Next, we can get the bishop pair with h3 or just improve the position with Rfe1. If Black tries to force some exchanges then the pressure on the d-file might be felt:} Nce5 15. Nxe5 Bxe2 16. Nxe2 Nxe5 17. c5 $1 {and Black will end up with a very weak pawn on [d6].}) *

