1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 {The correct move-order.} g6 {The Leningrad set-up.} 4. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] Threatening h4-h5. If White had played 3.Nf3 then the queen's route to [h5] would have been blocked and this wouldn't have been possible..} Bg7 5. h5 $1 Nxh5 6. Rxh5 $1 {You could play this exchange sacrifice in your sleep!} gxh5 7. Qxh5+ Kf8 8. Qxf5+ {Picking up a pawn with check.} Kg8 9. Nc3 {[%csl Gh8][%cal Ge1c1] White has a pawn for the exchange. The plan is to castle long and just get the rest of the pieces into play. Meanwhile, it is hard for Black to get any play and the rook on [h8] is especially hard to activate.} e6 10. Qh5 d6 (10... d5 {weakens the dark squares. White just continues with [Nf3] and [O-O-O].}) 11. Nf3 Bd7 12. O-O-O (12. O-O-O {I can't see Black getting out of this grip. I would go as far as to say that White is strategically winning already! A sample line goes:} Qe7 13. Bc4 Na6 14. Rh1 Rf8 15. a3 {don't hurry. The advantage stays. A plan for White is suddenly to play [Bd3] and start to look at the [h7]-pawn. The important thing is to keep control and don't allow any liberating moves from Black.}) *

