1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 ({Please notice the move order. I recommend starting with the more flexible} 3. e3 {. If Black plays ...[e7]-[e6] it doesn't matter, but it is an important detail against ...[g7]-[g6], which we have just seen.}) 3... e6 4. Nf3 b6 {The bishop will be great at [b7].} 5. Be2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. c4 ({We ignore Black's Nh5 threat. Otherwise, it is possible to play} 7. h3 {but I prefer not to lose any time.}) 7... Ne4 $5 {Black can play this immediately. Then it was good that we didn't waste any time on [h2]-[h3].} 8. Nfd2 $1 {The black knight should be exchanged or chases away.} O-O 9. Nxe4 Bxe4 10. Nc3 {Gaining a tempo.} Bb7 11. Bf3 {A simple plan: White just exchanges the strong black bishop.} Bxf3 12. Qxf3 (12. Qxf3 {White is much better. The rook is hanging, so Black should probably play:} Na6 {then we can start to build up on the queenside with} 13. a3 {. Later we will play [b2]-[b4] and [Rac1]. It also makes sense to flick in the move [h2]-[h3] to secure the bishop on the kingside just in case.}) *

