1. d4 d5 {[%cal Bg1f3]} 2. Nf3 ({This is a key move in my repertoire. We avoid the heavily analyzed positions after the critical move} 2. c4 {and instead strive for simple development and good control. After 2.c4 we have the starting position of the Queen's Gambit. It is important to realize that despite the tremendous success of the Netflix series we are not forced to enter it! Of course, White is doing fine, but you have to know a lot of theory and still, you can't be sure to get anything out of the opening. Black's most popular answers are: • Queen's Gambit Declined: 2...e6}) (2. Nf3 {• The Slav:} c6) (2. Nf3 {• Queen's Gambit Accepted: dxc4 And now it is just starting... Play can go in all sorts of directions. I have worked on these lines more or less my whole chess career being a 1. [d4] player myself, but also from the black side - I even made a Chessable course with a complete Black repertoire based on the QGD! And I can honestly tell you that I haven't found anything substantial for White. If you want to learn a ton of theory you are welcome to investigate it on your own, but maybe you feel just like me: sometimes I just want to play a game of chess without endless preparation. This is basically what this course is all about.}) 2... Nf6 {[%cal Be2e3]} (2... Nf6 {The most logical and the best response. Black occasionally tries other moves. They can be found in the chapter with 'minor lines' and different move-order issues. For now, we just look at the main move Nf6 . Because then what? It is still possible to play: •} 3. c4 {and enter the giant fields of the Queen's Gambit. But we want to stay outside the fence! • There is the trendy London Bf4 . It definitely is a decent option... • ...just like 3.c4 - but the London has been in the spotlight for years already, so my guess is that most black players have faced it numerous times already and have at least one good set-up prepared. I have played the London several times myself with excellent results, so I am not going to say anything bad about this opening! • In this course, I have opted for the little move 3.e3 .}) 3. e3 {[%cal Bd2d4,Be2e3,Bg1f3]} ({The ancient Colle system. It looks rather passive and is easy to underestimate. However, it is a very sound and flexible set-up with some deep positional ideas. I think a good way to look at it is this: You play a nice Queen's Gambit Declined in the forehand with an extra tempo. By the way, did I mention that I have made a course for Black on that exact opening? If you have that course you will love this one. White will bring out the light-squared bishop and castle in most lines and then react to whatever Black is doing. Chess understanding is far more important than memorizing a lot of lines, yet there are quite a lot of subtleties that ask questions here and there, so Black's life is not as easy as it might look. And the big advantage: you will get a game, where both players will have to think for themselves and play their own moves - or rather Black will be forced to work everything out, you can just follow my suggestions! If Black plays well then objectively speaking they are fine, but even the most simple positions seem to be more equal for White than for Black! The move} 3. e3 {is non-threatening, to say the least, so Black has almost a free choice. Popular moves are} e6 {, 3...c5 or 3...c6 . It is also possible to develop the light-squared bishop to [f5] or [g4]. And Black could consider 3...g6 as well. Let's go through all the possibilities one by one. Then, in the end, I am pretty sure that you will agree with me that the Colle is a very interesting opening! First, though, I would like to present some instructive Model Games to give you a good feel for what we are aiming for.}) *

