1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 {This game was played, when I researched the Colle for this course.} e6 4. Bd3 Bd6 5. Nbd2 {White is ready to push [e3]-[e4].} c5 {Active and good.} ({If} 5... Nbd7 6. e4 {White gets there first.}) 6. dxc5 $5 ({I wanted to see what happens when White takes here. I had already played a game with the Semi-Slav setup} 6. c3 {, now it was time for something different.}) 6... Bxc5 7. O-O ({White could also start with} 7. a3 {.}) 7... Nc6 8. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc1b2] Intending [b2]-[b4] and [Bb2] with good play.} ({Here} 8. c3 {would be a reversed Meran.}) 8... a5 9. b3 {I want the bishop on [b2]!} (9. c4 {was a good alternative.}) 9... O-O ({Better was the active} 9... e5 10. e4 Bg4 {. The position is quite tricky with all the tension in the centre, but Black is doing ok.}) 10. Bb2 {[%csl Ge5] Controlling [e5], which inspires my opponent to a false plan.} Nd7 $6 {Hard to explain, but I quickly found out, when I started to surprise my opponents with the Colle, that already after a few pretty normal moves they didn't know exactly how to proceed. This makes the opening a great practical weapon.} ({Normal was} 10... Qe7 11. c4 {and White is slightly better.}) 11. c4 {The knight is peculiar on [d7].} f5 $6 {A big weakening.} (11... dxc4 12. Nxc4 {was also very unpleasant for Black.}) 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Qc2 $1 {[%csl Gf5] Hitting the f-pawn and forcing Black to another serious weakening of the kingside.} g6 {[%cal Gb2h8]} 14. Rac1 Be7 15. Bb5 {Brings more confusion into Black's camp.} Ndb8 ({Or} 15... Na7 16. Be2 Nc6 17. Rfd1 {. White got the bishop from [d3] to [e2] for free, which means that it is much easier to attack the isolated [d5]-pawn. next up is [Nb1]-[c3].}) 16. Rfd1 Qb6 17. Be2 {White has a very harmonious position, but just look at Black!} Na6 $6 {This allows a nice finish, but there was nothing good for Black anyway.} 18. Nc4 $1 {Highlighting the consequences of the moves [f7]-[f5] and [g7]-[g6].} Qc5 ({Not} 18... dxc4 19. Bxc4+ Rf7 20. Qc3 {, threatening mate.}) 19. Rxd5 $1 {A nice rook sacrifice.} Qxd5 20. Nb6 {White wins material back, but the main idea is to give a check on the light squares and make a decisive battery with [Qc3].} Qd8 ({If} 20... Qf7 {I had planned} 21. Nxc8 $5 {(21.Nxa8 also wins. )} Raxc8 22. Bc4 {winning the queen.}) 21. Bc4+ {[%cal Gc4g8,Gb2h8]} Rf7 22. Qc3 $1 {Threatening mate. Black is forced to give up a lot of material.} Bf6 ({After} 22... Nd4 {White wins easily with} 23. Qxd4 Qxd4 24. exd4 {.}) 23. Qxf6 Qxf6 24. Bxf6 {White theatens [Ng5], so Black doesn't have time to move the rook from [a8].} Kf8 25. Bxf7 Kxf7 26. Be5 $1 {There is no [Rb8].} 1-0

