1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 {Popular among the many Slav players out there.} 4. Bd3 Bg4 5. Nbd2 Nbd7 {[%cal Ge7e5] A very ambitious move-order. Black hopes to use the pin on the [f3]-knight to get the break [e7]-[e5] in.} 6. h3 Bh5 7. O-O e5 8. e4 $1 {This counterstrike is strong, but also almost forced. Black was threatening to win a piece with [e5]-[e4], and if White took on [e5] with [dxe5] then after [Nxe5] Black of course would have had easy play.} dxe4 ({I have faced the more critical} 8... exd4 {see more in the theory section.}) 9. Nxe4 Be7 ({Also} 9... Nxe4 10. Bxe4 Nf6 11. Bg5 {is good for White.}) 10. Ng3 $1 {[%cal Gg3h5]} Bxf3 11. Qxf3 O-O ({Or} 11... exd4 12. Nf5 {.}) 12. Nf5 $1 {[%csl Gf5] The best square for a knight according to Kasparov! This game highlights why.} exd4 13. Bh6 $1 {Already decisive. Black is forced to give an exchange.} g6 ({Not} 13... gxh6 14. Qg3+ {.}) 14. Nxe7+ Qxe7 15. Rae1 Qd6 16. Bxf8 Nxf8 17. Bc4 {White keeps the intiative.} Kg7 18. Re2 {Planning to double rooks and penetrate on [e7].} Rd8 19. Rfe1 ({Better was} 19. a4 $1 {to keep the bishop on the strong square [c4]. Then White would be winning.}) 19... b5 20. Bd3 (20. Bb3 c5 {is not clear at all.}) 20... Ne6 21. b3 a6 22. h4 h5 23. g3 Nd5 24. Rxe6 $5 {It was a rapid game, so attacking is a good choice.} fxe6 25. Qe4 {[%csl Gg6]} Ne7 26. Qxe6 Qxe6 27. Rxe6 (27. Rxe6 {White won on time. Black can keep fighting with} Kf7 {.}) 1-0

