1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 c6 4. Bd3 Bg4 5. Nbd2 e6 {This is the usual solid structure in these Colle-Slav lines.} 6. O-O Nbd7 7. b3 Bd6 8. Bb2 {White develops.} Qc7 {[%csl Gh2] Hitting [h2]. But also controlling the [e5]-square. Black could also just have castled.} 9. h3 Bh5 10. c4 Bg6 {A typical move. Black wants to exchange our strong bishop.} 11. Qc2 O-O 12. Bxg6 hxg6 13. e4 {This thematic break changes the structure. The resulting type of middlegame appears again and again in my Colle repertoire - That is why I show this game. It is not spectacular or anything, but a nice positional display by a very strong grandmaster.} dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 {White is slightly better because of the extra space. Black has a sound and solid position, so a pretty normal situation after the opening.} Nf6 16. Qh4 ({I would probably have preferred} 16. Qe2 {, but the queen looks more threatening on [h4].}) 16... Qe7 ({Better was} 16... Rfe8 17. Rfe1 Qa5 {when Black's queen can go to [h5].}) 17. Rfe1 Ba3 {Black simplifies.} 18. Bxa3 Qxa3 19. Re2 c5 {Also thematic.} 20. dxc5 Qxc5 {This is the structure I was talking about. White has a 3v2 majority on the queenside, which means that it is potentially possible to create a passed pawn there. This is especially important in an ending, but it certainly gives White something to play for. It is often harder for Black to use their 4v3 advantage on the kingside.} 21. Rd1 {The open d-file is important.} Rfd8 22. Red2 {White gets there first.} Qe7 {This is too passive.} (22... Rxd2 23. Rxd2 e5 {would have given some counterchances.}) 23. Qf4 Rxd2 24. Qxd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2d8] White controls the only open file.} Rc8 25. Ne5 Qc7 26. Qd4 b6 27. b4 {[%csl Gc5] A nice move that prevents [Qc5]. Within a few moves White has seized a strong position that dominates Black and prevents all counterplay.} Qb7 28. a3 Qa6 29. Rd3 Qa4 30. g4 {The right plan, but White is a little impatient and actually allows Black to come into the game again. It was a rapid game, which explains the inaccuracy.} ({Keeping control is important. White should have played the extremely strong} 30. b5 $1 {and only then have started to advance on the kingside.}) 30... g5 $2 ({Black had to try} 30... b5 $1 31. c5 Nd5 {and it is not so clear anymore.}) 31. Qe3 Qc2 {Setting up a little tactics. White decides to fall for it...} 32. Qxg5 Qxf2+ 33. Kxf2 Ne4+ 34. Ke3 Nxg5 35. h4 {... Because the ending is easily winning for White!} f6 ({Or} 35... Nh7 36. Rd6 Nf6 37. Kd4 {and White can follow up with [g4]-[g5] and [Rd7].}) 36. hxg5 fxe5 37. Rc3 Kf7 38. Ke4 Kg6 39. Kxe5 Kxg5 40. c5 ({Perhaps more precise was} 40. Kxe6 Kxg4 41. c5 {and the c-pawn decides.}) 40... bxc5 41. bxc5 Rc6 42. Rc4 {But this is good enough. Black is running out of moves.} Kh4 43. Kf4 g5+ 44. Ke5 a5 45. Kf6 a4 46. Ke7 Rxc5 47. Rxc5 Kxg4 48. Kxe6 Kf4 49. Rc4+ Kf3 50. Rxa4 g4 51. Rxg4 1-0

