1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {The main move.} 4. Nbd2 ({White has many moves. I suggest} 4. Bd3 {, but soon it will transpose to the game. There is also the interesting Zukertort system with 4.b3 , which is completely different. I give that as a good alternative.}) 4... c5 ({Active and fine. Black could also just develop with} 4... Be7 {and [O-O], but White will play} 5. Bd3 {with the somewhat more pleasant position.}) 5. c3 {White plays a Semi-Slav structure with an extra move.} Nbd7 ({A flexible set-up. The main move is} 5... Nc6 {.}) 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 $1 {[%cal Ge3e4] White wants to push [e3]-[e4] with some initiative.} Qc7 9. e4 cxd4 {Giving White an isolated pawn.} 10. cxd4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Rxe4 $1 {This was the point of 8.Re1. The rook can go to [h4] next and participate in the coming attack.} Nf6 13. Rh4 {[%csl Gh7]} (13. Rh4 {h7 is soft. If Black plays} h6 {we just take it with the bishop.}) 13... g6 14. Bh6 {With tempo.} Re8 15. Rc1 {With tempo.} Qa5 16. Bd2 $1 {A strong move that forces the black queen to a worse square.} Qd5 (16... Qd8 {invites the pin} 17. Bg5 {. Then} Be7 18. Ne5 {is also terrible for Black.}) 17. Bg5 {Attacking the knight. It is a crucial defender. In the game Black tries to run away with the knight, but it will soon be missed on the kingside.} Nd7 (17... Be7 18. Ne5 {was also impossible to defend. For instance} Bd7 19. Bc4 Qd6 20. Qf3 Kg7 21. Rf4 {and White wins.}) 18. a3 ({Also good was} 18. Qd2 {.}) 18... f6 {This weakens the king's position, but there was no good move for Black.} 19. Bd2 Nb6 {Here White finds a nice combination that quickly decides the game.} 20. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Gh7]} fxg5 21. Rxh7 $1 {The spectacular point.} Re7 (21... Kxh7 22. Qh5+ Kg7 23. Qxg6+ Kf8 24. Bxg5 {and White wins.}) 22. Rh6 $1 {[%csl Gg6] g6 is another problem now that the [h7]-pawn is gone.} Bd7 (22... Rg7 23. Bxg6 {doesn't help much. The white queen is ready to join the party on the kingside.}) 23. Rxg6+ Rg7 24. Qh5 {It is over. Black just can't get any pieces into the defence, and the king for sure can't survive on its own.} Bc6 25. Rxg7+ Kxg7 26. Qh7+ Kf8 {[%csl Gg2]} 27. Rxc6 $1 {A nice finishing touch. Even when you are clearly winning you need to take care. Here Black was actually threatening mate in one on [g2]!} bxc6 (27... Qxc6 28. Bxg5 {was no better. For instance} Qd7 29. Bh6+ Ke8 30. Qg8+ Ke7 31. Bg5# {.}) 28. Bg6 {[%csl Gf7]} (28. Bg6 {Threatening mate on f7. If} e5 {then just} 29. Bxg5 {.}) 1-0

