1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 ({A favourite among Slav players. Black first consolidates the d5-pawn and prepares to develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4. Maybe the move c7-c6 isn't strictly necessary as preparation for the bishop sortie. Next, we will examine the direct} 3... Bf5 {(here and) 3...Bg4 (here) .}) 4. Bd3 {This prevents [Bf5].} Bg4 ({The natural continuation. The more modest Semi-Slav setup with} 4... e6 {is covered in the 3...e6 section.}) 5. Nbd2 {White intends to take back on [f3] with a knight. That's why I prefer to wait a little with the standard move [h2]-[h3].} Nbd7 {Very natural. Black just develops and even flirts with the active break [e7]-[e5]. It is no surprise that [Nbd7] is the most-played move. However White also has some possibilities!} 6. h3 {Now it is probably good to insert this little move.} Bxf3 7. Nxf3 {White has the bishops and should be happy. Only one idea can bother us.} Qc7 {[%cal Ge7e5] This is it. Black plans to strike in the centre with [e7]-[e5].} 8. Bd2 {An interesting subtlety.} ({The line after} 8. O-O e5 9. dxe5 Nxe5 {has scored well for Black although White of course is fine after something like} 10. Bd2 {.}) 8... e5 ({After the safe} 8... e6 {White gets the upper hand} 9. O-O Bd6 10. c4 { The bishops!}) 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Qxe5 11. Bc3 {The point of 8.Bd2 .} Qd6 {This has been played in an email game.} 12. Qf3 {[%csl Gf6] A strong improvement. To begin with Black must protect the knight.} Be7 13. O-O-O O-O-O ({Castling kingside is dangerous:} 13... O-O 14. h4 {, followed by [g2]-[g4], and White has a strong initiative.}) 14. g4 {[%csl Gc3,Gd3][%cal Gg4g5]} (14. g4 {White is clearly better. The bishops are strong and the threat g4-g5 is annoying. If Black plays} h6 {, we can renew the threat with} 15. h4 {.}) *

