1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 ({A favourite among Slav players. Black first consolidates the d5-pawn and prepares to develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4. Maybe the move c7-c6 isn't strictly necessary as preparation for the bishop sortie. Next, we will examine the direct} 3... Bf5 {(here and) 3...Bg4 (here) .}) 4. Bd3 {This prevents [Bf5].} Bg4 ({The natural continuation. The more modest Semi-Slav setup with} 4... e6 {is covered in the 3...e6 section.}) 5. Nbd2 {White intends to take back on [f3] with a knight. That's why I prefer to wait a little with the standard move [h2]-[h3].} Nbd7 {Very natural. Black just develops and even flirts with the active break [e7]-[e5]. It is no surprise that [Nbd7] is the most-played move. However White also has some possibilities!} 6. h3 {Now it is probably good to insert this little move.} Bh5 {Almost universally played.} 7. O-O e5 {This active move is well met by...} 8. e4 $1 {The opening of the centre is favourable for White who is better developed and has already castled.} exd4 {This is Black's best.} 9. Re1 {Staring down at the enemy king.} Be7 ({The line,} 9... dxe4 10. Nxe4 Be7 11. Nd6+ Kf8 12. Nf5 {, is risky for Black.}) 10. g4 $1 (10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nb3 O-O 12. Nbxd4 {is only equal.}) 10... Bg6 11. e5 Ne4 (11... Ng8 12. Nxd4 {must be good for White.}) 12. Bxe4 $1 ({The most precise. After} 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Bxe4 {Black is not forced to take on [e4] and can instead go for} Nc5 {with an ok position.}) 12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 {[%csl Gd4] Now [d4] is hanging.} Bxe4 ({Here,} 13... Nc5 {can be met by} 14. Nd6+ $1 Bxd6 15. exd6+ Ne6 16. Qxd4 {a nice line goes:} O-O 17. Rxe6 $5 fxe6 18. Bg5 Qb6 19. Qxb6 axb6 20. Ne5 {and Black will hardly survive this positional mess.}) 14. Rxe4 c5 15. c3 {[%csl Gd4] We need to challenge the black centre.} dxc3 16. bxc3 {[%cal Gd1e2,Gc3c4] White is slightly better. We can put the queen on [e2] or [c2], and play [c3]-[c4] with nice control.} *

