1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 ({A favourite among Slav players. Black first consolidates the d5-pawn and prepares to develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4. Maybe the move c7-c6 isn't strictly necessary as preparation for the bishop sortie. Next, we will examine the direct} 3... Bf5 {(here and) 3...Bg4 (here) .}) 4. Bd3 {This prevents [Bf5].} Bg4 ({The natural continuation. The more modest Semi-Slav setup with} 4... e6 {is covered in the 3...e6 section.}) 5. Nbd2 {White intends to take back on [f3] with a knight. That's why I prefer to wait a little with the standard move [h2]-[h3].} Nbd7 {Very natural. Black just develops and even flirts with the active break [e7]-[e5]. It is no surprise that [Nbd7] is the most-played move. However White also has some possibilities!} 6. h3 {Now it is probably good to insert this little move.} Bh5 {Almost universally played.} 7. O-O e5 {This active move is well met by...} 8. e4 $1 {The opening of the centre is favourable for White who is better developed and has already castled.} dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Bxe4 Nf6 11. Bg5 {With strong pressure.} ({Also good is} 11. Re1 {.}) 11... Qxd4 {[%cal Gh5d1] This surprising move is the best chance, using the fact that [Nf3] is pinned.} 12. Nxd4 Bxd1 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Raxd1 exd4 15. Rxd4 {White is much better in the ending, because of the better structure and more active pieces, but the opposite coloured bishops give Black some hope of surviving. It will be a long day though.} *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Colle System"]
