1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 ({A favourite among Slav players. Black first consolidates the d5-pawn and prepares to develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4. Maybe the move c7-c6 isn't strictly necessary as preparation for the bishop sortie. Next, we will examine the direct} 3... Bf5 {(here and) 3...Bg4 (here) .}) 4. Bd3 {This prevents [Bf5].} Bg4 ({The natural continuation. The more modest Semi-Slav setup with} 4... e6 {is covered in the 3...e6 section.}) 5. Nbd2 {White intends to take back on [f3] with a knight. That's why I prefer to wait a little with the standard move [h2]-[h3].} Nbd7 {Very natural. Black just develops and even flirts with the active break [e7]-[e5]. It is no surprise that [Nbd7] is the most-played move. However White also has some possibilities!} 6. h3 {Now it is probably good to insert this little move.} Bh5 {Almost universally played.} 7. O-O e6 {The safe choice.} 8. c4 Be7 ({This is solid but more passive. White goes for the same flexible set-up as against} 8... Bd6 {.}) 9. b3 g5 {Is a crazy move that is better than it looks. A simple way to play is:} 10. cxd5 cxd5 ({After} 10... exd5 11. e4 $1 {White opens up the centre, when [g7]-[g5] is really a move you would wish you never had made!}) 11. e4 g4 {The only reasonable idea.} 12. hxg4 Bxg4 13. Qe2 {Black doesn't have a real attack and the many weak squares on the kingside might begin to tell.} *

