1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 ({A favourite among Slav players. Black first consolidates the d5-pawn and prepares to develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4. Maybe the move c7-c6 isn't strictly necessary as preparation for the bishop sortie. Next, we will examine the direct} 3... Bf5 {(here and) 3...Bg4 (here) .}) 4. Bd3 {This prevents [Bf5].} Bg4 ({The natural continuation. The more modest Semi-Slav setup with} 4... e6 {is covered in the 3...e6 section.}) 5. Nbd2 {White intends to take back on [f3] with a knight. That's why I prefer to wait a little with the standard move [h2]-[h3].} Nbd7 {Very natural. Black just develops and even flirts with the active break [e7]-[e5]. It is no surprise that [Nbd7] is the most-played move. However White also has some possibilities!} 6. h3 {Now it is probably good to insert this little move.} Bh5 {Almost universally played.} 7. O-O e6 {The safe choice.} 8. c4 Be7 ({This is solid but more passive. White goes for the same flexible set-up as against} 8... Bd6 {.}) 9. b3 O-O 10. Bb2 c5 {Trying to solve all problems at once - and it almost works!} 11. dxc5 {A new move. We don't mind some simplifications.} Nxc5 12. Be2 dxc4 13. Nxc4 {The position is almost equal. Almost!} Rc8 14. Rc1 ({Even} 14. Nd4 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 {gives White a little.}) 14... Nd5 ({The interesting} 14... Bxf3 $5 {is met by} 15. gxf3 $1 {and the bishops should make us happy.}) (14... b5 {merely weakens} 15. Nce5 {White is better.}) 15. g4 $1 {White has the initiative.} Bg6 16. Nce5 {Attacking the bishop.} Be4 17. Qd4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc1c5]} (17. Qd4 {White threatens Rxc5 followed by Qxe4. A sample line goes} f6 18. Rxc5 $1 Bxc5 19. Qxe4 fxe5 20. Bxe5 Qe7 21. Bc4 {with great long-term compensation for the exchange. The engine is really excited! White has a pawn for the exchange and two strong bishops. The permanent outpost on [e5] is also nice.}) *

