1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 ({A favourite among Slav players. Black first consolidates the d5-pawn and prepares to develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4. Maybe the move c7-c6 isn't strictly necessary as preparation for the bishop sortie. Next, we will examine the direct} 3... Bf5 {(here and) 3...Bg4 (here) .}) 4. Bd3 {This prevents [Bf5].} Bg4 ({The natural continuation. The more modest Semi-Slav setup with} 4... e6 {is covered in the 3...e6 section.}) 5. Nbd2 {White intends to take back on [f3] with a knight. That's why I prefer to wait a little with the standard move [h2]-[h3].} Nbd7 {Very natural. Black just develops and even flirts with the active break [e7]-[e5]. It is no surprise that [Nbd7] is the most-played move. However White also has some possibilities!} 6. h3 {Now it is probably good to insert this little move.} Bh5 {Almost universally played.} 7. O-O e6 {The safe choice.} 8. c4 Be7 ({This is solid but more passive. White goes for the same flexible set-up as against} 8... Bd6 {.}) 9. b3 O-O 10. Bb2 a5 {A standard Slav move, taking space on the queenside and flirting with the idea to push the pawn to [a4].} 11. Qc2 Bg6 {An important defensive resource.} 12. Bxg6 hxg6 13. a4 $5 {I like this move that stops all Black's immediate ideas on the queenside. The hole on [b4] is a minor concern. White is slightly better with good control. You can compare with the [Bd6]-line.} *

