{Or 15...Qc7 16.b4!} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 ({A favourite among Slav players. Black first consolidates the d5-pawn and prepares to develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4. Maybe the move c7-c6 isn't strictly necessary as preparation for the bishop sortie. Next, we will examine the direct} 3... Bf5 {(here and) 3...Bg4 (here) .}) 4. Bd3 {This prevents [Bf5].} Bg4 ({The natural continuation. The more modest Semi-Slav setup with} 4... e6 {is covered in the 3...e6 section.}) 5. Nbd2 {White intends to take back on [f3] with a knight. That's why I prefer to wait a little with the standard move [h2]-[h3].} Nbd7 {Very natural. Black just develops and even flirts with the active break [e7]-[e5]. It is no surprise that [Nbd7] is the most-played move. However White also has some possibilities!} 6. h3 {Now it is probably good to insert this little move.} Bh5 {Almost universally played.} 7. O-O e6 {The safe choice.} 8. c4 Bg6 {Trying to exchange the active [d3]-bishop makes sense, but it loses time.} 9. Bxg6 ({Also possible is} 9. Qc2 {.}) 9... hxg6 10. Qc2 {[%csl Ge4] White has control over the important [e4]-square.} Bd6 ({Black could also try} 10... Bb4 {. First of all, Black is not really threatening to take on [d2] because the white bishop will be quite strong long-term. Secondly, White can meet it with the imaginative:} 11. Ng5 $5 {still controlling [e4]. This was played in an email game and White was quickly on top after} Qe7 12. a3 Bd6 13. Re1 {, intending to go [e3]-[e4].}) 11. e4 {The standard break.} dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Nf6 14. Qe2 (14. Qe2 {White is slightly better with a lot of extra space. A sample line goes:} O-O 15. Bd2 {a nice move. The bishop prepares the [b2]-[b4] gaining more space. Of course, a lot of other moves like [Rd1] or [Bg5] could also be played.} c5 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. b4 $1 Be7 18. Rfd1 Qc7 19. Rac1 {White has a nice pawn majority on the queenside.}) *

