1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 ({A favourite among Slav players. Black first consolidates the d5-pawn and prepares to develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4. Maybe the move c7-c6 isn't strictly necessary as preparation for the bishop sortie. Next, we will examine the direct} 3... Bf5 {(here and) 3...Bg4 (here) .}) 4. Bd3 {This prevents [Bf5].} Bg4 ({The natural continuation. The more modest Semi-Slav setup with} 4... e6 {is covered in the 3...e6 section.}) 5. Nbd2 {White intends to take back on [f3] with a knight. That's why I prefer to wait a little with the standard move [h2]-[h3].} Nbd7 {Very natural. Black just develops and even flirts with the active break [e7]-[e5]. It is no surprise that [Nbd7] is the most-played move. However White also has some possibilities!} 6. h3 {Now it is probably good to insert this little move.} Bh5 {Almost universally played.} 7. O-O e6 {The safe choice.} 8. c4 Bd6 {The most active spot for the bishop.} 9. b3 {I want to have the bishop on [b2].} (9. Qc2 {or 9.Qb3 are good alternatives.}) 9... e5 {This classical break leads to a pleasant position for White where Black is saddled with an isolated pawn.} 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 ({Black could also try} 11... Bxe5 12. Rb1 {but it doesn't change the evaluation. White is slightly better.}) 12. Be2 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc1b2] Black has no real activity to compensate for the IQP and has to defend an inferior position. Next we will play [Bb2] and welcome some piece exchanges. The isolated pawn is especially weak in endings with heavy pieces.} *

