1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 ({A favourite among Slav players. Black first consolidates the d5-pawn and prepares to develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4. Maybe the move c7-c6 isn't strictly necessary as preparation for the bishop sortie. Next, we will examine the direct} 3... Bf5 {(here and) 3...Bg4 (here) .}) 4. Bd3 {This prevents [Bf5].} Bg4 ({The natural continuation. The more modest Semi-Slav setup with} 4... e6 {is covered in the 3...e6 section.}) 5. Nbd2 {White intends to take back on [f3] with a knight. That's why I prefer to wait a little with the standard move [h2]-[h3].} Nbd7 {Very natural. Black just develops and even flirts with the active break [e7]-[e5]. It is no surprise that [Nbd7] is the most-played move. However White also has some possibilities!} 6. h3 {Now it is probably good to insert this little move.} Bh5 {Almost universally played.} 7. O-O e6 {The safe choice.} 8. c4 Bd6 {The most active spot for the bishop.} 9. b3 {I want to have the bishop on [b2].} (9. Qc2 {or 9.Qb3 are good alternatives.}) 9... O-O 10. Bb2 {An important position in this Colle Slav line. White has the somewhat easier play, but Black should be fine as well. Knowing a little more is important.} Re8 11. Qc2 e5 {This is similar to the 10...Qe7 mainline in some ways, but there are differences.} 12. cxd5 ({Here} 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 {doesn´t give White anything.}) 12... Bxf3 $1 {An important zwischenzug.} ({The line after} 12... cxd5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bxe5 Rxe5 16. Rac1 {is nice for White.}) 13. dxe5 $1 ({Not} 13. Nxf3 $2 e4 {.}) 13... Nxe5 14. Nxf3 Nxf3+ 15. gxf3 {White's pawn structure has been ruined, but the shelter in front of the king is still sufficient.} cxd5 16. f4 (16. f4 {White is better with the strong bishops. A sample line goes:} Rc8 17. Qd1 Qe7 18. Qf3 {, threatening [Bxf6] and [Qxd5].}) *

