1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 ({A favourite among Slav players. Black first consolidates the d5-pawn and prepares to develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4. Maybe the move c7-c6 isn't strictly necessary as preparation for the bishop sortie. Next, we will examine the direct} 3... Bf5 {(here and) 3...Bg4 (here) .}) 4. Bd3 {This prevents [Bf5].} Bg4 ({The natural continuation. The more modest Semi-Slav setup with} 4... e6 {is covered in the 3...e6 section.}) 5. Nbd2 {White intends to take back on [f3] with a knight. That's why I prefer to wait a little with the standard move [h2]-[h3].} Nbd7 {Very natural. Black just develops and even flirts with the active break [e7]-[e5]. It is no surprise that [Nbd7] is the most-played move. However White also has some possibilities!} 6. h3 {Now it is probably good to insert this little move.} Bh5 {Almost universally played.} 7. O-O e6 {The safe choice.} 8. c4 Bd6 {The most active spot for the bishop.} 9. b3 {I want to have the bishop on [b2].} (9. Qc2 {or 9.Qb3 are good alternatives.}) 9... O-O 10. Bb2 {An important position in this Colle Slav line. White has the somewhat easier play, but Black should be fine as well. Knowing a little more is important.} Qe7 {The main move.} 11. Qc2 {Sidestepping the pin of [Nf3].} e5 {This is the only way to get active counterplay. It leads to some exchanges and in the end White keeps a small pull.} 12. dxe5 ({The move} 12. cxd5 {, is met by} Bxf3 $1 {Still, White can play after} 13. dxe5 $1 Nxe5 14. Nxf3 Nxf3+ 15. gxf3 cxd5 16. f4 {the kingside has been weakened, but the bishops are good. In Nikolaidis-Pavlidis, Greece 2012 White won a fight.}) 12... Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Bxe5 Qxe5 15. cxd5 Qxd5 ({Accepting an isolated pawn with} 15... cxd5 {is not very wise. After} 16. Rac1 {White had a pleasant position in Andreikin-Grandelius, rapid 2024.}) 16. Ne4 $1 {The point of the simplifications. White keeps some initiative.} Nxe4 17. Bxe4 Bg6 {[%cal Gg6c2,Ge4d5] Only move. Apparently Black has solved all problems, yet after:} 18. Bxg6 hxg6 19. Rad1 Qe6 20. Rd3 (20. Rd3 {White controls the open d-file and is somewhat better, though objectively Black should hold. A sample line goes:} Rfd8 21. Rfd1 Qe7 22. Qd2 Rxd3 23. Qxd3 {}) *

