1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 ({A favourite among Slav players. Black first consolidates the d5-pawn and prepares to develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4. Maybe the move c7-c6 isn't strictly necessary as preparation for the bishop sortie. Next, we will examine the direct} 3... Bf5 {(here and) 3...Bg4 (here) .}) 4. Bd3 {This prevents [Bf5].} Bg4 ({The natural continuation. The more modest Semi-Slav setup with} 4... e6 {is covered in the 3...e6 section.}) 5. Nbd2 {White intends to take back on [f3] with a knight. That's why I prefer to wait a little with the standard move [h2]-[h3].} Nbd7 {Very natural. Black just develops and even flirts with the active break [e7]-[e5]. It is no surprise that [Nbd7] is the most-played move. However White also has some possibilities!} 6. h3 {Now it is probably good to insert this little move.} Bh5 {Almost universally played.} 7. O-O e6 {The safe choice.} 8. c4 Bd6 {The most active spot for the bishop.} 9. b3 {I want to have the bishop on [b2].} (9. Qc2 {or 9.Qb3 are good alternatives.}) 9... O-O 10. Bb2 {An important position in this Colle Slav line. White has the somewhat easier play, but Black should be fine as well. Knowing a little more is important.} Qe7 {The main move.} 11. Qc2 {Sidestepping the pin of [Nf3].} Bg6 {Trying to neutralize White's strong bishop.} 12. Bxg6 hxg6 13. e4 $1 {The typical break. In general in the Colle system we try to get this [e3]-[e4] push in because it frees our position and leads to a nice space advantage.} dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gf1e1] White was slightly better in Nakamura-Bluebaum, blitz 2021. White will just stabilize the position with improvement moves like [Rad1] and [Rfe1]. At an appropiate moment [Ne5] might be strong and later maybe expanding on the kingside.} *

