1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 ({A favourite among Slav players. Black first consolidates the d5-pawn and prepares to develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4. Maybe the move c7-c6 isn't strictly necessary as preparation for the bishop sortie. Next, we will examine the direct} 3... Bf5 {(here and) 3...Bg4 (here) .}) 4. Bd3 {This prevents [Bf5].} Bg4 ({The natural continuation. The more modest Semi-Slav setup with} 4... e6 {is covered in the 3...e6 section.}) 5. Nbd2 {White intends to take back on [f3] with a knight. That's why I prefer to wait a little with the standard move [h2]-[h3].} e6 {The most precise. It gives Black the extra opportunity to meet [h2]-[h3] with the surprising [Bf5]!?} 6. O-O ({On} 6. h3 {Black could consider} Bf5 $5 {the position after} 7. Bxf5 exf5 {looks fine for Black.}) 6... Nbd7 {The move order is not so important.} (6... Bd6 7. b3 {will just transpose to the mainline.}) ({Even} 6... Bf5 $5 {could be tried even though White didn't play [h2]-[h3]. In an email game White just responded with} 7. Qe2 {. However, also Bxf5 exf5 c4 looks better for White.}) 7. b3 Bd6 8. Bb2 Qc7 {Attacking [h2] before White has time to play [c2]-[c4] and [Qc2].} 9. h3 Bf5 $5 {Here this idea is not so convincing.} 10. Qe2 {[%cal Ge3e4] Instead of taking on [f5] and strenghtening Black's grip on the [e4]-square we just protect the bishop and prepares to advance in the centre.} Bxd3 ({Or} 10... O-O 11. e4 {after the simplification} dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Bxe4 14. Qxe4 {.}) 11. Qxd3 O-O 12. e4 {White is slightly better. Black has nothing better than to simplify.} dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 {[%cal Gc2c4,Ga1d1,Gf1e1] White is very comfortable with all the extra space. We will play [c2]-[c4] and centralize the rooks on [e1] and [d1].} *

