1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 ({A favourite among Slav players. Black first consolidates the d5-pawn and prepares to develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4. Maybe the move c7-c6 isn't strictly necessary as preparation for the bishop sortie. Next, we will examine the direct} 3... Bf5 {(here and) 3...Bg4 (here) .}) 4. Bd3 {This prevents [Bf5].} Bg4 ({The natural continuation. The more modest Semi-Slav setup with} 4... e6 {is covered in the 3...e6 section.}) 5. Nbd2 {White intends to take back on [f3] with a knight. That's why I prefer to wait a little with the standard move [h2]-[h3].} e6 {The most precise. It gives Black the extra opportunity to meet [h2]-[h3] with the surprising [Bf5]!?} 6. O-O ({On} 6. h3 {Black could consider} Bf5 $5 {the position after} 7. Bxf5 exf5 {looks fine for Black.}) 6... Nbd7 {The move order is not so important.} (6... Bd6 7. b3 {will just transpose to the mainline.}) ({Even} 6... Bf5 $5 {could be tried even though White didn't play [h2]-[h3]. In an email game White just responded with} 7. Qe2 {. However, also Bxf5 exf5 c4 looks better for White.}) 7. b3 Bd6 8. Bb2 e5 {This break should always be taken into consideration. Also in this case it leads to some exchanges.} 9. dxe5 Nxe5 (9... Bxe5 {can be met by} 10. Qc1 {and White can hope for a small edge.}) 10. Be2 Qc7 {Keeping the tension makes sense.} 11. Nd4 Bd7 ({After} 11... Bxe2 12. Qxe2 {White has the [f5]-square for the knight.}) 12. h3 O-O 13. c4 (13. c4 {White has some pull. A sample line goes:} dxc4 14. bxc4 Rad8 15. Qc2 b6 16. N4b3 c5 17. f4 $1 Nc6 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Ne4 Be7 20. Qc3 {, and Black is in big trouble.}) *

