1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 ({A favourite among Slav players. Black first consolidates the d5-pawn and prepares to develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4. Maybe the move c7-c6 isn't strictly necessary as preparation for the bishop sortie. Next, we will examine the direct} 3... Bf5 {(here and) 3...Bg4 (here) .}) 4. Bd3 {This prevents [Bf5].} Bg4 ({The natural continuation. The more modest Semi-Slav setup with} 4... e6 {is covered in the 3...e6 section.}) 5. Nbd2 {White intends to take back on [f3] with a knight. That's why I prefer to wait a little with the standard move [h2]-[h3].} e6 {The most precise. It gives Black the extra opportunity to meet [h2]-[h3] with the surprising [Bf5]!?} 6. O-O ({On} 6. h3 {Black could consider} Bf5 $5 {the position after} 7. Bxf5 exf5 {looks fine for Black.}) 6... Nbd7 {The move order is not so important.} (6... Bd6 7. b3 {will just transpose to the mainline.}) ({Even} 6... Bf5 $5 {could be tried even though White didn't play [h2]-[h3]. In an email game White just responded with} 7. Qe2 {. However, also Bxf5 exf5 c4 looks better for White.}) 7. b3 Bd6 8. Bb2 e5 {This break should always be taken into consideration. Also in this case it leads to some exchanges.} 9. dxe5 Nxe5 (9... Bxe5 {can be met by} 10. Qc1 {and White can hope for a small edge.}) 10. Be2 Nxf3+ 11. Bxf3 $1 {We would like to exchange the light-squared bishops.} Bf5 ({The obvious} 11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3 {is not easy at all. White has broken with both, [c2]-[c4] and [e3]-[e4], and of course, also [Bxf6] is in the air.}) 12. c4 O-O 13. cxd5 cxd5 {This is forced.} ({White wins after} 13... Nxd5 $2 14. e4 {.}) 14. Rc1 {[%csl Gd5,Bf1][%cal Gd2b1,Gb1c3,Bd1e2,Bf1d1,Bd2f1,Bf1g3] White is somewhat better with long-term play against the isolated d-pawn. It is not clear what we should do with our knight though. It is rather passive on [d2]. Here are some options, which can be used depending on what Black does: The knight can go to [b1] and then [c3], or we can play [Qe2], [Rfd1], and then [Nf1]-[g3]. Sometimes even [g2]-[g3] followed by [Bg2] and [Nf3].} (14. Rc1 {Here is a sample line:} Qe7 15. Nb1 Rad8 16. Qd4 $1 {the centralized queen is strong} a6 17. Rfd1 Rfe8 18. Qh4 Be5 19. Bxe5 Qxe5 20. Nc3 {play continues, of course, but I prefer White. The exchange of the dark-squared bishops has helped us and the d-pawn is always a problem for Black.}) ({The greedy} 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Bxd5 Rad8 {gives Black good play for the pawn with very active pieces. Let's avoid that!}) *

