1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c6 ({A favourite among Slav players. Black first consolidates the d5-pawn and prepares to develop the light-squared bishop to f5 or g4. Maybe the move c7-c6 isn't strictly necessary as preparation for the bishop sortie. Next, we will examine the direct} 3... Bf5 {(here and) 3...Bg4 (here) .}) 4. Bd3 {This prevents [Bf5].} Bg4 ({The natural continuation. The more modest Semi-Slav setup with} 4... e6 {is covered in the 3...e6 section.}) 5. Nbd2 {White intends to take back on [f3] with a knight. That's why I prefer to wait a little with the standard move [h2]-[h3].} e6 {The most precise. It gives Black the extra opportunity to meet [h2]-[h3] with the surprising [Bf5]!?} 6. O-O ({On} 6. h3 {Black could consider} Bf5 $5 {the position after} 7. Bxf5 exf5 {looks fine for Black.}) 6... Nbd7 {The move order is not so important.} (6... Bd6 7. b3 {will just transpose to the mainline.}) ({Even} 6... Bf5 $5 {could be tried even though White didn't play [h2]-[h3]. In an email game White just responded with} 7. Qe2 {. However, also Bxf5 exf5 c4 looks better for White.}) 7. b3 Bd6 8. Bb2 O-O {The most natural move, getting the king to safety before active operations are started.} 9. c4 ({We go for the same structure again and again. Here you could also consider:} 9. Qe1 $5 {which was played by expert, Jussupow. White gets out of the pin and prepares [Ne5].}) 9... Re8 10. h3 (10. Qc2 e5 {is ok for Black.}) 10... Bxf3 ({Not very likely to happen, but after} 10... Bh5 {we have transposed to the line starting with 5...Nbd7 .}) 11. Nxf3 e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. cxd5 Nxd3 {The best chance.} 14. Qxd3 Nxd5 15. Rad1 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gd1d8] White has some pull down the d-file and [Bb2] is really strong.} *

