1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {Black develops the bishop as active as possible and tries to save the move [c7]-[c6].} 4. Nbd2 {So we can take back on [f3] with the knight.} ({White could also play} 4. h3 {which is kind of the principled reaction. What I didn't like that much was:} Bxf3 $5 {, giving the bishop saves time and is tempting.} 5. Qxf3 e6 {Black is ready to play [c7]-[c5] with a sound position; and if} 6. c4 {, then apart from transposing to the 4. [e3] Slav with [c7]-[c6], Black can give a disturbing check:} Bb4+ {for instance} 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ 8. Nxd2 O-O {, and Black might get [c7]-[c5] in with good play.}) 4... e6 5. h3 Bxf3 {Not many players are ready to just take on [f3], but here I actually think it is the safest.} 6. Nxf3 c5 {And Black has quite ok play. That said after the natural follow-up...} 7. Be2 Nc6 8. O-O (8. O-O {White of course has the bishops which gives some advantage, but Black has a very sound position. A sample line goes:} Bd6 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. c4 {, and the bishops might begin to tell. Anyway, you can play this for sure.}) *

