1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {Black develops the bishop as active as possible and tries to save the move [c7]-[c6].} 4. Nbd2 {So we can take back on [f3] with the knight.} ({White could also play} 4. h3 {which is kind of the principled reaction. What I didn't like that much was:} Bxf3 $5 {, giving the bishop saves time and is tempting.} 5. Qxf3 e6 {Black is ready to play [c7]-[c5] with a sound position; and if} 6. c4 {, then apart from transposing to the 4. [e3] Slav with [c7]-[c6], Black can give a disturbing check:} Bb4+ {for instance} 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ 8. Nxd2 O-O {, and Black might get [c7]-[c5] in with good play.}) 4... e6 5. h3 Bh5 {Everybody plays this more or less automatically.} 6. g4 $1 Bg6 7. Ne5 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gh3h4] White already has some serious initiative. We don't intend to take on [g6] right away, rather, we play [h3]-[h4] and threaten to win the bishop.} (7. Ne5 Be4 {doesn't help:} 8. f3 Bg6 9. h4 $1 {and Black is in trouble.}) 7... Nbd7 {This looks natural, but the bishop is a target.} 8. h4 $1 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gh4h5] Already threatening [h4]-[h5].} h6 (8... h5 {is no better. After} 9. Nxg6 fxg6 10. g5 {White is strategically winning.}) ({And} 8... Nxe5 {loses a piece after} 9. dxe5 {the knight is hanging and [h4]-[h5] is also threatened.}) 9. Nxg6 fxg6 10. Bd3 {[%csl Gg6] Attacking the sorry [g6]-pawn.} Kf7 11. e4 $1 {[%csl Gf7] White opens up the position and is clearly winning. The vulnerable black king on [f7] and the permanently weak, [g6]-pawn, decide the game.} *

