1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {Black develops the bishop as active as possible and tries to save the move [c7]-[c6].} 4. Nbd2 {So we can take back on [f3] with the knight.} ({White could also play} 4. h3 {which is kind of the principled reaction. What I didn't like that much was:} Bxf3 $5 {, giving the bishop saves time and is tempting.} 5. Qxf3 e6 {Black is ready to play [c7]-[c5] with a sound position; and if} 6. c4 {, then apart from transposing to the 4. [e3] Slav with [c7]-[c6], Black can give a disturbing check:} Bb4+ {for instance} 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ 8. Nxd2 O-O {, and Black might get [c7]-[c5] in with good play.}) 4... e6 5. h3 Bh5 {Everybody plays this more or less automatically.} 6. g4 $1 Bg6 7. Ne5 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gh3h4] White already has some serious initiative. We don't intend to take on [g6] right away, rather, we play [h3]-[h4] and threaten to win the bishop.} (7. Ne5 Be4 {doesn't help:} 8. f3 Bg6 9. h4 $1 {and Black is in trouble.}) 7... Bd6 8. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] This is quite similar.} h5 {Let's go with this move for a change.} 9. Nxg6 fxg6 10. g5 Ng4 {Played in an email game.} (10... Nfd7 11. Bd3 Nf8 {is depressing. White can start playing on the other flank as well with} 12. c4 {, preparing [Qc2]. I doubt that Black will survive for long.}) 11. Bd3 $1 {[%csl Gg6]} O-O {[%csl Gf2] This is the idea.} 12. Bxg6 Rxf2 ({Of course not} 12... Nxf2 13. Qxh5 {and White threatens mate in one!}) 13. Rg1 $1 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Gg1g4] Threatening [Rxg4].} ({Not} 13. Bxh5 $2 Nxe3 {, and the white queen is trapped.}) 13... Qf8 ({The engine proposes} 13... Rf5 {, of course, White can take the exchange, but also here it is better to sacrifice it!} 14. Rxg4 $1 hxg4 15. Qxg4 {White is much better.}) 14. Rxg4 $1 hxg4 15. Qxg4 {[%cal Gg4e6] White is winning. Black can't protect [e6] in a sensible way.} *

