1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {Black develops the bishop as active as possible and tries to save the move [c7]-[c6].} 4. Nbd2 {So we can take back on [f3] with the knight.} ({White could also play} 4. h3 {which is kind of the principled reaction. What I didn't like that much was:} Bxf3 $5 {, giving the bishop saves time and is tempting.} 5. Qxf3 e6 {Black is ready to play [c7]-[c5] with a sound position; and if} 6. c4 {, then apart from transposing to the 4. [e3] Slav with [c7]-[c6], Black can give a disturbing check:} Bb4+ {for instance} 7. Bd2 Bxd2+ 8. Nxd2 O-O {, and Black might get [c7]-[c5] in with good play.}) 4... e6 5. h3 Bh5 {Everybody plays this more or less automatically.} 6. g4 $1 Bg6 7. Ne5 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gh3h4] White already has some serious initiative. We don't intend to take on [g6] right away, rather, we play [h3]-[h4] and threaten to win the bishop.} (7. Ne5 Be4 {doesn't help:} 8. f3 Bg6 9. h4 $1 {and Black is in trouble.}) 7... Nfd7 {Already the only move to stay in the game!} 8. Nxg6 {Grabbing the bishop is the positional idea.} ({Not} 8. h4 Nxe5 9. dxe5 h5 $1 {and the pawn advance on the kingside has merely weakened our position.}) 8... hxg6 9. Bg2 {[%csl Gc1,Gg2]} ({White has a comfortable position with the bishop pair. It was even possible to break at once with} 9. c4 {or 9.e4 , but why not just finish our development? Next, we can castle and then decide which pawn break is the most effective.}) *

