1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 {Also a very natural active development move. Black plays a London reversed!} 4. Bd3 {We challenge the strong black bishop. This is also known to be good in the traditional London!} ({White could also strike with} 4. c4 {but then you must be prepared to play one of the biggest Slav mainlines after} c6 {.}) 4... Bg6 {This is very popular, both here and in the similar situations in the London.} 5. O-O ({The active} 5. Ne5 {is nothing special. After} e6 {it doesn´t give much to take the bishop.}) 5... e6 6. c4 ({White has many choices.} 6. b3 {is a popular solid move.}) (6. Ne5 Bd6 7. f4 {also looks interesting, but I prefer the active positional break with [c2]-[c4].}) 6... c6 7. Qc2 {White goes for a flexible setup.} ({Also interesting is} 7. Bxg6 $5 hxg6 8. Nbd2 {the open h-file shouldn't worry us too much and White can play for the [e4]-break or just develop slower. Maybe it will be necessary to play [h2]-[h3] sooner or later, but again it is not dangerous.}) 7... Nbd7 8. Nbd2 {[%cal Ge3e4] White has a fine reversed London! We will probably get [e3]-[e4] in with good play.} *

