1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 {Also a very natural active development move. Black plays a London reversed!} 4. Bd3 {We challenge the strong black bishop. This is also known to be good in the traditional London!} ({White could also strike with} 4. c4 {but then you must be prepared to play one of the biggest Slav mainlines after} c6 {.}) 4... e6 {This is another tempting way to play for Black, just protecting the bishop. The idea is often seen in the Slav.} 5. Bxf5 exf5 {[%csl Ge4] The double pawn is not weak in itself, actually it gives Black complete control over the important [e4]-square.} 6. Qd3 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gd3f5,Gd3b5] This gains a useful tempo.} Qc8 ({Not} 6... g6 $2 7. Qb5+) 7. O-O Bd6 {A great post for the bishop.} 8. b3 $1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gc1a3,Gc2c4] So we want to exchange it! White prepares [Ba3] and also the positional [c2]-[c4].} O-O 9. c4 c6 10. Ba3 $1 Bxa3 11. Nxa3 {[%cal Ga3b1,Gb1c3,Ga1b1,Gf1c1] White is slightly better with the superior pawn structure and some positional initiative on the queenside. We are in no hurry, so it makes sense to regroup the knight with [Na3]-[b1]-[c3], and then decide on the rooks. They may stand optimal on [b1] and [c1] to support a future pawn storm.} *

