1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 {Also a very natural active development move. Black plays a London reversed!} 4. Bd3 {We challenge the strong black bishop. This is also known to be good in the traditional London!} ({White could also strike with} 4. c4 {but then you must be prepared to play one of the biggest Slav mainlines after} c6 {.}) 4... Bxd3 5. Qxd3 ({You could consider} 5. cxd3 $5 {to get a more original position. Objectively it is probably balanced, but White has nice control over the central squares.}) 5... Nbd7 6. O-O c5 {is possible.} 7. b3 (7. Nbd2 {, intending [e3]-[e4] is also fine.}) 7... e6 8. c4 $5 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gd4c5] This creates a lot of tension in the centre. White must be ready to play with hanging pawns though.} Be7 9. Nc3 {[%csl Bc4,Bd4] Now if Black doesn't want to end up with an isolated d-pawn it is time to take on [c4] and [d4], giving White the mentioned hanging pawns.} dxc4 10. bxc4 cxd4 11. exd4 O-O 12. Bf4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4][%cal Ga1b1,Gf1c1] White has some pressure and the hanging pawns cover a lot of squares. The rooks should probably be developed to [c1] and [b1]. If Black plays [b7]-[b6] at some moment, then the white a-pawn can come forward.} *

