1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 {Also a very natural active development move. Black plays a London reversed!} 4. Bd3 {We challenge the strong black bishop. This is also known to be good in the traditional London!} ({White could also strike with} 4. c4 {but then you must be prepared to play one of the biggest Slav mainlines after} c6 {.}) 4... Bxd3 5. Qxd3 ({You could consider} 5. cxd3 $5 {to get a more original position. Objectively it is probably balanced, but White has nice control over the central squares.}) 5... Nbd7 6. O-O e6 {Played in nearly all games.} 7. Nbd2 c5 {An aggressive approach.} 8. e4 {Going for complications.} ({It is possible to start with the subtle} 8. Re1 $5 {Next, we will go [e3]-[e4]. Of course, Black has an extra option:} cxd4 9. exd4 {. This is the typical Carlsbad structure with reversed colours. The knight seems somewhat misplaced on [d7] - it would rather be on [c6], but the position is basically balanced.}) 8... cxd4 9. exd5 {Going for a small, but stable plus.} ({Tempting is} 9. e5 {but the position after} Ng8 {is far from clear. The centre is closed and the knight will come to [e7] and [c6]. A possible continuation is} 10. Nb3 Ne7 11. Re1 Nc6 12. Nbxd4 Be7 13. c3 O-O {=}) 9... Nxd5 10. Nxd4 Be7 {Black should finish development and get castled.} 11. N2f3 O-O 12. c4 {[%cal Bc1e3,Bc1f4,Bf1d1] White has some initiative, but Black is pretty solid. Depending on where the [d5]-knight goes, White will develop the bishop to [e3] or [f4] and place a rook on [d1] with nice active coordination.} *

