1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 {Also a very natural active development move. Black plays a London reversed!} 4. Bd3 {We challenge the strong black bishop. This is also known to be good in the traditional London!} ({White could also strike with} 4. c4 {but then you must be prepared to play one of the biggest Slav mainlines after} c6 {.}) 4... Bxd3 5. Qxd3 ({You could consider} 5. cxd3 $5 {to get a more original position. Objectively it is probably balanced, but White has nice control over the central squares.}) 5... c6 6. O-O e6 7. Nbd2 {[%cal Ge3e4] Going for the typical [e4]-break.} ({Slow play with} 7. b3 {is of course also possible, but then Black is fine.}) 7... Nbd7 ({Or} 7... Bd6 8. e4 {, the bishop is usually better on e7 in this structure. A likely continuation is:} dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Nd7 11. Bg5 {and White has the usual small, but long-lasting pull based on more space and more active pieces.}) 8. e4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Be7 {Black simply develops. The king looks forward to getting to safety.} 10. c4 {Many other moves could be played, but it makes sense to go for the same setup as after 9...Nxe4 .} O-O 11. Rd1 ({Also fine is} 11. Bf4 {a plausible continuation could be} Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Nf6 13. Qc2 {, and White has the somewhat easier play.}) 11... c5 {Black tries to solve all problems at once.} (11... Nxe4 {which will transpose to 9...Nxe4 after 12.Qxe4 Nf6 13.Qe2 .}) 12. Nxf6+ Nxf6 13. b3 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gc1b2,Gb2g7] Intending [Bb2]. The bishop will be excellent there after the [d4]-pawn disappears.} cxd4 14. Bb2 {[%cal Gb2d4] White will take on [d4] next. The pawn majority on the queenside gives some chances, especially in an ending. Objectively the position is probably balanced, but as usual it is easier to play with White.} *

