1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 {Also a very natural active development move. Black plays a London reversed!} 4. Bd3 {We challenge the strong black bishop. This is also known to be good in the traditional London!} ({White could also strike with} 4. c4 {but then you must be prepared to play one of the biggest Slav mainlines after} c6 {.}) 4... Bxd3 5. Qxd3 ({You could consider} 5. cxd3 $5 {to get a more original position. Objectively it is probably balanced, but White has nice control over the central squares.}) 5... c6 6. O-O e6 7. Nbd2 {[%cal Ge3e4] Going for the typical [e4]-break.} ({Slow play with} 7. b3 {is of course also possible, but then Black is fine.}) 7... Nbd7 ({Or} 7... Bd6 8. e4 {, the bishop is usually better on e7 in this structure. A likely continuation is:} dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Nd7 11. Bg5 {and White has the usual small, but long-lasting pull based on more space and more active pieces.}) 8. e4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 {It makes sense to simplify to release some of the pressure.} 10. Qxe4 Nf6 ({On} 10... Bd6 11. Bg5 {is annoying for Black.}) 11. Qe2 {I prefer to have the queen here.} Be7 {Sound and solid. But also a little passive.} ({The move,} 11... Bd6 {allows the pin,} 12. Bg5 {, which is pleasant for White.}) 12. c4 O-O 13. Rd1 ({If} 13. Bf4 {, then maybe} Qa5 {with counterplay, or even} 14. c5 {.}) 13... Qc7 14. g3 (14. g3 {White prepares Bf4. The position is more or less balanced, but the extra space makes the white position easier to play. A top game continued:} Rad8 15. Bf4 Qa5 16. a3 Qh5 17. Kg2 Rfe8 18. h3 Qf5 19. Re1 h6 {Melkumyan - Gledura, Budva 2023, and the simplest was} 20. Rad1 {with a small advantage for White.}) *

