1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose as an alternative against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... Nc6 {This natural move is played a lot. The question is if White is threatening to take on [c5]? I think the answer is yes!} 5. dxc5 $1 {Here White can really use the extra move compared to a normal Semi-Slav.} e5 6. b4 $1 {[%csl Gc5] White protects the extra pawn. Black doesn't have enough compensation.} e4 7. Nd4 Ne5 {This looks active, but in fact it makes White's task easier.} 8. Nd2 a5 {This has been played in some games. In all of them White has responded with [Bb2], but it is not necessary.} 9. f4 $5 ({The move} 9. Bb2 {is, of course, also fine.}) 9... exf3 10. N2xf3 (10. N2xf3 {White is much better. We have a pawn more and Black has no initiative. After} Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 {we will play [Bd3] and castle short and actually, we have the initiative on the kingside with nice pieces and the open f-file.}) *

