1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose as an alternative against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... Nc6 {This natural move is played a lot. The question is if White is threatening to take on [c5]? I think the answer is yes!} 5. dxc5 $1 {Here White can really use the extra move compared to a normal Semi-Slav.} e5 6. b4 $1 {[%csl Gc5] White protects the extra pawn. Black doesn't have enough compensation.} Bg4 {This also looks active.} 7. h3 {But what should Black do now?} Bh5 {The most natural move, keeping the pin.} ({Moves like} 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 {and 7...Be6 8.Nbd2 are just good for White.}) 8. Be2 {A new move. It is simple and good.} e4 9. Nd4 Bxe2 10. Qxe2 Ne5 {[%csl Gd3] Heading for the [d3]-square. This is the only way to get some positional compensation for the pawn.} 11. O-O Nd3 ({On} 11... Be7 12. Qb5+ {are annoying. Either Black must accept a queen exchange or give the [b7]-pawn as well, which is more than the position can bear.}) 12. Nd2 Be7 13. f3 $1 (13. f3 {Undermining the black outpost on d3. White is winning. A sample line shows the problem for Black:} O-O 14. fxe4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 $1 Nxc1 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Raxc1 {and wins.}) *

