1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose as an alternative against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... Nc6 {This natural move is played a lot. The question is if White is threatening to take on [c5]? I think the answer is yes!} 5. dxc5 $1 {Here White can really use the extra move compared to a normal Semi-Slav.} a5 {A move well-known from the Slav. Black tries to prevent [b2]-[b4].} 6. Bb5 $1 {[%cal Gb5e8,Gb2b4] By pinning the knight we are ready to play [b2]-[b4] after all.} Bd7 {This breaks the pin. Now White can only get [b4] in if we are willing to capture on [c6] and unfortunately it turns out that it is not so clear.} 7. a4 $1 {A nice idea.} ({Critical is} 7. b4 {The next sequence of moves are move os less forced.} axb4 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. cxb4 b6 10. cxb6 Qxb6 11. a3 {White secures the extra pawn. The computer claims Black has decent compensation after} Ba4 {or 11...e6 but ok, I think White must be preferable. We are strong on the dark squares and a pawn is a pawn!}) 7... e6 {Play now becomes rather forced.} 8. b4 axb4 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 10. cxb4 b6 {[%cal Gf8b4,Gc5b6] This regains the pawn because [b4] is hanging with check.} 11. Nd4 $1 {[%csl Gc6]} ({Of course not} 11. b5 $2 Bxb5 {.}) 11... Bb7 12. c6 $1 Bxb4+ 13. Bd2 Bxd2+ 14. Nxd2 Ba6 {[%cal Ga6f1]} 15. Nb5 $1 {[%csl Gc6] Making short castle possible. The strong passed pawn on [c6] gives us a huge advantage.} O-O 16. O-O (16. O-O {White had a pleasant position in Sadorra-Li, Irving 2018. After} e5 17. Qb3 Re8 18. Rfc1 Re6 19. a5 $1 bxa5 20. c7 Qd7 {White missed the nice} 21. Na7 $1 Ree8 22. Qb6 Bc8 23. Rxa5 {with a completely winning position thanks to the monster pawn on [c7].}) *

