1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose as an alternative against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... Nbd7 {This covers [c5].} 5. c4 $1 {A surprising reaction. White moves the c-pawn again, like we didn't know it is allowed to move two squares to begin with! The justification is that the black knight is misplaced on [d7].} ({Of course,} 5. Nbd2 {also makes perfect sense, but why not try to exploit your opponent's slight inaccuracy?}) 5... dxc4 {This leads to a kind of Queen's Gambit Accepted.} 6. Bxc4 e6 7. O-O a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] A normal move. Black wants to play [b7]-[b5] and [Bb7] with a good game.} 8. a4 {So we prevent [b7]-[b5].} cxd4 {It is tempting to give us an isolated pawn.} 9. exd4 ({We could play} 9. Nxd4 {but it is just equal.}) 9... Nb6 {The only way to use that the knight is already on [d7]. It would rather be on [c6] to put pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 10. Bb3 Be7 11. Nc3 O-O 12. Ne5 {A nice outpost.} Nbd5 {[%csl Gd5] Black has control over the important [d5]-square in front of the isolated pawn. A concept well known since Nimzowitsch! In this case however White has a free choice among several good moves.} 13. h4 ({A modern engine suggestion. Other good moves were} 13. Qd3 {, 13.Re1 or 13.Bg5 .}) 13... Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] The best way to develop. The bishop can go to [c6] next.} 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. h5 (15. h5 {White intends h6 with good play. Black can't prevent it as this nice sample line shows:} h6 $2 16. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 17. Qg4+ Kh8 18. Bxd5 exd5 19. Qxd7 {and wins.}) *

