1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose as an alternative against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... cxd4 {A popular exchange.} 5. exd4 {This position could come from a Caro-Kann. The way to approach it is that what we have on the board is the so-called Carlsbad structure from the Queen's Gambit with colours reversed. If you already - and why shouldn't you? - play the QGD with Black you will immediately realize that this is a very pleasant version of the line. There is no real pressure on White's position and the bishop will get to [f4] with easy play. That said, of course, the psychology is different whether you play White or Black. Here it is important to play the position, not the result! By that, I mean that usually when playing White, you are educated to search for an advantage in all lines. In this case, however, you should be happy that you have an easy game. Maybe Black can equalize theoretically, but from a practical point of view, we have nothing to complain about.} Qc7 {[%csl Gf4] Which tries to stop us from playing [Bf4]. It should be met by...} 6. g3 $1 {[%cal Gc1f4] Next we play [Bf4].} Bg4 7. Bf4 {Nobody has dared to play this. True, at first this might look like a mistake.} Qb6 {Attacking [b2]; and because of the pressure on [Nf3] we can't respond with the natural [Qb3].} 8. Nbd2 $1 {The point. If Black makes a neutral move like [e7]-[e6] or [Nc6] we have time to play [Qb3] with a nice position. The critical must be to take the bait.} Qxb2 9. Rb1 Qxc3 ({After} 9... Qxa2 10. Rxb7 Nbd7 11. Bb5 {, Black will never get out of it.}) 10. Rxb7 ({The most natural. The engine actually also likes} 10. Bb5+ Nbd7 11. O-O {but I am no computer, and the pawn on [b7] was just such a temptation!}) 10... Nbd7 11. h3 $1 {A little surprise. The position is extremely concrete and precision is needed.} Bxf3 ({After} 11... Bh5 12. Bb5 {wins for White. The black bishop is offside on [h5].}) 12. Qxf3 {White even offers a queen exchange.} Qc1+ (12... Qxf3 13. Nxf3 {is worse and 12...Qc6 13.Qb3 is too dangerous.}) ({Pawn grapping with} 12... Qxd4 {is asking for too much. After} 13. Nb3 Qb2 14. Bb5 {Black is completely busted.}) 13. Qd1 Qxd1+ 14. Kxd1 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gf1b5] White has great play for the pawn with the rook strongly placed on the seventh rank. White threatens [Bb5].} a6 15. Bd3 {[%csl Ge8][%cal Gd1e2,Gh1c1,Gd3c2,Gc2a4] White is close to winning. The bishop can come to [a4] and after [Ke2] the last rook joins the battle.} *

