1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... e6 {The safest move and also the most played. Black simply protects the [c5]-pawn.} 5. Bd3 {The natural move.} (5. Nbd2 {will probably transpose after} Nc6 {.}) (5. Be2 {contains a small finesse. In certain lines, the bishop won't be exposed} Nc6 6. O-O {(played several times by Keymer. The idea is still to meet)} Bd6 {with} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 Bd6 {, and now either} 9. Nbd2 {or 9.Bb2 , I prefer the bishop on the more active [d3]-square.}) 5... Nbd7 (5... Nbd7 {This is more clumsy. The point is that the common} 6. dxc5 {can now be met by} Nxc5 {. However, in other lines, the black knight is not so well placed on [d7]. White has a very straightforward plan.}) 6. Nbd2 b6 {Developing the queenside first is a decent alternative.} 7. O-O Bb7 8. Qe2 {[%cal Ge3e4]} Ne4 {Otherwise White push [e3]-[e4].} 9. c4 {White must play active and try to use the lead in development.} ({The line} 9. Ne5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 a6 $1 {, stopping [Bb5]+, has scored excellent for Black. In fact, the position is highly unclear!}) 9... Nxd2 10. Bxd2 dxc4 {Is positionally sound, but White has the initiative.} 11. Bxc4 a6 {Intending [b6]-[b5].} 12. Rfd1 b5 13. Bd3 c4 {Black should keep the position closed.} 14. Bc2 Be7 15. b3 {[%csl Gc4] The [c4]-pawn is also a target.} ({Note that} 15. e4 {also looks quite good.}) 15... cxb3 16. axb3 O-O 17. e4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] White is better with the strong centre.} *

