on} 6. dxc5 {can now be met by} Nxc5 {. However, in other lines, the black knight is not so well placed on [d7]. White has a very straightforward plan.}) 6. Nbd2 b6 {Developing the queenside first is a decent alternative.} 7. O-O Bb7 8. Qe2 {[%cal Ge3e4]} Ne4 {Otherwise White push [e3]-[e4].} 9. c4 {White must play active and try to use the lead in development.} ({The line} 9. Ne5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 a6 $1 {, stopping [Bb5]+, has scored excellent for Black. In fact, the position is highly unclear!}) 9... Bd6 {The best.} 10. cxd5 ({Keeping the tension is also possible} 10. b3 O-O 11. Bb2 {, but Black is fine here.}) 10... exd5 11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 {White has good coordination.} Qe7 ({Probably} 12... a6 {weakens more tan it helps. White can centralize the rooks or even consider} 13. Ne5 $5 {with interesting play.}) 13. Ba6 $1 Bxa6 14. Qxa6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Bd4c5,Bb2h8] The exchange of the light-squared bishops has left the [d5]-pawn somewhat exposed, but basically the position is balanced. I think White has the easiest play in a practical game. It is nice that we can decide when to play [dxc5] and open up for [Bb2].} *

