1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... e6 {The safest move and also the most played. Black simply protects the [c5]-pawn.} 5. Bd3 {The natural move.} (5. Nbd2 {will probably transpose after} Nc6 {.}) (5. Be2 {contains a small finesse. In certain lines, the bishop won't be exposed} Nc6 6. O-O {(played several times by Keymer. The idea is still to meet)} Bd6 {with} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 Bd6 {, and now either} 9. Nbd2 {or 9.Bb2 , I prefer the bishop on the more active [d3]-square.}) 5... Nbd7 (5... Nbd7 {This is more clumsy. The point is that the common} 6. dxc5 {can now be met by} Nxc5 {. However, in other lines, the black knight is not so well placed on [d7]. White has a very straightforward plan.}) 6. Nbd2 Bd6 {The typical move. The bishop is good here.} ({On} 6... Be7 {we play} 7. O-O O-O 8. Qe2 {, intending [e3]-[e4] with good play.}) 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 $1 {[%cal Ge3e4] White wants to push [e3]-[e4].} Qc7 ({Or} 8... e5 9. e4 $1) 9. e4 $1 {White has the initiative.} cxd4 {Giving White an isolated pawn.} 10. cxd4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Rxe4 $1 {Again this promising rook lift.} Nf6 13. Rh4 g6 (13... h6 {invites} 14. Bxh6 $1 {with a crushing attack.}) 14. Bh6 {White develops with tempo.} Re8 15. Rc1 {And again.} Qa5 16. Bd2 $1 {Forcing the black queen to go to a bad square.} Qd5 ({The line} 16... Qd8 17. Bg5 Be7 18. Ne5 {is also terrible.}) 17. Bg5 {White had a decisive attack in Sheers-Rosenthal, email 2016. See the Model Games for the spectacular finish.} *

