1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... e6 {The safest move and also the most played. Black simply protects the [c5]-pawn.} 5. Bd3 {The natural move.} (5. Nbd2 {will probably transpose after} Nc6 {.}) (5. Be2 {contains a small finesse. In certain lines, the bishop won't be exposed} Nc6 6. O-O {(played several times by Keymer. The idea is still to meet)} Bd6 {with} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 Bd6 {, and now either} 9. Nbd2 {or 9.Bb2 , I prefer the bishop on the more active [d3]-square.}) 5... Be7 {This looks somewhat passive compared to [Bd6], but of course, it is a fine move.} (5... Bd6 {should transpose to 5...Nc6 (here or) 5...Nbd7 (here. After ) 6.Nbd2 O-O 7.O-O Black should play one of the knight moves.}) 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. O-O (7. O-O {Here} Nc6 {or 7...Nbd7 transpose elsewhere, but Black might try:}) 7... b6 {We meet it in standard fashion.} 8. e4 ({White can also play the non-commital} 8. b3 Bb7 9. Bb2 {with a very harmonious position.}) 8... Ba6 {The point of Black's play. With the knight still on [b8] this is legal.} 9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. e5 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5] Gaining space.} Nd7 (10... Ne4 11. Qe2 Nxd2 12. Bxd2 { is pleasant for White.}) 11. Ne1 $1 {[%cal Ge1d3,Gd1g4,Gf2f4] A really nice move. The knight will be great on [d3] and the move also prepares [f2]-[f4] or even [Qg4]. Objectively speaking, Black is probably fine, but White has some initiative.} *

