1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... e6 {The safest move and also the most played. Black simply protects the [c5]-pawn.} 5. Bd3 {The natural move.} (5. Nbd2 {will probably transpose after} Nc6 {.}) (5. Be2 {contains a small finesse. In certain lines, the bishop won't be exposed} Nc6 6. O-O {(played several times by Keymer. The idea is still to meet)} Bd6 {with} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 Bd6 {, and now either} 9. Nbd2 {or 9.Bb2 , I prefer the bishop on the more active [d3]-square.}) 5... c4 {Closing the position can hardly be recommended. It is not so bad though!} 6. Bc2 Bd6 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. b3 {[%csl Gc4] Looks good for White because...} b5 {...is strongly met by...} 9. bxc4 bxc4 10. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5] With a big advantage. If Black takes on [e4], the [c4]-pawn is weak afterwards; and if Black doesn't take, then we will push [e4]-[e5].} *

