1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... e6 {The safest move and also the most played. Black simply protects the [c5]-pawn.} 5. Bd3 {The natural move.} (5. Nbd2 {will probably transpose after} Nc6 {.}) (5. Be2 {contains a small finesse. In certain lines, the bishop won't be exposed} Nc6 6. O-O {(played several times by Keymer. The idea is still to meet)} Bd6 {with} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 Bd6 {, and now either} 9. Nbd2 {or 9.Bb2 , I prefer the bishop on the more active [d3]-square.}) 5... c4 {Closing the position can hardly be recommended. It is not so bad though!} 6. Bc2 b5 7. Nbd2 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Re1 Ne4 {This is the idea.} (9... Be7 10. e4 {is pleasant for White and 9...Bd6 brings us back into the mainline.}) 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Nd2 f5 {This is most likely a better version than the same position with the bishop on [d6].} 12. a4 ({White can also try the less forcing} 12. Qh5+ $5 g6 13. Qh3 {with interesting play.}) 12... b4 {This is the difference. After [Nxc4] the bishop doesn't hang.} 13. Nxc4 Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c4,Gc8c3] Attacking the knight. Black will win the pawn back, but there will be a price to pay.} 14. Bb3 Bd5 15. Ne5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 bxc3 17. bxc3 Rxc3 ({Natural to recapture the pawn. Safer was} 17... Kf7 $5 {, and according to the engine, Black has decent compensation.}) 18. Bxd5 Qxd5 19. Qxd5 exd5 20. Rb1 {[%cal Gb1b8,Gb1b7] And White has strong pressure in the ending. The white rook will penetrate Black's position.} *

