1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... e6 {The safest move and also the most played. Black simply protects the [c5]-pawn.} 5. Bd3 {The natural move.} (5. Nbd2 {will probably transpose after} Nc6 {.}) (5. Be2 {contains a small finesse. In certain lines, the bishop won't be exposed} Nc6 6. O-O {(played several times by Keymer. The idea is still to meet)} Bd6 {with} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 Bd6 {, and now either} 9. Nbd2 {or 9.Bb2 , I prefer the bishop on the more active [d3]-square.}) 5... b6 6. Nbd2 Bb7 7. O-O Be7 ({The most played move is} 7... Nbd7 {which transposes to 5...[Nbd7]. Black could also play 7...Bd6 which we will meet in the same way as [Be7] 8.Re1 , followed by [e3]-[e4]. When the position opens up, the bishop is better placed on [e7].}) 8. Re1 {[%cal Ge3e4]} ({White can also go for a kind os Stonewall setup with} 8. Ne5 {, followed by [f2]-[f4]. In general, I like to break with [e3]-[e4].}) 8... O-O ({Black could prevent the central break with} 8... Ne4 {but then White can switch to} 9. c4 O-O 10. cxd5 exd5 11. b3 {, followed by 12. [Bb2] with a harmonious position. It is probably balanced, but personally, I would take White.}) 9. e4 cxd4 ({After} 9... dxe4 10. Nxe4 {Black should probably take on [d4] anyway, which will transpose.}) 10. Nxd4 {We don't want to end up with an IQP.} dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nbd7 {The position is balanced. We come across many similar versions of this structure during my Colle-repertoire, because I more or less always try to get [e3]-[e4] in. Although objectively equal, I think White has good practical chances with the pawn majority on the queenside. A good starting move is probably the flexible...} 12. Qe2 {We don't mind that a few pieces disappear from the board, because the chances on the queenside remain and are even bigger in an ending.} *

