the king to safety before we start real action. Possible is} 6. Nbd2 {intending to meet} Bd6 {with the immediate} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 {, but I prefer castling first.}) 6... b6 {Black tries to fix the queenside.} ({After} 6... c4 7. Bc2 {is rather similar to 5...c4 . White will play [Nbd2] and play for [e3]-[e4] and/or attack the black queenside with moves like [a2]-[a4] and [b2]-[b3].}) 7. Nbd2 Bb7 8. Re1 {[%cal Ge3e4] Preparing [e3]-[e4].} Be7 9. dxc5 {An important exchange. No matter how Black takes back, White can move forward.} bxc5 10. e4 {[%cal Ge4d5,Ge4e5] Objectively the position is probably balanced, at least that is what the engine says! But White has the dynamic possibilities either to take on [d5] or play [e4]-[e5], which is a big practical advantage.} O-O 11. e5 ({This is the move we really would like to play. Also good is} 11. exd5 {, so I will give that as a more positional alternative.}) 11... Nd7 12. Nf1 {Opening for the bishop.} Qb6 {An active move.} ({The line} 12... Qc7 13. Bf4 {must be fine for White .}) 13. Bc2 {[%csl Gh7][%cal Gd1d3] Preparing [Qd3].} d4 ({Or} 13... Ba6 {, then I suggest} 14. Ng3 {just to avoid any [Bxf1] ideas. We need as many pieces as possible to attack.}) 14. Qd3 {It is important to create a weakness in Black's shelter.} g6 15. Bh6 {Using the new square.} Rfd8 16. Rab1 Qc7 17. Qe2 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4][%cal Gf1d2,Gc2d3,Gh2h4] This was seen in an email game, which ended in a draw. The position is very complicated and both sides have chances. White can make small improvements like [N1d2] and [Bd3] with good control over [c4] and [e4] and the h-pawn can always move forward.} *

