1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... e6 {The safest move and also the most played. Black simply protects the [c5]-pawn.} 5. Bd3 {The natural move.} (5. Nbd2 {will probably transpose after} Nc6 {.}) (5. Be2 {contains a small finesse. In certain lines, the bishop won't be exposed} Nc6 6. O-O {(played several times by Keymer. The idea is still to meet)} Bd6 {with} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 Bd6 {, and now either} 9. Nbd2 {or 9.Bb2 , I prefer the bishop on the more active [d3]-square.}) 5... Nc6 {Black also plays the most natural.} 6. O-O ({I like to get the king to safety before we start real action. Possible is} 6. Nbd2 {intending to meet} Bd6 {with the immediate} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 {, but I prefer castling first.}) 6... b6 {Black tries to fix the queenside.} ({After} 6... c4 7. Bc2 {is rather similar to 5...c4 . White will play [Nbd2] and play for [e3]-[e4] and/or attack the black queenside with moves like [a2]-[a4] and [b2]-[b3].}) 7. Nbd2 Bb7 8. Re1 {[%cal Ge3e4] Preparing [e3]-[e4].} Be7 9. dxc5 {An important exchange. No matter how Black takes back, White can move forward.} bxc5 10. e4 {[%cal Ge4d5,Ge4e5] Objectively the position is probably balanced, at least that is what the engine says! But White has the dynamic possibilities either to take on [d5] or play [e4]-[e5], which is a big practical advantage.} O-O 11. exd5 exd5 ({• The trade} 11... Qxd5 {gives Black a very active queen, but also a weak pawn structure on the queenside.} 12. Qc2 Rfd8 13. Bf1 {White has consolidated and can continue with [Nc4] or [Ne4] with some advantage. In an email game, Black immediately came in trouble after the careless} Rab8 $6 14. Nc4 {, followed by [Bf4] with great piece play.}) ({• The following line} 11... Nxd5 12. Nc4 {is nice for White with the super square for the knight on [c4].}) 12. Nf1 Re8 {This was Kovacevic-Spassky, Bugojno 1984.} 13. Bf4 {[%csl Gd5,Gf5][%cal Gf1e3] In the game White played [Ng3], but this is stronger. Next the knight might go to [e3] with some pressure. White is more comfortable.} *

