1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... e6 {The safest move and also the most played. Black simply protects the [c5]-pawn.} 5. Bd3 {The natural move.} (5. Nbd2 {will probably transpose after} Nc6 {.}) (5. Be2 {contains a small finesse. In certain lines, the bishop won't be exposed} Nc6 6. O-O {(played several times by Keymer. The idea is still to meet)} Bd6 {with} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 Bd6 {, and now either} 9. Nbd2 {or 9.Bb2 , I prefer the bishop on the more active [d3]-square.}) 5... Nc6 {Black also plays the most natural.} 6. O-O ({I like to get the king to safety before we start real action. Possible is} 6. Nbd2 {intending to meet} Bd6 {with the immediate} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 {, but I prefer castling first.}) 6... Bd6 {Now it will be a Meran with an extra tempo for White. Usually, the position comes from the Semi-Slav: 1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 e6 5.e3 Nbd7 6.Bd3 . Also the so-called Anti-Meran move 6.Qc2 is very popular, so let's check the equivalent move here as well.} 7. Nbd2 e5 {A thematic move, of course, but creating such infight in the centre with the king still on [e8] can't be recommended.} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. e4 {The typical way to meet such [e5]-ideas: take on [c5] and play [e3]-[e4] yourself.} dxe4 {Black tries to simplify.} 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge4c6] Even the ending is not so simple for Black. To begin with [Bxc6]+ and [Nxe5] is threatened.} f6 13. b4 {White needs to play active. Taking the initiative is alpha and omega. If Black gets time all problems can quickly be solved.} Bb6 ({Safer is} 13... Be7 {, but White is still having a rather pleasant endgame after} 14. a4 {.}) 14. a4 $1 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Ga4a5] Using the black bishop as a target.} a6 15. a5 Ba7 ({After} 15... Bc7 16. Be3 {, and White has a big edge.}) 16. b5 $1 {A strong engine novelty. White sacrifices a pawn for long-term compensation.} (16. Ba3 {, preventing short castling can't be bad either, for instance,} Kf7 17. Nd2 {, and White is better.}) 16... axb5 17. a6 $1 {The point. Black is tied up to the defence of the queenside.} O-O 18. Bd5+ Kh8 19. Ba3 Re8 20. Nd2 (20. Nd2 {Black can hardly move. The best play goes something like this:} Bb8 21. Bc5 Bc7 22. Nf1 e4 23. Ne3 Be5 24. Ra3 f5 25. a7 {, and White is strategically winning according to computer.}) *

