the king to safety before we start real action. Possible is} 6. Nbd2 {intending to meet} Bd6 {with the immediate} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 {, but I prefer castling first.}) 6... Bd6 {Now it will be a Meran with an extra tempo for White. Usually, the position comes from the Semi-Slav: 1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 e6 5.e3 Nbd7 6.Bd3 . Also the so-called Anti-Meran move 6.Qc2 is very popular, so let's check the equivalent move here as well.} 7. Nbd2 e5 {A thematic move, of course, but creating such infight in the centre with the king still on [e8] can't be recommended.} 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. e4 {The typical way to meet such [e5]-ideas: take on [c5] and play [e3]-[e4] yourself.} O-O 10. exd5 {White opens the position and plays for initiative. Positionally Black is doing ok, so we have to create some threats!} Qxd5 {The black queen is exposed here.} 11. Qc2 ({We have a choice:} 11. Qe2 Bg4 12. Ne4 {is also good.}) 11... Bg4 ({Black has also tried} 11... h6 {but the simple} 12. b4 Bb6 13. Ne4 {looks good for White.}) 12. Ne4 $1 Bxf3 13. gxf3 {White has scored impressive 6/6 from this position! This shows that it is really difficult to handle for Black.} Kh8 {The relatively best.} 14. c4 {Winning a piece.} Qd7 $2 15. Nxc5 Qh3 {Black's attack can easily be refuted.} 16. Bf5 Qxf3 17. Qd3 {It was over in Narciso Dublan-Barczay, Budapest 2001.} *

