1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... e6 {The safest move and also the most played. Black simply protects the [c5]-pawn.} 5. Bd3 {The natural move.} (5. Nbd2 {will probably transpose after} Nc6 {.}) (5. Be2 {contains a small finesse. In certain lines, the bishop won't be exposed} Nc6 6. O-O {(played several times by Keymer. The idea is still to meet)} Bd6 {with} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 Bd6 {, and now either} 9. Nbd2 {or 9.Bb2 , I prefer the bishop on the more active [d3]-square.}) 5... Nc6 {Black also plays the most natural.} 6. O-O ({I like to get the king to safety before we start real action. Possible is} 6. Nbd2 {intending to meet} Bd6 {with the immediate} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 {, but I prefer castling first.}) 6... Bd6 {Now it will be a Meran with an extra tempo for White. Usually, the position comes from the Semi-Slav: 1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 e6 5.e3 Nbd7 6.Bd3 . Also the so-called Anti-Meran move 6.Qc2 is very popular, so let's check the equivalent move here as well.} 7. Nbd2 O-O {The obvious move. Delaying castling is possible, but risky.} ({The move} 7... Qc7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 {transposes to 6...Qc7 .}) 8. dxc5 {The standard move in the Meran. White can also keep the tension with the interesting 8. [Qe2].} (8. Qe2 {, intending [e3]-[e4]. After the flexible response} Qc7 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. e4 {which leads to a position I have already mentioned. Black has several decent moves, but the most precise is} h6 {with a very complicated game with chances for both sides.}) (8. dxc5 {Even against c4!? Bc2} e5 $1 {I couldn't find any real advantage for White.}) 8... Bxc5 9. b4 {White continues with the normal Semi-Slav play.} ({Both,} 9. e4 Qc7 {, and 9.Qe2 Qc7 have also been played a lot.}) 9... Be7 {This is safer, but more passive. Of course in a normal Semi-Slav Meran such moves would be regarded as unambitious, but with colours reversed, also the chess psychology is kind of reversed! It is fair to play pretty solid with Black and primarely try to equalize in the opening. It is up to White to prove an advantage, and that is often easier said than done.} 10. b5 ({The most forcing move, but not necessarily the best! I will give} 10. Bb2 {as a good alternative.}) 10... Na5 11. Bb2 {[%cal Gc3c4] White will try to get [c3]-[c4] in.} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] Black should focus on development. The light-squared bishop will be happy on [b7].} (11... Qc7 {has been played to try to slow down the c4 break, but White can play it anyway. 12.c4! N dxc4 13.Rc1 , followed by [Nxc4]. Maybe Black can survive with 13...a6! 14.Nxc4 axb5 15.Nce5 Nc6 16.Bxb5 Rxa2 17.Qb3 Ra8 White regains the pawn and has some initiative, but the position is simplified.}) 12. Qe2 {[%csl Gc4] Developing and keeping control over [c4].} Bb7 13. Rfd1 Rc8 ({The regrouping} 13... Nd7 {should be met by} 14. Nb3 $1 {N} Nxb3 15. axb3 Nc5 16. Bc2 {, and White is slightly better. The [c6]-square could be interesting later on.}) 14. c4 dxc4 15. Nxc4 Nxc4 16. Bxc4 Qc7 (16... Bd6 {looks more risky at first, but Black can put the queen on [e7] with an ok position.}) 17. Rac1 Qb8 18. Ne5 {White has a slight initiative, although the position is more or less balanced.} *

