the king to safety before we start real action. Possible is} 6. Nbd2 {intending to meet} Bd6 {with the immediate} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 {, but I prefer castling first.}) 6... Bd6 {Now it will be a Meran with an extra tempo for White. Usually, the position comes from the Semi-Slav: 1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 e6 5.e3 Nbd7 6.Bd3 . Also the so-called Anti-Meran move 6.Qc2 is very popular, so let's check the equivalent move here as well.} 7. Nbd2 O-O {The obvious move. Delaying castling is possible, but risky.} ({The move} 7... Qc7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 {transposes to 6...Qc7 .}) 8. dxc5 {The standard move in the Meran. White can also keep the tension with the interesting 8. [Qe2].} (8. Qe2 {, intending [e3]-[e4]. After the flexible response} Qc7 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. e4 {which leads to a position I have already mentioned. Black has several decent moves, but the most precise is} h6 {with a very complicated game with chances for both sides.}) (8. dxc5 {Even against c4!? Bc2} e5 $1 {I couldn't find any real advantage for White.}) 8... Bxc5 9. b4 {White continues with the normal Semi-Slav play.} ({Both,} 9. e4 Qc7 {, and 9.Qe2 Qc7 have also been played a lot.}) 9... Be7 {This is safer, but more passive. Of course in a normal Semi-Slav Meran such moves would be regarded as unambitious, but with colours reversed, also the chess psychology is kind of reversed! It is fair to play pretty solid with Black and primarely try to equalize in the opening. It is up to White to prove an advantage, and that is often easier said than done.} 10. Bb2 e5 {The most played.} ({• A sensible move is} 10... b6 {, preparing [Bb7]. It gives White time to fulfill a nice positional plan.} 11. a3 Bb7 12. c4 {. Suddenly White has a very harmonious position and is very comfortable. It may not look as much, but such positions are hard to play for Black, while White has easy moves like [Qe2], [Rac1], and [Rfd1] to start with.}) ({•} 10... a6 {, stopping [b4]-[b5].} 11. a4 {, renewing the idea. ( White can also go for 11.a3 just intending [c4]. If Black responds 11...b5 , then after 12.a4 Rb8 play is pretty similar to the mainline. I think perhaps 11. [a4] is preferable, but it is good to know both ideas. ) The only move that has been played is} Bd7 12. b5 {this is in my opinion much better than 12. [e4], which so far has been the traditional response.} axb5 13. axb5 Na5 14. Qe2 Qc7 15. e4 {White has a good play. A sample line goes:} dxe4 16. Nxe4 Nb3 17. Rxa8 Rxa8 18. c4 {, and the white pieces are very active.}) {11...e5 12.e4 should be compared with the mainline 10...[e5]. 11...b6 is natural. Black prepares [Bb7]. 12.Qe2 , improving the queen slightly. It was also possible to play [b4]-[b5] at once. 12...Bb7 13.b5 the position gets simplified, but White keeps some pressure. 13...axb5 14.axb5 Na5 15.c4 this is necessary to open the long diagonal for [Bb2]. 15...dxc4 16.Nxc4 Nxc4 17.Bxc4 Rxa1 18.Rxa1 Qc7 . After a more or less forced sequence, it is time to take stock. The position is balanced, but the extra space on the queenside gives White some hope. Also, [b6] is potentially much weaker than [b5]. All in all, not much but something! Play can continue: 19.Rc1 Rc8 20.Qd1 Qb8 21.Nd4 , and the game goes on.} 11. e4 {This confrontation in the centre always happens whenever Black goes [e5].} Bg4 ({Pinning the knight is a very active attempt to solve all problems. After} 11... dxe4 12. Nxe4 {White has good piece play.}) 12. h3 {Asking the bishop what it wants to do!} (12. Re1 {is also fine.}) 12... Bh5 (12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 d4 {the only way to justify [Bxf3].} 14. a3 {, protecting the [b4]-pawn. After} a5 $5 15. Nc4 {the position is balanced. Still, after some simplification like} dxc3 16. Bxc3 axb4 17. axb4 Bxb4 18. Rxa8 Qxa8 19. Bxe5 Nxe5 20. Nxe5 Re8 21. Rb1 {White can continue to play.}) 13. Re1 d4 {Here White has an interesting option.} 14. Bc4 {The bishop is very strong here.} dxc3 ({Black has to try to destroy the white structure.} 14... Rc8 15. Qb3 {is good for White.}) 15. Bxc3 Bxb4 16. Bxb4 Nxb4 ({No better is} 16... Bxf3 17. Nxf3 Nxb4 18. Nxe5 {with pressure on [f7].}) 17. g4 Bg6 18. Nxe5 {White keeps the best chances in a complex postion, that is hard to play for both sides.} *

