the king to safety before we start real action. Possible is} 6. Nbd2 {intending to meet} Bd6 {with the immediate} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 {, but I prefer castling first.}) 6... Bd6 {Now it will be a Meran with an extra tempo for White. Usually, the position comes from the Semi-Slav: 1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 e6 5.e3 Nbd7 6.Bd3 . Also the so-called Anti-Meran move 6.Qc2 is very popular, so let's check the equivalent move here as well.} 7. Nbd2 O-O {The obvious move. Delaying castling is possible, but risky.} ({The move} 7... Qc7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 {transposes to 6...Qc7 .}) 8. dxc5 {The standard move in the Meran. White can also keep the tension with the interesting 8. [Qe2].} (8. Qe2 {, intending [e3]-[e4]. After the flexible response} Qc7 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. e4 {which leads to a position I have already mentioned. Black has several decent moves, but the most precise is} h6 {with a very complicated game with chances for both sides.}) (8. dxc5 {Even against c4!? Bc2} e5 $1 {I couldn't find any real advantage for White.}) 8... Bxc5 9. b4 {White continues with the normal Semi-Slav play.} ({Both,} 9. e4 Qc7 {, and 9.Qe2 Qc7 have also been played a lot.}) 9... Bd6 {The Meran move.} 10. Bb2 {The natural follow-up to [dxc5] and [b2]-[b4], but as we have seen already the direct [b4]-[b5] is always worth a thought or two.} ({The position after} 10. b5 Na5 {(10...Ne5 11.Nxe5 Bxe5 12.Bb2 Qe7 is also ok for Black. )} 11. c4 dxc4 12. Nxc4 Nxc4 13. Bxc4 e5 {has been tested in some email games, but White could maybe try the new move} 14. h3 {N. If} e4 {, then} 15. Nd2 $1 {with an exciting position. The white bishop will be superb on [b2]. Still, the game seems balanced to me.}) {14...Qe7 15.Bb2 is maybe a tad better for White.} 10... b6 11. a3 ({This is what I played. White can also try} 11. Rc1 {after the following more or less forced moves} Bb7 12. b5 Ne5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Nf3 Bd6 15. c4 dxc4 16. Rxc4 $5 e5 {an interesting position arises. White can try:} 17. Ng5 $1 {(17.Bxe5 Bxf3! equalizes. )} h6 18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 Bxe4 20. Rxe4 Qe7 21. Qb3 {White has some play on the light squares and the better bishop. Still, the engine calls it 0.00.}) 11... a5 {Played by Caruana.} 12. b5 Ne5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Nf3 {White needs to get [c3]-[c4] in.} ({Playing with the pawn,} 14. f4 Bd6 15. c4 {, is the other way to do it. However, after} Bb7 {Black looks fine. In general, I don't like to move my f-pawn if it isn't necessary.}) 14... Bd6 15. c4 dxc4 16. Bxf6 $5 ({Black had no problems after} 16. Bxc4 Bb7 {= in Bluebaum-Caruana, rapid 2024.}) 16... gxf6 ({Not} 16... Qxf6 $2 17. Be4 {and wins.}) 17. Be4 {The best chance.} (17. Bxc4 Bb7 {= this is too easy for Black.}) 17... Ra7 18. Qc2 f5 19. Bc6 {[%csl Gc4] White will regain the pawn and have some chances. After all, Black's structure is somewhat weakened and White has some potential on the light squares. Again, the computer claims that it is just equal. By now, we are getting used to it!} *

