 {. In this case, Black can force the play with dxe4} 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 f5 15. Bxd5+ Kh8 {, followed by [e5]-[e4] with good counterplay.}) 12... Be6 13. Rc1 {[%cal Gc4c5,Gb4b5] White keeps the tension. Both [c4]-[c5] and [b4]-[b5] is constantly in the air.} Rad8 14. c5 ({White can also play more controlled with} 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. Qc2 a6 {( If 15...h6 , then 16.b5 . )} 16. Ng5 h6 17. Nge4 {With a small positional edge.}) 14... Bb8 15. b5 e4 {Black must seek counterplay.} (15... Na5 {drops the e-pawn.}) 16. bxc6 bxc6 {Black doesn't need to hurry with taking on [d3] or [f3]. The piece is not running away.} 17. Nd4 Qc7 {[%csl Gh2] Only move.} ({After the forced continuation, this is more or less strategically winning for White:} 17... exd3 18. Nxc6 Qc7 19. Nxb8 Rxb8 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. Nb3 Bf5 22. Nd4 {}) 18. f4 $1 exd3 19. Nxe6 fxe6 20. Nf3 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gd1d3,Gb2g7] White will take the [d3]-pawn next and enjoy a nice bishop on [b2].} *

