ck equalizes.}) 11... e5 12. e4 ({White can even try} 12. c4 $5 e4 13. Bxf6 $1 gxf6 {( Not 13...Qxf6 14.Bxe4  )} 14. cxd5 exf3 15. dxc6 fxg2 16. Re1 Bxh2+ $1 {(16...bxc6 17.Ne4  )} 17. Kxh2 Qxd3 18. Qf3 {this has been played in an email game. Black should probably play the safe [Qd6]+ and take on [c6] with the queen, although White keeps some chances even in the ending. Grabbing the knight loses:} Qxd2 $2 19. Qxg2+ Kh8 20. Rg1 $1 Bg4 21. cxb7 $1 Rab8 22. Qxg4 Qd6+ 23. f4 Rg8 24. Rad1 $1 Qc7 25. Qf5 {.}) 12... dxe4 {Black tries to solve all problems with some forcing moves, but there is a problem!} 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 f5 15. Bd5+ Kh8 16. h4 {[%cal Gf3g5] Threatening [Ng5].} ({Also possible is} 16. c4 e4 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Qd4 Qe7 {. This was played in a blitz game, where White went for [Ne5]. A rook to [d1] first seems to give good winning chances, for instance:} 19. Rfd1 $1 Bc7 20. Ne5 Bxe5 21. Qxe5 Qxe5 22. Bxe5 Be6 23. Rd6 Bxc4 24. Rxc6 {, and White can keep pressing for a long time in this ending.}) 16... h6 17. Ng5 $1 {Anyway!} Qf6 ({The knight can't be taken:} 17... hxg5 18. Qh5#) 18. Qh5 Bd7 19. Nf7+ Kh7 20. Nxd6 Qxd6 21. c4 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gd1d7] Next comes [Rad1] with a promising position.} *

