the king to safety before we start real action. Possible is} 6. Nbd2 {intending to meet} Bd6 {with the immediate} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 {, but I prefer castling first.}) 6... Bd6 {Now it will be a Meran with an extra tempo for White. Usually, the position comes from the Semi-Slav: 1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 e6 5.e3 Nbd7 6.Bd3 . Also the so-called Anti-Meran move 6.Qc2 is very popular, so let's check the equivalent move here as well.} 7. Nbd2 O-O {The obvious move. Delaying castling is possible, but risky.} ({The move} 7... Qc7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 {transposes to 6...Qc7 .}) 8. dxc5 {The standard move in the Meran. White can also keep the tension with the interesting 8. [Qe2].} (8. Qe2 {, intending [e3]-[e4]. After the flexible response} Qc7 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. e4 {which leads to a position I have already mentioned. Black has several decent moves, but the most precise is} h6 {with a very complicated game with chances for both sides.}) (8. dxc5 {Even against c4!? Bc2} e5 $1 {I couldn't find any real advantage for White.}) 8... Bxc5 9. b4 {White continues with the normal Semi-Slav play.} ({Both,} 9. e4 Qc7 {, and 9.Qe2 Qc7 have also been played a lot.}) 9... Bd6 {The Meran move.} 10. Bb2 {The natural follow-up to [dxc5] and [b2]-[b4], but as we have seen already the direct [b4]-[b5] is always worth a thought or two.} ({The position after} 10. b5 Na5 {(10...Ne5 11.Nxe5 Bxe5 12.Bb2 Qe7 is also ok for Black. )} 11. c4 dxc4 12. Nxc4 Nxc4 13. Bxc4 e5 {has been tested in some email games, but White could maybe try the new move} 14. h3 {N. If} e4 {, then} 15. Nd2 $1 {with an exciting position. The white bishop will be superb on [b2]. Still, the game seems balanced to me.}) {14...Qe7 15.Bb2 is maybe a tad better for White.} 10... a6 {Preventing [b4]-[b5] for the time being.} 11. a3 {[%cal Gc3c4] Preparing [c3]-[c4].} ({The active} 11. a4 {can be met by} e5 {N} 12. e4 dxe4 {(12...Be6!?)} 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 h6 {, a good prophylactic move.} 15. b5 Na5 16. Bd5 Qe7 17. c4 Be6 {, and Black equalizes.}) 11... e5 12. e4 ({White can even try} 12. c4 $5 e4 13. Bxf6 $1 gxf6 {( Not 13...Qxf6 14.Bxe4  )} 14. cxd5 exf3 15. dxc6 fxg2 16. Re1 Bxh2+ $1 {(16...bxc6 17.Ne4  )} 17. Kxh2 Qxd3 18. Qf3 {this has been played in an email game. Black should probably play the safe [Qd6]+ and take on [c6] with the queen, although White keeps some chances even in the ending. Grabbing the knight loses:} Qxd2 $2 19. Qxg2+ Kh8 20. Rg1 $1 Bg4 21. cxb7 $1 Rab8 22. Qxg4 Qd6+ 23. f4 Rg8 24. Rad1 $1 Qc7 25. Qf5 {.}) 12... Bg4 13. h3 Bh5 ({The trade} 13... Bxf3 14. Qxf3 {is nice for White with strong play on the light squares.}) 14. c4 {A nice strike that asks some questions that Black needs to answer.} ({Also possible is} 14. exd5 Nxd5 {, but it's not convincing.}) 14... dxe4 {Simplifying is not good.} 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd1b3,Ga1d1] The bishop is extremely strong on [e4]. White can continue with [Qb3], getting out of the pin, and then put a rook on [d1] with a nice position.} *

