ck equalizes.}) 11... b5 {Black stops White's [c4]-plan, but the [b5]-pawn will be a target.} 12. a4 $1 {[%csl Gb5] Hitting [b5].} Rb8 (12... bxa4 13. Rxa4 {leaves Black with a very weak [a6]-pawn.}) 13. axb5 {Fixing the weakness on [b5].} ({White can also play without taking on b5 first:} 13. Qe2 $5 Qb6 14. e4 {with similar play as we will see in the mainline.}) 13... axb5 14. Qe2 {[%csl Gb5]} ({Hitting the target one more time and forcing the black queen to take up a defensive role. White could also change the pawn structure completely with} 14. Nd4 {, leading to some strategically complex middlegames. I will give Nd4 as an alternative.}) 14... Qb6 15. e4 $1 {[%cal Ge4e5] White starts playing in the centre while still putting pressure on [b5].} Nh5 {...is a radical way to resolve the tension with tactics.} 16. g3 Bxg3 17. hxg3 Nxg3 {This was Santos Latasa-Iniyan, rapid 2024. The precise} 18. Qd1 Nxf1 19. Qxf1 $16 {Would have been good for White. Soon the many white pieces will have a party going.} *

