1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 {A strong positional move. The game is now a Queen's Gambit with colours reversed.} 4. c3 {I suggest we go for a Semi-Slav setup. There are many alternatives though.} ({•} 4. Be2 {This has been quite popular lately. White just makes a natural move and clearly plays a QGD in the forehand with an extra tempo. Having made a Chessable course on the QGD for Black, of course, I find this idea very sympathetic, but probably not enough for an advantage.}) ({•} 4. dxc5 {White plays a Queen's Gambit Accepted! Also not a real try for an opening edge.}) ({•} 4. b3 {is interesting. White goes for the Zukertort setup, which I will propose against the absolute mainline 3...[e6]. Here, when the light-squared bishop is not locked behind a pawn on [e6], I am not so sure. Critical in my opinion is:} cxd4 5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4 {with a complex game with chances for both sides. Black can also refrain from taking on [d4] and just develop naturally with [Nc6] and [Bg4] when we have a kind of Tartakower QGD reversed.}) ({•} 4. Nbd2 $5 {is a mix of several ideas. White waits to determine the exact route. This gives Black time to decide and after the natural:} cxd4 5. exd4 {we are in the Exchange Caro-Kann! Black has several good ways to continue. All these lines are more or less balanced.}) ({• In the end, I settled for} 4. c3 {, but also here, I believe that Black can equalize with precise play. However, as we will see there are many ways to go wrong!}) 4... e6 {The safest move and also the most played. Black simply protects the [c5]-pawn.} 5. Bd3 {The natural move.} (5. Nbd2 {will probably transpose after} Nc6 {.}) (5. Be2 {contains a small finesse. In certain lines, the bishop won't be exposed} Nc6 6. O-O {(played several times by Keymer. The idea is still to meet)} Bd6 {with} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 Bd6 {, and now either} 9. Nbd2 {or 9.Bb2 , I prefer the bishop on the more active [d3]-square.}) 5... Nc6 {Black also plays the most natural.} 6. O-O ({I like to get the king to safety before we start real action. Possible is} 6. Nbd2 {intending to meet} Bd6 {with the immediate} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. b4 {, but I prefer castling first.}) 6... Bd6 {Now it will be a Meran with an extra tempo for White. Usually, the position comes from the Semi-Slav: 1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 e6 5.e3 Nbd7 6.Bd3 . Also the so-called Anti-Meran move 6.Qc2 is very popular, so let's check the equivalent move here as well.} 7. Nbd2 O-O {The obvious move. Delaying castling is possible, but risky.} ({The move} 7... Qc7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 {transposes to 6...Qc7 .}) 8. dxc5 {The standard move in the Meran. White can also keep the tension with the interesting 8. [Qe2].} (8. Qe2 {, intending [e3]-[e4]. After the flexible response} Qc7 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. e4 {which leads to a position I have already mentioned. Black has several decent moves, but the most precise is} h6 {with a very complicated game with chances for both sides.}) (8. dxc5 {Even against c4!? Bc2} e5 $1 {I couldn't find any real advantage for White.}) 8... Bxc5 9. b4 {White continues with the normal Semi-Slav play.} ({Both,} 9. e4 Qc7 {, and 9.Qe2 Qc7 have also been played a lot.}) 9... Bd6 {The Meran move.} 10. Bb2 {The natural follow-up to [dxc5] and [b2]-[b4], but as we have seen already the direct [b4]-[b5] is always worth a thought or two.} ({The position after} 10. b5 Na5 {(10...Ne5 11.Nxe5 Bxe5 12.Bb2 Qe7 is also ok for Black. )} 11. c4 dxc4 12. Nxc4 Nxc4 13. Bxc4 e5 {has been tested in some email games, but White could maybe try the new move} 14. h3 {N. If} e4 {, then} 15. Nd2 $1 {with an exciting position. The white bishop will be superb on [b2]. Still, the game seems balanced to me.}) {14...Qe7 15.Bb2 is maybe a tad better for White.} 10... a6 {Preventing [b4]-[b5] for the time being.} 11. a3 {[%cal Gc3c4] Preparing [c3]-[c4].} ({The active} 11. a4 {can be met by} e5 {N} 12. e4 dxe4 {(12...Be6!?)} 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 h6 {, a good prophylactic move.} 15. b5 Na5 16. Bd5 Qe7 17. c4 Be6 {, and Black equalizes.}) 11... b5 {Black stops White's [c4]-plan, but the [b5]-pawn will be a target.} 12. a4 $1 {[%csl Gb5] Hitting [b5].} Rb8 (12... bxa4 13. Rxa4 {leaves Black with a very weak [a6]-pawn.}) 13. axb5 {Fixing the weakness on [b5].} ({White can also play without taking on b5 first:} 13. Qe2 $5 Qb6 14. e4 {with similar play as we will see in the mainline.}) 13... axb5 14. Nd4 {[%cal Gd4b5,Gd4c6]} Nxd4 15. exd4 {A very interesting position. It is hard to judge, but it seems somewhat easier to play with White.} Qc7 {[%csl Gh2]} 16. h3 Re8 {The moves are not forced, of course, but very natural.} 17. Re1 ({The desireable} 17. Nf3 {loses some control over [e4], and can met by} Bd7 18. Re1 Ne4 $5 {a nice positional pawn sacrifice. If we accept, then after} 19. Bxe4 dxe4 20. Rxe4 Bc6 {Black has great play on the light squares.}) 17... Bd7 18. Nb3 {[%csl Gc5]} Ra8 {Fighting for the a-file.} ({•} 18... e5 {, seeking counterplay.} 19. dxe5 Bxe5 20. Nc5 {, threatening [Na6]. White might eliminate the [d7]-bishop and play against the weak [b5]-pawn with [Ra5].}) ({•} 18... Ne4 {this is not as strong as last time we saw it. Here White just ignores the knight.} 19. Qc2 Bc6 20. Nc5 {White is better. In the end, we will take on [e4] if we can exchange the light-squared bishops.}) 19. Rxa8 Rxa8 20. Nc5 {[%csl Gc5] The knight on [c5] is very annoying for Black. It is hardly ever good to take it.} Bc6 ({Bad is} 20... Bxc5 21. dxc5 $1 {If} e5 {, then} 22. Qe2 {, attacking [b5] and [e5].}) 21. Qe2 {[%csl Gb5] Attacking [b5].} Qb8 ({Or} 21... Ra2 22. Bb1 Ra8 23. Bc1 {with similar ideas as in the mainline.}) 22. Bc1 {White tries to improve the passive bishop. White is somewhat better, primarely because it is really hard for Black to come up with anything active.} *

