1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {This is by far the most played move and the significance even raises when you add 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 to the list, when it is also very common for Black to play [d5] in one of the following moves. Black focuses on sound development and intends to move the dark-squared bishop and castle.} 4. Bd3 {Other moves are possible, but this is what we do. The bishop is good here.} c5 {This is the most popular setup.} 5. c3 ({This takes us back to the 3...c5 chapter. It makes sense to play like this for the practical player. As we have seen, this reversed Semi-Slav contains a lot of interesting possibilities later on, and knowing it well will pay off. Still, I will offer the Zukertort-system with} 5. b3 {as an alternative. I mean, it is not like 4.c3 is just good for White in all lines. Black has several ways to get a more or less balanced game, so being able to play different set-ups after 3.e3 can only be an advantage.}) ({Please, notice that} 5. O-O $6 {is a serious inaccuracy. Black can get a good game by advancing on the queenside with tempo:} c4 $1 6. Be2 b5 7. b3 Bb7 {, and White can't break the black pawchain. If} 8. a4 {, then just} a6 {.}) *

