1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {This is by far the most played move and the significance even raises when you add 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 to the list, when it is also very common for Black to play [d5] in one of the following moves. Black focuses on sound development and intends to move the dark-squared bishop and castle.} 4. Bd3 {Other moves are possible, but this is what we do. The bishop is good here.} Bd6 {Imitating White. In general [d6] is a more active post for the bishop than [e7].} 5. Nbd2 Nbd7 6. O-O e5 {This is too hasty.} 7. e4 $1 {[%csl Ge8] A typical counterstrike in the centre. The black king would wish it was already on [g8].} dxe4 8. Nxe4 Nxe4 9. dxe5 {A nice improvement.} ({Also,} 9. Bxe4 exd4 10. Qxd4 {gives White a slight pull.}) 9... Nxe5 10. Bxe4 (10. Bxe4 {White is better in an open position. Black already needs to take care. The natural} O-O {loses a pawn after} 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Bxh7+ Kxh7 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Qxe5 {and White has good winning chances despite the opposite coloured bishops.}) *

