1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {This is by far the most played move and the significance even raises when you add 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 to the list, when it is also very common for Black to play [d5] in one of the following moves. Black focuses on sound development and intends to move the dark-squared bishop and castle.} 4. Bd3 {Other moves are possible, but this is what we do. The bishop is good here.} Bd6 {Imitating White. In general [d6] is a more active post for the bishop than [e7].} 5. Nbd2 Nbd7 6. O-O e5 {This is too hasty.} 7. e4 $1 {[%csl Ge8] A typical counterstrike in the centre. The black king would wish it was already on [g8].} O-O (7... exd4 $2 8. e5 $1 {wins a piece for White.}) 8. Re1 {Improving the position and keeping the tension at the same time.} dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Rxe4 $5 {This is pretty dangerous for Black.} f5 11. Rh4 (11. Rh4 {And White has a strong initiative. In a game, Black played the obvious} e4 $2 {but was crushed after} 12. Bc4+ Kh8 13. Ng5 $1 {Already there is no defence.} Nf6 14. Nxh7 $1 {and White won.}) *

