1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {This is by far the most played move and the significance even raises when you add 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 to the list, when it is also very common for Black to play [d5] in one of the following moves. Black focuses on sound development and intends to move the dark-squared bishop and castle.} 4. Bd3 {Other moves are possible, but this is what we do. The bishop is good here.} Bd6 {Imitating White. In general [d6] is a more active post for the bishop than [e7].} 5. Nbd2 Nbd7 6. O-O O-O {Keeping the symmetry.} (6... c5 {can be met with either} 7. c3 {or 7.b3 , with a transposition to other lines.}) 7. e4 {Now, finally White breaks the symmetry.} dxe4 (7... e5 {transposes to 6...e5 7.e4 O-O .}) 8. Nxe4 Nxe4 9. Bxe4 {White has extra space and nice piece play in an open position.} Nf6 {The most straightforward.} 10. Bg5 $5 {We are ready to exchange the bishop for a knight to keep some initiative.} ({The most played is in fact} 10. Bd3 {, but I am not sure that White is better.}) 10... h6 ({Or} 10... Be7 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Qd3 {, attacking [h7]. Next comes [Rad1] with some pressure. It won´t be easy for Black to get [Bc8] into play.}) ({The line} 10... c5 $5 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Qe2 {also leaves White with the easier play.}) 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Qe2 {[%csl Ge5] Keeping an eye on [e5].} ({If} 12. c3 {, then} e5 {N , and I think Black equalizes.}) 12... c5 ({Of course not} 12... e5 $2 13. dxe5 Bxe5 14. Nxe5 Qxe5 15. Bh7+ {, winning the queen.}) 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. c3 {[%csl Gc8,Ge4] White has a strong bishop on [e4] vs a passive one on [c8], so this position is not so easy for Black although the engine thinks it is almost balanced.} *

