1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {This is by far the most played move and the significance even raises when you add 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 to the list, when it is also very common for Black to play [d5] in one of the following moves. Black focuses on sound development and intends to move the dark-squared bishop and castle.} 4. Bd3 {Other moves are possible, but this is what we do. The bishop is good here.} b6 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc8b7] Black hopes to cover the [e4]-square before White can make the [e3]-[e4] break. By the way, this is what I recommended for Black in my QGD course!} 5. Nbd2 ({In the course, I focused on} 5. O-O {, which is the normal move. The text is much more subtle though.}) 5... Bb7 6. Qe2 {[%cal Ge3e4] The point. We are ready to play [e3]-[e4]!} Be7 7. e4 $1 dxe4 8. Nxe4 Nbd7 {Trying to keep everything together.} ({Solid is} 8... Nxe4 9. Bxe4 Bxe4 10. Qxe4 Qd5 {but after} 11. Qxd5 exd5 12. Bf4 {White has some pressure in the ending.}) 9. O-O O-O 10. Rd1 (10. Rd1 {It's not easy for Black to shake our grip on the position. They have nice tactics though that almost solve all their problems. It is tempting to remove the queen from the d-file. After} Qc8 11. Bg5 {, White keeps some pressure, though the machine isn't impressed.}) 10... Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Bxe4 12. Qxe4 c5 $1 ({This is it!} 12... Nf6 13. Qe2 {is pleasant for White.}) 13. Bf4 {White keeps some pressure with the more active pieces.} ({If} 13. dxc5 {then Black has prepared} Nxc5 $1 {, hitting our queen so we don't have time to take on [d8].}) *

