1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {This is by far the most played move and the significance even raises when you add 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 to the list, when it is also very common for Black to play [d5] in one of the following moves. Black focuses on sound development and intends to move the dark-squared bishop and castle.} 4. Bd3 {Other moves are possible, but this is what we do. The bishop is good here.} b6 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc8b7] Black hopes to cover the [e4]-square before White can make the [e3]-[e4] break. By the way, this is what I recommended for Black in my QGD course!} 5. Nbd2 ({In the course, I focused on} 5. O-O {, which is the normal move. The text is much more subtle though.}) 5... Bb7 6. Qe2 {[%cal Ge3e4] The point. We are ready to play [e3]-[e4]!} Ne4 {This is consequent. Black prevents [e4].} ({Of course, we need to see what happens if Black just allows the central break:} 6... Nbd7 7. e4 dxe4 8. Nxe4 Be7 {transposes to 6...Be7 .}) 7. Bb5+ {An interesting novelty.} c6 ({If} 7... Bc6 8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Nd2 {is good for White.}) 8. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4] So we wasted two moves to provoke the black pawn to [c6]? Yes, now Black has problems with the knight on [e4].} f5 {Black secures the outpost.} ({The line after} 8... c5 9. Bb5+ {followed by [Nxe4] or 8...Nxd2 9.Bxd2 is comfortable for White.}) 9. Ne5 {[%csl Ge8][%cal Ge2h5] Threatening [Qh5]+.} g6 {White has several good options.} 10. O-O {The simplest.} ({Interesting is} 10. Bxe4 $5 fxe4 11. Qg4 Qe7 12. f3 {with the initiative.}) 10... Nd7 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. f3 Nxd2 13. Bxd2 {[%cal Ge3e4,Gc2c4] The position is simplified, but White is somewhat better. Sooner or later the breaks [c2]-[c4] or [e3]-[e4] comes. The pawn on [f5] has permanently weakened Black's structure.} *

