1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {This is by far the most played move and the significance even raises when you add 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 to the list, when it is also very common for Black to play [d5] in one of the following moves. Black focuses on sound development and intends to move the dark-squared bishop and castle.} 4. Bd3 {Other moves are possible, but this is what we do. The bishop is good here.} c6 {Black creates the Semi-Slav pawn formation. We do it a lot ourselves, so it is hard to criticize. Still, it is rather passive and we can go for the [e3]-[e4] break as usual.} 5. O-O Bd6 (5... Bd6 {Also possible is a Zukertort set-up with} 6. b3 O-O 7. Bb2 Nbd7 8. Nbd2 {.}) 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. Re1 ({A small refinement. The direct} 7. e4 {was, of course, also fine.}) 7... Nbd7 8. e4 $1 {The break comes.} dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Rxe4 $1 {This was the idea with 7.Re1 . White gets a strong initiative. The rook is on the way to [h4].} Re8 11. Rh4 $5 ({Attacking h7. Transferring the rook to h4 was the idea, but sometimes it is stronger just to have an idea than actually to execute it! Here both} 11. Qe2 {or 11.Bd2 looks good. White is much better in both cases.}) 11... Nf8 {The point of 10...Re8 . The knight is safe here.} 12. Ng5 $5 ({White continues with very aggressive moves. It was possible to slow down and just go} 12. Bd2 {with a big advantage. Black lacks counterplay.}) 12... f5 {This has never been played, but it is probably the best.} ({Options like} 12... g6 13. Qf3 f5 14. Bd2 { or 12...h6 13.Qh5 are really bad for Black.}) 13. Qh5 {Creating some more weaknesses around the black king.} g6 14. Qf3 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ga1e1]} (14. Qf3 {White is better. We can bring in the reserves with Bd2 and Re1. If Black plays} Be7 {then} 15. Qg3 {keeps the pressure.}) *

