1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {This is by far the most played move and the significance even raises when you add 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 to the list, when it is also very common for Black to play [d5] in one of the following moves. Black focuses on sound development and intends to move the dark-squared bishop and castle.} 4. Bd3 {Other moves are possible, but this is what we do. The bishop is good here.} c6 {Black creates the Semi-Slav pawn formation. We do it a lot ourselves, so it is hard to criticize. Still, it is rather passive and we can go for the [e3]-[e4] break as usual.} 5. O-O Bd6 (5... Bd6 {Also possible is a Zukertort set-up with} 6. b3 O-O 7. Bb2 Nbd7 8. Nbd2 {.}) 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. Re1 ({A small refinement. The direct} 7. e4 {was, of course, also fine.}) 7... Nbd7 8. e4 $1 {The break comes.} dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Rxe4 $1 {This was the idea with 7.Re1 . White gets a strong initiative. The rook is on the way to [h4].} Nf6 ({Preventing Rh4 with} 10... Be7 {loses time. White is much better after} 11. Qe2 {.}) 11. Rh4 $18 {The attack is rather primitive, but it turns out that Black can't get out of the grip.} Be7 (11... g6 {is met by} 12. Qd2 $1 {N like in the mainline. The queen is on the way to [h6].} Re8 13. Ne5 {followed by [Qf4] gives White decisive pressure.}) 12. Ne5 {Activating the knight and opening for the queen.} c5 13. Qf3 {The queen joins the party. It was not possible to sacrifice on [h7] yet.} cxd4 14. Bh6 $5 {The most spectacular. Other moves were just as good. Now Black should probably play [g7]-[g6] and give an exchange, but let's see what happens if the sacrifice is accepted.} gxh6 15. Qg3+ $1 Kh8 16. Rxh6 {[%csl Gh7][%cal Gg3h4] Next is [Qh4] and Black can resign.} *

