{If 17...Kxg7 , then 18.Rxh7+!} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {This is by far the most played move and the significance even raises when you add 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 to the list, when it is also very common for Black to play [d5] in one of the following moves. Black focuses on sound development and intends to move the dark-squared bishop and castle.} 4. Bd3 {Other moves are possible, but this is what we do. The bishop is good here.} c6 {Black creates the Semi-Slav pawn formation. We do it a lot ourselves, so it is hard to criticize. Still, it is rather passive and we can go for the [e3]-[e4] break as usual.} 5. O-O Bd6 (5... Bd6 {Also possible is a Zukertort set-up with} 6. b3 O-O 7. Bb2 Nbd7 8. Nbd2 {.}) 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. Re1 ({A small refinement. The direct} 7. e4 {was, of course, also fine.}) 7... Nbd7 8. e4 $1 {The break comes.} dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Rxe4 $1 {This was the idea with 7.Re1 . White gets a strong initiative. The rook is on the way to [h4].} Nf6 ({Preventing Rh4 with} 10... Be7 {loses time. White is much better after} 11. Qe2 {.}) 11. Rh4 $18 {The attack is rather primitive, but it turns out that Black can't get out of the grip.} Be7 (11... g6 {is met by} 12. Qd2 $1 {N like in the mainline. The queen is on the way to [h6].} Re8 13. Ne5 {followed by [Qf4] gives White decisive pressure.}) 12. Ne5 {Activating the knight and opening for the queen.} g6 {This is the only move that has ever been played and you understand why. The threats against [h7] looks devastating.} 13. Bh6 Nd7 {[%cal Ge7h4,Gh6f8] Hitting the white rook.} ({The position after} 13... Re8 14. Qf3 {is hopeless. White can continue with [Rf4].}) 14. Rh3 Re8 15. Qf3 {[%cal Gf3f7] Threatening mate.} Nxe5 16. dxe5 (16. dxe5 {White is strategically winning. Here are some sample lines: •} Qc7 17. Qe3 f5 {, hoping to close the position.} 18. Bxf5 $1 exf5 19. Qb3+ {, the queen penetrates.} Kh8 20. Qf7 Rg8 21. Qxh7+ $1 {Black is mated.} Kxh7 22. Bf8+ Bh4 23. Rxh4#) (16. dxe5 {•} Qd4 17. Bg7 $1 {, a very unusual fianchetto!} h5 18. Bf6 Bxf6 19. Qxf6 Qd8 20. Qf4 Kg7 21. g4 {Black can´t defend the kingside.}) *

