1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {This is by far the most played move and the significance even raises when you add 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 to the list, when it is also very common for Black to play [d5] in one of the following moves. Black focuses on sound development and intends to move the dark-squared bishop and castle.} 4. Bd3 {Other moves are possible, but this is what we do. The bishop is good here.} Be7 {Black plays a solid developing move in the spirit of the Queen's Gambit Declined.} 5. O-O ({White could also start with} 5. Nbd2 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Nbd2 ({The flexible} 6. b3 b6 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 {is very symmetrical, but, of course, it is possible to play like that.}) 6... b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb8d7] Planning [Bb7] and [Nbd7].} 7. e4 $1 {I believe White should strike at once.} ({• After} 7. b3 Bb7 8. Bb2 Nbd7 {looks pretty equal.}) ({• The most popular is} 7. Ne5 Bb7 8. f4 c5 {gives Black good counterplay.}) 7... dxe4 8. Nxe4 {This is also pretty equal, but White has some initiative.} Bb7 (8... Nbd7 9. Qe2 Bb7 10. Rd1 {transposes to b6 .}) 9. Nxf6+ $5 ({White could also go for} 9. Qe2 Nbd7 10. Rd1 {, which transposes to 4...b6 .}) 9... Bxf6 10. Qe2 Nd7 (10... Qd6 {was seen in Bu-Dubov, China 2024. After} 11. Be3 {N} Nd7 12. Rad1 {White is somewhat more comfortable.}) 11. Rd1 Qe7 12. Bf4 (12. Bf4 {White has some pressure. The position is probably equal, but Black must take care. The natural:} c5 13. dxc5 Nxc5 {loses an exchange after} 14. Bd6 $1) *

