1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {This is by far the most played move and the significance even raises when you add 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 to the list, when it is also very common for Black to play [d5] in one of the following moves. Black focuses on sound development and intends to move the dark-squared bishop and castle.} 4. Bd3 {Other moves are possible, but this is what we do. The bishop is good here.} Be7 {Black plays a solid developing move in the spirit of the Queen's Gambit Declined.} 5. O-O ({White could also start with} 5. Nbd2 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Nbd2 ({The flexible} 6. b3 b6 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 {is very symmetrical, but, of course, it is possible to play like that.}) 6... Nbd7 {A flexible move, waiting to see which setup White goes for.} 7. Qe2 {[%cal Ge3e4] Preparing [e3]-[e4]. White has many other good options; basically, it is often just a matter of taste. • In general in this repertoire, I have tried to get the central break [e3]-[e4] in to open the position and get active piece play.} ({• You could also play more quietly with} 7. b3 {. • Another option is to go for the original Zukertort plan with} Ne5 {, followed by 8. [f4].}) 7... c5 8. c3 b6 {The most precise.} (8... Qc7 9. e4 dxe4 10. Nxe4 {or 8...c4 9.Bc2 b5 10.e4 gives White more chances to come out of the opening with a real edge.}) 9. e4 dxe4 10. Nxe4 Bb7 {A critical position. Black has managed to get both [Bb7] and [c7]-[c5] in. In many of the previous lines, Black only managed one of them! So is everything then fine for Black? Yeah, the position is probably balanced, but White can ask the usual questions.} 11. Rd1 Qc7 12. Bg5 Rfe8 {Protecting the bishop. The position is balanced. Both sides have succeeded in keeping the tension without giving anything away. A possible continuation is:} 13. Nxf6+ ({If} 13. dxc5 {Black has} Bxe4 $1 14. Bxe4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Nxc5) 13... Bxf6 {The best.} ({After} 13... Nxf6 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Ne5 {White is more active.}) 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. Ba6 {The game is equal, but we can keep playing. The majority on the queenside always gives some chances.} *

