1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {This is by far the most played move and the significance even raises when you add 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 to the list, when it is also very common for Black to play [d5] in one of the following moves. Black focuses on sound development and intends to move the dark-squared bishop and castle.} 4. Bd3 {Other moves are possible, but this is what we do. The bishop is good here.} Be7 {Black plays a solid developing move in the spirit of the Queen's Gambit Declined.} 5. O-O ({White could also start with} 5. Nbd2 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Nbd2 ({The flexible} 6. b3 b6 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 {is very symmetrical, but, of course, it is possible to play like that.}) 6... c5 {A good active positional move.} 7. c3 {Now play transposes to the lines we saw in the 3...[c5] chapter. I will give an interesting alternative though that tries to benefit from Black's move-order.} ({As usual also} 7. b3 {is possible.}) 7... Nc6 8. dxc5 Bxc5 {And we are in the 3...c5 chapter.} *

