1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {This is by far the most played move and the significance even raises when you add 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 to the list, when it is also very common for Black to play [d5] in one of the following moves. Black focuses on sound development and intends to move the dark-squared bishop and castle.} 4. Bd3 {Other moves are possible, but this is what we do. The bishop is good here.} Be7 {Black plays a solid developing move in the spirit of the Queen's Gambit Declined.} 5. O-O ({White could also start with} 5. Nbd2 {.}) 5... O-O 6. Nbd2 ({The flexible} 6. b3 b6 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 {is very symmetrical, but, of course, it is possible to play like that.}) 6... c5 {A good active positional move.} 7. dxc5 $5 {White has a good score with this.} Bxc5 8. e4 {We can go for this typical break, but without the move [c3].} ({A good positional setup that I would probably choose myself if I had the position is} 8. b3 Nc6 9. Bb2 {. Usually, this arises after 5. [b3]. White has a very harmonious position and could continue in good positional style with an early [c4].}) ({It is also possible to flick in} 8. a3 {, if we are allowed, we will play [b2]-[b4] next; and if} a5 {, then} 9. b3 Nc6 10. Bb2 {, followed by c4.}) {In case of 9...b6 , then 10.Bb2 Bb7 11.Qe2 Nbd7 12.c4 .} 8... Nc6 ({Taking on e4 makes White's play pretty easy and straightforward.} 8... dxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Bxe4 {, the bishop is strong here. White is comfortable in the ending; after} Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Nd7 {, intending Nf6... • I prefer this continuation:} 12. Bd3 Nf6 13. Ne5 {, White is slightly better in my opinion. Soon the pawns on the queenside will start moving.}) {• White could win a pawn, but after a long more or less forced sequence: 12.Bxb7 Bxb7 13.Rxd7 Rfd8 14.Rxd8+ Rxd8 15.Be3 Bxe3 16.fxe3 Bxf3 17.gxf3 Rd2 18.Rc1 Kf8 , Black has enough compensation.} 9. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Preventing [Nb4] and flirting with playing [b2]-[b4] ourselves.} a5 {The most natural response, preventing [b2]-[b4].} 10. h3 h6 {Black can play other moves, but it doesn't really matter.} 11. Re1 {With an interesting position with chances for both sides. White can put the queen on [e2] and then decide if the [e4]-[e5] advance is any good, depending what Black has done. An idea could also be just to take on [d5]. If Black takes back with the pawn, then we can go [Nb3] and [Be3] and play against the IQP. If Black takes back with the knight, we have [Ne4] with active pieces.} *

