1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 g6 {A popular move. Black wants to fianchetto the bishop and later maybe play [c7]-[c5] with a reversed Catalan. After White's next it turns out to be nothing more than a dream.} 4. b4 $1 {[%csl Gc5] Effectively stopping all Black's [c5]-ideas. Suddenly Black's dream of playing some kind of Catalan might even turn out to be a nightmare! White's [b2]-[b4] move is not only a prophylactic way of throwing a spanner in the works, no it is a prelude to a grand expansion on the queenside that could dictate the rest of the game.} Bg7 {Black should get on with the development. It is too early to do something extravagant.} ({The immediate} 4... a5 5. b5 Bg7 {only gives White extra possibilities. Instead of the standard [Bb2], interesting is} 6. Ba3 $5 {, the bishop stands well here.}) ({Also,} 4... c6 {doesn't do much and will most likely just transpose to later lines after} 5. c4 {.}) 5. Bb2 {Also a natural move. Having said a...} O-O 6. c4 $1 {I think this is the most precise, that explains the exclamation mark. Then it is easier to remember!} ({The move} 6. Nbd2 {is also very popular and there are many games with it, also because the position often arises after the moves 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 g6 3.Nbd2 d5 4.e3 Bg7 5.b4 . In that case, the knight is of course already on [d2]. In our move order, maybe we can benefit from the fact that the knight hasn't moved yet. In most cases, but not all, it will turn up on [d2] anyway. 6...a5 7.b5 a4! This aggressive approach equalizes by force, as far as I can see. I will highlight Black's idea, but not go into too much detail: After 8.Ba3 Re8 , the rook leaves the bishop's diagonal. Black wants to follow up with [Nbd7] and [e7]-[e5], with or without [c7]-[c6], that is not so important. Despite a lot of analysis, I haven't been able to find anything substantial for White. I think it is a clean equalizer.}) 6... Bf5 7. Nc3 $5 {The knight is a little more active here than on [d2].} c6 8. Be2 {It is possible just to continue to develop the kingside.} ({Playing on the queenside with} 8. Rc1 {or even 8.a4 was also interesting. I like to push the a-pawn in these lines!}) 8... Nbd7 9. O-O ({White could consider} 9. cxd5 {with a fixed pawn structure in the centre, Black's [g7]-bishop is quite passive.}) 9... Ne4 10. cxd5 ({This is a good time to change the structure. Keeping the tension with} 10. Rc1 {is also fine.}) 10... Nxc3 11. Bxc3 cxd5 12. Qb3 Nf6 13. Rfc1 {[%cal Gb4b5,Gf6e4,Gc3e1] White has good play on the queenside. We will take extra space with [b5] and if Black tries [Ne4] the bishop just drops back to [e1].} *

