nue to develop the kingside.} ({Playing on the queenside with} 8. Rc1 {or even 8.a4 was also interesting. I like to push the a-pawn in these lines!}) 8... Nbd7 9. O-O ({White could consider} 9. cxd5 {with a fixed pawn structure in the centre, Black's [g7]-bishop is quite passive.}) 9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nb6 11. Bb3 (11. Bb3 {White was slightly better in Miles-Rumpf, 1997. That game continued:} Nbd5 12. Nxd5 $5 cxd5 13. Ne5 Qd6 14. a4 {, and now Black shouldn't have taken on [b4].} Qxb4 15. Ba3 Qa5 16. Bxe7 Rfe8 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Nd3 {with a positional advantage because of the weak d5-pawn.}) ({Also fine is} 11. Be2 Nbd5 12. Qb3 {.}) *

