1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 g6 {A popular move. Black wants to fianchetto the bishop and later maybe play [c7]-[c5] with a reversed Catalan. After White's next it turns out to be nothing more than a dream.} 4. b4 $1 {[%csl Gc5] Effectively stopping all Black's [c5]-ideas. Suddenly Black's dream of playing some kind of Catalan might even turn out to be a nightmare! White's [b2]-[b4] move is not only a prophylactic way of throwing a spanner in the works, no it is a prelude to a grand expansion on the queenside that could dictate the rest of the game.} Bg7 {Black should get on with the development. It is too early to do something extravagant.} ({The immediate} 4... a5 5. b5 Bg7 {only gives White extra possibilities. Instead of the standard [Bb2], interesting is} 6. Ba3 $5 {, the bishop stands well here.}) ({Also,} 4... c6 {doesn't do much and will most likely just transpose to later lines after} 5. c4 {.}) 5. Bb2 {Also a natural move. Having said a...} O-O 6. c4 $1 {I think this is the most precise, that explains the exclamation mark. Then it is easier to remember!} ({The move} 6. Nbd2 {is also very popular and there are many games with it, also because the position often arises after the moves 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 g6 3.Nbd2 d5 4.e3 Bg7 5.b4 . In that case, the knight is of course already on [d2]. In our move order, maybe we can benefit from the fact that the knight hasn't moved yet. In most cases, but not all, it will turn up on [d2] anyway. 6...a5 7.b5 a4! This aggressive approach equalizes by force, as far as I can see. I will highlight Black's idea, but not go into too much detail: After 8.Ba3 Re8 , the rook leaves the bishop's diagonal. Black wants to follow up with [Nbd7] and [e7]-[e5], with or without [c7]-[c6], that is not so important. Despite a lot of analysis, I haven't been able to find anything substantial for White. I think it is a clean equalizer.}) 6... c6 {Protecting [d5] is the most played move. I am not sure we were actually intending to take on [d5], so Black could try many other moves as well.} 7. a4 $1 {I think we should advance on the queenside at once.} Bf5 {It can also go to [f5].} 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 9. Be2 {White just develops.} Ne4 {[%cal Ge7e5] A natural move in connection with [Bf5]. Black opens up for [Bg7] and will try to get [e5] in.} 10. O-O Re8 11. cxd5 {Simple and good.} ({The engine proposes the new move} 11. a5 $5 {which definitely is interesting.}) 11... cxd5 12. Nxe4 ({Here White could also consider} 12. Qb3 {.}) 12... Bxe4 ({If} 12... dxe4 {, then} 13. Nd2 e5 14. d5 $1 {is promising for White, for instance,} Nf6 15. Bc4 Nxd5 16. Qb3 Be6 17. Nxe4 {with strong pressure.}) 13. Ne5 ({In So-Vachier-Lagrave, rapid 2017 White played} 13. Qb3 {which also is fine. Black could have tried:} Bxf3 14. Bxf3 e6 {with a very solid position.}) 13... Nxe5 14. dxe5 (14. dxe5 {White is better because of the extra space. A sample line goes:} Rc8 15. Qd4 Rc2 16. Bd1 Rc4 17. Qd2 Qb6 18. b5 Rec8 19. Bb3 R4c7 20. Rac1 {with good chances, even after the exchange of all the rooks. The black d-pawn is a target, especially since White can always chase the bishop away with [f3].}) *

