1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 g6 {A popular move. Black wants to fianchetto the bishop and later maybe play [c7]-[c5] with a reversed Catalan. After White's next it turns out to be nothing more than a dream.} 4. b4 $1 {[%csl Gc5] Effectively stopping all Black's [c5]-ideas. Suddenly Black's dream of playing some kind of Catalan might even turn out to be a nightmare! White's [b2]-[b4] move is not only a prophylactic way of throwing a spanner in the works, no it is a prelude to a grand expansion on the queenside that could dictate the rest of the game.} Bg7 {Black should get on with the development. It is too early to do something extravagant.} ({The immediate} 4... a5 5. b5 Bg7 {only gives White extra possibilities. Instead of the standard [Bb2], interesting is} 6. Ba3 $5 {, the bishop stands well here.}) ({Also,} 4... c6 {doesn't do much and will most likely just transpose to later lines after} 5. c4 {.}) 5. Bb2 {Also a natural move. Having said a...} O-O 6. c4 $1 {I think this is the most precise, that explains the exclamation mark. Then it is easier to remember!} ({The move} 6. Nbd2 {is also very popular and there are many games with it, also because the position often arises after the moves 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 g6 3.Nbd2 d5 4.e3 Bg7 5.b4 . In that case, the knight is of course already on [d2]. In our move order, maybe we can benefit from the fact that the knight hasn't moved yet. In most cases, but not all, it will turn up on [d2] anyway. 6...a5 7.b5 a4! This aggressive approach equalizes by force, as far as I can see. I will highlight Black's idea, but not go into too much detail: After 8.Ba3 Re8 , the rook leaves the bishop's diagonal. Black wants to follow up with [Nbd7] and [e7]-[e5], with or without [c7]-[c6], that is not so important. Despite a lot of analysis, I haven't been able to find anything substantial for White. I think it is a clean equalizer.}) 6... c6 {Protecting [d5] is the most played move. I am not sure we were actually intending to take on [d5], so Black could try many other moves as well.} 7. a4 $1 {I think we should advance on the queenside at once.} Nbd7 {This looks a little clumsy at first, but Black plays for the [e7]-[e5] break.} 8. Nbd2 Re8 9. Be2 ({This is the safest spot for the bishop in these lines.} 9. Bd3 {can be met by the dynamic break.} e5 $1 10. dxe5 Ng4 {, followed by [Ndxe5].}) 9... Ne4 {[%cal Ge7e5] Opens for [Bg7].} ({The immediate} 9... e5 {is premature. After} 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7 12. f4 {White has a pawn more.}) 10. Nxe4 ({I have found a new interesting idea in this line, that is why I am recommending it. White could also play the more solid} 10. O-O Nxd2 11. Qxd2 dxc4 12. Bxc4 e5 13. Qc2 {with good chances for at least a slight edge.}) 10... dxe4 11. Nd2 e5 12. Nxe4 {This is my idea.} ({The position after} 12. d5 cxd5 13. cxd5 Nf6 {seems ok for Black.}) 12... exd4 13. Nd6 {[%csl Gd6] A fantastic outpost.} Re6 14. c5 {[%csl Gd6] The point. We establish our super knight on [d6]. Now Black has two moves. The straightforward [dxe3] or the more tricky [d3]!?} d3 $5 15. Bxg7 dxe2 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Ge2d1] The point. Fortunately we can protect [Bg7] with our queen.} 16. Qd4 f6 17. Bh6 {The bishop is saved.} b6 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gb6c5,Gd7c5] But Black keeps playing annoying moves! It is hard to find time to capture the [e2]-pawn.} 18. Nxc8 {Probably best. The knight was not secure anymore with Black ready to destroy the [c5]-pawn.} Qxc8 19. Bf4 {[%csl Ge5] Controlling [e5].} bxc5 20. bxc5 Ne5 21. Bxe5 Rxe5 22. Qc4+ Rd5 23. Qxe2 Rxc5 24. O-O {White has a small edge. The black pawn structure is somewhat compromised and the king surely would have preferred if the pawn was still on [f7].} *

