ck could try many other moves as well.} 7. a4 $1 {I think we should advance on the queenside at once.} Nbd7 {This looks a little clumsy at first, but Black plays for the [e7]-[e5] break.} 8. Nbd2 Re8 9. Be2 ({This is the safest spot for the bishop in these lines.} 9. Bd3 {can be met by the dynamic break.} e5 $1 10. dxe5 Ng4 {, followed by [Ndxe5].}) 9... Ne4 {[%cal Ge7e5] Opens for [Bg7].} ({The immediate} 9... e5 {is premature. After} 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7 12. f4 {White has a pawn more.}) 10. Nxe4 ({I have found a new interesting idea in this line, that is why I am recommending it. White could also play the more solid} 10. O-O Nxd2 11. Qxd2 dxc4 12. Bxc4 e5 13. Qc2 {with good chances for at least a slight edge.}) 10... dxe4 11. Nd2 e5 12. Nxe4 {This is my idea.} ({The position after} 12. d5 cxd5 13. cxd5 Nf6 {seems ok for Black.}) 12... exd4 13. Nd6 {[%csl Gd6] A fantastic outpost.} Re6 14. c5 {[%csl Gd6] The point. We establish our super knight on [d6]. Now Black has two moves. The straightforward [dxe3] or the more tricky [d3]!?} dxe3 15. Bxg7 exf2+ {This intermediate move wins a pawn.} 16. Kxf2 Kxg7 17. Rf1 {[%csl Gf7][%cal Gf2g1] White is ready to make a castle by hand with [Kg1] next. This looks quite promising with very active pieces. The knight is fantastic on [d6] and [f7] is an obviouis target that also can be attacked with [Bc4]. The white queen can be nicely centralized on [d4]. So, lots of potential!} *

