1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 g6 {A popular move. Black wants to fianchetto the bishop and later maybe play [c7]-[c5] with a reversed Catalan. After White's next it turns out to be nothing more than a dream.} 4. b4 $1 {[%csl Gc5] Effectively stopping all Black's [c5]-ideas. Suddenly Black's dream of playing some kind of Catalan might even turn out to be a nightmare! White's [b2]-[b4] move is not only a prophylactic way of throwing a spanner in the works, no it is a prelude to a grand expansion on the queenside that could dictate the rest of the game.} Bg7 {Black should get on with the development. It is too early to do something extravagant.} ({The immediate} 4... a5 5. b5 Bg7 {only gives White extra possibilities. Instead of the standard [Bb2], interesting is} 6. Ba3 $5 {, the bishop stands well here.}) ({Also,} 4... c6 {doesn't do much and will most likely just transpose to later lines after} 5. c4 {.}) 5. Bb2 {Also a natural move. Having said a...} O-O 6. c4 $1 {I think this is the most precise, that explains the exclamation mark. Then it is easier to remember!} ({The move} 6. Nbd2 {is also very popular and there are many games with it, also because the position often arises after the moves 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 g6 3.Nbd2 d5 4.e3 Bg7 5.b4 . In that case, the knight is of course already on [d2]. In our move order, maybe we can benefit from the fact that the knight hasn't moved yet. In most cases, but not all, it will turn up on [d2] anyway. 6...a5 7.b5 a4! This aggressive approach equalizes by force, as far as I can see. I will highlight Black's idea, but not go into too much detail: After 8.Ba3 Re8 , the rook leaves the bishop's diagonal. Black wants to follow up with [Nbd7] and [e7]-[e5], with or without [c7]-[c6], that is not so important. Despite a lot of analysis, I haven't been able to find anything substantial for White. I think it is a clean equalizer.}) 6... c6 {Protecting [d5] is the most played move. I am not sure we were actually intending to take on [d5], so Black could try many other moves as well.} 7. a4 $1 {I think we should advance on the queenside at once.} a5 {Striking at the white structure, but after [b5] we benefit from the move [a4], because we can always take back on [b5] with the a-pawn.} 8. b5 Bg4 ({The bishop gets out. Black doesn't have many squares for the pieces and} 8... cxb5 9. axb5 dxc4 10. Bxc4 {looks very nice for White, although Black can try} Nbd7 11. Nc3 Nb6 {, but after} 12. Bb3 {, I prefer White. Next, we will castle and in the long run, the strong central pawn on [d4] might give us a positional plus. The free a-pawn is not running anywhere.}) (8... Ne4 9. Nbd2 {also looks good for White. In general, the inclusion of [a5] and [b5] just gives us extra space.}) 9. Nbd2 Ne4 {Almost the only active move.} 10. Be2 Nxd2 11. Nxd2 {I prefer to get rid of Black's active bishop as well.} Bxe2 12. Qxe2 {[%cal Ge1g1] The many exchanges have removed some of the tension in the position. I like our prospects on the queenside where the huge space advantage gives us something to work with. First, we castle though!} *

