1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 g6 {A popular move. Black wants to fianchetto the bishop and later maybe play [c7]-[c5] with a reversed Catalan. After White's next it turns out to be nothing more than a dream.} 4. b4 $1 {[%csl Gc5] Effectively stopping all Black's [c5]-ideas. Suddenly Black's dream of playing some kind of Catalan might even turn out to be a nightmare! White's [b2]-[b4] move is not only a prophylactic way of throwing a spanner in the works, no it is a prelude to a grand expansion on the queenside that could dictate the rest of the game.} Bg7 {Black should get on with the development. It is too early to do something extravagant.} ({The immediate} 4... a5 5. b5 Bg7 {only gives White extra possibilities. Instead of the standard [Bb2], interesting is} 6. Ba3 $5 {, the bishop stands well here.}) ({Also,} 4... c6 {doesn't do much and will most likely just transpose to later lines after} 5. c4 {.}) 5. Bb2 {Also a natural move. Having said a...} O-O 6. c4 $1 {I think this is the most precise, that explains the exclamation mark. Then it is easier to remember!} ({The move} 6. Nbd2 {is also very popular and there are many games with it, also because the position often arises after the moves 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 g6 3.Nbd2 d5 4.e3 Bg7 5.b4 . In that case, the knight is of course already on [d2]. In our move order, maybe we can benefit from the fact that the knight hasn't moved yet. In most cases, but not all, it will turn up on [d2] anyway. 6...a5 7.b5 a4! This aggressive approach equalizes by force, as far as I can see. I will highlight Black's idea, but not go into too much detail: After 8.Ba3 Re8 , the rook leaves the bishop's diagonal. Black wants to follow up with [Nbd7] and [e7]-[e5], with or without [c7]-[c6], that is not so important. Despite a lot of analysis, I haven't been able to find anything substantial for White. I think it is a clean equalizer.}) 6... c6 {Protecting [d5] is the most played move. I am not sure we were actually intending to take on [d5], so Black could try many other moves as well.} 7. a4 $1 {I think we should advance on the queenside at once.} Bg4 {Developing the bishop makes the most sense.} 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 ({Or} 8... Ne4 9. Be2 {when simplifications always end up with White having some plusses because of the extra space on the queenside.}) 9. Be2 Re8 {[%cal Gf6e4,Ge7e5] A good improving move. Black wants to play [Ne4] and [e7]-[e5].} 10. Qb3 {[%csl Gd5] This puts pressure on the [d5]-pawn and prevents [Ne4].} (10. Qb3 {White could also just castle, but I like this active Qb3-prophylactic idea. Black should probably play a defensive move like} e6 {, but that is saying goodbye to the [e5]-plan and White is just slightly better with the extra space on the queenside.}) *

