1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 {The Zukertort system is characterized by [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], often in combination with a later [Ne5] and [f2]-[f4]. The long-term goal is an attack on the kingside! Please notice that I wasn't so keen on it if Black had started with 3...c5 , because then the light-squared bishop could be developed actively on [g4]. Here, when [e7]-[e6] has already been played, the bishop is stuck behind the pawns.} Nc6 6. O-O ({The moves can be played in almost random order, so} 6. Bb2 {is also fine.}) 6... b6 {Black can try to solve the problems with the passive [Bc8].} 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. Nbd2 Be7 9. dxc5 $5 ({Again} 9. Ne5 {is the most played and, of course, fine.}) 9... bxc5 10. c4 ({In this position} 10. e4 {isn't as strong as when the black bishop is on [d6], because White is threatening to play [e4]-[e5]. Here, Black can just castle with a fine position.}) 10... O-O 11. a3 ({Controlling the b4-square. Nakamura has played} 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Rc1 {which is also interesting. On} Nb4 13. Bb1 {is good for White.}) 11... a5 ({Black has other moves as well. The most popular is} 11... d4 {but after} 12. exd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 cxd4 14. Nf3 {White is better. It is not a good sign for Black if they have to take on [f3] to save the d-pawn.}) 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Qc2 {The position is balanced, but personally, I like the nice coordination of the white pieces. There are several plans: you can play [Rfe1] and push [e3]-[e4] or centralize the rooks on [c1] and [d1] and exert pressure on the hanging pawns.} *

