1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 {The Zukertort system is characterized by [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], often in combination with a later [Ne5] and [f2]-[f4]. The long-term goal is an attack on the kingside! Please notice that I wasn't so keen on it if Black had started with 3...c5 , because then the light-squared bishop could be developed actively on [g4]. Here, when [e7]-[e6] has already been played, the bishop is stuck behind the pawns.} Nc6 6. O-O ({The moves can be played in almost random order, so} 6. Bb2 {is also fine.}) 6... b6 {Black can try to solve the problems with the passive [Bc8].} 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. Nbd2 Be7 9. dxc5 $5 ({Again} 9. Ne5 {is the most played and, of course, fine.}) 9... bxc5 10. c4 ({In this position} 10. e4 {isn't as strong as when the black bishop is on [d6], because White is threatening to play [e4]-[e5]. Here, Black can just castle with a fine position.}) 10... d4 11. exd4 cxd4 12. a3 {[%cal Gb3b4] Planning [b3]-[b4] with good play on the queenside.} a5 {Black must stop it.} 13. Qc2 ({White could also start with} 13. Ne4 {.}) 13... h6 ({Quite similar is} 13... O-O 14. Rad1 {, followed by [Ne4].}) 14. Ne4 O-O 15. Rad1 e5 {This was Iturrizaga-Fier, Isle of Man 2023. The position is very complicated, probably balanced somehow, but easier to play for White after:} 16. Rfe1 {White is strong on the light squares and the majority on the queenside shouldn't be underestimated. Sometimes White might play [c4]-[c5], freeing the [c4]-square for the bishop and making the jump [Nd6] possible.} *

