1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 {The Zukertort system is characterized by [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], often in combination with a later [Ne5] and [f2]-[f4]. The long-term goal is an attack on the kingside! Please notice that I wasn't so keen on it if Black had started with 3...c5 , because then the light-squared bishop could be developed actively on [g4]. Here, when [e7]-[e6] has already been played, the bishop is stuck behind the pawns.} Nc6 6. O-O ({The moves can be played in almost random order, so} 6. Bb2 {is also fine.}) 6... b6 {Black can try to solve the problems with the passive [Bc8].} 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. Nbd2 Bd6 9. dxc5 $5 ({Let's try this again.} 9. Ne5 {is of course the typical system move and also fine, but I prefer to open up for [Bb2].}) 9... bxc5 10. e4 (10. e4 {White has a good play. e4-e5 is a threat and after} Bc7 {Keymer-Bok, rapid 2024, White could have played} 11. Bxf6 {N} Qxf6 12. exd5 exd5 13. Re1+ {, and Black either has to move the king or allow} Ne7 14. Qe2 {which looks very promising for White. [Bb5]+ or just [Rad1] or [c2]-[c4] are nice options.}) *

