1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 {The Zukertort system is characterized by [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], often in combination with a later [Ne5] and [f2]-[f4]. The long-term goal is an attack on the kingside! Please notice that I wasn't so keen on it if Black had started with 3...c5 , because then the light-squared bishop could be developed actively on [g4]. Here, when [e7]-[e6] has already been played, the bishop is stuck behind the pawns.} Nc6 6. O-O ({The moves can be played in almost random order, so} 6. Bb2 {is also fine.}) 6... Bd6 ({Or} 6... Be7 {will lead to the same thing. And 6...cxd4 transpose to 5...cxd4 .}) 7. dxc5 $5 {A modern solution, which I like.} ({A more traditional way of playing is} 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2 b6 9. a3 Bb7 10. Ne5 Rc8 11. f4 Ne7 12. Qf3 {, planning [Qh3] with complicated play.}) 7... Bxc5 8. Bb2 {[%csl Gb2] The bishop is nice now with no pawns blocking it.} O-O 9. Nbd2 {...or first 9.a3 , it doesn't really matter.} Qe7 ({If} 9... Nb4 10. Be2 {then White will play [a2]-[a3] and kick the knight back. ( On 9...Re8 I like the immediate 10.c4! with good play. Black doesn't have time to play e5 in a good way: 10...e5 11.cxd5 Qxd5 12.Bc4 Qd7 13.Ng5 Rf8 and here is the nice positional move 14.Nde4 gave White a strong positional initiative in an email game. )}) 10. a3 {[%csl Gb4] Intending to play [b3]-[b4] and also preventing [Nb4] for good.} ({The move} 10. c4 {could also be considered.}) 10... e5 {[%cal Ge5e4] Black seeks counterplay in the centre. The threat is [e5]-[e4] winning a piece. White can meet the idea with a cunning counterstrike.} ({If} 10... a5 {, it weakens the queenside. After} 11. c4 {White has a good play.}) 11. b4 Bb6 12. b5 {[%csl Ge5] The [e5]-pawn hangs, so Black is forced to push it.} e4 13. bxc6 bxc6 ({Not} 13... exd3 14. cxb7 $1 {a fun line goes:} dxc2 15. bxc8=N {and White wins.}) 14. Bxf6 $1 gxf6 {This is forced.} ({After} 14... Qxf6 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Bxe4 {White has won a pawn.}) 15. Be2 ({Here} 15. Nd4 {was also possible.}) 15... exf3 16. Nxf3 {[%csl Gf6,Gf7] White is for preference because of the superior pawn structure.} *

