1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 {The Zukertort system is characterized by [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], often in combination with a later [Ne5] and [f2]-[f4]. The long-term goal is an attack on the kingside! Please notice that I wasn't so keen on it if Black had started with 3...c5 , because then the light-squared bishop could be developed actively on [g4]. Here, when [e7]-[e6] has already been played, the bishop is stuck behind the pawns.} Nbd7 {This is a more passive square than [c6], but of course now it is not so attractive for White to play [dxc5], because Black can take back with the knight.} 6. O-O Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2 b6 9. Ne5 {White goes for the desired setup.} ({Now} 9. c4 {is met by} Bb7 {with complete symmetry. It looks equal.}) 9... Nxe5 {With the bishop on [e7] compared to on [d6] this move is possible.} 10. dxe5 Nd7 ({Also} 10... Ne8 11. f4 {is promising for White.}) 11. c4 $1 {A precise move that makes sure that we keep the initiative. After the standard} Bb7 12. cxd5 Bxd5 ({Not} 12... exd5 13. Qg4 {and White will soon get a strong attack.}) 13. f4 {[%cal Gd1g4] White is much better. The battle will take place on the kingside, where White has great potential. For starters the queen can go to [g4] or [h5]. Black majority on the queenside is useless here in the middlegame.} *

