1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 {The Zukertort system is characterized by [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], often in combination with a later [Ne5] and [f2]-[f4]. The long-term goal is an attack on the kingside! Please notice that I wasn't so keen on it if Black had started with 3...c5 , because then the light-squared bishop could be developed actively on [g4]. Here, when [e7]-[e6] has already been played, the bishop is stuck behind the pawns.} Nbd7 {This is a more passive square than [c6], but of course now it is not so attractive for White to play [dxc5], because Black can take back with the knight.} 6. O-O Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2 b6 9. Ne5 {White goes for the desired setup.} ({Now} 9. c4 {is met by} Bb7 {with complete symmetry. It looks equal.}) 9... Bb7 10. Qf3 $5 ({A little finesse. The by far most played move is the standard} 10. f4 {, but we can get the setup in an improved version.}) 10... Qc7 11. Qh3 {[%cal Ge5d7,Gd4c5,Gb2f6,Gh3h7]} (11. Qh3 {White is threatening to take on d7, then take on c5, and finally Bxf6 followed by mate on h7! After} h6 {or 11...g6 White plays 12.f4 with a typical Zukertort attack!}) *

