1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 {The Zukertort system is characterized by [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], often in combination with a later [Ne5] and [f2]-[f4]. The long-term goal is an attack on the kingside! Please notice that I wasn't so keen on it if Black had started with 3...c5 , because then the light-squared bishop could be developed actively on [g4]. Here, when [e7]-[e6] has already been played, the bishop is stuck behind the pawns.} Nbd7 {This is a more passive square than [c6], but of course now it is not so attractive for White to play [dxc5], because Black can take back with the knight.} 6. O-O Bd6 7. Bb2 Qc7 {[%csl Ge5] Black covers the [e5]-square.} 8. c4 $1 e5 {In a way, a desireable break. It leads to some simplifications and at the end of the day White is comfortable.} 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Bxe5 11. Bxe5 Qxe5 12. Nd2 O-O ({Or} 12... Bg4 13. Qc2 {.}) 13. cxd5 Qxd5 14. Qc2 (14. Qc2 {White is slightly better. Ne4 is a kind of threat, but also Nc4 is often strong. An important detail is that:} Rd8 {doesn't work because of} 15. Ne4 $1 Qxd3 16. Rfd1 {and the back rank hurts.}) *

