1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 {The Zukertort system is characterized by [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], often in combination with a later [Ne5] and [f2]-[f4]. The long-term goal is an attack on the kingside! Please notice that I wasn't so keen on it if Black had started with 3...c5 , because then the light-squared bishop could be developed actively on [g4]. Here, when [e7]-[e6] has already been played, the bishop is stuck behind the pawns.} Nbd7 {This is a more passive square than [c6], but of course now it is not so attractive for White to play [dxc5], because Black can take back with the knight.} 6. O-O Bd6 7. Bb2 Qc7 {[%csl Ge5] Black covers the [e5]-square.} 8. c4 $1 dxc4 9. bxc4 ({If you don't like the hanging pawns, then} 9. Bxc4 {also gives White an edge.}) 9... O-O 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3b5]} a6 {Black must prevent [Nb5].} 11. Qe2 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gc3e4] This is a new move. In general, White has a promising version of a hanging pawns position because there is no pressure against the centre at all. Of course, clinically speaking there are no hanging pawns yet, but since Black can take on [d4] any move, it makes sense to talk about it! Next comes [Rad1] and maybe [Ne4] to open up for the white pieces.} ({There were other good moves as well: •} 11. d5 exd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. cxd5 {looks pretty dangerous for Black with two threatening white bishops.}) ({• Also the more positional} 11. Qc2 h6 12. Ne4 {must be better for White.}) *

