1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 {The Zukertort system is characterized by [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], often in combination with a later [Ne5] and [f2]-[f4]. The long-term goal is an attack on the kingside! Please notice that I wasn't so keen on it if Black had started with 3...c5 , because then the light-squared bishop could be developed actively on [g4]. Here, when [e7]-[e6] has already been played, the bishop is stuck behind the pawns.} Nbd7 {This is a more passive square than [c6], but of course now it is not so attractive for White to play [dxc5], because Black can take back with the knight.} 6. O-O Bd6 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2 {White finishes the first part of the typical setup. Black needs to solve the problem with [Bc8]. It belongs on [b7], so [b7]-[b6] or first [Qc7], and then [b7]-[b6] is the most natural. Black has other moves as well, but we can always play [c2]-[c4] or [Ne5] with interesting play. I will not go into too much detail. This Zukertort alternative is meant as inspiration, not a complete repertoire on its own!} b6 9. Ne5 {Going for the Zukertort setup.} Bb7 ({If} 9... Qc7 {, then we are in time to protect the knight with} 10. f4 {.}) 10. f4 {The standard setup.} ({It is also possible to start with} 10. Qe2 {, and wait a move or two with [f2]-[f4].}) 10... Ne4 {A critical line. Otherwise, White can take control over the [e4]-square with [Qf3].} 11. Nxe4 {White has to eliminate the knight before Black can safeguard it with [f7]-[f5].} dxe4 12. Bc4 {The pawn on [e4] is not weak, but it blocks the [b7]-bishop.} Nxe5 13. dxe5 $1 {This is the right recapture.} ({The following line,} 13. fxe5 Be7 {is not so clear. Black will try to get counterplay and push White back with [a7]-[a6] and [b6]-[b5].}) 13... Be7 14. Qg4 $1 (14. Qg4 {A novelty! White has a strong initiative on the kingside. The move f4-f5 is already a threat. If Black tries to get counterplay with} Qd2 {, then the cool} 15. Qg3 {keeps control, and Balck can't play} Qxc2 {because after} 16. Rf2 {the queen is lost.}) *

