1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 {The Zukertort system is characterized by [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], often in combination with a later [Ne5] and [f2]-[f4]. The long-term goal is an attack on the kingside! Please notice that I wasn't so keen on it if Black had started with 3...c5 , because then the light-squared bishop could be developed actively on [g4]. Here, when [e7]-[e6] has already been played, the bishop is stuck behind the pawns.} Nbd7 {This is a more passive square than [c6], but of course now it is not so attractive for White to play [dxc5], because Black can take back with the knight.} 6. O-O Bd6 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2 {White finishes the first part of the typical setup. Black needs to solve the problem with [Bc8]. It belongs on [b7], so [b7]-[b6] or first [Qc7], and then [b7]-[b6] is the most natural. Black has other moves as well, but we can always play [c2]-[c4] or [Ne5] with interesting play. I will not go into too much detail. This Zukertort alternative is meant as inspiration, not a complete repertoire on its own!} Qc7 {This covers the [e5]-square, but sometimes the move-order matters. Here White has an extra interesting idea.} 9. c4 $1 {With the queen on [c7] and the knight on [d7], the hanging pawns structure is favourable for White.} b6 ({After} 9... cxd4 10. exd4 b6 11. Rc1 {the queen looks silly on [c7].}) {Or 10...dxc4 11.bxc4 b6 12.Qe2 and White is very comfortable.} 10. cxd5 exd5 11. e4 $5 {This is it. White could also play more positionally with [Rc1], but why not grab the initiative?} cxd4 12. Rc1 {[%cal Gc1c7] Winning a nice tempo.} Qb8 13. exd5 {Opening the position.} Nc5 14. Bb1 Nxd5 15. Ne4 {[%csl Gd4] White has a strong initiative. We will regain the pawn on [d4] and have very active pieces.} *

