1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 {The Zukertort system is characterized by [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], often in combination with a later [Ne5] and [f2]-[f4]. The long-term goal is an attack on the kingside! Please notice that I wasn't so keen on it if Black had started with 3...c5 , because then the light-squared bishop could be developed actively on [g4]. Here, when [e7]-[e6] has already been played, the bishop is stuck behind the pawns.} b6 {Black first develop the queenside.} 6. O-O Bb7 7. Bb2 {If Black plays Nc6 or Nbd7 it will transpose to other lines.} Bd6 ({Similar to Bd6 is} 7... Be7 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. dxc5 $5 bxc5 10. c4 {the engine calls it equal, but White scores really well in top games.}) 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. dxc5 $5 ({I focus on this move once more. The standard} 9. Ne5 {is the most played and it leads to traditional positions when White protects the knight with [f2]-[f4] in Zukertort style.}) 9... bxc5 ({After the solid} 9... Bxc5 10. c4 {White keeps a small positional initiative in a rather balanced game. The point is that it is fully playable for White! We put the queen on [e2], centralize the rooks, and see what happens.}) 10. c4 {It was not possible to play [e3]-[e4].} Nc6 11. a3 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gd1c2,Gb2g7,Gd3h7] Covering the [b4]-square. White will play [Qc2] next, probably followed by [Rad1]. The position seems balanced, but the white bishops are strong.} *

