1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 {The Zukertort system is characterized by [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], often in combination with a later [Ne5] and [f2]-[f4]. The long-term goal is an attack on the kingside! Please notice that I wasn't so keen on it if Black had started with 3...c5 , because then the light-squared bishop could be developed actively on [g4]. Here, when [e7]-[e6] has already been played, the bishop is stuck behind the pawns.} cxd4 {Black's most important strategic decision: should [cxd4] be played or not. As usual, there are pros and cons. Keeping the tension means that White sometimes has the extra option to play [dxc5] and open up the long diagonal for [Bb2], but taking on [d4] determines the central structure which makes it harder for Black to get counterplay.} 6. exd4 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. Bb2 b6 $5 {[%cal Gc8a6]} ({Here} 8... Nc6 {is normal with a transposition to the mainline. The idea behind [b7]-[b6] is perhaps to play [Ba6], which is possible because the knight is still on [b8].}) 9. Re1 {An intelligent waiting move. If Black plays [Ba6] I plan to answer [c4], and then maybe the knight will be better placed on [c3], depending on what happens.} (9. Nbd2 Ba6 10. c4 {. Nc6 11.Rc1 Rc8 has been played in some games. I think Black is ok.}) 9... Ba6 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Ga6d3] The independent idea.} ({If} 9... Bb7 10. Nbd2 {, then, I guess,} Nc6 {with a transposition to mainline.}) 10. c4 {[%cal Gb1c3] White avoids the exchange of the strong [Bd3]. Next up is [Nc3] with a fine position. Probably, Black will have to lose a tempo and play [Bb7] anyway.} *

