1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 {The Zukertort system is characterized by [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], often in combination with a later [Ne5] and [f2]-[f4]. The long-term goal is an attack on the kingside! Please notice that I wasn't so keen on it if Black had started with 3...c5 , because then the light-squared bishop could be developed actively on [g4]. Here, when [e7]-[e6] has already been played, the bishop is stuck behind the pawns.} cxd4 {Black's most important strategic decision: should [cxd4] be played or not. As usual, there are pros and cons. Keeping the tension means that White sometimes has the extra option to play [dxc5] and open up the long diagonal for [Bb2], but taking on [d4] determines the central structure which makes it harder for Black to get counterplay.} 6. exd4 Nc6 {The most natural and by far the most played move. It is possible to start by developing the dark-squared bishop and castle, but it is more than likely that Black sooner or later will play [Nc6] with a transposition.} (6... Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Bb2 b6 9. Re1 {is similar to 6...[Bd6].}) 7. O-O Be7 {Is also very popular.} 8. Bb2 O-O 9. a3 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gc6b4]} ({Sooner or later, this move has to be played to prevent Nb4. It is possible to start with} 9. Nbd2 {because} Nb4 10. Be2 b6 11. a3 Nc6 12. Bd3 {is just a transposition.}) 9... b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] The bishop belongs on [b7].} 10. Nbd2 Bb7 11. Qe2 {[%csl Ge4] The queen is good here. White has excellent control over the [e4]-square. The plan is to follow up with [Ne5], and then it is important that Black can't play [Nxe5] followed by [Ne4].} Rc8 12. Ne5 {White can also stay calm and improve the position first with [Rfe1] and [Rac1].} Qc7 {A deep move.} 13. f4 ({The prophylactic} 13. Rac1 {that protects [c2] might be better.}) 13... Nxe5 {If Black doesn't take, White has a nice position with a good grip.} 14. fxe5 Ne4 $1 {The point of [Qc7]. If White takes on [e4], [c2] will be hanging in the end.} 15. a4 $5 {Taking some space. It is a really difficult position for both sides.} h6 {Played in two email games.} ({Black could try} 15... Bg5 16. Nf3 Be7 {hoping to repeat moves. White can keep the game going with} 17. Qe3 {.}) 16. Rae1 ({The email games went} 16. Bxe4 dxe4 17. c4 Qc6 {and Black can break with [f7]-[f6] with good counterplay.}) 16... Bb4 {[%cal Gb4e1] The most natural.} 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. c4 Qc6 19. Rf2 (19. Rf2 {This is a probably better version for White than the email games. Still, after} a6 {, followed by ...[b6]-[b5], it is far from clear.}) *

