1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 {The Zukertort system is characterized by [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], often in combination with a later [Ne5] and [f2]-[f4]. The long-term goal is an attack on the kingside! Please notice that I wasn't so keen on it if Black had started with 3...c5 , because then the light-squared bishop could be developed actively on [g4]. Here, when [e7]-[e6] has already been played, the bishop is stuck behind the pawns.} cxd4 {Black's most important strategic decision: should [cxd4] be played or not. As usual, there are pros and cons. Keeping the tension means that White sometimes has the extra option to play [dxc5] and open up the long diagonal for [Bb2], but taking on [d4] determines the central structure which makes it harder for Black to get counterplay.} 6. exd4 Nc6 {The most natural and by far the most played move. It is possible to start by developing the dark-squared bishop and castle, but it is more than likely that Black sooner or later will play [Nc6] with a transposition.} (6... Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Bb2 b6 9. Re1 {is similar to 6...[Bd6].}) 7. O-O Be7 {Is also very popular.} 8. Bb2 O-O 9. a3 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gc6b4]} ({Sooner or later, this move has to be played to prevent Nb4. It is possible to start with} 9. Nbd2 {because} Nb4 10. Be2 b6 11. a3 Nc6 12. Bd3 {is just a transposition.}) 9... b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] The bishop belongs on [b7].} 10. Nbd2 Bb7 11. Qe2 {[%csl Ge4] The queen is good here. White has excellent control over the [e4]-square. The plan is to follow up with [Ne5], and then it is important that Black can't play [Nxe5] followed by [Ne4].} Rc8 12. Ne5 {White can also stay calm and improve the position first with [Rfe1] and [Rac1].} Nxe5 {This is possible, when the bishop is on [e7] instead of on [d6].} 13. dxe5 Nd7 14. b4 $1 {[%csl Gc5] A nice positional move, that covers [c5] and prevents [Nc5].} a5 {[%csl Gb4] Black confronts the important [b4]-pawn.} 15. c3 {So White protects it. It is of less importance that [Bb2] is locked inside, what matters is that Black's pieces completely lack good squares.} d4 $5 {The best chance. If Black plays more quiet, White will stabilize the position with [f2]-[f4] and [Nf3], and then it will be too late for Black to do anything active.} 16. cxd4 axb4 {The point. Black regains the pawn.} 17. axb4 Bxb4 18. Ne4 (18. Ne4 {White has a promising position. A sample line goes:} Ra8 19. Rxa8 Bxa8 20. Bc1 {, a nice regrouping. After} Bd5 21. Ng5 g6 22. h4 {, all play takes place on the kingside, and there White is clearly better.}) *

