1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 {The Zukertort system is characterized by [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], often in combination with a later [Ne5] and [f2]-[f4]. The long-term goal is an attack on the kingside! Please notice that I wasn't so keen on it if Black had started with 3...c5 , because then the light-squared bishop could be developed actively on [g4]. Here, when [e7]-[e6] has already been played, the bishop is stuck behind the pawns.} cxd4 {Black's most important strategic decision: should [cxd4] be played or not. As usual, there are pros and cons. Keeping the tension means that White sometimes has the extra option to play [dxc5] and open up the long diagonal for [Bb2], but taking on [d4] determines the central structure which makes it harder for Black to get counterplay.} 6. exd4 Nc6 {The most natural and by far the most played move. It is possible to start by developing the dark-squared bishop and castle, but it is more than likely that Black sooner or later will play [Nc6] with a transposition.} (6... Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Bb2 b6 9. Re1 {is similar to 6...[Bd6].}) 7. O-O Bd6 {The most active square for the bishop.} ({The line} 7... Nb4 8. Be2 Be7 9. a3 Nc6 10. Bd3 {will just transpose to normal lines.}) 8. Bb2 O-O 9. a3 ({Sooner or later this must be played to prevent Nb4. It was possible to start with} 9. Nbd2 {.}) 9... b6 10. Nbd2 Bb7 {An important position in the Zukertort system.} 11. Ne5 {A key move. We might as well play it at once.} (11. Ne5 Rc8 {the most played.} 12. Qe2 {now the game transposes to the mainline after} Ne7 {or 12...a5 13.f4 Ne7 .}) (11. Ne5 Qc7 {it is not clear that [Qc7] is a good move. White just continues with the normal} 12. Qe2 {or 12.f4 , and again Black's best setup involves [Ne7].}) 11... Nd7 12. f4 f5 {This is a radical attempt to stop White's attack before it even got started. Positionally, it is ugly though!} 13. Qe2 Ndxe5 {It Black doesn't take, then the backwards [e6] pawn is pretty weak.} 14. fxe5 Be7 15. Kh1 {[%cal Gg2g4] Next comes [g2]-[g4] and White gets huge pressure. Typically, White will play [Rg1] and [Raf1] to bring in more power.} *

