{And on 21.g4 Bxe5 comes. The engine manages to hold Black's position somehow, but it will be difficult for an unprepared human at the board!} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 {The Zukertort system is characterized by [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], often in combination with a later [Ne5] and [f2]-[f4]. The long-term goal is an attack on the kingside! Please notice that I wasn't so keen on it if Black had started with 3...c5 , because then the light-squared bishop could be developed actively on [g4]. Here, when [e7]-[e6] has already been played, the bishop is stuck behind the pawns.} cxd4 {Black's most important strategic decision: should [cxd4] be played or not. As usual, there are pros and cons. Keeping the tension means that White sometimes has the extra option to play [dxc5] and open up the long diagonal for [Bb2], but taking on [d4] determines the central structure which makes it harder for Black to get counterplay.} 6. exd4 Nc6 {The most natural and by far the most played move. It is possible to start by developing the dark-squared bishop and castle, but it is more than likely that Black sooner or later will play [Nc6] with a transposition.} (6... Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Bb2 b6 9. Re1 {is similar to 6...[Bd6].}) 7. O-O Bd6 {The most active square for the bishop.} ({The line} 7... Nb4 8. Be2 Be7 9. a3 Nc6 10. Bd3 {will just transpose to normal lines.}) 8. Bb2 O-O 9. a3 ({Sooner or later this must be played to prevent Nb4. It was possible to start with} 9. Nbd2 {.}) 9... b6 10. Nbd2 Bb7 {An important position in the Zukertort system.} 11. Ne5 {A key move. We might as well play it at once.} (11. Ne5 Rc8 {the most played.} 12. Qe2 {now the game transposes to the mainline after} Ne7 {or 12...a5 13.f4 Ne7 .}) (11. Ne5 Qc7 {it is not clear that [Qc7] is a good move. White just continues with the normal} 12. Qe2 {or 12.f4 , and again Black's best setup involves [Ne7].}) 11... Ne7 {[%cal Ge7f5] A good regrouping. The knight is on the way to [f5], where it helps to defend the kingside, primarily by just being there.} (11... Rc8 {the most played.} 12. Qe2 {now the game transposes to the mainline after} Ne7 {or 12...a5 13.f4 Ne7 .}) (11... Qc7 {it is not clear that [Qc7] is a good move. White just continues with the normal} 12. Qe2 {or 12.f4 , and again Black's best setup involves [Ne7].}) 12. Qe2 {[%csl Ge4] A perfect square for the queen, keeping an eye on [e4] just in case. And also makes room for [Ra1] to join the forthcoming battle.} Rc8 ({Wrong is} 12... Ng6 13. f4 {with a strong grip. White could even consider taking on [g6] and playing without [f2]-[f4]. That also looks good.}) 13. f4 {This move is a vital part of the system, so we might as well play it now.} (13. Rae1 {could also be considered, but when in doubt: Play the move that you know you have to play!}) 13... a5 $5 {A strange move, because it weakens the [b5]-square, but it is a computer favourite, so we better check it!} 14. c3 {A new deep move. Now the [c2]-pawn is never hanging, so Black can't play [b5] - we just take it!} ({The most popular move is} 14. Rf3 {with the idea to play [Rh3] and attack. After} b5 $1 15. Rh3 h6 $1 {it is surprisingly difficult to break through. Black is ready to play [b4] and often [Ne4] as a positional pawn sacrifice, like} 16. g4 Ne4 $1 17. Nxe4 dxe4 18. Bxe4 Bxe4 19. Qxe4 Bxe5 20. fxe5 b4 {, and Black has a good play with a nice square on [d5].}) (14. Rac1 {to protect [c2] is also a good prophylactic move.}) 14... a4 {A natural follow-up.} ({Here} 14... Nf5 15. g4 Nh4 16. a4 {looks good for White, who will build up on the kingside and never allow any counterplay on the other flank.}) 15. b4 {[%csl Ga4] Maybe the black a-pawn will be weak.} Nf5 {This clever move is the idea of 11...Ne7 .} 16. Rf3 {[%cal Gf3h3] Making a rook lift to add more firepower.} (16. g4 Nh4 {is pretty unclear, but of course playable for White.}) 16... Be7 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf5d6] A nice preparation for the regrouping [Nf5]-[d6] when Black controls the important [e4]-square.} 17. Rh3 g6 18. Bb5 (18. Bb5 {Suddenly attacking the a-pawn. The position is very complex but after} Ra8 19. Qd1 {the a-pawn is doomed. The engine doesn't panic and offers} Nh5 20. Rf3 Bd6 {with counterplay. If} 21. Bxa4 {then} Qh4 {is strong.}) *

