a5 13.f4 Ne7 .}) (11... Qc7 {it is not clear that [Qc7] is a good move. White just continues with the normal} 12. Qe2 {or 12.f4 , and again Black's best setup involves [Ne7].}) 12. Qe2 {[%csl Ge4] A perfect square for the queen, keeping an eye on [e4] just in case. And also makes room for [Ra1] to join the forthcoming battle.} Rc8 ({Wrong is} 12... Ng6 13. f4 {with a strong grip. White could even consider taking on [g6] and playing without [f2]-[f4]. That also looks good.}) 13. f4 {This move is a vital part of the system, so we might as well play it now.} (13. Rae1 {could also be considered, but when in doubt: Play the move that you know you have to play!}) 13... g6 {This asks for trouble.} 14. g4 {Now Black won't get [Nf5] in.} ({Also fine was} 14. Rae1 {.}) 14... Ne8 {[%cal Gf1f2,Ga1f1,Gf4f5] This is passive, but Black needs to be careful. White can quickly bring in more troops with [Rf2] and [Raf1] and maybe break with [f4]-[f5].} 15. Rae1 ({In some email games White has played} 15. Qe3 {, but I prefer to active the last rook.}) 15... f6 16. Bc1 $5 (16. Bc1 {But we just leave it where it is! This is a really dangerous position for Black. Taking the knight is bad:} fxe5 17. fxe5 Rxf1+ 18. Rxf1 Bb8 19. Qf2 Ng7 20. Qf7+ Kh8 21. Nf3 Qe8 22. Ng5 {and even exchange won't save Black.} Qxf7 23. Nxf7+ Kg8 24. Nh6+ Kh8 25. Rf7 Re8 26. Bg5 Ng8 27. Rxb7 {and White is completely winning.}) *

