1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Bd3 c5 5. b3 {The Zukertort system is characterized by [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], often in combination with a later [Ne5] and [f2]-[f4]. The long-term goal is an attack on the kingside! Please notice that I wasn't so keen on it if Black had started with 3...c5 , because then the light-squared bishop could be developed actively on [g4]. Here, when [e7]-[e6] has already been played, the bishop is stuck behind the pawns.} cxd4 {Black's most important strategic decision: should [cxd4] be played or not. As usual, there are pros and cons. Keeping the tension means that White sometimes has the extra option to play [dxc5] and open up the long diagonal for [Bb2], but taking on [d4] determines the central structure which makes it harder for Black to get counterplay.} 6. exd4 Nc6 {The most natural and by far the most played move. It is possible to start by developing the dark-squared bishop and castle, but it is more than likely that Black sooner or later will play [Nc6] with a transposition.} (6... Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Bb2 b6 9. Re1 {is similar to 6...[Bd6].}) 7. O-O Bd6 {The most active square for the bishop.} ({The line} 7... Nb4 8. Be2 Be7 9. a3 Nc6 10. Bd3 {will just transpose to normal lines.}) 8. Bb2 O-O 9. a3 ({Sooner or later this must be played to prevent Nb4. It was possible to start with} 9. Nbd2 {.}) 9... b6 10. Nbd2 Bb7 {An important position in the Zukertort system.} 11. Ne5 {A key move. We might as well play it at once.} (11. Ne5 Rc8 {the most played.} 12. Qe2 {now the game transposes to the mainline after} Ne7 {or 12...a5 13.f4 Ne7 .}) (11. Ne5 Qc7 {it is not clear that [Qc7] is a good move. White just continues with the normal} 12. Qe2 {or 12.f4 , and again Black's best setup involves [Ne7].}) 11... Ne7 {[%cal Ge7f5] A good regrouping. The knight is on the way to [f5], where it helps to defend the kingside, primarily by just being there.} (11... Rc8 {the most played.} 12. Qe2 {now the game transposes to the mainline after} Ne7 {or 12...a5 13.f4 Ne7 .}) (11... Qc7 {it is not clear that [Qc7] is a good move. White just continues with the normal} 12. Qe2 {or 12.f4 , and again Black's best setup involves [Ne7].}) 12. Qe2 {[%csl Ge4] A perfect square for the queen, keeping an eye on [e4] just in case. And also makes room for [Ra1] to join the forthcoming battle.} Rc8 ({Wrong is} 12... Ng6 13. f4 {with a strong grip. White could even consider taking on [g6] and playing without [f2]-[f4]. That also looks good.}) 13. f4 {This move is a vital part of the system, so we might as well play it now.} (13. Rae1 {could also be considered, but when in doubt: Play the move that you know you have to play!}) 13... Nf5 {The most interesting setup and the idea behind [Ne7]. It is a really demanding position to play for both sides and it is hard to judge. Intuitively, you should think that White will get a huge attack with [g4], but the engines show that Black's position is hard to break.} 14. g4 {Anyway, this is the consequent attacking move. It is important to play it at once before Black can play [Be7], allowing the knight to retreat to [d6] and later jump to [e4].} Nh4 15. c3 ({A quiet move that secures the structure.} 15. Rf2 {, followed by [Rad1] was also possible; or 15.Rae1 again: everybody joins the party! but here 15...Qe7 hitting [a3] is a little annoying. After 15. [c3] I prefer White, but the position is complicated, and balanced even according to the engine.}) (15. c3 {An email game continued:} Rc7 16. a4 Nd7 17. Rad1 Qe7 18. Rf2 {, and Black's lack of counterplay is beginning to be a problem, maybe not for a computer but surely for a human!}) *

