1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 {A flexible move order, especially popular among Nimzo/Queen's Indian players.} 3. e3 (3. e3 {We stay true to our repertoire. Black's by far two most popular moves are} c5 {and b6 . They will be covered in depth in the next chapters. Of course, there is also 3...d5 with a direct transposition to the Colle. In this introduction I will mention a few rare alternatives and then show a Model Game of mine, that illustrates what can happen if Black plays too flexibly.}) 3... Be7 {It always makes sense to develop.} ({•} 3... Nc6 {is a weird move in the style of the Tango 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 Nc6 . 4.a3 taking control over [b4] and maybe even preparing to play [b2]-[b4]. Of course, many other moves are also good. 4...d5 5.Nbd2 ( Also good is 5.b3 , followed by [Bb2]. ) 5...Bd6 6.b4Ν , a logical novelty. 6...e5 ( After 6...O-O 7.Bb2 White has control over [e5]. ) 7.b5 e4 , forced. 8.bxc6 exf3 9.Nxf3 bxc6 10.c4 White is slightly better because of the superior pawn structure. 10...dxc4 ( After 10...O-O 11.c5! Be7 12.Qc2 Black really lacks space. White will follow up with [Bd3] with a dominant position. ) And 11.Qc2 that avoids 11.Bxc4 Bf5 which of course is also fine for White, but after 11. [Qc2], followed by [Bxc4] White has a pleasant position with the better pawn structure.}) ({•} 3... g6 {, mixing [e7]-[e6] and [g7]-[g6] looks strange.} 4. b3 $5 {I like this setup, which we will see again in the Anti-King's Indian chapter.} Bg7 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Be2 {White has a very harmonious position.} d5 {with the pawn already on [e6] this is more natural than playing with [d7]-[d6].} 7. O-O {White will play [c2]-[c4] or [Nbd2] first and then [c2]-[c4] with a slight edge.}) ({•} 3... d6 {very flexible, but allowing White to take the centre.} 4. Bd3 Nbd7 {, intending [e6]-[e5]. ( If 4...Be7 5.e4 ⩲)} 5. O-O e5 6. Nbd2 $5 {a new move. ( The natural 6.e4 Be7 actually transposes to a position from 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Bd3 . It is also good for White, but I would like to introduce a different approach. ) If} Be7 {, then} 7. dxe5 {, simplifying to make it easier to play.} dxe5 8. b3 {, intending [Bb2] with pressure on [e5].} O-O 9. Bb2 Bd6 10. e4 {White is better in this almost symmetrical position. Next, we play [Nc4].}) 4. Bd3 O-O ({Here it would be natural to transpose to a normal Colle with} 4... d5 {.}) 5. e4 {We take the centre.} d5 {Black can't just sit and wait, while we build up.} 6. e5 {Now we get a French type of position.} Nfd7 ({Nobody has tried} 6... Ne4 {. After the simple} 7. Nbd2 {White is better.}) 7. h4 {[%csl Gh7][%cal Gd3h7,Gf3g5,Gd1h5] A strong move. Already White can start a furious attack and Black might be blown away. We threaten to take on [h7] and play [Ng5]. Let's see what could happen if Black prevents it.} h6 ({The natural} 7... c5 $2 {loses at once after} 8. Bxh7+ Kxh7 9. Ng5+ {.}) 8. Rh3 $1 {[%csl Gh6][%cal Gh3g3] Planning [Rg3]. It turns out that [h6] is also a target.} c5 9. Bxh6 $1 {White crashes through.} gxh6 10. Rg3+ Kh8 11. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2h6] And it is all over.} *

