1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O {This was another game of mine from the research phase. In the theory chapter you will se that the immediate [Nbd2] was more precise.} c5 6. Nbd2 d6 7. c3 {White creates the Colle structure.} Nbd7 8. e4 $1 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] Taking space in the centre.} Qc7 9. Re1 Rd8 $6 {It was clear that my opponent had to find every single move by himself. It costs a lot of time and the results were not always worth the effort.} ({Normal was} 9... Be7 {but White has a pleasant position with the centre.}) 10. d5 $1 {Going for a superior structure forever.} (10. e5 Nd5 {(10...dxe5 11.dxe5 Nd5 (11...Ng4 12.Qa4!) 12.Qa4 ±)} 11. Nc4 h6 {⩲}) (10. Nf1 Be7 11. Ng3 {.}) 10... e5 {Not a nice move to play, but White was threatening to take on [e6] and play [Ng5], and opening the e-file with [exd5] was certainly out of the question.} 11. a4 a6 {Black has to stop [a5].} (11... Be7 12. a5 O-O 13. axb6 axb6 14. Bb5 {gives White a grip on the light squares.}) 12. Qe2 {[%csl Ga6]} Ra8 {A forced loss of time.} 13. Nc4 h6 $6 ({This was the last chance for} 13... Be7 {followed by [O-O].}) 14. Nh4 g6 {Otherwise comes [Nf5].} 15. f4 {White has a strong initiative. Suddenly the play is very concrete and sharp.} exf4 16. Bxf4 Nh5 ({Not} 16... g5 17. e5 {and White breaks through.}) 17. Be3 Ne5 18. Nf3 {Getting the knight back into play.} ({Maybe better} 18. Nxe5 $1 dxe5 19. Nf3 {.}) 18... Nxc4 19. Bxc4 Bg7 20. Qd2 $1 {[%csl Gh6] Hitting [h6] and preventing Black from castling.} Qd7 21. Bd3 {So the bishop can't be hit by [b5].} Nf6 22. Bf4 Ng4 {Preventing [e4]-[e5].} 23. h3 $1 Ne5 24. Nxe5 dxe5 25. Be3 {White is strategically winning. Black still can't castle and the queenside is vulnerable too.} Qd6 26. b4 $1 cxb4 27. cxb4 Bf8 ({Also horrible is} 27... h5 28. a5 b5 29. Bc5) 28. Qf2 Be7 {The best.} (28... Qxb4 {allows} 29. Qf6 $1 Rh7 30. Qxe5+ {and White is completely winning.}) 29. Bxb6 Qxb4 30. Be3 {Threatening [Rab1].} Qc3 31. Qe2 h5 {Will Black manage to castle?} 32. Rec1 Qa5 33. Qb2 $1 {[%cal Gb2b7,Gb2e5] With a decisive doublethreat.} Bc8 34. Qxe5 f6 35. Qg3 g5 36. Qf2 $6 {In time trouble I play a little too safe, just enjoying the extra pawn and the good position.} (36. e5 $1 {wins at once:} Qxd5 37. Bg6+ Kf8 38. exf6 Bxf6 39. Rf1 Kg7 40. Rxf6 $1 Kxf6 41. Bc2 {and [Rd1] or [Rf1]+ follows.}) 36... g4 37. h4 Bd7 38. Rc4 $6 ({Again} 38. e5 $1 {was strong.}) 38... Rb8 39. Rac1 Rg8 40. g3 Rb3 41. Bf1 Kf7 42. Rc7 $1 {With extra time it was easy to conclude the attack.} Rd8 ({On} 42... Qxa4 43. e5 {or 43.Bc4 decides.}) 43. e5 $1 Rxe3 ({Not} 43... Qxd5 44. Bc4 {.}) 44. Qxe3 fxe5 45. Qh6 $1 {The queen penetrates.} Bf6 46. Qh7+ Bg7 47. Qf5+ Ke8 48. Qg6+ Kf8 49. Bd3 ({I had planned} 49. Bd3 Qxd5 50. Rf1+ {( The computer gives 50.Bc4! Qd4+ 51.Kf1 and Black has to give the queen to avoid immediate mate. )} Ke7 51. Qxg7+ Kd6 52. Rxd7+ Rxd7 53. Qf8+ Kc7 54. Rc1+) 1-0

