1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 {The Queen's Indian move. The bishop will be nice on [b7].} 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. Nbd2 ({The most precise. More natural is} 5. O-O {which in nearly all cases will just transpose, but Black might play} d5 {and we can't get the desired setup with [Qe2] and [e4] in time. As we saw in the Model Games, I played 5. [O-O] myself when I had the position in a game in the Danish league. It was played at the time when I was researching for this course, so I wasn't sure exactly what moves to play. I knew the grander picture, but not all the details!}) 5... c5 {A natural strike that tries to distract White from taking the centre.} 6. O-O Nc6 7. c3 Qc7 $5 (7... Be7 8. e4 {is nice for White and 7...d5 8.Re1 transposes to the 3...c5 Colle.}) 8. a3 {A necessary preparation for the desirable [e3]-[e4].} ({The immediate} 8. e4 {is met by} cxd4 9. cxd4 Nb4 10. Bb1 Rc8 {, followed by [Nc2] with good play for Black.}) 8... d5 ({Good for White is} 8... Be7 9. e4 {.}) 9. e4 $1 {White takes the initiative. We are not afraid of playing with an isolated pawn if we are calling the shots. The black queen is rather vulnerable on [c7] if the c-file opens up.} cxd4 ({Or} 9... dxe4 10. Nxe4 {and if Black doesn't take on [d4], White is just better.}) 10. cxd4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 {[%csl Gd4] A critical position. White has an isolated d-pawn, so it is crucial to grasp the initiative. If play slows down, Black might be better.} Be7 {The only move that has been played.} ({The piece trade} 11... Nxe4 12. Bxe4 {only activates White's bishop.}) 12. Nxf6+ ({A strong novelty in connection with the following move. However,} 12. Bg5 {is also fine.}) 12... Bxf6 13. d5 $1 {A standard move in many IQP positions.} exd5 ({Declining with} 13... Ne5 {might be best but after} 14. Bb5+ {Black is forced to play} Kf8 {, not many players would like that, but the position is not so clear. At least White can get some positional advantage in an ending after} 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. Bc6 Bxc6 17. dxc6 Qc7 18. Qa4 Rc8 19. Be3 Qxc6 20. Qxa7 Bxb2 21. Rab1 Ra8 22. Qxb6 Qxb6 23. Bxb6 {because} Bxa3 $2 24. Ra1 {loses a piece for Black.}) 14. Re1+ {White has great play for the pawn.} Kf8 15. h4 (15. h4 {It will be very hard for Black to liberate the position. Having a king on f8 is never fun. A sample line goes:} h6 16. h5 Kg8 17. Qa4 Rf8 18. Bf4 Qd7 19. Rac1 {with big pressure. Pawn grabbing loses:} Bxb2 $2 20. Rc2 Bf6 21. Bb5 $1 Rc8 22. Rec1 {, and knight is gone.}) *

