1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 {The Queen's Indian move. The bishop will be nice on [b7].} 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. Nbd2 ({The most precise. More natural is} 5. O-O {which in nearly all cases will just transpose, but Black might play} d5 {and we can't get the desired setup with [Qe2] and [e4] in time. As we saw in the Model Games, I played 5. [O-O] myself when I had the position in a game in the Danish league. It was played at the time when I was researching for this course, so I wasn't sure exactly what moves to play. I knew the grander picture, but not all the details!}) 5... c5 {A natural strike that tries to distract White from taking the centre.} 6. O-O cxd4 {Changing the structure is a popular choice among Queen's Indian players, who are reluctant to enter Colle positions with [d5].} 7. exd4 Be7 8. Re1 {Typical, White will play [Re1], [c2]-[c3] and [a2]-[a4]. You can do it in any order. Sometimes, White instead chooses a setup with [b2]-[b3], [Bb2], and [c2]-[c4], but that is another story.} O-O 9. c3 d6 {Black goes for flexibility.} 10. a4 {The standard setup. White might push the a-pawn further to create a weakness in Black's structure on the queenside.} a6 {So Black always can meet [a4]-[a5] with [b6]-[b5]. Anyway, the move [a7]-[a6] is a vital part of Black's hedgehog setup.} 11. Nc4 ({More common is} 11. Nf1 Nbd7 12. Ng3 {or first 11.Qe2 but 11. [Nc4] contains a specific idea.}) 11... Nbd7 12. Bf4 {[%csl Gd6] This is it. The pawn on [d6] is under attack.} Qc7 13. Ne3 (13. Ne3 {I think White is slightly better here. The next phase is about maneuvering. A sample line goes:} Rfe8 14. Nd2 {N} Bf8 15. Bg3 {so the bishop will not be hit by [e6]-[e5]. The position is strategically complex, but I prefer White.}) *

