1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 {The Queen's Indian move. The bishop will be nice on [b7].} 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. Nbd2 ({The most precise. More natural is} 5. O-O {which in nearly all cases will just transpose, but Black might play} d5 {and we can't get the desired setup with [Qe2] and [e4] in time. As we saw in the Model Games, I played 5. [O-O] myself when I had the position in a game in the Danish league. It was played at the time when I was researching for this course, so I wasn't sure exactly what moves to play. I knew the grander picture, but not all the details!}) 5... c5 {A natural strike that tries to distract White from taking the centre.} 6. O-O Be7 {Here White has several well explored setups, like [c2]-[c3] followed by [Qe2] or [b2]-[b3] followed by [Bb2]. Instead, I would like to surprise the opponent with an unusual idea.} 7. e4 $5 c4 {Exchanging the c-pawn for White's e-pawn loses time.} 8. Bxc4 Nxe4 9. Nxe4 Bxe4 10. d5 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gb8c6]} ({White is much better.} 10. d5 {is even stronger than 10.Re1 , which has been played in all games, reaching the position. With [d4]-[d5] we take space in the centre and make it hard for Black to get [Nb8] into play. Next, we can attack the bishop on [e4]. Taking on [d5] would leave Black with a sick structure and a really bad game.}) *

