1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 {The Queen's Indian move. The bishop will be nice on [b7].} 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. Nbd2 ({The most precise. More natural is} 5. O-O {which in nearly all cases will just transpose, but Black might play} d5 {and we can't get the desired setup with [Qe2] and [e4] in time. As we saw in the Model Games, I played 5. [O-O] myself when I had the position in a game in the Danish league. It was played at the time when I was researching for this course, so I wasn't sure exactly what moves to play. I knew the grander picture, but not all the details!}) 5... c5 {A natural strike that tries to distract White from taking the centre.} 6. O-O Be7 {Here White has several well explored setups, like [c2]-[c3] followed by [Qe2] or [b2]-[b3] followed by [Bb2]. Instead, I would like to surprise the opponent with an unusual idea.} 7. e4 $5 cxd4 8. e5 $1 {The point.} Nd5 9. Nxd4 {Suddenly it looks more like a Sicilian than a Colle! But it also looks like White has good chances!} Nc6 {Immediately confronting White's centralized knight.} 10. Nxc6 {We lose no time!} Bxc6 (10... dxc6 11. Qg4 {is nice for White.}) 11. Nf3 Qc7 12. a3 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gc2c4] Covering [b4]. White is ready to play [c2]-[c4].} b5 {So Black prevents it.} 13. Re1 {[%csl Ge5] Protecting the e-pawn.} O-O 14. Nd4 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gd4c6] White had a good position in an email game. The [b5]-pawn is attacked and in worst case White can take the bishop pair.} *

