1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 {The Queen's Indian move. The bishop will be nice on [b7].} 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. Nbd2 ({The most precise. More natural is} 5. O-O {which in nearly all cases will just transpose, but Black might play} d5 {and we can't get the desired setup with [Qe2] and [e4] in time. As we saw in the Model Games, I played 5. [O-O] myself when I had the position in a game in the Danish league. It was played at the time when I was researching for this course, so I wasn't sure exactly what moves to play. I knew the grander picture, but not all the details!}) 5... c5 {A natural strike that tries to distract White from taking the centre.} 6. O-O Be7 {Here White has several well explored setups, like [c2]-[c3] followed by [Qe2] or [b2]-[b3] followed by [Bb2]. Instead, I would like to surprise the opponent with an unusual idea.} 7. e4 $5 cxd4 8. e5 $1 {The point.} Nd5 9. Nxd4 {Suddenly it looks more like a Sicilian than a Colle! But it also looks like White has good chances!} O-O 10. Be4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge4b7,Gc2c4] Pinning the knight and threatening [c2]-[c4].} ({Playing with the knight,} 10. N2f3 {, also looks fine.}) 10... Qc8 {Black protects the bishop.} 11. c4 Nb4 (11... Nb4 {This has been played in some games, where White continued} 12. a3 {. Much stronger is:}) 12. Qg4 (12. Qg4 {Black is in trouble. A sample line goes:} N8c6 13. Nxc6 {(13.N4f3 is also interesting. )} Bxc6 14. a3 Na6 {( Not 14...Bxe4 15.Nxe4 Nc6 16.Bh6 . )} 15. Bc2 $1 {keeping the bishop. White has good attacking chances.}) 12... N8c6 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. a3 Na6 15. Bc2 $1 {Keeping the bishop. White has good attacking chances.} *

