1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 b6 {The Queen's Indian move. The bishop will be nice on [b7].} 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. Nbd2 ({The most precise. More natural is} 5. O-O {which in nearly all cases will just transpose, but Black might play} d5 {and we can't get the desired setup with [Qe2] and [e4] in time. As we saw in the Model Games, I played 5. [O-O] myself when I had the position in a game in the Danish league. It was played at the time when I was researching for this course, so I wasn't sure exactly what moves to play. I knew the grander picture, but not all the details!}) 5... Be7 {Black could also consider ...[c5].} ({The position after} 5... d5 6. Qe2 $1 {, intending [e3]-[e4] we know from the Colle section.}) 6. e4 {We go forward, when we have the chance.} d6 ({A usual} 6... d5 7. e5 Nfd7 8. O-O {leads to a somewhat better Frech for White.}) ({And} 6... c5 {can be met} 7. c3 {, just keeping the structure and a positional plus.}) 7. O-O O-O ({Or} 7... Nbd7 8. Re1 e5 9. c3 {, and White has a pleasant advantage.}) 8. c3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Gf1e1,Gd2f1,Gf1g3] White is slightly, but very comfortably, better with a nice centre. Next [Re1] and then probably the regrouping [Nd2]-[f1]-[g3]. Later play in the centre or on either side of the board depending of what Black does.} *

