1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 c5 {A good move that attacks the white central pawn. Very often it will transpose to other chapters: the Colle if Black continues with [d7]-[d5], or the Queen's Indian setup if Black plays an early [b7]-[b6]. There are a few independent lines though, which we will soon discover.} 4. Bd3 ({We nearly always play this. That is not to say it is the only move. White can choose different setups: •} 4. c3 {with a Semi-Slav structure. • 4.b3 , followed by [Bb2] with a Zukertort position.}) 4... Nc6 5. O-O Be7 (5... d5 {is a Colle.}) 6. dxc5 ({Tempting because Black has already moved the bishop and will lose a tempo to regain the pawn. White's most popular move is} 6. b3 {with a Zukertort setup.}) ({For us it would make sense to play} 6. c3 O-O 7. Nbd2 {with a standard position.}) 6... Bxc5 7. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc1b2] Intending to expand with [b2]-[b4] and [Bb2].} d5 ({Or} 7... a5 8. c4 {and White is very comfortable. The knight can come to [c3].}) 8. b4 Bd6 9. c4 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gb1d2] White has a pleasant position. If Black doesn't do anything drastic we will continue with [Bb2] and [Nbd2] with a harmonious setup.} *

