1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 c5 {A good move that attacks the white central pawn. Very often it will transpose to other chapters: the Colle if Black continues with [d7]-[d5], or the Queen's Indian setup if Black plays an early [b7]-[b6]. There are a few independent lines though, which we will soon discover.} 4. Bd3 ({We nearly always play this. That is not to say it is the only move. White can choose different setups: •} 4. c3 {with a Semi-Slav structure. • 4.b3 , followed by [Bb2] with a Zukertort position.}) 4... Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. Nbd2 (6. Nbd2 {Now play is more or less bound to transpose to lines we have seen elsewhere, like} b6 7. e4 $1 cxd4 8. e5 Nd5 9. Nxd4 Bb7 10. Be4 {.}) ({Also possible is} 6. dxc5 $5 Bxc5 7. c4 {or the standard 6.b3 .}) *

