1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 c5 {A good move that attacks the white central pawn. Very often it will transpose to other chapters: the Colle if Black continues with [d7]-[d5], or the Queen's Indian setup if Black plays an early [b7]-[b6]. There are a few independent lines though, which we will soon discover.} 4. Bd3 ({We nearly always play this. That is not to say it is the only move. White can choose different setups: •} 4. c3 {with a Semi-Slav structure. • 4.b3 , followed by [Bb2] with a Zukertort position.}) 4... b6 ({The move} 4... d5 {leads immediately to the Colle, where White already has played [Bd3]. Since that is our general setup, it is no problem, of course.}) ({The position after} 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 {has been covered in the 3...b6 move order.}) 5. O-O Ba6 {[%csl Gd3] Black would like to exchange the white super bishop on [d3].} ({The position after} 5... Bb7 6. Nbd2 {was covered in detail in the 3...[b6] chapter. Here I will just mention that because our knight is not on [d2] already we have a sharper approach available: 6.c4 Be7 7.Nc3 , the mainline goes: 7...cxd4 8.exd4 d5 ( This is quite dangerous, so Black could consider 8...d6 or; 8...O-O but White should be better in any case. ) 9.cxd5 Nxd5 10.Ne5 O-O 11.Qg4! White has a huge score here. 11...Nf6 (11...f5 12.Qe2  ) 12.Qh4 with a lot of pressure, for instance, 12...Ne4 13.Qh3! Qxd4 14.Bf4 Nf6 15.Ne2 , and Black is in trouble. So this 6. [c4] line is definitely worth investigating further on your own, but it is outside the scope of this repertoire. I prefer to keep things as simple as possible and just transpose to lines we already know.}) 6. Bxa6 Nxa6 7. e4 $1 {This direct move gives White the initiative. Black is behind in development and the knight is stranded on [a6] for the time being.} d6 {Black tries to keep the position closed.} 8. c4 {[%csl Ga6][%cal Gd1a4,Ga4e8] I like what Aryan Tari just did. The text move threatens [Qa4]+ so Black is forced to lose more time.} ({However,} 8. Qe2 Nc7 9. Rd1 {also looks very strong.}) 8... Nb8 9. Nc3 ({The immediate} 9. d5 {would have prevented any [cxd4] ideas for Black, not that they are any good.}) 9... Be7 10. d5 $1 {[%csl Gd5] White has a large positional advantage with more space and the good bishop, Tari-Fuentes, blitz 2023.} *

