1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 c5 {A good move that attacks the white central pawn. Very often it will transpose to other chapters: the Colle if Black continues with [d7]-[d5], or the Queen's Indian setup if Black plays an early [b7]-[b6]. There are a few independent lines though, which we will soon discover.} 4. Bd3 ({We nearly always play this. That is not to say it is the only move. White can choose different setups: •} 4. c3 {with a Semi-Slav structure. • 4.b3 , followed by [Bb2] with a Zukertort position.}) 4... b6 ({The move} 4... d5 {leads immediately to the Colle, where White already has played [Bd3]. Since that is our general setup, it is no problem, of course.}) ({The position after} 4... cxd4 5. exd4 b6 {has been covered in the 3...b6 move order.}) 5. O-O Ba6 {[%csl Gd3] Black would like to exchange the white super bishop on [d3].} ({The position after} 5... Bb7 6. Nbd2 {was covered in detail in the 3...[b6] chapter. Here I will just mention that because our knight is not on [d2] already we have a sharper approach available: 6.c4 Be7 7.Nc3 , the mainline goes: 7...cxd4 8.exd4 d5 ( This is quite dangerous, so Black could consider 8...d6 or; 8...O-O but White should be better in any case. ) 9.cxd5 Nxd5 10.Ne5 O-O 11.Qg4! White has a huge score here. 11...Nf6 (11...f5 12.Qe2  ) 12.Qh4 with a lot of pressure, for instance, 12...Ne4 13.Qh3! Qxd4 14.Bf4 Nf6 15.Ne2 , and Black is in trouble. So this 6. [c4] line is definitely worth investigating further on your own, but it is outside the scope of this repertoire. I prefer to keep things as simple as possible and just transpose to lines we already know.}) 6. Bxa6 Nxa6 7. e4 $1 {This direct move gives White the initiative. Black is behind in development and the knight is stranded on [a6] for the time being.} cxd4 {This leads to a kind of Sicilian.} ({The e-pawn is untouchable:} 7... Nxe4 $2 8. Qe2 {wins one of the knights.}) 8. e5 Nd5 9. Nxd4 {I prefer this, but it was also possible to take with the queen. Black has a difficult choice now.} Be7 10. Qg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4g7] The most precise. White immediately hits the [g7]-pawn.} ({The line,} 10. c4 Ndc7 11. Qg4 O-O 12. Bh6 Ne8 {wasn't that clear in Fries Nielsen-Neffe, Germany 2003, although also here White was better after} 13. Nd2 {.}) 10... Qc7 ({It was too depressing to play} 10... Kf8 {and 10...g6 weakens the kingside too much. The option, 10...O-O 11.Bh6 was, of course, out of the question.}) 11. Re1 {[%csl Ge5] Just protecting the important [e5]-pawn. White is much better as it isn't clear how Black should deal with the threat on the [g7]-pawn.} ({White could grab the pawn, but} 11. Qxg7 O-O-O {is more messy.}) *

