[PlyCount "27"]
[GameId "2164710461698465"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 {Here too we just play the solid move [e2]-[e3], preparing to finish the development of the kingside with [Be2] and [O-O]. Again, it is completely similar to my Queen's Gambit Declined repertoire with colours reversed, of course with an extra tempo. To begin with, I was going to suggest something else against 2...g6 , but then a friend of mine - who is also a GM - said: 'Why not play [e2]-[e3] anyway? It is good. The King's Indian is nothing to fear!'. So I went deeper inside the various lines after 3.e3 and soon discovered that they were indeed very playable for White, and also very easy for Black to underestimate because of their innocent appearance. So here we are!} Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O {Black has three main setups: • ...[c7]-[c5] and go for a Benoni which they won't get!. • ...[d7]-[d6] and go for a King's Indian which they won't get!. • ...[d7]-[d5] and go for a Grunfeld which they won't get!. Apart from these, there are also a few random lines, which I will cover here.} b6 {This is actually a splendid move. Black will fianchetto the light-squared bishop. Of course, we could do the same and play [b3]. It doesn't give much though and there is something much more in the spirit of the position.} (5... c6 {this is a typical semi-waiting move in King's Indian positions.} 6. b4 $5 {( White could also play the simple 6.c4 in general we refrain from it and in this case, the move 6. [b4]!? is very tempting. ) The pawn move} d5 {is the obvious move. ( And 6...a5 is met by 7.b5 . ) ( And 6...d6 7.Bb2 is a good version of the King's Indian. ) After} 7. Nbd2 {the position should be compared with the Colle-section. In the Colle, we played a quick [c2]-[c4] to put Black's centre under pressure and kind of force the response ...[c7]-[c6]. Here the black pawn is already on [c6], so we can just develop.} a5 {, the most played. ( If Black develops the bishop 7...Bf5 I think we should just take more space on the queenside with 8.a4 . ) ( Similarly after 7...Bg4 8.a4 White has comfortable play. )} 8. b5 c5 {Black uses the long diagonal to get a kind of reversed Catalan. ( After 8...cxb5 9.Bxb5 Bd7 10.Rb1 White keeps a lot of pressure on the black queenside. )} 9. dxc5 {a strong exchange sacrifice suggested by Stockfish.} Ne4 10. Nxe4 Bxa1 11. Ng3 Bg7 12. Ba3 {White has a pawn for the exchange and the pawns on [b5] and [c5] take away a lot of squares for the black pieces. It looks highly promising for White.}) 6. c4 $1 {The principled move. We shouldn't fall asleep just because we play the Colle! It is important to take our chances and change direction whenever it is appropriate.} ({The following line,} 6. b3 Bb7 7. Bb2 {, has been played many times. I like the setup in general, but here there is a concrete problem:} c5 8. c4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 {so far so good. Most players continue with [Nc6] or [d7]-[d6] now when everything is sort of under control. Strong is:} d5 $1 {and Black equalizes on the spot, for instance} 10. Nd2 Nc6 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Bf3 Rc8 {.}) 6... Bb7 7. Nc3 {Now Black has several plausible moves. All in all, White can expect to be slightly better with the extra space.} d5 {The Grunfeld move.} ({•} 7... d6 {Black stays flexible in King's Indian style.} 8. Qc2 {, controlling [e4].} Nbd7 9. Rd1 {trying to make it hard for Black to achieve the standard [e5]-break.} Re8 10. e4 $1 e5 11. d5 {this is a normal King's Indian position with a totally misplaced black bishop on [b7]. White is much better.}) ({•} 7... e6 {a kind of Queen's Indian, albeit with the bishop on [g7] instead of on [e7].} 8. b4 {White grabs extra space.} d6 {( On 8...d5 I recommend the new move 9.Qb3Ν with the idea 9...dxc4 10.Qxc4 . Probably White will follow up with [a4] and [Ba3] with some pressure. ) (8...a5 can't be good. After 9.b5 White has too much space, for instance 9...d6 10.Qc2 Nbd7 11.Ba3 It is hard for Black to get [e5] in and White will play for the [c5] break. ) (8...c5 is met by 9.bxc5 bxc5 10.Ba3 Na6 and now the strong 11.Qa4Ν White is ready to increase the pressure with [Rab1]. )} 9. Qc2 {, controlling the [e4]-square.} Nbd7 10. Rb1 {( The former World Champion Ding Liren has played 10.Ba3 , but I prefer the little rook move. An email game went: )} c5 11. bxc5 dxc5 12. Rd1 cxd4 13. exd4 {the hanging pawns are well protected and quite strong.} Rc8 14. a4 {White was in control. The bishop can come to [a3]. Black lacks space and counterplay. It is important that Black can't take on [f3]:} Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Rxc4 16. Qb3 Rc8 17. Ba3 Re8 18. Nb5 {and Black is in big trouble.}) ({•} 7... Ne4 {, trying to release some of the pressure through exchanges.} 8. Nxe4 Bxe4 9. d5 $1 {a nice move that cuts the bishops escape route.} Bxf3 {Sad, but there is nothing better.} 10. Bxf3 {White is better with extra space and the bishops.}) ({•} 7... c5 {the Benoni-move is hardly good with the bishop on [b7].} 8. d5 d6 9. e4 {White is just better. A plan is [Bf4], [Nd2], [Re1] with firm control. Later White can play for the [e4]-[e5] break with the help of the f-pawn.}) 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bd2 {[%cal Gd5c3,Gd2c3] An important move. Now [Nxc3] will always be met by [Bxc3]. Black doesn't get the usual Grunfeld to play against the white centre.} Nd7 ({The continuation} 9... Nxc3 10. Bxc3 Nd7 11. Qa4 a6 12. Rfd1 {was pleasant for White in Melkumyan-Gupta, Poland 2016. Black is rather cramped and doesn't have any freeing breaks available.}) 10. Nxd5 {The most forcing.} Bxd5 11. Qc2 Nf6 {Controlling [e4].} ({The typical strike} 11... c5 {backfires after} 12. e4 $1 Bb7 13. d5 {and White is much better with the strong d-pawn.}) 12. Rfd1 {White is slightly better. In Paravyan-Alekseenko, Russia 2018 Black tried to liberate himself with...} c5 ({Also} 12... Be4 13. Qa4 {is pleasant for White. If} Qd7 14. Qa6 {, and moves like [Rac1] or [Ne5] are in the air.}) 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Bc3 $1 {White was much better with good pieces and a sound pawn structure.} *

