[PlyCount "47"]
[GameId "2164710461723042"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 {Please notice the move order. If White goes for a flexible set-up involving the moves [e2]-[e3] and [b2]-[b3] there are usually many transpositions.} g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. Be2 d6 6. d4 {We are slowly but surely getting into our repertoire.} Nbd7 7. O-O {White's setup looks quite innocent, but its appearance might make Black underestimate what we are doing. In fact we have a very sound position.} e5 8. dxe5 {This surprising change of the structure is generally good for White.} Ng4 {[%cal Gg7b2] This way, using the pin of the [e5]-pawn, Black regains material, but White has a strong positional idea.} 9. c4 Ngxe5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 {The most natural.} (10... dxe5 11. Qc2 {followed by [Rd1] is also pleasant for White.}) 11. Qd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2b2,Gf2f4] The queen protects the bishop on [b2]. White intends [f2]-[f4] to grab space and force [Ne5] back and exchange the good King's Indian bishop on [g7].} Re8 12. f4 Nd7 ({Or} 12... Ng4 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Bxg4 Bxg4 15. Nc3 {and White is much better.}) 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Nc3 {Black lacks space and there is no way to create counterplay. In the game Black tries to fight for the centre, but this only makes White's play easier.} f5 15. Bf3 {[%cal Gf3a8] The bishop is nice here.} Rb8 16. Qd4+ Qf6 17. Nb5 $1 {White wins material.} c5 ({Or} 17... Qxd4 18. exd4 {and [c7] falls. If} c6 {, then} 19. Nxd6 Re6 20. c5 {.}) 18. Qd2 {[%csl Gd6] Now [d6] is hanging.} Nf8 19. Nc7 $1 {Going to [d5].} Rd8 20. Nd5 {The black queen is expelled from the long diagonal.} Qf7 21. Qc3+ Kh6 ({Or} 21... Kg8 22. Nf6+ Kh8 23. Nd7+ {and [Nxb8].}) 22. Be2 {[%csl Gh6][%cal Gf1f3,Gf3h3] Intending [Rf3]-[h3] mate!} Qg7 23. Qe1 {[%cal Ge1h4] Threatening [Qh4] mate.} g5 24. Qg3 (24. Qg3 {Black is busted. The direct threat is Qh3 and Qh5 mate. If} g4 {then} 25. Qh4+ {isn't mate, but there is a free rook on [d8].}) 1-0

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Colle System"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
