[White "Overview & Model Games: Anti King's Indian"]
[Black "Anton, D. - Shyam"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "E61"]
[PlyCount "95"]
[GameId "2164710461731235"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. b4 {Again, please notice the somewhat avantgarde move-order.} Bg7 4. Bb2 d6 5. e3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Re8 8. Nc3 Nbd7 9. d4 e4 10. Nd2 {This is a really complicated middlegame. Black plays the legendary King's Indian Defence. Though it sounds scary to face, White has a lot of resources, and the modern engines believe in our play on the queenside without being afraid of the attack. However, some caution is needed. Like a friend of mine said: Yes, White is better the whole game, just until you are mated! I know this line is not for everybody's liking, so my main suggestion is the more positional [b3]-setup without [c4], but this is truly fascinating stuff - and the engine might be right that this is simply good for White. By the way, I also gave the line with reversed colours as my suggestion for Black in my Queen's Gambit Declined course, so I also believe in it!} Nf8 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gc8f5] Black wants a setup with [h5] and [Bf5]. Later the [f8]-knight can come out to [h7] and [g5].} 11. a4 h5 12. a5 {[%cal Ga5a6] White just pushes the pawns on the queenside. In the game, Black decides to prevent [a5]-[a6] for good. In the theory section, I also check some alternatives.} a6 13. Qc2 Bf5 14. Rfc1 ({A good move. However, I suggest the novelty} 14. Rfb1 $1 {as a slight improvement, as you can see in the theory chapter. Both moves, 14.Rfc1 and 14.Rfb1 , are very subtle. The [f1]-rook is activated because White will primarily play on the queenside. But there is a much deeper idea: the white queen will drop back to [d1] and help to defend the kingside. So, by starting with the rook move, we make sure that the [f1]-rook wouldn't be cut off from the action on the queenside.}) 14... N8h7 15. Qd1 h4 {[%cal Gh4h3]} 16. h3 $1 {[%csl Gh3] A key move. It is necessary to stop Black from playing [h4]-[h3]. Of course, now the [h3]-pawn is a target, but Black is not strong enough to sacrifice on it in the next few moves.} Qd7 17. Nf1 Ng5 18. Nh2 Kh7 19. Rab1 Bh6 20. Nd5 {This changes the structure and opens the c-file for White's rook.} ({Perhaps stronger was} 20. Ng4 $1 {with a big advantage. Exchanges are good for White, and if} Nh5 21. Nd5 {looks good.}) 20... Nxd5 21. cxd5 Rec8 22. Bc3 {[%cal Gb4b5] White wants to play [b4]-[b5] with some initiative.} b5 $5 23. axb6 cxb6 24. b5 a5 ({Better was} 24... axb5 25. Bxb5 Qe7 {and anything could still happen.}) 25. Bb2 {[%csl Gc6] Now there is a juicy square on [c6] for a rook.} Rxc1 26. Rxc1 Qd8 ({Or} 26... Rc8 27. Rc6 $1) 27. Bg4 $1 {[%csl Gf5] Exchanging the light-squared bishop that still could defend the [c6]-square.} Bxg4 28. Qxg4 f5 29. Qe2 $1 {White keeps control.} (29. Qxh4 a4 30. Ba3 Ra5 {would give Black counterplay.}) 29... Kg8 30. Rc6 Nh7 31. Nf1 {[%cal Gf1d2,Gd2c4] The passive knight has done its duty in the defence. Now it is on the way to greener pastures.} Nf6 32. Nd2 Bf8 33. Ba3 Rb8 34. Nc4 Ne8 {Black is tied to the defence of the weak [b6]- and [d6]-pawns. White opens the kingside and activates the queen.} 35. f3 exf3 36. Qxf3 Rb7 37. Qf4 {[%csl Gd6] Black's position is beginning to crack.} Kh7 38. Nxd6 Nxd6 39. Bxd6 Bh6 40. Qe5 Rd7 41. Kf2 {A cool move, just defending [e3].} f4 42. exf4 Bg7 43. Qe6 Bxd4+ 44. Kf3 Rg7 45. Rc8 Qd7 46. Qxd7 Rxd7 47. Ke4 Bf6 48. Be5 {A really impressive game by White.} 1-0

