1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 {This is clearly the most played move and among King's Indian afficionados it is a must.} 6. b3 {This little positional move is my main recommendation. White wants to follow up with [Bb2] and try to keep as much control as possible while aiming for a small, but long-term edge.} ({• I will not disappoint more hardcore players and chicken out so easily, so I give} 6. c4 {as an alternative, where White is allowing the feared King's Indian attack! • After 6.b3 Black has two major plans: going for a ...[c7]-[c5] setup or trying to get ...[e7]-[e5] in, either directly or by preparing it with ...[Nc6] or ...[Nbd7]. There exist a few other possibilities, which we will see straight away.}) 6... b6 {Black also prepares to fianchetto the queenside bishop.} ({•} 6... c6 7. Bb2 {White is going for the usual setup, while Black is more or less obliged to play Nbd7 sooner than later, which will transpose to the 6...Nbd7 chapter.}) ({•} 6... a5 {, a natural reaction in the AlphaZero times in which we live. Here, White can just ignore Black's plan.} 7. Bb2 a4 8. b4 {White is better. It isn't clear what the black pawn is doing on [a4].}) 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. c4 {This line should be compared with 5...b6 from the Introduction chapter. There we played [c2]-[c4] straight away, here we had already committed to a [b3]-setup.} Nbd7 {The natural square for the knight.} ({If} 8... e6 {, then} 9. Qc2 $5 {is similar to the mainline. The black knight belongs on [d7] in this structure.}) 9. Qc2 $5 ({A Nakamura speciality. It avoids} 9. Nc3 Ne4 {where Black tries to ease the tension by exchanging a pair of knights. This is not really a problem, also here White is slightly better after} 10. Nxe4 ({or just} 10. Qc2) 10... Bxe4 11. Nd2 Bb7 12. Bf3 {, exchanging Black's strong bishop.}) 9... Be4 10. Qc1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gb1c3] White is ready to play [Nc3].} Bb7 {Now we can improve the position with [Rd1] or use the fact that our queen now is on [c1] and go for the following.} 11. Nc3 Ne4 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. d5 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Gc1b2]} ({Also the simple} 13. Nd2 Bb7 14. Bf3 {gives White a small edge.}) 13... Bxb2 14. Qxb2 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 {[%csl Gc5,Ge5][%cal Gb3b4,Gf2f4] White is slightly better here. The knight looks good because Black apparently is strong on the dark squares, but in fact it is White's extra space that defines the position and the long-term prospects. White can take the [c5]-square away from the knight with [b3]-[b4] and the [e5]-square with [f2]-[f4]. The bishop can be activated later from for instance [h3]. The extra space makes White's position much easier to play for sure.} *

