1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 {This is clearly the most played move and among King's Indian afficionados it is a must.} 6. b3 {This little positional move is my main recommendation. White wants to follow up with [Bb2] and try to keep as much control as possible while aiming for a small, but long-term edge.} ({• I will not disappoint more hardcore players and chicken out so easily, so I give} 6. c4 {as an alternative, where White is allowing the feared King's Indian attack! • After 6.b3 Black has two major plans: going for a ...[c7]-[c5] setup or trying to get ...[e7]-[e5] in, either directly or by preparing it with ...[Nc6] or ...[Nbd7]. There exist a few other possibilities, which we will see straight away.}) 6... b6 {Black also prepares to fianchetto the queenside bishop.} ({•} 6... c6 7. Bb2 {White is going for the usual setup, while Black is more or less obliged to play Nbd7 sooner than later, which will transpose to the 6...Nbd7 chapter.}) ({•} 6... a5 {, a natural reaction in the AlphaZero times in which we live. Here, White can just ignore Black's plan.} 7. Bb2 a4 8. b4 {White is better. It isn't clear what the black pawn is doing on [a4].}) 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. c4 {This line should be compared with 5...b6 from the Introduction chapter. There we played [c2]-[c4] straight away, here we had already committed to a [b3]-setup.} Nbd7 {The natural square for the knight.} ({If} 8... e6 {, then} 9. Qc2 $5 {is similar to the mainline. The black knight belongs on [d7] in this structure.}) 9. Qc2 $5 ({A Nakamura speciality. It avoids} 9. Nc3 Ne4 {where Black tries to ease the tension by exchanging a pair of knights. This is not really a problem, also here White is slightly better after} 10. Nxe4 ({or just} 10. Qc2) 10... Bxe4 11. Nd2 Bb7 12. Bf3 {, exchanging Black's strong bishop.}) 9... e6 10. Nc3 {[%csl Ge4] White controls the [e4]-square, so there is no ...[Ne4] anymore.} Qe7 11. Rad1 a6 {Hedgehog-style. Black covers [b5].} 12. e4 $1 {[%cal Gf1e1,Ge4e5,Gd4d5] White goes forward and is definitely in control. Black is solid, but rather restrained. White can improve the position further by [Rfe1] and be ready to strike with [d4]-[d5] or [e4]-[e5].} *

