1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 {This is clearly the most played move and among King's Indian afficionados it is a must.} 6. b3 {This little positional move is my main recommendation. White wants to follow up with [Bb2] and try to keep as much control as possible while aiming for a small, but long-term edge.} ({• I will not disappoint more hardcore players and chicken out so easily, so I give} 6. c4 {as an alternative, where White is allowing the feared King's Indian attack! • After 6.b3 Black has two major plans: going for a ...[c7]-[c5] setup or trying to get ...[e7]-[e5] in, either directly or by preparing it with ...[Nc6] or ...[Nbd7]. There exist a few other possibilities, which we will see straight away.}) 6... b6 {Black also prepares to fianchetto the queenside bishop.} ({•} 6... c6 7. Bb2 {White is going for the usual setup, while Black is more or less obliged to play Nbd7 sooner than later, which will transpose to the 6...Nbd7 chapter.}) ({•} 6... a5 {, a natural reaction in the AlphaZero times in which we live. Here, White can just ignore Black's plan.} 7. Bb2 a4 8. b4 {White is better. It isn't clear what the black pawn is doing on [a4].}) 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. c4 {This line should be compared with 5...b6 from the Introduction chapter. There we played [c2]-[c4] straight away, here we had already committed to a [b3]-setup.} Nbd7 {The natural square for the knight.} ({If} 8... e6 {, then} 9. Qc2 $5 {is similar to the mainline. The black knight belongs on [d7] in this structure.}) 9. Qc2 $5 ({A Nakamura speciality. It avoids} 9. Nc3 Ne4 {where Black tries to ease the tension by exchanging a pair of knights. This is not really a problem, also here White is slightly better after} 10. Nxe4 ({or just} 10. Qc2) 10... Bxe4 11. Nd2 Bb7 12. Bf3 {, exchanging Black's strong bishop.}) 9... Ne4 10. Rd1 {White is very comfortable. The bishop on [b2] is protected and the rook on the d-file makes it hard for Black to liberate the position. Maybe, White doesn't have a real advantage yet, but clearly the easiest play, which in itself is an accomplishment. Let's see a couple of examples from Nakamura's games:} (10. Rd1 {•} f5 11. Nc3 e6 12. b4 {White took more space on the queenside.} Qe7 {this was Nakamura-Niemann, blitz 2024. Here} 13. Nd2 Nxd2 14. Qxd2 {would have given White better prospects because of the potential to advance further on the queenside.}) (10. Rd1 {•} a5 11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. Bxc3 f5 {Nakamura-Niemann, blitz 2024,} 13. Ng5 $1 Rf6 14. d5 {Black is completely outplayed.}) (10. Rd1 {•} e6 {Nakamura-Fressinet, blitz 2023. Also here [Nc3] is fine, but also} 11. b4 $5 {N, again taking more space.}) *

