1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3 c5 {[%cal Gg7a1] Using the power of the strong King's Indian bishop on [g7] to put pressure on the white centre.} 7. Bb2 b6 8. c4 Bb7 9. Nc3 Nbd7 {Black tries to stay flexible. This has been played many times. White can also just continue with small developing moves like [Qc2], but it is very tempting to close the centre.} 10. d5 {[%csl Gb7] Now [Bb7] is misplaced and White's extra space begins to be felt. Black's best is to exchange some pieces.} Ne4 11. Rc1 {The most precise. The white queen stays on the d-file to prevent ...[e7]-[e5].} ({The line after} 11. Qc2 Nxc3 12. Bxc3 Bxc3 13. Qxc3 e5 $1 {is not so clear.}) 11... Nxc3 12. Bxc3 Bxc3 13. Rxc3 {Here Black can't fix the centre with [e7]-[e5] so White will stabilize the position and have great long-term potential with the extra space.} *

