1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3 c5 {[%cal Gg7a1] Using the power of the strong King's Indian bishop on [g7] to put pressure on the white centre.} 7. Bb2 cxd4 {The critical continuation.} (7... Nc6 8. c4 {(8.d5 also looks strong. )} cxd4 9. Nxd4 {transposes to the mainline.}) (7... Nbd7 8. c4 {( also here 8.d5 looks good, but let's keep it simple. )} b6 {can transpose to 7...[b6].}) 8. Nxd4 $1 {[%csl Gb2]} ({An important move. White shouldn't block the bishop on b2. After} 8. exd4 d5 {the position is fine for Black, [Bb2] is passive, just shooting into its own d-pawn while [Bg7] is much more active.}) 8... Nc6 {The by far most played.} 9. c4 ({Also possible is} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. c4 {as played in many games by Nakamura. I like to keep the tension with 9. [c4] more.}) 9... Bd7 ({If} 9... Nxd4 {then recapture with the bishop} 10. Bxd4 {so it remains active.}) 10. Nc3 {Black has tried several moves here.} Nxd4 11. exd4 $1 {In this case, we take with the pawn. Black doesn't have control over [d5].} (11. Qxd4 Bc6 12. Qd2 {is possible, but Black seems to be doing ok.}) 11... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] The typical way of creating counterchances. Black will try to get ...[b7]-[b5] in.} 12. Bf3 {[%csl Gb7] A strong move that attacks [b7] and pin it at the same time.} Rb8 13. Re1 (13. Re1 {White has more space and some pressure. If} b5 {then} 14. cxb5 axb5 15. d5 $1 {secures the advantage. The white knight can go to [e2] and later maybe jump to [d4] and [c6].}) *

