1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3 c5 {[%cal Gg7a1] Using the power of the strong King's Indian bishop on [g7] to put pressure on the white centre.} 7. Bb2 cxd4 {The critical continuation.} (7... Nc6 8. c4 {(8.d5 also looks strong. )} cxd4 9. Nxd4 {transposes to the mainline.}) (7... Nbd7 8. c4 {( also here 8.d5 looks good, but let's keep it simple. )} b6 {can transpose to 7...[b6].}) 8. Nxd4 $1 {[%csl Gb2]} ({An important move. White shouldn't block the bishop on b2. After} 8. exd4 d5 {the position is fine for Black, [Bb2] is passive, just shooting into its own d-pawn while [Bg7] is much more active.}) 8... Nc6 {The by far most played.} 9. c4 ({Also possible is} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. c4 {as played in many games by Nakamura. I like to keep the tension with 9. [c4] more.}) 9... Bd7 ({If} 9... Nxd4 {then recapture with the bishop} 10. Bxd4 {so it remains active.}) 10. Nc3 {Black has tried several moves here.} Qa5 11. a3 {Getting ready to kick the queen away with [b3]-[b4].} Rfc8 12. b4 Qd8 {That's why Black took the f-rook.} 13. Rc1 (13. Rc1 {White has the easiest game. The lack of space makes it hard for Black to create counterplay. We can put the queen on b3 and the rook on d1 which looks good. Another idea is to play Nf3 to keep as many pieces on the board as possible, which is a good strategy when you have extra space. Maybe Black should take on d4:} Nxd4 14. exd4 {then the game can continue} e6 15. Qb3 b6 16. Rfe1 {White has the better chances.}) *

