1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3 c5 {[%cal Gg7a1] Using the power of the strong King's Indian bishop on [g7] to put pressure on the white centre.} 7. Bb2 cxd4 {The critical continuation.} (7... Nc6 8. c4 {(8.d5 also looks strong. )} cxd4 9. Nxd4 {transposes to the mainline.}) (7... Nbd7 8. c4 {( also here 8.d5 looks good, but let's keep it simple. )} b6 {can transpose to 7...[b6].}) 8. Nxd4 $1 {[%csl Gb2]} ({An important move. White shouldn't block the bishop on b2. After} 8. exd4 d5 {the position is fine for Black, [Bb2] is passive, just shooting into its own d-pawn while [Bg7] is much more active.}) 8... Nc6 {The by far most played.} 9. c4 ({Also possible is} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. c4 {as played in many games by Nakamura. I like to keep the tension with 9. [c4] more.}) 9... Bd7 ({If} 9... Nxd4 {then recapture with the bishop} 10. Bxd4 {so it remains active.}) 10. Nc3 {Black has tried several moves here.} a6 ({The inclusion of} 10... Rc8 11. Rc1 {doesn't change much.}) 11. Nf3 {A novelty in a position that has been played hundreds of times! The normal moves are [Rc1] or [Qd2], but the point of [Nf3] is that it avoids [Nxd4] which is a key move for Black in most of the lines.} Ne4 {Trying to exploit that we left the long diagonal open.} (11... Qa5 12. a3 {or 11...Rc8 12.Qd2 is quite comfortable for White.}) 12. Qc1 {Protecting the [b2]-bishop.} Nxc3 13. Bxc3 Bxc3 14. Qxc3 (14. Qxc3 {The position has been simplified, but White's extra space gives hope for the future. If} Qa5 {, then we should keep the queens on the board to get more winning chances} 15. Qb2 {, next we can centralize the rooks with [Rfd1] and [Rac1].}) *

