1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3 Nbd7 {[%cal Ge7e5] The most popular move. Black wants to get the typical King's Indian break ...[e7]-[e5] in, and because of certain issues on the [a1]-[h8] diagonal, we can't really prevent the plan. However, it turns out that the resulting positions are positionally better for White. This is important info! Few players are aware of this.} 7. Bb2 Re8 {The idea is still to go ...[e7]-[e5] as should be quite obvious, but Black prepares for it a little more.} 8. Nbd2 $5 {I want to suggest something original!} ({The normal} 8. c4 c6 ({or} 8... e5 9. dxe5) 9. Nc3 e5 10. Qc2 {is quite pleasant for White. It is a relative to the King's Indian attack, but there I propose a quick [b3]-[b4] for White, here we have already played the slower [b2]-[b3], so it is not a direct transposition.}) 8... e5 ({Waiting even further with} 8... c6 {can be met by} 9. a4 $5 e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Bc4 h6 12. e4 {and despite the simplifications White has a certain positional pull. The rook goes to [e1], maybe the a-pawn is pushed further. If Black goes [a7]-[a5] then the pawn can be weak after a subsequent [Bf1] and [Nc4].}) 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Bc4 $1 {[%csl Gf7] Targeting [f7].} h6 ({Not} 10... e4 11. Ng5 Re7 12. f3 $1 {and Black is busted.}) 11. e4 {I think White is slightly better with more active pieces. We will play [a2]-[a4] and put the rook on [e1], then everything is protected and it is easier for White to improve the position further, depending on what Black does.} *

