1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3 Nbd7 {[%cal Ge7e5] The most popular move. Black wants to get the typical King's Indian break ...[e7]-[e5] in, and because of certain issues on the [a1]-[h8] diagonal, we can't really prevent the plan. However, it turns out that the resulting positions are positionally better for White. This is important info! Few players are aware of this.} 7. Bb2 c6 8. Nbd2 $5 {Also here we refrain from the most played.} (8. c4 Qc7 9. Nc3 e5 10. Qc2 {like after 7...Re8 , White is better, but I prefer another route.}) 8... Qc7 9. c4 {OK, we finally play this. There is a very specific idea involved though.} e5 10. Qc2 {[%csl Ge4] Controlling the [e4]-square.} Re8 {Almost exclusively played.} ({The trade,} 10... exd4 11. Nxd4 {, is at least somewhat better for White.}) 11. c5 $1 {This is the point!} exd4 ({After} 11... dxc5 12. dxc5 {White is better. We will play [b3]-[b4] to protect the [c5]-pawn and then have ideas like [Nd2]-[c4]-[d6]. If Black plays [b7]-[b6] we just take it and put pressure on the c-file.}) 12. cxd6 {A little nice intermediate move.} Qxd6 13. Bxd4 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gd2c4,Gc2b2] White has a good play. A rook will come to [d1], maybe [Nc4] is strong, and maybe the queen will go to [b2] to increase the pressure on the long diagonal.} *

