1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3 Nbd7 {[%cal Ge7e5] The most popular move. Black wants to get the typical King's Indian break ...[e7]-[e5] in, and because of certain issues on the [a1]-[h8] diagonal, we can't really prevent the plan. However, it turns out that the resulting positions are positionally better for White. This is important info! Few players are aware of this.} 7. Bb2 e5 {The normal continuation. Why prepare the push even more, when it is possible to play right away? Well, some precaution is often suitable, also here!} 8. dxe5 Ng4 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gg7b2] This is the tactical justification of Black's play. The [e5]-pawn is pinned and will be regained.} 9. c4 $1 {We use the time to improve our structure.} Ngxe5 {The most logical recapture.} ({•} 9... Ndxe5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 {just transposes.}) ({•} 9... dxe5 10. h3 Nh6 {can hardly be recommended. After} 11. Qc2 Re8 12. Nc3 {White is much better, for instance,} e4 13. Nd2 f5 14. Rfd1 c6 15. c5 $1 Qe7 {has been played and now instead of sacrificing the c-pawn, White could have played the simple} 16. Bc4+ Kh8 17. b4 {with a good position. The knight can be regrouped with [Ne2].}) 10. Nxe5 ({I prefer this. The most popular is} 10. Nc3 {which is also not bad, but not as good!}) 10... dxe5 {The pawn structure is fixed now and White has the somewhat more free game.} 11. Qc2 Re8 12. Rd1 {Taking the open file.} Qg5 {Looks scary for White, but easy now: there is no attack!} 13. Nc3 Nf6 14. Nb5 $1 {The attack on [c7] is quite disturbing for Black.} (14. Nb5 {A sample line is:} Bh3 15. Bf1 Rec8 16. e4 Bg4 17. Re1 {White is better. We can push [c4]-[c5] next, and get extra space and a nice square con [c4] for the pieces.}) *

