1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3 e5 {Probably Black can get away with this without any preperation.} 7. dxe5 Ng4 8. Bb2 Nxe5 ({The move} 8... Nc6 {transposes to previous lines.}) 9. Nxe5 ({A decent alternative is} 9. Qc1 {. If} Bg4 {, then} 10. Nbd2 {.}) 9... dxe5 ({Black can try the rare} 9... Bxe5 {. If White exchanges on [e5], Black is probably ok, so I suggest} 10. Qc1 {, followed by [c2]-[c4]. If now} Qf6 {then [c2]-[c3] is interesting:} 11. c3 $5 {the bishop on [e5] doesn't feel that secure and after} Qe7 {we go} 12. c4 {anyway.}) 10. Qe1 ({More normal looking is} 10. Nc3 {which also gives White some pull.}) 10... Bf5 {[%csl Gc2] Attacking [c2].} 11. Qc3 {A cool move. The queen defends [c2] and prevents [e5]-[e4]. Play might continue:} Nd7 12. Nd2 Qe7 13. e4 Be6 14. Nc4 {[%cal Ga2a4,Gb2a3,Gc4a5] White is better. Sometimes [a2]-[a4] and [Ba3] can be annoying for Black, and also the simple [Na5] might cause some trouble.} *

