1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. b3 e5 {Probably Black can get away with this without any preperation.} 7. dxe5 dxe5 {The pawn can't be taken because of problems on the long diagonal. The open d-file means that the queens most likely will come off.} 8. Ba3 {[%cal Ga3f8] Gaining a tempo by attacking the black rook.} Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Re8 10. Nc3 e4 ({If Black doesn't play this White gets a comfortable position, for instance:} 10... Bf5 11. Nb5 Na6 12. Rac1 {, and the knight is quite annoying on [b5], where it attacks [a7] and can't be pushed back with [c7]-[c6] because of [Nd6].}) 11. Nd4 ({Or} 11. Nd2 a6 {with similar complicated play.}) 11... a6 {[%csl Gb5] Covering the [b5]-square.} 12. Bf1 {[%cal Ga3b2] The start of a longer regrouping. White will play [Bb2] which is possible after [Bf1], because the knight on [d4] can retreat to [e2] if hit by ...[c7]-[c5]. In general, the position is balanced, but the far-advanced black e-pawn might be weak, and it leaves a lot of squares behind that White can hope to exploit later.} *

