1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. c4 {This is the principled continuation.} c5 (6... c5 {Always a popular move, if Black is ready to play a Benoni after} 7. d5 {.}) 7. Nc3 {In this repertoire we don't hurry to play [d4]-[d5].} Nc6 {OK, if we are provoked then we do it!} 8. d5 $1 {This is just good for White. The black knight is forced to an inferior square.} Nb8 {Passive.} 9. h3 {Preventing [Bg4]. Of course, it was also possible to play [e3]-[e4] at once. White is very comfortable. I will just show what happens if Black tries to get a Modern Benoni type of game.} e6 10. e4 exd5 11. exd5 Re8 12. Bd3 {White controls the [e4]-square and at the same time is preventing [Bf5]. Black really lacks space.} (12. Bd3 {A sample line goes:} a6 13. Bf4 Qc7 14. Qd2 Nbd7 15. a4 {and White is clearly better. Black's only active continuation:} Ne5 {is met by} 16. Nxe5 dxe5 17. Bg5 {with strong positional pressure and a wonderful protected passed d-pawn.}) *

