1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. c4 {This is the principled continuation.} c5 (6... c5 {Always a popular move, if Black is ready to play a Benoni after} 7. d5 {.}) 7. Nc3 {In this repertoire we don't hurry to play [d4]-[d5].} Nc6 {OK, if we are provoked then we do it!} 8. d5 $1 {This is just good for White. The black knight is forced to an inferior square.} Na5 9. h3 {Again this little move. And again [e3]-[e4] was also fine!} e5 {Let's see this setup for a change.} 10. e4 {[%csl Ga5] The knight on [a5] is bad.} Nh5 {[%cal Gh5f4] Black seeks counterplay with [Nf4].} (10... h6 11. a3 b6 12. b4 Nb7 {was very passive for Black in Keymer-Indijc, blitz 2022.}) 11. Re1 {A well-known antidote from similar King's Indian positions.} Nf4 12. Bf1 $1 {This simple prophylactic regrouping is good. Later the black knight can be chased back with [g3].} (12. Bxf4 exf4 {is unclear.}) 12... b6 {[%cal Ga5b7] Sooner or later this move has to be played so the knight can get back.} 13. Kh2 {[%csl Gh3][%cal Gg2g3] Protecting [h3] and preparing [g2]-[g3].} Bd7 14. g3 Nh5 15. Rb1 {White is better in this strategically demanding position. Play will take place on the flanks. White will play [a2]-[a3] and [b2]-[b4], while Black will try to get [f7]-[f5] in. Playing [f7]-[f5] often weakens more than it helps, that is the problem for the black side, but of course, we don't need to care.} (15. Rb1 {A sample line goes:} Kh8 16. b3 f5 17. exf5 gxf5 {( Or 17...Bxf5 18.Bd3 with control over e4. )} 18. Ng5 Qe8 19. Be2 Nf6 20. Nb5 $1 Qb8 21. Ne6 {and Black is being outplayed on the light squares.}) *

