1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. c4 {This is the principled continuation.} c5 (6... c5 {Always a popular move, if Black is ready to play a Benoni after} 7. d5 {.}) 7. Nc3 {In this repertoire we don't hurry to play [d4]-[d5].} Bf5 {[%cal Gf6e4] This is a good move. The bishop gets out and Black prepares [Ne4]. Still, White keeps the upperhand.} 8. d5 {[%cal Gf3d2,Ge3e4]} ({The most played move is} 8. b3 {, but the text is stronger.}) 8... Ne4 {Otherwise White might play [Nd2] and [e3]-[e4] kicking the bishop home.} 9. Nxe4 Bxe4 10. Ng5 $1 {This specific idea is the reason why we entered this line. After the forced} Bf5 11. e4 Bc8 {On [d7] it takes a square away from the knight.} 12. f4 $1 {[%cal Ge4e5] White is having a nice position with a lot of potential in the centre with a later [e4]-[e5].} *

