1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. c4 {This is the principled continuation.} c5 (6... c5 {Always a popular move, if Black is ready to play a Benoni after} 7. d5 {.}) 7. Nc3 {In this repertoire we don't hurry to play [d4]-[d5].} cxd4 (7... Nbd7 {is rather passive. White can do almost anything, but in the light of the previous lines I will suggest} 8. d5 {and White has a good Benoni. The knight on d7 makes it hard for Black to play ...e7-e6 or ...e7-e5. If you don't like this, then the flexible 8.Qc2 or 8.b3 also seems fine.}) 8. exd4 Nc6 9. d5 {White expands with tempo.} Nb8 10. Nd4 {White has good control.} Nbd7 (10... Na6 11. Be3 {will probably transpose.}) 11. Be3 Nc5 12. Bf3 $1 (12. Bf3 {A nice move that keeps control over the e4-square. White has a pleasant position. Typical play continues:} a5 {to secure the knight on [c5].} 13. b3 Bd7 14. Re1 Re8 15. h3 Rc8 16. Qd2 {Black lacks counterplay and all active moves will backfire. White can slowly build up and later decide where to strike.}) *

