1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. c4 {This is the principled continuation.} c5 (6... c5 {Always a popular move, if Black is ready to play a Benoni after} 7. d5 {.}) 7. Nc3 {In this repertoire we don't hurry to play [d4]-[d5].} cxd4 (7... Nbd7 {is rather passive. White can do almost anything, but in the light of the previous lines I will suggest} 8. d5 {and White has a good Benoni. The knight on d7 makes it hard for Black to play ...e7-e6 or ...e7-e5. If you don't like this, then the flexible 8.Qc2 or 8.b3 also seems fine.}) 8. exd4 d5 {Going for a position with an isolated white d-pawn. In fact this is a reversed Tarrasch with two extra moves for White! That can't be bad.} 9. h3 {Preventing [Bg4].} Nc6 10. Re1 {Improving the rook. White is in no hurry to take on [d5].} dxc4 (10... Be6 11. c5 {is good for White.}) 11. Bxc4 Na5 12. Bf1 b6 {Intending [Bb7]. A sympathetic plan, sure, but Black will have no time to fulfill it.} (12... Be6 {almost asks for the positional exchange sacrifice} 13. Rxe6 $1 fxe6 14. Ng5 {, and White has great play. If Black protects [e6] with the queen then [Qe1] keeps the pressure.}) ({Also after} 12... a6 13. Bg5 {White has the initiative.}) 13. b4 {Launching a strong forcing sequence. Also fine were standard moves like [Ne5] or [Bg5].} Nc6 14. b5 Na5 15. Ba3 {[%csl Ge7]} Re8 16. Ne5 (16. Ne5 {White is clearly calling the shots. It will be hard for Black to defend. A sample line goes} Bb7 17. Qd2 Rc8 18. Bb4 e6 19. Rad1 Bf8 20. a3 {and it is hard to get out of the grip.}) *

