1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. c4 {This is the principled continuation.} Nc6 7. d5 $1 ({There is no need to allow} 7. Nc3 e5 {.}) 7... Ne5 ({White gets a good version of a classical King's Indian after} 7... Nb8 8. Nc3 e5 9. e4 {.}) 8. Nxe5 dxe5 9. Nc3 e6 {Attacking the white centre and getting rid of the double pawn.} 10. e4 exd5 11. cxd5 ({Creating even more imbalance with} 11. exd5 $5 {is also interesting.}) 11... Ne8 {[%cal Ge8d6] The knight will be excellent on [d6].} 12. Be3 Nd6 13. Rc1 (13. Rc1 {White's pressure down the c-file gives us the edge. A possible continuation is:} Bd7 14. Qd2 f5 15. exf5 gxf5 16. f4 $1 e4 17. Rc2 {, followed by [Rfc1] with strong pressure on the queenside. It is also nice that we can always play [Bd4] and exchange Black's strong bishop if we like.}) *

