1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. c4 {This is the principled continuation.} Nbd7 {Going for the legendary King's Indian Attack setup. I am pretty sure this is what you will face in at least 3 out of 4 games if Black is a King's Indian player, so it is a very important line. It also means that I will cover the other black setups a bit more lightly. Usually, it is White who plays the King's Indian Attack! It comes for instance after the moves 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 e6 4.O-O Be7 5.d3 O-O 6.Nbd2 c5 7.e4 Nc6 8.Re1 b5 9.e5 Nd7 . Although, White has won some nice attacking games I sincerely believe that Black is absolutely fine - and I gave it to Black in my QGD course. So, playing it with an extra move is of course nice.} 7. Nc3 e5 ({If Black plays slow with} 7... c6 {then we will expand on the queenside} 8. b4 {with good play. Compare with the mainline.}) 8. b4 {White ignores Black's plan and starts active operations on the queenside.} Re8 {Preparing ...[e5]-[e4].} 9. Bb2 {Developing while waiting for Black to play the committal ...[e5]-[e4] move.} exd4 10. Nxd4 {With the bishop on [b2], I think it would be imprecise to take with the pawn.} Ne5 11. Qb3 (11. Qb3 {White secures the extra space and is ready to centralize the rooks. A game continued:} Bg4 12. f3 Bd7 13. Rad1 {Lysyj-Levin, Russia 2012. White will play [e3]-[e4] and maintain a lot of extra space.}) *

