1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. c4 {This is the principled continuation.} Nbd7 {Going for the legendary King's Indian Attack setup. I am pretty sure this is what you will face in at least 3 out of 4 games if Black is a King's Indian player, so it is a very important line. It also means that I will cover the other black setups a bit more lightly. Usually, it is White who plays the King's Indian Attack! It comes for instance after the moves 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 e6 4.O-O Be7 5.d3 O-O 6.Nbd2 c5 7.e4 Nc6 8.Re1 b5 9.e5 Nd7 . Although, White has won some nice attacking games I sincerely believe that Black is absolutely fine - and I gave it to Black in my QGD course. So, playing it with an extra move is of course nice.} 7. Nc3 e5 ({If Black plays slow with} 7... c6 {then we will expand on the queenside} 8. b4 {with good play. Compare with the mainline.}) 8. b4 {White ignores Black's plan and starts active operations on the queenside.} Re8 {Preparing ...[e5]-[e4].} 9. Bb2 {Developing while waiting for Black to play the committal ...[e5]-[e4] move.} e4 10. Nd2 c6 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd6d5] This is a move that you are quite likely to face in a practical game. Black wants to play [d5] and secure the [e4]-pawn, which sounds like a good plan. In fact it is a strategic mistake, because it gives White a strong initiative on the queenside.} 11. a4 {Our standard reaction.} d5 12. a5 {[%cal Gb4b5,Ga5a6] Now [b4]-[b5] followed by [a5]-[a6] to undermine the black pawn chain is in the air, so Black is more or less obliged to play ...[a7]-[a6] to stop it.} a6 13. Qb3 {With threats to the black d-pawn.} Nf8 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Rfc1 {[%cal Gc3a4,Gb4b5] White is much better. We will continue with [Na4] and try to penetrate. Soon we will also play [b4]-[b5] and open more lines. In the meantime Black has no attack.} *

