1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. c4 {This is the principled continuation.} Nbd7 {Going for the legendary King's Indian Attack setup. I am pretty sure this is what you will face in at least 3 out of 4 games if Black is a King's Indian player, so it is a very important line. It also means that I will cover the other black setups a bit more lightly. Usually, it is White who plays the King's Indian Attack! It comes for instance after the moves 1.Nf3 d5 2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 e6 4.O-O Be7 5.d3 O-O 6.Nbd2 c5 7.e4 Nc6 8.Re1 b5 9.e5 Nd7 . Although, White has won some nice attacking games I sincerely believe that Black is absolutely fine - and I gave it to Black in my QGD course. So, playing it with an extra move is of course nice.} 7. Nc3 e5 ({If Black plays slow with} 7... c6 {then we will expand on the queenside} 8. b4 {with good play. Compare with the mainline.}) 8. b4 {White ignores Black's plan and starts active operations on the queenside.} Re8 {Preparing ...[e5]-[e4].} 9. Bb2 {Developing while waiting for Black to play the committal ...[e5]-[e4] move.} e4 10. Nd2 Nf8 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gh7h5,Gf8h7,Gh7g5] The standard move. Black wants to play [h5] and [Bf5] and [Nf8]-[h7]-[g5] and attack. Well, the attacking part we will come back to.} 11. a4 {Forward!} h5 12. a5 {Forward!} N8h7 13. Qc2 ({White plays like in the mainline. Here} 13. a6 bxa6 {is not clear because the a-pawn is protected.}) 13... Bf5 {Protecting [e4].} 14. Rfb1 {A deep regrouping. The queen can drop back to [d1] and help on the kingside. Moving the rook in advance means that it can unfold its power on the queenside instead of being stuck on [f1]. I believe White's play on the queenside is stronger than Black's chances on the kingside. A sample line goes:} Ng5 15. Qd1 h4 16. h3 {Stopping the pawn is important. If Black manages to play [h2]-[h3] the light squares around our king will be severely weakened.} Qd7 17. Bf1 {[%csl Gh3] Prophylaxis against any sacrifices on [h3]. White will continue to push on the queenside, just like in the mainline.} *

