1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d5 {Grunfeld players will likely go for this, either here or already on one of the previous moves.} 6. b4 $5 {I propose this radical move that takes space on the queenside and prevents [c7]-[c5].} ({• Of course, White could try a number of other moves, like} 6. Nbd2 {or 6.c3 , and allow ...[c7]-[c5], which is a Catalan with reversed colours. Then White can take on [c5] and often be able to keep the pawn, but Black always gets typical Catalan long-term compensation. • Instead, after 6.b4 , the position and subsequent lines should be compared to the Colle with 3...[g6]. Also there White played a [b4]-setup, the difference is that here White has already played [Be2] and [O-O], which means that our play on the queenside is much slower to begin with. A fact that Black can maybe expose.}) 6... c6 {A popular solid setup.} 7. Nbd2 Bf5 8. c4 {A typical strategic battle unfolds: Black can use the [e4]-square while White expands on the queenside.} Ne4 9. Bb2 {In the pure Colle move-order, White had played an early [a2]-[a4] as well. The difference is not that big. The extra space on the queenside gives White the easiest play.} Nxd2 ({Here} 9... Nd7 10. a4 {is a direct transposition to the Colle. White could also use the move order and play: 10.Nxe4 Bxe4 11.Nd2 Bf5 12.cxd5 and we are in the mainline!}) 10. Nxd2 Nd7 11. cxd5 {Changing the structure to a more static one, where White's initiative on the queenside will dictate the events.} ({Also fine is} 11. Qb3 {.}) 11... cxd5 12. Qb3 Nf6 13. Rfc1 Qd7 14. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3e5] Intending [Ne5] gave White the advantage in Ivanisevic-Ivic, Serbia 2019.} *

