1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d5 {Grunfeld players will likely go for this, either here or already on one of the previous moves.} 6. b4 $5 {I propose this radical move that takes space on the queenside and prevents [c7]-[c5].} ({• Of course, White could try a number of other moves, like} 6. Nbd2 {or 6.c3 , and allow ...[c7]-[c5], which is a Catalan with reversed colours. Then White can take on [c5] and often be able to keep the pawn, but Black always gets typical Catalan long-term compensation. • Instead, after 6.b4 , the position and subsequent lines should be compared to the Colle with 3...[g6]. Also there White played a [b4]-setup, the difference is that here White has already played [Be2] and [O-O], which means that our play on the queenside is much slower to begin with. A fact that Black can maybe expose.}) 6... b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gc7c5] A natural move, preparing [Bb7] and again making ...[c7]-[c5] possible.} 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. Nbd2 {White goes for the standard flexible and harmonious piece constellation.} Nbd7 9. c4 {With all pieces in position, it is time to strike.} c5 {The counterstrike. Otherwise Black will remain in a passive position.} 10. dxc5 bxc5 11. b5 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gb2h8] Notice this important change of the structure. By taking on [c5] with the d-pawn White has opened the long diagonal for [Bb2], and by playing [b4]-[b5] White has created an outside pawn majority where the a- and b-pawn can run through the lonely black a-pawn in an ending. White has a huge score in this position. In most cases Black guards the [d5]-pawn:} e6 12. a4 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gd1b3,Gf1d1] White is better. We are in no hurry to force events. First improve the position with moves like [Rc1], [Qb3] and [Rfd1]. In general it is fine to exchange some pieces because the pawn majority is a long-term asset, that especially will show its power in an ending.} *

