1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d5 {Grunfeld players will likely go for this, either here or already on one of the previous moves.} 6. b4 $5 {I propose this radical move that takes space on the queenside and prevents [c7]-[c5].} ({• Of course, White could try a number of other moves, like} 6. Nbd2 {or 6.c3 , and allow ...[c7]-[c5], which is a Catalan with reversed colours. Then White can take on [c5] and often be able to keep the pawn, but Black always gets typical Catalan long-term compensation. • Instead, after 6.b4 , the position and subsequent lines should be compared to the Colle with 3...[g6]. Also there White played a [b4]-setup, the difference is that here White has already played [Be2] and [O-O], which means that our play on the queenside is much slower to begin with. A fact that Black can maybe expose.}) 6... a5 $1 {The critical response.} 7. b5 ({White could consider just protecting the b-pawn with} 7. c3 {N this has never been played, but is a completely new direction that could be tried as a surprise.}) 7... c5 {Black doesn't give White any spare time.} 8. bxc6 ({White changes the structure. It was possible to play more flexibly with} 8. c4 {or 8.Bb2 .}) 8... Nxc6 {Black develops the knight and prepares to follow up with the active [Re8] and [e7]-[e5].} ({The rare} 8... bxc6 {seems playable. White has scored well with} 9. Ba3 {but probably 9.c4 is even stronger. In any case White keeps some pressure.}) 9. c3 $5 ({Kramnik's move. It has only been played once, by Kramnik of course, but it often transposes to other lines. White has several moves to choose from: • The most popular is} 9. a4 {, which takes the nice [b5]-square under firm control. • Another move is 9.Nbd2 , usually with the intention of playing a quick [c2]-[c4]. • Also, the direct 9.c4 is often seen. It can be hard to distinguish between the different moves, but there are two basic plans: attack the black centre with [c2]-[c4] or play for the [b5]-square. • My proposition, 9.c3 , is part of the second plan. In fact it is a deep prophylactic move that prepares for Black's [e5]-plan.}) 9... Bf5 {Active development is always a good choice.} 10. a4 {[%cal Gb1a3,Ga3b5] Now there is time for this. The plan is still [Na3]-[b5].} ({I don't like the immediate} 10. Na3 Ne4 11. Nb5 {because of} Na7 $1 {exchanging our strong knight.}) (10. Nbd2 {is possible, but Black can play} Qc7 11. a4 e5 {⇆}) 10... Re8 {Preparing the break [e7]-[e5].} 11. Na3 {White follows the standard plan.} ({Tempting is} 11. Bb2 {with the idea:} e5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Rxe5 14. c4 {but after the simple} Re7 15. Na3 Rd7 {Black seems to be ok. The game is balanced.}) 11... e5 12. Nb5 Ne4 ({Here} 12... Rc8 13. Ba3 Ne4 {transposes.}) 13. Ba3 Rc8 (13... Rc8 {This position was reached in the top game Dominguez-Vachier Lagrave, blitz 2018. White played} 14. Qb3 {. Maybe it was better to go Rc1 .}) 14. Rc1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf3d2] A complex position. The engine says it is completely equal, but it always says that! I would rather call it balanced with chances for both sides, however I prefer White because it is not clear what Black should do. If Black plays [Bf8] and exchanges the dark-squared bishops, then Black is permanently somewhat weak on the dark squares, especially around the king. White, on the other hand, could consider playing [Nd2] next, and get rid of the strong knight on [e4].} *

