1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O d5 {Grunfeld players will likely go for this, either here or already on one of the previous moves.} 6. b4 $5 {I propose this radical move that takes space on the queenside and prevents [c7]-[c5].} ({• Of course, White could try a number of other moves, like} 6. Nbd2 {or 6.c3 , and allow ...[c7]-[c5], which is a Catalan with reversed colours. Then White can take on [c5] and often be able to keep the pawn, but Black always gets typical Catalan long-term compensation. • Instead, after 6.b4 , the position and subsequent lines should be compared to the Colle with 3...[g6]. Also there White played a [b4]-setup, the difference is that here White has already played [Be2] and [O-O], which means that our play on the queenside is much slower to begin with. A fact that Black can maybe expose.}) 6... a5 $1 {The critical response.} 7. b5 ({White could consider just protecting the b-pawn with} 7. c3 {N this has never been played, but is a completely new direction that could be tried as a surprise.}) 7... c5 {Black doesn't give White any spare time.} 8. bxc6 ({White changes the structure. It was possible to play more flexibly with} 8. c4 {or 8.Bb2 .}) 8... Nxc6 {Black develops the knight and prepares to follow up with the active [Re8] and [e7]-[e5].} ({The rare} 8... bxc6 {seems playable. White has scored well with} 9. Ba3 {but probably 9.c4 is even stronger. In any case White keeps some pressure.}) 9. c3 $5 ({Kramnik's move. It has only been played once, by Kramnik of course, but it often transposes to other lines. White has several moves to choose from: • The most popular is} 9. a4 {, which takes the nice [b5]-square under firm control. • Another move is 9.Nbd2 , usually with the intention of playing a quick [c2]-[c4]. • Also, the direct 9.c4 is often seen. It can be hard to distinguish between the different moves, but there are two basic plans: attack the black centre with [c2]-[c4] or play for the [b5]-square. • My proposition, 9.c3 , is part of the second plan. In fact it is a deep prophylactic move that prepares for Black's [e5]-plan.}) 9... a4 {This was Black's response in the mentioned Kramnik game. Black exploits that White didn't play [a2]-[a4].} 10. Nbd2 {White changes direction.} ({Kramnik played} 10. Ba3 Re8 11. Nbd2 Qa5 12. c4 {, and got a great position, Kramnik-Grover, blitz 2023.}) (10. Nbd2 {After} Qa5 $1 {it would be impossible to answer [Nbd2] because the c-pawn is hanging.}) {However Black could have played...} 10... Qa5 11. c4 {[%cal Gc1a3,Ga1b1,Gb1b7] White is better, or perhaps more precise: has potential to be better! The bishop can go to [a3] like Kramnik did and the rook can come to [b1] with considerable pressure on Black's position.} *

