1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 {This is an important part of the course for the practical player. In top tournaments you don't see a lot of Benoni or Volga Gambits these days, but everywhere else they are still pretty popular.} 3. e3 {This makes the repertoire consistent.} ({The principled move} 3. d5 $1 {is almost without any doubt good for White, but you need to know a lot of different lines, like} b5 {or 3...e6 or 3...g6 .}) ({Maybe I will cover} 3. d5 $1 {in a future course! But in this one, it is 3.e3 .}) 3... g6 {This is what Black usually does. The bishop will be strong on g7. Often the position is reached via the Anti-King's Indian move-order 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 g6 3.e3 c5 or 3...Bg7 followed by ...[c7]-[c5]. But Black could also transpose to other major lines, for instance with 3...d5 or 3...cxd4 4.exd4 d5 which is covered in the Colle.} 4. Be2 {White could also take on [c5], but I prefer to develop the kingside first. Play is similar to an English/Reti with reversed colours.} Bg7 5. O-O O-O ({Black could also try} 5... d5 {and play a reversed Catalan, but it is quite risky as we will see in the theory section. Just castling is much more natural.}) 6. dxc5 {Now we take. Please notice that this is also an Anti King's Indian with ...[c5].} Qa5 {The best. Black wants to regain the pawn. If we had taken on [c5] straight away, then [Qa5] would have been a check. Here we don't have to put our knight on [d2].} 7. a3 {With this clever move, White manages to get the dark-squared bishop to the excellent [b2]-square. For starters, White threatens to play [b2]-[b4] and protect [c5], so Black has to take it.} ({Strong is also} 7. c4 Qxc5 8. Nc3 {followed by [e3]-[e4] with a firm Maroczy pawn formation. This is what I suggest in the theory section. But here I would like to present a fine alternative way of playing, which is very simple.}) 7... Qxc5 8. b4 Qc7 9. Bb2 {White has a pleasant position as we will see straight away in a nice Model Game.} *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Colle System"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Overview & Model Games: Anti-Benoni"]
[Black "Wojtaszek, R. vs. Volokitin"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "A48"]
[PlyCount "97"]
[GameId "2164710462312917"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. d4 g6 ({Also} 2... c5 {is met by} 3. e3 {.}) 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O c5 {We have an English/Reti with reversed colours.} 6. dxc5 {Not forced, but it gives White pretty easy play.} Qa5 {This way Black makes sure to regain the pawn, but it allows us to expand on the queenside and get the bishop to [b2].} 7. a3 ({In the Anti-King's Indian part I recommended} 7. c4 Qxc5 8. Nc3 {intending to go [e3]-[e4]. The [a2]-[a3] + [b2]-[b4] followed by [Bb2] as White does in the game is another sympathetic way to play.}) 7... Qxc5 8. b4 Qc7 9. Bb2 d5 ({Now it is a reversed Catalan, but a very nice one for us. I think Black should go for a flexible setup with} 9... b6 10. c4 Bb7 11. Nc3 d6 12. Rc1 Nbd7 {of course, White's extra space makes the game rather pleasant, but Black is solid.}) 10. Nbd2 {[%cal Gc2c4,Ga1c1] White will play [Rc1] and [c4] with great play.} Bg4 ({Or} 10... Rd8 11. c4 dxc4 12. Bxc4 {and White is better.}) 11. Rc1 {[%cal Gc2c4] There is no way Black can stop [c2]-[c4] from coming, and when it comes White has a very comfortable initiative.} Nbd7 12. c4 dxc4 13. Rxc4 {Hitting the queen.} Qb8 14. Qa1 $1 {[%csl Ga1][%cal Gb2g7,Gf1c1,Gc1c8] A really nice setup. The queen is good on the long diagonal and the back rank is cleared so [Rfc1] can come next.} Bxf3 {Simplifications won't help.} 15. Nxf3 Rc8 16. Rfc1 Rxc4 17. Bxc4 e6 $6 ({Better was} 17... Qf8 {but Black's position is unpleasant.}) 18. Bb5 $1 {[%cal Gb5d7,Gb2g7] The bishops show their strength. White threatens to take on [d7].} Qf8 {Protecting the bishop. White could just play [Rc7] now, but Wojtaszek exchanges everything and gets a winning ending.} 19. Bxd7 Nxd7 20. Bxg7 Qxg7 21. Qxg7+ Kxg7 22. Rc7 Rd8 23. g4 {White wins at least a pawn and keeps very dominant pieces. It is over.} Nf6 24. Ne5 Rf8 25. Rxb7 a6 26. a4 h5 27. h3 hxg4 28. hxg4 Nd5 29. b5 axb5 30. axb5 g5 31. e4 Nc3 32. f3 Na4 33. Kf2 Nc5 34. Rc7 Na4 35. Ke3 Kg8 36. Nd7 Rd8 37. b6 {Winning more material.} Rxd7 38. Rxd7 Nxb6 39. Rd8+ Kg7 40. Kd4 Kf6 41. Kc5 Na4+ 42. Kb4 Nb6 43. Kb5 Ke7 44. Rg8 Nd7 45. Rxg5 Kf6 46. f4 e5 47. Rf5+ Ke6 48. fxe5 Nxe5 49. g5 {It was a blitz game. I guess this was played. Anyway, we are a long way from the opening...} 1-0

