1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 {This makes the repertoire consistent.} ({The principled move} 3. d5 $1 {is almost without any doubt good for White, but you need to know a lot of different lines, like} b5 {or 3...e6 or 3...g6 . I may cover 3. [d5]! in a future course!}) 3... g6 ({Here Black could transpose to other major lines, for instance with} 3... d5 {(here or) 3...cxd4 4.exd4 d5 (here which is covered in the Colle.)}) 4. Be2 {The simplest.} ({• You could consider} 4. d5 $5 Bg7 5. Nc3 {and play might continue} O-O 6. Bc4 d6 7. O-O { White has more space and is slightly better, but in this repertoire, I basically refrain from playing an early [d4]-[d5]. There are exceptions though, as you will soon find out.}) ({• The most popular is} 4. dxc5 Qa5+ 5. Nbd2 Bg7 {( After 5...Qxc5 6.a3 will just transpose. )} 6. a3 Qxc5 7. b4 Qc7 8. Bb2 O-O 9. c4 {White has a good version of the Reti with colours reversed: Lots of freedom and both space and nice development on the queenside. In other words: easy to play. It scores well also. I am not sure that White is really better if Black plays precise. Black should strive for a flexible setup with [b7]-[b6], [Bb7], [d7]-[d6] and [Nbd7]. Afterwards, they can regroup with [Rac8], [Qb8], and [Qa8] in a very harmonious position that is hard to break down. A likely continuation is:} b6 10. Be2 Bb7 11. O-O d6 12. Rc1 {( White can also go for 12.Qb3 Nbd7 13.Rfc1 but it doesn't really change anything. )} Nbd7 13. Qb3 Rac8 14. Rfd1 Qb8 {, followed by [Qa8] with a balanced position. Of course, the line is tempting for White, and none of the moves are forced, so lots of opportunities for both sides to take different paths. My overall estimation is that it is equal and that it is hard for White to come up with a convincing plan.}) 4... Bg7 {After [g7]-[g6] you more or less automatically go [Bg7].} ({Here} 4... d5 5. O-O Bg7 {transposes to the mainline.}) 5. O-O cxd4 {Changing the structure is possible.} 6. exd4 d5 {This is pleasant for White. The bishop doesn't belong on [g7] in these reversed Carlsbad structures.} *

