1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 {This makes the repertoire consistent.} ({The principled move} 3. d5 $1 {is almost without any doubt good for White, but you need to know a lot of different lines, like} b5 {or 3...e6 or 3...g6 . I may cover 3. [d5]! in a future course!}) 3... g6 ({Here Black could transpose to other major lines, for instance with} 3... d5 {(here or) 3...cxd4 4.exd4 d5 (here which is covered in the Colle.)}) 4. Be2 {The simplest.} ({• You could consider} 4. d5 $5 Bg7 5. Nc3 {and play might continue} O-O 6. Bc4 d6 7. O-O { White has more space and is slightly better, but in this repertoire, I basically refrain from playing an early [d4]-[d5]. There are exceptions though, as you will soon find out.}) ({• The most popular is} 4. dxc5 Qa5+ 5. Nbd2 Bg7 {( After 5...Qxc5 6.a3 will just transpose. )} 6. a3 Qxc5 7. b4 Qc7 8. Bb2 O-O 9. c4 {White has a good version of the Reti with colours reversed: Lots of freedom and both space and nice development on the queenside. In other words: easy to play. It scores well also. I am not sure that White is really better if Black plays precise. Black should strive for a flexible setup with [b7]-[b6], [Bb7], [d7]-[d6] and [Nbd7]. Afterwards, they can regroup with [Rac8], [Qb8], and [Qa8] in a very harmonious position that is hard to break down. A likely continuation is:} b6 10. Be2 Bb7 11. O-O d6 12. Rc1 {( White can also go for 12.Qb3 Nbd7 13.Rfc1 but it doesn't really change anything. )} Nbd7 13. Qb3 Rac8 14. Rfd1 Qb8 {, followed by [Qa8] with a balanced position. Of course, the line is tempting for White, and none of the moves are forced, so lots of opportunities for both sides to take different paths. My overall estimation is that it is equal and that it is hard for White to come up with a convincing plan.}) 4... Bg7 {After [g7]-[g6] you more or less automatically go [Bg7].} ({Here} 4... d5 5. O-O Bg7 {transposes to the mainline.}) 5. O-O d5 {Going for a reversed Catalan. Not the most common, but these days the Catalan is a main weapon against the QGD, so why not?} ({Perhaps more natural is} 5... O-O 6. dxc5 {with a transposition to the Anti King's Indian line with [c5].}) 6. dxc5 O-O {This is the real Catalan move you would like to play. White has a big choice between various setups, where you have an extra tempo, but I think only one move hits the nail on the head.} 7. Nc3 $1 {This is a good version of a well-known Catalan line with reversed colours. A very concrete line, where the extra move really matters, you can add. It is not so easy for Black to win the pawn back. The knight on [c3] attacks the d-pawn and ties the black queen to its defence. Black has tried three different moves.} e6 {Protecting [d5] so the queen can move around.} 8. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4] The standard idea: White wants to play [b2]-[b4], but first moves the rook out of the long-range of [Bg7].} a5 {Black prevents it.} 9. a3 {But we insists!} Nfd7 {Intending [Nxc5]. Now [Bg7] is targeting the white knight so it is impossible to play [b2]-[b4].} ({After} 9... Qe7 10. b4 {is just for White.}) 10. e4 {A novelty! We use the fact that the black knight no longer controls [e4].} Bxc3 {Not fun, but the only follow-up.} ({If} 10... Nxc5 {, then} 11. exd5 {is worse, and 10...dxe4 11.Nxe4 is even worse!}) 11. bxc3 Nxc5 12. exd5 {White has a strong intiative.} exd5 ({Also terrible for Black is} 12... Qxd5 13. Bh6 {.}) 13. Bg5 {A highly disturbing move.} Qd6 ({Or} 13... f6 14. Bh6 Re8 15. c4 $1 {and Black's position starts to fall apart.}) 14. Bc4 $1 {A nice move. Black is forced to give the d-pawn, which is a really bad sign.} Be6 $2 {Loses after...} 15. Bh6 Re8 16. Qd4 {[%cal Gd4g7] Because with the bishop on [e6] there is no [Ne6].} *

