1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 {This makes the repertoire consistent.} ({The principled move} 3. d5 $1 {is almost without any doubt good for White, but you need to know a lot of different lines, like} b5 {or 3...e6 or 3...g6 . I may cover 3. [d5]! in a future course!}) 3... g6 ({Here Black could transpose to other major lines, for instance with} 3... d5 {(here or) 3...cxd4 4.exd4 d5 (here which is covered in the Colle.)}) 4. Be2 {The simplest.} ({• You could consider} 4. d5 $5 Bg7 5. Nc3 {and play might continue} O-O 6. Bc4 d6 7. O-O { White has more space and is slightly better, but in this repertoire, I basically refrain from playing an early [d4]-[d5]. There are exceptions though, as you will soon find out.}) ({• The most popular is} 4. dxc5 Qa5+ 5. Nbd2 Bg7 {( After 5...Qxc5 6.a3 will just transpose. )} 6. a3 Qxc5 7. b4 Qc7 8. Bb2 O-O 9. c4 {White has a good version of the Reti with colours reversed: Lots of freedom and both space and nice development on the queenside. In other words: easy to play. It scores well also. I am not sure that White is really better if Black plays precise. Black should strive for a flexible setup with [b7]-[b6], [Bb7], [d7]-[d6] and [Nbd7]. Afterwards, they can regroup with [Rac8], [Qb8], and [Qa8] in a very harmonious position that is hard to break down. A likely continuation is:} b6 10. Be2 Bb7 11. O-O d6 12. Rc1 {( White can also go for 12.Qb3 Nbd7 13.Rfc1 but it doesn't really change anything. )} Nbd7 13. Qb3 Rac8 14. Rfd1 Qb8 {, followed by [Qa8] with a balanced position. Of course, the line is tempting for White, and none of the moves are forced, so lots of opportunities for both sides to take different paths. My overall estimation is that it is equal and that it is hard for White to come up with a convincing plan.}) 4... Bg7 {After [g7]-[g6] you more or less automatically go [Bg7].} ({Here} 4... d5 5. O-O Bg7 {transposes to the mainline.}) 5. O-O d5 {Going for a reversed Catalan. Not the most common, but these days the Catalan is a main weapon against the QGD, so why not?} ({Perhaps more natural is} 5... O-O 6. dxc5 {with a transposition to the Anti King's Indian line with [c5].}) 6. dxc5 Qa5 {Black regains the pawn this way. The downside is that it helps White to develop the queenside with tempo.} 7. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Threatening [b2]-[b4].} Qxc5 8. b4 {Getting the bishop to [b2] with tempo.} Qc7 9. Bb2 O-O 10. Nbd2 {[%cal Gc2c4,Ga1c1] White has a very harmonious position. The plan is to play [c2]-[c4] and [Rc1] which would be rather uncomfortable for the black queen.} Rd8 {Trying to disturb White's plan.} (10... Bg4 11. Rc1 {doesn't really help Black.}) 11. c4 {We play it anyway. There is no need to prepare it with [Rc1].} dxc4 12. Bxc4 {White has the initiative.} Bg4 13. Rc1 $1 (13. Rc1 {A novelty!Black is in trouble. The threat Bxf7+ is awkward to meet.} Bxf3 14. Qxf3 {, and Black hasn't time to take on [d2].}) (13. Rc1 {If} Qd7 {, then} 14. Qb3 {with strong threats.}) *

