1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 ({Black can play} 3... c5 {in every move, and here it sends us to the Benoni 2...c5 chapter.}) 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O c5 {A natural move. This is a Reti with colours reversed. Since we have no intention of entering the regular Benoni territory we don't play [d4]-[d5]. Fortunately there is another direct route to take.} 6. dxc5 {A standard reaction, also in the English/Reti.} Na6 {Black wants to take on [c5] with the knight and tries to lure us to take on [a6].} 7. c4 ({We go for some fluid positional play. Actually, it is also fine to take on a6:} 7. Bxa6 bxa6 8. b3 {the bishop will be good on [b2]} Qc7 {(8...Ne4 9.Nd4)} 9. Bb2 Bb7 {(9...Qxc5?! 10.Ba3)} 10. Nbd2 Qxc5 11. c4 d6 12. Qe2 {(1–0 Markowski,T 2548-Nguyen,P 2422 POL-chT Ekstraliga Warsaw 2020 4.5 with a complex strategic game ahead. The position is balanced. In general. I am not too keen to give my bishop with [Bxa6] in such positions. Also here, we see that Black's [Bb7] is really strong. But we have the best pawn structure, so clearly there is also potential in White's position.)}) 7... Nxc5 8. b4 $1 {White fights for the initiative. The black knight must go to [e4], but which knight?} Nfe4 {[%cal Gg7a1]} 9. Nd4 {This is forced.} Ne6 10. Bb2 Qb6 {[%csl Gb4] Attacking [b4] and increasing the pressure on [d4]. Black must create counterplay.} ({Giri has played} 10... d5 {, but after} 11. Nxe6 Bxe6 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Qd4+ Kg8 14. Rd1 Nf6 15. c5 {White had a big advantage with the strong majority on the queenside, Anton-Giri rapid 2021}) 11. a3 d5 {And now this tactical strike.} ({If} 11... a5 {, then} 12. Nd2 {is good for White.}) 12. Bf3 $1 ({I don't like} 12. cxd5 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Bxd4 14. Qxd4 Qxd4 15. exd4 {Black will soon regain the pawn and we will be left with a potential weak [d4]-pawn.}) 12... Nxd4 {Black play some forcing moves.} 13. Bxd4 Bxd4 14. Qxd4 Qxd4 15. exd4 Rd8 {A very interesting ending. Black might keep the balance with some precise active moves.} 16. a4 {Taking space and in some lines the knight can go to [a3] and protect [c4].} Bf5 17. Bxe4 ({After} 17. Re1 e5 $1 18. cxd5 Ng5 {1/2-1/2 Anton Guijarro-Vachier Lagrave FIDE Grand Swiss Riga 2021 Black had enough counterplay to equalize.}) 17... dxe4 ({Not} 17... Bxe4 18. c5 {}) 18. Rd1 {1-0 Giacomini,H 2126-Alquist,E 1960 EU-ch Seniors 65 22nd Acqui Terme 2023 9 The engine calls it completely equal, but I think White has some chances with the better structure and a potential passed pawn on the queenside. Anyway, White won the only game that has been played so far!} *

