1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 ({Black can play} 3... c5 {in every move, and here it sends us to the Benoni 2...c5 chapter.}) 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O c5 {A natural move. This is a Reti with colours reversed. Since we have no intention of entering the regular Benoni territory we don't play [d4]-[d5]. Fortunately there is another direct route to take.} 6. dxc5 {A standard reaction, also in the English/Reti.} Qc7 ({This should just transpose to} 6... Qa5 {if Black takes on c5 next, but it can also lead to a version of the 6...Na6 line.}) 7. c4 Na6 {Tempting now that White can't play [Bxa6].} 8. Nc3 Nxc5 9. b4 {I suggest we do the same as in the 6...Na6 line.} ({The most popular move from White has been} 9. Qc2 {, but after} d6 {Black is ok.}) 9... Nce4 10. Bb2 ({Interesting is} 10. Nb5 {N , followed by [Bb2] to avoid to exchange of the knights.}) 10... Nxc3 11. Bxc3 d5 $6 ({Better is} 11... b6 12. Rc1 {with a balanced position where White enjoys some extra space.}) 12. c5 $1 Bf5 13. Rc1 $16 {1-0 Trifan,A 2296-Enzmann,S 2142 BL2-Sued 2223 Germany 2022 4.7 White is much better. The pawn majority on the queenside is tying Black down and the control over the [e5]-square makes it hard to come up with some counterplay.} *

