1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 ({Black can play} 3... c5 {in every move, and here it sends us to the Benoni 2...c5 chapter.}) 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O c5 {A natural move. This is a Reti with colours reversed. Since we have no intention of entering the regular Benoni territory we don't play [d4]-[d5]. Fortunately there is another direct route to take.} 6. dxc5 {A standard reaction, also in the English/Reti.} Qa5 {Black should forcus on winning the pawn back.} 7. c4 ({This has a very specific idea. Also fine is the well-known} 7. a3 Qxc5 8. b4 Qc7 9. Bb2 {which we will see more of in the 2...[c5] chapter.}) 7... Qxc5 8. Nc3 d6 9. e4 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4] This was the idea. White gets a good Maroczy with pawns on [c4] and [e4] that secures extra space and makes it hard for Black to get active play.} Bg4 ({The quieter} 9... Nc6 10. Be3 Qa5 11. h3 { leads to a very pleasant position for White, where the Maroczy pawns on [c4] and [e4] prevent any active counterplay.}) 10. Be3 Qa5 {Probably the best square for the queen. Retreating down the c-file is more passive.} ({After} 10... Qc8 11. Rc1 $1 {Black can't take the c-pawn anyway.} Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Qxc4 $2 13. e5 $1 {and White wins material.}) 11. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Intending [b2]-[b4] to push the annoying black queen back.} ({White could also go for} 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 {we have the bishops, and the plan with [a2]-[a3] and [b2]-[b4] can follow.}) 11... Nc6 ({Black has tried} 11... Rc8 12. b4 Qd8 {but after the simple} 13. Qb3 {White is much better due to the extra space.}) 12. b4 Qh5 $5 {is quite tricky.} 13. Re1 {White improves the position. The e-file might be important.} ({The obvious} 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 {isn't clear at all after} Qh4 {∞ Black gets a lot of counter chances on the dark squares.}) (13. Rc1 {seems strong, but Black has} Bh6 $1 {when it is not completely clear what is going on.}) 13... Rfd8 14. Rc1 Ne5 {Black has to go for this. If Black plays more quiet White will stabilize the position and enjoy all the extra space.} 15. Nxe5 dxe5 {Attacking the white queen.} 16. Nd5 {Active defence.} Bxe2 17. Nxf6+ {A good intermediate move.} ({If} 17. Qxe2 {Black has sufficient counterplay after} Ng4 18. h3 Nxe3 19. Qxh5 gxh5 20. Nxe3 Rd3 {.}) 17... exf6 ({Much worse is} 17... Bxf6 18. Qxe2 Qxe2 19. Rxe2 {and White has a nice ending. The black bishop is really passive and it almost feels like we are a paw up.}) 18. Qxe2 Qxe2 19. Rxe2 Rd3 20. a4 ({Black can probably defend after} 20. Rd2 Rxa3 21. Rd7 Rb8 {.}) 20... f5 $1 {The point of [exf6]. Black gets some activity.} 21. exf5 gxf5 22. g3 {[%csl Gf4] Preventing [f5]-[f4] and creating some luft for the king. White is better in the ending with the 3 vs. 2 on the queenside and a strong bishop.} *

