1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 ({Black can play} 3... c5 {in every move, and here it sends us to the Benoni 2...c5 chapter.}) 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O c5 {A natural move. This is a Reti with colours reversed. Since we have no intention of entering the regular Benoni territory we don't play [d4]-[d5]. Fortunately there is another direct route to take.} 6. dxc5 {A standard reaction, also in the English/Reti.} Qa5 {Black should forcus on winning the pawn back.} 7. c4 ({This has a very specific idea. Also fine is the well-known} 7. a3 Qxc5 8. b4 Qc7 9. Bb2 {which we will see more of in the 2...[c5] chapter.}) 7... Qxc5 8. Nc3 d6 9. e4 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4] This was the idea. White gets a good Maroczy with pawns on [c4] and [e4] that secures extra space and makes it hard for Black to get active play.} Bg4 ({The quieter} 9... Nc6 10. Be3 Qa5 11. h3 { leads to a very pleasant position for White, where the Maroczy pawns on [c4] and [e4] prevent any active counterplay.}) 10. Be3 Qa5 {Probably the best square for the queen. Retreating down the c-file is more passive.} ({After} 10... Qc8 11. Rc1 $1 {Black can't take the c-pawn anyway.} Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Qxc4 $2 13. e5 $1 {and White wins material.}) 11. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Intending [b2]-[b4] to push the annoying black queen back.} ({White could also go for} 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 {we have the bishops, and the plan with [a2]-[a3] and [b2]-[b4] can follow.}) 11... Nc6 ({Black has tried} 11... Rc8 12. b4 Qd8 {but after the simple} 13. Qb3 {White is much better due to the extra space.}) 12. b4 Qh5 $5 {is quite tricky.} 13. Re1 {White improves the position. The e-file might be important.} ({The obvious} 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 {isn't clear at all after} Qh4 {∞ Black gets a lot of counter chances on the dark squares.}) (13. Rc1 {seems strong, but Black has} Bh6 $1 {when it is not completely clear what is going on.}) 13... Bh6 14. h3 $1 {[%csl Gg4]} ({This is a problem for Black. If you don't like the complications, then} 14. Qd2 Bxe3 15. Qxe3 {is a safe way to keep an edge.}) 14... Bxe3 15. hxg4 Bxf2+ 16. Kxf2 Nxg4+ 17. Kg1 Nce5 {[%csl Gh2][%cal Ge5f3] It looks threatening, but a couple of precise moves refutes the attack.} 18. Qd2 f5 {Black needs to bring in more pieces and open some lines.} (18... Nxf3+ 19. Bxf3 Qh2+ 20. Kf1 Ne5 {can be met by} 21. Ke2 Nxc4 22. Qd4 {( Or 22.Qg5 e6 23.Rh1 exchanging queens. )} Ne5 23. Nd5 {and White's extra piece is stronger than the three pawns.}) 19. Bd1 $1 {A precise move.} f4 ({After} 19... Nxf3+ 20. gxf3 {the white queen covers h2.}) 20. Nd5 {Black's attack is running out of steam and White is just much better.} *

