1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 ({Black can play} 3... c5 {in every move, and here it sends us to the Benoni 2...c5 chapter.}) 4. Be2 O-O 5. O-O c5 {A natural move. This is a Reti with colours reversed. Since we have no intention of entering the regular Benoni territory we don't play [d4]-[d5]. Fortunately there is another direct route to take.} 6. dxc5 {A standard reaction, also in the English/Reti.} Qa5 {Black should forcus on winning the pawn back.} 7. c4 ({This has a very specific idea. Also fine is the well-known} 7. a3 Qxc5 8. b4 Qc7 9. Bb2 {which we will see more of in the 2...[c5] chapter.}) 7... Qxc5 8. Nc3 d6 9. e4 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Ge4] This was the idea. White gets a good Maroczy with pawns on [c4] and [e4] that secures extra space and makes it hard for Black to get active play.} Bg4 ({The quieter} 9... Nc6 10. Be3 Qa5 11. h3 { leads to a very pleasant position for White, where the Maroczy pawns on [c4] and [e4] prevent any active counterplay.}) 10. Be3 Qa5 {Probably the best square for the queen. Retreating down the c-file is more passive.} ({After} 10... Qc8 11. Rc1 $1 {Black can't take the c-pawn anyway.} Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Qxc4 $2 13. e5 $1 {and White wins material.}) 11. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Intending [b2]-[b4] to push the annoying black queen back.} ({White could also go for} 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 {we have the bishops, and the plan with [a2]-[a3] and [b2]-[b4] can follow.}) 11... Nc6 ({Black has tried} 11... Rc8 12. b4 Qd8 {but after the simple} 13. Qb3 {White is much better due to the extra space.}) 12. b4 Qh5 $5 {is quite tricky.} 13. Re1 {White improves the position. The e-file might be important.} ({The obvious} 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 {isn't clear at all after} Qh4 {∞ Black gets a lot of counter chances on the dark squares.}) (13. Rc1 {seems strong, but Black has} Bh6 $1 {when it is not completely clear what is going on.}) 13... Ne5 {The most forcing move.} 14. Nxe5 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 Qxe5 16. Rac1 (16. Rac1 {White is slightly better. If allowed we will play f2-f3 next and protect everything and secure the extra space. It is not good for Black to take on e4 as this sample line shows:} Nxe4 17. Nb5 $1 a6 {(17...Nf6 18.Bxa7 Qxe2 19.Rxe2 is good for White. )} 18. Bd4 Qg5 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Nc7 Rac8 21. Nd5 {, and Black is in trouble.}) *

