1. d4 f5 {The Dutch. It leads to unbalanced play, that is the positive thing I have to say. In my opinion, Black voluntarily weakens the kingside permanently!} 2. Bf4 $1 {Okay, I started this repertoire by promising that there would be no London in it. It just happens that [Bf4] against the Dutch is a favourite of mine - and that it is good! Furthermore, a system with [e2]-[e3] seems too tame here, and I guess that Black would be happy to see it on the board.} Nf6 3. e3 {Here play divides. These days, most Dutch players go for the so-called Leningrad variation with [g7]-[g6], [Bg7], [O-O] and so on, when they face a normal white setup with [c2]-[c4] and [g2]-[g3]. They are therefore inclined to do it against 2. [Bf4] as well, but here it is actually pretty dangerous for Black because White can launch a quick raid with the h-pawn as we will see soon. Safer is a more old-fashioned line with [e7]-[e6] and [b7]-[b6], but also here White can get good play.} g6 (3... e6 {is a more positional approach and Black's best bet.}) 4. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] White takes the initiative. Already [h4]-[h5] is a threat. If Black takes it with the knight, we sacrifice the exchange before they can write down the move. This line is highly promising for White. I will start by showing two games. The first is by a student of mine rated around 2100. We had investigated the [Bf4]-Dutch quite deeply and I felt really proud when he completely outplayed and beat the strong Swedish grandmaster Axel Smith - yes, the Woodpecker author! The other game is by yours truly and it shows how fast Black can get into serious trouble with pretty normal moves.} *

