1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 g6 4. h4 $1 {White wants to play [h4]-[h5].} h6 {So [h4]-[h5] can be met with [g6]-[g5].} 5. Nc3 e6 6. Qf3 $1 {[%csl Gc7,Gg6][%cal Gf3g3] An excellent square for the queen: it gets out of the way as preparation for long castling and it helps to break in the centre with [e4]. There is even a cunning trap: White threatens [Qg3] which attacks [g6] and [c7]. That explains Black's next move.} Rg8 {This can't be good!} (6... d6 7. e4 {is also great for White.}) 7. e4 Nc6 8. O-O-O {White is almost winning already! It only took 8 moves starting with [Bf4] against the Dutch.} fxe4 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 {[%cal Gf4h6,Gf4c7,Gd4d5] The [f4]-bishop stands really well, attacking both [c7] and [h6]. Now White threatens to smash through with [d5].} d5 11. Qe3 {[%csl Gh6] Hitting [h6]. Black decides to give the pawn to get the king to safety, pretty desperate you can say!} Bd7 (11... g5 12. hxg5 hxg5 {saves the pawn, but not the game.} 13. Bg3 Bd7 14. Bd3 {Black has no moves because} Qf6 {is met by} 15. Bxc7 {for instance} Nxd4 16. Be5 {winning a piece.}) 12. Bxh6 Bxh6 13. Qxh6 Qf6 14. Nf3 O-O-O 15. Qg5 {With a pawn more and a positional superior position I just play it safe.} Qg7 16. c3 Rdf8 17. Bd3 Rf6 18. Rd2 a6 19. Re1 Qf7 20. Qe3 {Black doesn't have any real counterplay.} Rf8 21. Ng5 Qg8 22. g3 Na5 23. Rde2 e5 24. Qxe5 Rxf2 25. Rxf2 Rxf2 26. Rf1 {Exchanging pieces is a good strategy when you are material up.} Nc6 27. Qe3 Rf8 28. Rxf8+ Qxf8 29. Kd2 Ne7 30. Qf3 {OK, we can slowly get the queens off the board if you like.} Qh8 31. Qf7 Nf5 32. Bxf5 gxf5 ({Or} 32... Bxf5 33. Ne6 {.}) 33. Nh7 {Now I also have [Qf8].} f4 $5 {Desperation.} 34. Qxf4 {A nice detail.} Kd8 ({Not} 34... Qxh7 35. Qf8+ Be8 36. Qxe8# {.}) 35. Qf6+ 1-0

