1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 {The correct move-order.} d6 {Black could start with [d7]-[d6]. The intention is still to play [g7]-[g6] and [Bg7] and so on, but hopefully, avoid the raid by the white h-pawn.} 4. Nc3 {Keeping all options open.} c6 {Flexible, but non-developing.} 5. Bd3 Qa5 {Pinning the knight and preventing [e3]-[e4].} ({After} 5... g6 6. h4 $1 {is still dangerous for Black.}) 6. Nf3 {So White just switches to quick development.} Nd5 ({Now} 6... g6 {is met by} 7. O-O Bg7 8. h3 O-O 9. Bh2 {a nice prophylactic setup. White can play all over the board, depending on what Black does. [Re1] followed by [e3]-[e4] is an obvious plan.}) 7. O-O $1 Nxc3 ({If} 7... Nxf4 8. exf4 {, followed by [Re1] with heavy pressure on the e-file.}) 8. bxc3 {Sacrificing the pawn.} ({Also strong is} 8. Qe1 {N that regains the piece and prepares the e4-break.}) 8... Qxc3 9. Re1 (9. Re1 {Next White will push e3-e4 with a strong initiative. I doubt that Black can survive for long. A game continued:} g6 10. e4 fxe4 11. Bxe4 {with a winning initiative in Jarvinen-Haanpaa, Finland 2008.}) *

