1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 {The correct move-order.} g6 {The Leningrad set-up.} 4. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] Threatening h4-h5. If White had played 3.Nf3 then the queen's route to [h5] would have been blocked and this wouldn't have been possible..} Bg7 5. h5 $1 d6 {Black can ignore the white h-pawn. Now White has several tempting moves.} 6. h6 ({In the end, I went with this AlphaZero move, just pushing Black back and establishing a strong pawn on h6 that will annoy Black for the rest of the game. Other good moves were:} 6. Bc4 {or 6.Nc3 .}) 6... Bf8 7. c4 e6 8. Nc3 Be7 9. Qc2 {Preparing long castling.} O-O 10. O-O-O {[%cal Gf2f3,Gg2g4] White has a promising position. A plan with [f2]-[f3], followed by [g2]-[g4] looks strong.} *

