1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 {The correct move-order.} g6 {The Leningrad set-up.} 4. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] Threatening h4-h5. If White had played 3.Nf3 then the queen's route to [h5] would have been blocked and this wouldn't have been possible..} h6 {Preparing to meet [h4]-[h5] with [g6]-[g5].} 5. Nc3 d6 {Black's typical pawn formation in the Leningrad Dutch.} ({Black could also start with} 5... Bg7 {but after} 6. Qf3 $1 {Black has to play ...[d7]-[d6] anyway with a transposition. I have won several blitz games after} O-O $2 7. Qg3 {with a double threat on [c7] and [g6].}) ({Also} 5... e6 {is strongly met by} 6. Qf3 $1 {as we saw in the illustrative game from the overview.}) 6. Qf3 $1 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Ge1c1,Ge3e4,Gf3g3] The queen is excellent here. Basically, it prepares long castling, but sometimes it also help carrying out the nice [e3]-[e4] break to open the centre. Finally, the queen can go to [g3] and attack the soft [g6]-pawn.} e6 {[%cal Gd8e7] This is a flexible setup. Black intends [Qe7].} 7. O-O-O ({Not so clear is} 7. Qg3 Rg8 {.}) 7... Nc6 ({Here} 7... Qe7 8. e4 Nc6 {will transpose to the mainline.}) 8. e4 {[%csl Ge8] White hopes to open the position, while Black's king is still in the centre.} Qe7 {Black, on the other hand, tries to keep everything as closed as possible.} 9. exf5 gxf5 ({Opening the e-file is too dangerous: After} 9... exf5 10. Nh3 {White is ready to play [Bb5] and [Rhe1].}) 10. Bc4 $1 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Gd4d5] Putting pressure on [e6] and threatens to open the centre with [d4]-[d5].} Na5 $1 {The solution found in email chess!} 11. Be2 Qf7 12. Nh3 Bd7 13. d5 $1 {Even without the support from the bishop this break is strong. It leads to a lot of exchanges, but the resulting ending is very pleasant for White.} exd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Qxd5 Qxd5 16. Rxd5 Nc6 17. Bh5+ Kd8 {This has been seen, but after the simple...} 18. Bd2 {[%cal Gh3f4] ...followed by [Nf4] White is definitely better in the ending with much more active pieces and a superior pawn structure.} *

