1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 {The correct move-order.} g6 {The Leningrad set-up.} 4. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] Threatening h4-h5. If White had played 3.Nf3 then the queen's route to [h5] would have been blocked and this wouldn't have been possible..} h6 {Preparing to meet [h4]-[h5] with [g6]-[g5].} 5. Nc3 d6 {Black's typical pawn formation in the Leningrad Dutch.} ({Black could also start with} 5... Bg7 {but after} 6. Qf3 $1 {Black has to play ...[d7]-[d6] anyway with a transposition. I have won several blitz games after} O-O $2 7. Qg3 {with a double threat on [c7] and [g6].}) ({Also} 5... e6 {is strongly met by} 6. Qf3 $1 {as we saw in the illustrative game from the overview.}) 6. Qf3 $1 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Ge1c1,Ge3e4,Gf3g3] The queen is excellent here. Basically, it prepares long castling, but sometimes it also help carrying out the nice [e3]-[e4] break to open the centre. Finally, the queen can go to [g3] and attack the soft [g6]-pawn.} e6 {[%cal Gd8e7] This is a flexible setup. Black intends [Qe7].} 7. O-O-O ({Not so clear is} 7. Qg3 Rg8 {.}) 7... Nc6 ({Here} 7... Qe7 8. e4 Nc6 {will transpose to the mainline.}) 8. e4 {[%csl Ge8] White hopes to open the position, while Black's king is still in the centre.} Qe7 {Black, on the other hand, tries to keep everything as closed as possible.} 9. exf5 gxf5 ({Opening the e-file is too dangerous: After} 9... exf5 10. Nh3 {White is ready to play [Bb5] and [Rhe1].}) 10. Bc4 $1 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Gd4d5] Putting pressure on [e6] and threatens to open the centre with [d4]-[d5].} Na5 $1 {The solution found in email chess!} 11. Be2 Nc6 {Already a draw offer?} 12. d5 $1 ({We decline and refrain from} 12. Bc4 {.}) 12... Nxd5 ({After} 12... Ne5 13. Bxe5 dxe5 {comes} 14. Bb5+ {, a disturbing check. White is much better after} Kf7 15. Bc4 {.}) 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. Qxd5 {[%cal Ge2h5] White is positionally better. There is also a check on [h5] looming.} Be6 15. Bh5+ Kd7 {[%csl Gd7] Forced, but the drifting king is a problem for Black.} 16. Qb5 {[%csl Gb7]} Kc8 17. Ne2 {[%cal Gf4e3,Ge2f4] Black held in an email game, but it was no walk in the park. White can withdraw the bishop to [e3] or [d2] and put the knight on [f4] with nice piece play.} *

