1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 {The correct move-order.} g6 {The Leningrad set-up.} 4. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] Threatening h4-h5. If White had played 3.Nf3 then the queen's route to [h5] would have been blocked and this wouldn't have been possible..} h6 {Preparing to meet [h4]-[h5] with [g6]-[g5].} 5. Nc3 d6 {Black's typical pawn formation in the Leningrad Dutch.} ({Black could also start with} 5... Bg7 {but after} 6. Qf3 $1 {Black has to play ...[d7]-[d6] anyway with a transposition. I have won several blitz games after} O-O $2 7. Qg3 {with a double threat on [c7] and [g6].}) ({Also} 5... e6 {is strongly met by} 6. Qf3 $1 {as we saw in the illustrative game from the overview.}) 6. Qf3 $1 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Ge1c1,Ge3e4,Gf3g3] The queen is excellent here. Basically, it prepares long castling, but sometimes it also help carrying out the nice [e3]-[e4] break to open the centre. Finally, the queen can go to [g3] and attack the soft [g6]-pawn.} c6 {Another flexible move. Again Black intends to meet [Qg3] with [Rg8].} 7. Bc4 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gf3g3] Now [Qg3] is a major threat.} d5 ({An ugly move that weakens e5, but} 7... e6 8. e4 {was even worse.}) 8. Bd3 Be6 9. h5 $1 ({White could also play more quietly with} 9. Qh3 {, followed by [f2]-[f3] and [O-O-O]. Later [g2]-[g4] can open the kingside.}) 9... Nxh5 (9... g5 10. Be5 {is not nice.}) 10. Rxh5 {The standard sacrifice.} gxh5 11. Bxf5 $1 {A nice detail. White wins the [f5]-pawn with a little tactics.} Bf7 ({Or} 11... Bxf5 12. Qxh5+ Kd7 13. Qxf5+ e6 14. Qh3 {White has a pawn and the usual long-term initiative for the exchange.}) 12. Qh3 Nd7 13. Nf3 (13. Nf3 {White was much better in Andreikin-Markgraf, EU-cup 2018. Black can hardly move. The game continued:} Bg7 14. O-O-O e6 $5 15. Bxe6 Bxe6 16. Qxe6+ Qe7 17. Qh3 Qf7 18. Ne2 {, followed by [Ng3] and [Nxh5] and it was over.}) *

