1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 ({Please notice the move order. I recommend starting with the more flexible} 3. e3 {. If Black plays ...[e7]-[e6] it doesn't matter, but it is an important detail against ...[g7]-[g6], which we have just seen.}) 3... e6 4. Nf3 Be7 {Black just develops the kingside.} 5. Be2 ({The by far most popular move is} 5. h3 {but maybe we don't have to secure our bishop.}) 5... O-O 6. O-O Nh5 ({Here} 6... b6 {will transpose to the mainline.}) 7. c4 {We just leave the bishop on [f4]. The point is that if Black takes it, the pawn on [f4] secures complete control over the important [e5]-square and the rook can use the semi-open e-file.} Nxf4 {Otherwise, Black's operation makes no sense.} 8. exf4 Bf6 {The dark-squared bishop is strong, especially since White doesn't have one anymore.} 9. Nc3 c5 ({Black's only active plan. Again} 9... b6 {will transpose to a position from the 4...[b6] move order.}) 10. Qd2 ({White keeps the tension. Also good is} 10. dxc5 {.}) 10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nc6 12. Nf3 {White has nice pressure down the d- and e-files and it is hard for Black to develop the queenside. For starters, we can centralize the rooks with [Rfe1] and [Rad1], and later maybe expand on the queenside with [a2]-[a3] + [b2]-[b4].} *

