1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 ({Please notice the move order. I recommend starting with the more flexible} 3. e3 {. If Black plays ...[e7]-[e6] it doesn't matter, but it is an important detail against ...[g7]-[g6], which we have just seen.}) 3... e6 4. Nf3 b6 {The bishop will be great at [b7].} 5. Be2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. c4 ({We ignore Black's Nh5 threat. Otherwise, it is possible to play} 7. h3 {but I prefer not to lose any time.}) 7... O-O ({If} 7... Nh5 {, then} 8. Nc3 O-O {transposes back to the current variation.}) 8. Nc3 Nh5 9. Re1 ({Most people play} 9. Bg3 {, it is not bad, but Black is not really threatening to take on [f4], because it opens the e-file for our rook and the [f4]-pawn stops all black activity on the kingside.}) 9... Nxf4 {Not forced, but why else did Black play [Nh5]?} 10. exf4 Bf6 {A good place for the bishop.} 11. Rc1 (11. Rc1 {White has complete control. If Black plays} c5 {, we respond with} 12. d5 $1 {shutting [Bb7] out. Otherwise, we can slowly improve the position. I like the regrouping [g2]-[g3], followed by [Bf1] and [Bg2].}) *

