1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 ({Please notice the move order. I recommend starting with the more flexible} 3. e3 {. If Black plays ...[e7]-[e6] it doesn't matter, but it is an important detail against ...[g7]-[g6], which we have just seen.}) 3... e6 4. Nf3 b6 {The bishop will be great at [b7].} 5. Be2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. c4 ({We ignore Black's Nh5 threat. Otherwise, it is possible to play} 7. h3 {but I prefer not to lose any time.}) 7... O-O ({If} 7... Nh5 {, then} 8. Nc3 O-O {transposes back to the current variation.}) 8. Nc3 d6 9. h3 {Always a useful move and here it is setting a cunning trap.} Qe8 ({I have won several blitz games after} 9... Nbd7 $2 10. Ng5 $1) ({Black could consider} 9... Ne4 {, please compare with the mainline 8...[Ne4].} 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. Nd2 Bb7 12. Bf3 {White is slightly better.}) 10. Rc1 {Developing and improving.} Nbd7 {Now Black has [Bd8] as a response to [Ng5].} 11. Nb5 ({But now c7 is also weak!} 11. b4 {is also good for White.}) 11... Qb8 12. Ng5 e5 13. Bh2 {It is hard to say if the bishop should retreat to [h2] or [g3]. This time I have chosen [h2]!} a6 14. Nc3 {White will install a knight on [e6] with a big advantage.} *

