1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 ({Please notice the move order. I recommend starting with the more flexible} 3. e3 {. If Black plays ...[e7]-[e6] it doesn't matter, but it is an important detail against ...[g7]-[g6], which we have just seen.}) 3... e6 4. Nf3 b6 {The bishop will be great at [b7].} 5. Be2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. c4 ({We ignore Black's Nh5 threat. Otherwise, it is possible to play} 7. h3 {but I prefer not to lose any time.}) 7... O-O ({If} 7... Nh5 {, then} 8. Nc3 O-O {transposes back to the current variation.}) 8. Nc3 Ne4 9. Nxe4 {The knight was annoying so let's get rid of it!} Bxe4 10. Bg3 ({A prophylactic move. Now the bishop can't be hit. A simple positional alternative is} 10. Nd2 Bb7 11. Bf3 {which has scored extremely well.}) 10... Bf6 {A nice spot for the bishop.} 11. Nd2 Bb7 12. b4 {White gains space on the queenside. Soon we will simplify with [Bf3] and exchange the strong [Bb7] which should give some nice long-term pressure.} *

