1. d4 g6 {A normal move. Black wants to fianchetto the kingside bishop with [Bg7] and later decide if [Nf6] is to be played or not.} (1... g6 {The move allows} 2. e4 $1 {, when Black must be ready to play a Modern/Pirc. That is outside the scope of this repertoire, but of course, 2.e4 is a good move.}) 2. Nf3 Bg7 3. e3 {We more or less have to do this to stay in our comfort zone.} f5 {Here we are unfortunately kind of move-ordered, because against the Dutch I propose an entirely different setup. That said, even here it is possible to come up with something original.} 4. b4 $5 {Taking space on the queenside just as we did against the King's Indian Attack and Grunfeld.} d6 5. Nbd2 Nh6 $5 {Intending [Nf7] is playable as well.} 6. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4g8] Taking the important diagonal that Black's [f5]-move weakened.} Nf7 {Necessary to be able to castle.} 7. O-O e6 {A flexible move that takes the stings out of [Bc4].} 8. a4 {We use the free move to take more space.} ({The immediate} 8. Re1 O-O 9. e4 $2 {backfires after} fxe4 10. Nxe4 d5 {and Black wins a piece.}) 8... O-O 9. Bb2 {First development.} Re8 10. Ba2 {Then a nice prophylactic move.} b6 11. Re1 {[%cal Ge3e4] And finally the execution of the plan.} Bb7 12. e4 (12. e4 {White has nice play. A sample line goes:} fxe4 13. Nxe4 d5 {now, with the bishop on [a2], this doesn't win a piece.} 14. Ng3 c5 15. bxc5 bxc5 16. c4 {, there is maximum tension in the centre. It is a position where you shouldn't hurry to exchange the pawns because it gives freedom to the opponent's pieces.} Na6 17. Rc1 Nb4 18. Bb3 {I prefer White. Probably, Black has to take on [d4] and [c4] which in the end leave them with a weak pawn on [e6].}) *

