1. d4 g6 {A normal move. Black wants to fianchetto the kingside bishop with [Bg7] and later decide if [Nf6] is to be played or not.} (1... g6 {The move allows} 2. e4 $1 {, when Black must be ready to play a Modern/Pirc. That is outside the scope of this repertoire, but of course, 2.e4 is a good move.}) 2. Nf3 Bg7 3. e3 {We more or less have to do this to stay in our comfort zone.} f5 {Here we are unfortunately kind of move-ordered, because against the Dutch I propose an entirely different setup. That said, even here it is possible to come up with something original.} 4. b4 $5 {Taking space on the queenside just as we did against the King's Indian Attack and Grunfeld.} d6 5. Nbd2 Nh6 $5 {Intending [Nf7] is playable as well.} 6. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4g8] Taking the important diagonal that Black's [f5]-move weakened.} Nf7 {Necessary to be able to castle.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Ng5 {A forcing move.} d5 9. Nxf7 Rxf7 10. Be2 e5 {If Black doesn't play this move now White will prevent it with [Nf3].} 11. dxe5 Bxe5 12. Rb1 {[%cal Gd2f3,Gc2c4,Gc1b2] White is better. White can hit the bishop with [Nf3] and follow up with [c2]-[c4]. Later, if we want, we can exchange the dark-squared bishops with [Bb2]. Black's other bishop will always be bad in such structures.} *

