1. d4 g6 {A normal move. Black wants to fianchetto the kingside bishop with [Bg7] and later decide if [Nf6] is to be played or not.} (1... g6 {The move allows} 2. e4 $1 {, when Black must be ready to play a Modern/Pirc. That is outside the scope of this repertoire, but of course, 2.e4 is a good move.}) 2. Nf3 Bg7 3. e3 {We more or less have to do this to stay in our comfort zone.} f5 {Here we are unfortunately kind of move-ordered, because against the Dutch I propose an entirely different setup. That said, even here it is possible to come up with something original.} 4. b4 $5 {Taking space on the queenside just as we did against the King's Indian Attack and Grunfeld.} Nf6 {Black goes for a normal Leningrad.} 5. Be2 {We prioritize rapid development.} ({Also fine is} 5. Bb2 O-O 6. c4 {, and I prefer White.}) 5... O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Bb2 {Now it is hard for Black to get ...[e7]-[e5] in, in a good way, but it is still the only sensible plan.} Qe8 ({Trying to develop the light-squared bishop is a mistake:} 7... b6 8. c4 e6 9. Nc3 {White is better. If} Bb7 $6 {then} 10. d5 $1 e5 11. Ng5 Bc8 12. c5 {is strong, for instance,} bxc5 13. bxc5 dxc5 14. Ba3 Na6 15. Rc1 {, planning [Na4] and taking on [c5].}) 8. c4 Nbd7 9. Nc3 c6 (9... e5 {is bad because of} 10. Nb5 $1) 10. Qc2 e5 11. b5 (11. b5 {White's play on the queenside comes first. A sample line goes:} e4 12. Nd2 c5 13. Nb3 b6 14. a4 {, followed by [a4]-[a5] and [Rfd1] with strong pressure.}) *

