1. d4 g6 {A normal move. Black wants to fianchetto the kingside bishop with [Bg7] and later decide if [Nf6] is to be played or not.} (1... g6 {The move allows} 2. e4 $1 {, when Black must be ready to play a Modern/Pirc. That is outside the scope of this repertoire, but of course, 2.e4 is a good move.}) 2. Nf3 Bg7 3. e3 {We more or less have to do this to stay in our comfort zone.} d6 {Black plays for [e7]-[e5]. Against our [e3]-move there were many other plausible continuations.} (3... c5 4. Be2 {you could also take on [c5], but this is easy. Pretty soon Black will play [Nf6] with a transposition to other lines.}) (3... d5 4. Be2 {this will also transpose, but here also 4.c4 is good.}) (3... Nf6 {this is the most direct transposition.}) 4. Be2 e5 {This is possible, but it leads to a nice ending for White.} 5. dxe5 dxe5 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Nc3 {[%csl Gd8][%cal Gc1d2,Ge1c1] I like White. We will play [Bd2] and castle long with a big lead in development. Black's king is badly placed on [d8].} *

