1. d4 g6 {A normal move. Black wants to fianchetto the kingside bishop with [Bg7] and later decide if [Nf6] is to be played or not.} (1... g6 {The move allows} 2. e4 $1 {, when Black must be ready to play a Modern/Pirc. That is outside the scope of this repertoire, but of course, 2.e4 is a good move.}) 2. Nf3 Bg7 3. e3 {We more or less have to do this to stay in our comfort zone.} d6 {Black plays for [e7]-[e5]. Against our [e3]-move there were many other plausible continuations.} (3... c5 4. Be2 {you could also take on [c5], but this is easy. Pretty soon Black will play [Nf6] with a transposition to other lines.}) (3... d5 4. Be2 {this will also transpose, but here also 4.c4 is good.}) (3... Nf6 {this is the most direct transposition.}) 4. Be2 Nc6 {This is another way to prepare for [e7]-[e5].} 5. O-O e5 6. dxe5 {Always take. Of course, it is not forced, but it makes it much easier to remember!} dxe5 7. Qxd8+ Nxd8 {This way Black is better off than with the king on [d8]. Still, it loses time and White dictates the play.} 8. Nc3 c6 {Covering [b5] and [d5].} ({On} 8... Ne7 9. Nb5 $1 {is strong.}) 9. a4 {Grabbing space and securing the important [c4]-square because Black no longer can play [b5].} Bf5 {[%csl Gc2] Hitting [c2].} ({After} 9... Ne7 10. Rd1 O-O 11. e4 Ne6 12. Be3 {Black can hardly move. White will probably play [Bc4] next.}) 10. e4 Bg4 11. Nd1 {[%cal Gd1e3] White regroups. The knight can go to [e3] next and later maybe to [c4]. If Black takes on [f3] and tries to get to [d4] with a knight we can always cover that square with [c2]-[c3]. The position is unpleasant for Black.} *

