1. d4 g6 {A normal move. Black wants to fianchetto the kingside bishop with [Bg7] and later decide if [Nf6] is to be played or not.} (1... g6 {The move allows} 2. e4 $1 {, when Black must be ready to play a Modern/Pirc. That is outside the scope of this repertoire, but of course, 2.e4 is a good move.}) 2. Nf3 Bg7 3. e3 {We more or less have to do this to stay in our comfort zone.} d6 {Black plays for [e7]-[e5]. Against our [e3]-move there were many other plausible continuations.} (3... c5 4. Be2 {you could also take on [c5], but this is easy. Pretty soon Black will play [Nf6] with a transposition to other lines.}) (3... d5 4. Be2 {this will also transpose, but here also 4.c4 is good.}) (3... Nf6 {this is the most direct transposition.}) 4. Be2 Nd7 {[%cal Ge7e5] Black prepares the [e5]-break. Of course you have to understand what is White's idea. It is quite simple: When Black plays [e5] we take it! In the following lines, we will meet this strategy in various positions, so we really can appreciate its strenght.} 5. O-O e5 ({Here} 5... Ngf6 6. b3 {or 6.c4 will transpose to the Anti King's Indian part.}) 6. dxe5 {Again: there are other fine moves, but this is what we do in this repertoire!} dxe5 ({We have already seen} 6... Nxe5 {in the [Nc6] line.}) 7. e4 {You can also start with [Nc3], but I have a concrete reason for prefering 7. [e4].} Ngf6 {Attacking the e-pawn.} ({The passive} 7... Ne7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. a4 {is nice for White.}) 8. Bc4 {A novelty! This is my idea.} (8. Nc3 O-O {has been played in several games, but in my opinion, it is ok for Black.}) 8... O-O ({Not} 8... Nxe4 9. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 10. Qd5+ {followed by [Qxe4] with great play.}) 9. Qe2 {We cover [e4] this way.} c6 {Black's typical structure.} 10. a4 {The standard setup on the queenside.} Qc7 ({Or} 10... Nc5 11. Nbd2 Qe7 12. b3 {, followed by [Ba3].}) 11. Nbd2 Nb6 ({The sharp} 11... Nh5 {intending [Nf4] is met by the cool} 12. g3 {and Black gets nowhere.}) 12. Bb3 {I prefer to stay on this diagonal.} ({Possible is} 12. Bd3 {, and leads to similar play. A sample line goes:} a5 13. b3 Nh5 14. g3 Re8 15. Ba3 Bh3 16. Rfd1 h6 17. Nc4 Nxc4 18. Bxc4 Bf8 {and Black seems ok although I still slightly prefer White.}) 12... a5 {[%csl Gb3,Gg7] Black blocks the a-pawn. The position is almost equal. Still, I think White has a slight edge. This is because [Bg7] is staring at its own pawn on [e5], while [Bb3] is much more active.} 13. Re1 Nh5 {This is Black's usual plan in similar positions.} 14. Nc4 (14. g3 {is also possible.}) 14... Nxc4 15. Bxc4 Nf4 16. Qe3 {[%cal Ge3c3] The queen looks clumsy on [e3], but next move it might go to [c3]. White is somewhat more comfortable, but there is nothing concrete going on.} *

