1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Nf3 {I guess in 9 out of 10 games Black will respond automatically with} Nf6 {, but there are some alternatives. Often they will just transpose, but since we generally refrain from an early c2-c4 in this repertoire some lines are quite playable for Black. On the top level, the active move 2...c5 has been very popular lately, but as we will see it is not really a problem for Colle-players!}) 2... c6 {If Black is a Slav-player, this is a natural move.} 3. e3 Bg4 4. h3 {It is possible just to play [Nbd2], but I like chasing the bishop. White is slightly better after [Bxf3], so Black should withdraw.} Bh5 5. Nbd2 ({The simplest.} 5. g4 {is consequent} Bg6 6. Ne5 {the point. White gains the pair of bishops with a pleasant position.} Nd7 7. Nxg6 hxg6 8. c4 e6 {now after} 9. Nc3 Ngf6 {. Or 9.Qb3 Qb6 10.Nc3 Ngf6 we transpose to one of the modern mainlines of the Slav. White is slightly better, but in this repertoire, we try to avoid heavy theory!}) ({Here Nf6} 5. g4 Bg6 6. Ne5 {is good for White.}) 5... Nd7 6. Bd3 (6. e4 $2 {an original solution. I kind of like White.}) 6... e5 ({The more normal} 6... Ngf6 {transposes to the Colle 3...c6.}) 7. g4 {Novelty!} e4 {Otherwise, the e-pawn is lost.} 8. gxh5 exd3 ({Really bad for Black is} 8... exf3 9. Qxf3 {where White keeps the extra pawn and has the bishops.}) 9. cxd3 (9. cxd3 {White is better, although the position is quite unclear. A sample line goes:} Qc7 {, controlling [e5].} 10. Nf1 Ngf6 11. Nh4 {White keeps the extra pawn, but Black can castle long with some compensation.}) (9. cxd3 Ngf6 {is met by} 10. Ne5 {.}) *

