1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Nf3 {I guess in 9 out of 10 games Black will respond automatically with} Nf6 {, but there are some alternatives. Often they will just transpose, but since we generally refrain from an early c2-c4 in this repertoire some lines are quite playable for Black. On the top level, the active move 2...c5 has been very popular lately, but as we will see it is not really a problem for Colle-players!}) 2... c6 {If Black is a Slav-player, this is a natural move.} 3. e3 ({The Colle-concept. Of course, you could choose other anti-Slav lines like} 3. g3 {or 3.Bf4 .}) 3... Bf5 4. Bd3 {This is what we do in the normal Colle.} e6 $5 ({Black could also take on} 4... Bxd3 {or play 4...Bg6 , but that is likely to transpose to the Colle. I mean, it is hard not to play ...[Nf6] soon.}) 5. O-O ({We could play} 5. Bxf5 exf5 6. O-O {which would probably just transpose to the mainline, but like I mentioned in the next note I prefer to wait a little. If we compare it with the Colle 3...Bf5 , here we can't force Black to play the move [Qc8], that's the difference!}) 5... Nf6 {Now it is quite similar to some Colle positions, we have seen. I am in no hurry to take on [f5] because that would only strenghtens Black's control over the important [e4]-square. Instead, it is good to develop the queenside and take some space there.} 6. b3 Nbd7 7. c4 Bd6 8. Bxf5 {OK, finally we take.} exf5 9. Qd3 {[%csl Gf5] Forcing a slight weakness.} g6 10. Ba3 {[%csl Gd6] We exchange Black's strong bishop.} Bxa3 11. Nxa3 {[%cal Ga3b1,Gb1c3] The position is rather balanced, but White's better structure and extra space on the queenside give us something to build on. I suggest that we start by improving the knight with [Na3]-[b1]-[c3] with a more normal setup. Then we can decide how to advance further.} *

