1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Nf3 {I guess in 9 out of 10 games Black will respond automatically with} Nf6 {, but there are some alternatives. Often they will just transpose, but since we generally refrain from an early c2-c4 in this repertoire some lines are quite playable for Black. On the top level, the active move 2...c5 has been very popular lately, but as we will see it is not really a problem for Colle-players!}) 2... Nc6 {Played by Chigorin-players. We have no intention of playing an early [c2]-[c4] though.} 3. e3 {You guessed it!} Bg4 ({Inferior is the reversed Jobava variation} 3... Bf5 {I think, I will go for} 4. Bb5 {with good play, but 4.a3 , followed by [c2]-[c4] is also strong. [Nc6] is generally misplaced when there is no threat to go to [b4].}) 4. Bb5 $1 {Pinning the knight and being ready to damage Black's structure if we want to.} ({The most popular is} 4. Be2 {which is also fine, but we can already exploit Black's opening play and strive for more.}) 4... e6 5. Nbd2 {A flexible move. We decide if or when we will play [c2]-[c4].} Bd6 6. c4 {Here it is good.} dxc4 ({Of course not} 6... Nge7 $2 7. c5 {, and the bishop is lost.}) 7. Bxc6+ $1 {Ruining Black's queenside.} bxc6 8. Qa4 Ne7 9. Qxc4 {[%csl Gc6,Gc7] White is much better because of the superior pawn structure. White has several good plans. Just castle with or without [h2]-[h3] and maybe push [e3]-[e4] is one of them.} *

