1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Nf3 {I guess in 9 out of 10 games Black will respond automatically with} Nf6 {, but there are some alternatives. Often they will just transpose, but since we generally refrain from an early c2-c4 in this repertoire some lines are quite playable for Black. On the top level, the active move 2...c5 has been very popular lately, but as we will see it is not really a problem for Colle-players!}) 2... Nc6 {Played by Chigorin-players. We have no intention of playing an early [c2]-[c4] though.} 3. e3 {You guessed it!} Bg4 ({Inferior is the reversed Jobava variation} 3... Bf5 {I think, I will go for} 4. Bb5 {with good play, but 4.a3 , followed by [c2]-[c4] is also strong. [Nc6] is generally misplaced when there is no threat to go to [b4].}) 4. Bb5 $1 {Pinning the knight and being ready to damage Black's structure if we want to.} ({The most popular is} 4. Be2 {which is also fine, but we can already exploit Black's opening play and strive for more.}) 4... e6 5. Nbd2 {A flexible move. We decide if or when we will play [c2]-[c4].} Nge7 {Protecting the other knight and avoiding a double pawn..} 6. h3 {It makes sense to include this useful move as Black will not give the bishop for a knight.} Bh5 7. O-O a6 {The point of [Nge7], but we just go back.} 8. Be2 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Gb2b3,Gc2c4] White is better. The knight on [e7] has to be moved to develop the kingside and the other knight on [c6] isn't that great either. White will play [c2]-[c4] or [b2]-[b3] first with good play.} *

