1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Nf3 {I guess in 9 out of 10 games Black will respond automatically with} Nf6 {, but there are some alternatives. Often they will just transpose, but since we generally refrain from an early c2-c4 in this repertoire some lines are quite playable for Black. On the top level, the active move 2...c5 has been very popular lately, but as we will see it is not really a problem for Colle-players!}) 2... Bf5 (2... Bf5 {This is somewhat inaccurate because of} 3. c4 $1) 3. e3 {But let's see what happens if we just play the concept move.} e6 4. Bd3 Bxd3 (4... Bg6 5. O-O {doesn't change much; 4...Nf6 is a direct transposition to Colle with 3...[Bf5].}) 5. Qxd3 c6 6. O-O f5 $5 {Black creates a Stonewall formation known from the Dutch. It is a big achievement that the passive bishop on [c8] has been exchanged, still White has good chances to come out on top because of the nice [e5]-square that Black's last move permanently weakened.} ({The more normal} 6... Nf6 {leads to the Colle.}) 7. b3 Nd7 8. c4 {White builds up with natural moves.} Nh6 ({Played by Morozevich. Black must be careful. The natural} 8... Ngf6 {is in fact a blunder.} 9. Ng5 $1 Qe7 10. Ba3 $1 {and Black is busted.}) 9. a4 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gc1a3] Taking space. White will exchange the bishops with [Ba3] and combine some pressure on the queenside with control over the important [e5]-square.} *

