1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Nf3 {I guess in 9 out of 10 games Black will respond automatically with} Nf6 {, but there are some alternatives. Often they will just transpose, but since we generally refrain from an early c2-c4 in this repertoire some lines are quite playable for Black. On the top level, the active move 2...c5 has been very popular lately, but as we will see it is not really a problem for Colle-players!}) 2... Bg4 {A kind of reversed Trompowsky!} 3. Ne5 $1 ({Going for a big advantage. I mean Bg4 can't be correct, can it? Otherwise, the concept move} 3. e3 {could, of course, be played as well.}) 3... Bh5 {This is sometimes seen in the Trompowsky, especially in the old days. It is just bad!} 4. g4 $1 Bg6 ({Not} 4... f6 5. gxh5 fxe5 6. dxe5 {and White is close to winning.}) 5. h4 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gh4h5] The bishop is a target.} f6 (5... h6 6. Nxg6 fxg6 7. Qd3 {is horrible for Black.}) 6. Nxg6 hxg6 7. Qd3 {[%csl Gg6]} Kf7 8. h5 $1 (8. h5 {White is close to winning. A sample line goes:} gxh5 9. Rxh5 Rxh5 10. gxh5 e6 11. Qg6+ Ke7 12. Qh7 Kf7 13. Bh3 {, threatening [Bxe6]+} Ne7 14. Nd2 {, followed by [Nf3]. Black won't survive this.}) *

