1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Nf3 {I guess in 9 out of 10 games Black will respond automatically with} Nf6 {, but there are some alternatives. Often they will just transpose, but since we generally refrain from an early c2-c4 in this repertoire some lines are quite playable for Black. On the top level, the active move 2...c5 has been very popular lately, but as we will see it is not really a problem for Colle-players!}) 2... Bg4 {A kind of reversed Trompowsky!} 3. Ne5 $1 ({Going for a big advantage. I mean Bg4 can't be correct, can it? Otherwise, the concept move} 3. e3 {could, of course, be played as well.}) 3... Bf5 4. c4 {We should continue with active moves so Black won't have time to consolidate.} e6 {The most natural way to defend [d5].} 5. Qb3 {[%csl Gb7] Attacking [b7]. We go for a small, but long-term plus.} ({The engine proposes} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. e4 $1 Bxe4 7. Nc3 {with a strong initiative for the pawn.}) 5... Nc6 {This is forced.} (5... b6 6. Nc3 {is really bad.}) 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Qa4 Qd7 8. Nc3 {[%csl Gc6,Gc7][%cal Gc1f4] White is at least slightly better because of the better structure and good squares for the pieces. The dark-squared bishop will probably go to [f4]. If Black plays [Bd6] we can kick the bishop away with [c4]-[c5] first and then play [Bf4].} *

