1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Nf3 {I guess in 9 out of 10 games Black will respond automatically with} Nf6 {, but there are some alternatives. Often they will just transpose, but since we generally refrain from an early c2-c4 in this repertoire some lines are quite playable for Black. On the top level, the active move 2...c5 has been very popular lately, but as we will see it is not really a problem for Colle-players!}) 2... Bg4 {A kind of reversed Trompowsky!} 3. Ne5 $1 ({Going for a big advantage. I mean Bg4 can't be correct, can it? Otherwise, the concept move} 3. e3 {could, of course, be played as well.}) 3... Bf5 4. c4 {We should continue with active moves so Black won't have time to consolidate.} f6 {Weakening the kingside.} 5. Nf3 {The pawn on [f6] makes Black's development awkward.} e6 6. Nc3 c6 7. e3 ({It was also good to go for a Catalan type of position with} 7. g3 {.}) 7... Bd6 8. Nh4 $1 {[%csl Gf5] Going after the black bishop.} Ne7 9. Nxf5 Nxf5 {This might look almost ok for Black, but I think White is much better!} 10. Qb3 {[%csl Gb7] Attacking [b7].} Qd7 11. Bd3 {White has the bishops and especially the light-squared one is really strong. Already [Bxf5] must be taken serious. The move [f7]-[f6] has also weakened Black's structure.} *

