1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Nf3 {I guess in 9 out of 10 games Black will respond automatically with} Nf6 {, but there are some alternatives. Often they will just transpose, but since we generally refrain from an early c2-c4 in this repertoire some lines are quite playable for Black. On the top level, the active move 2...c5 has been very popular lately, but as we will see it is not really a problem for Colle-players!}) 2... e6 3. e3 {If you want to play a Catalan ( 3.g3 or a London) ( 3.Bf4 or a normal QGD) ( 3.c4 ) then you're welcome. In this repertoire, we go for [e2]-[e3]!} f5 $6 ({This leads to a kind of Dutch Stonewall. Positionally, it was more sensible to play a Colle with} 3... Nf6 {, but some players just won't listen, will they?}) 4. Bd3 {The bishop could also just go to [e2].} Nf6 5. O-O Bd6 {The bishop is active here and it covers the big hole on [e5] that is the consequence of the move [f7]-[f5].} 6. c4 {There is no law against us playing [c2]-[c4]! In most lines, we don't, but not in all. And here it is just good. We transpose to a typical Dutch position, where we have a clear-cut plan.} c6 7. b3 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gc1a3] We want to trade the dark-squared bishops with [Ba3] and leave Black with a very bad bishop on [c8] and a terrible hole on [e5].} Qe7 {[%csl Ga3] Preventing [Ba3] for now.} 8. a4 {[%cal Gc1a3] But not for long.} a5 {The main move.} ({Or} 8... O-O 9. Ba3 {, and White is pleasantly better.}) 9. Ba3 Bxa3 10. Nxa3 O-O 11. Ne5 ({The most precise. Usually White starts to regroup the knight from a3 with} 11. Nc2 {but then Black has time for} b6 {, followed by [Bb7], and White is probably only marginally better.}) 11... b6 ({Or} 11... Nbd7 12. f4 {and White is better. Just compare the two bishops.}) 12. cxd5 exd5 ({If} 12... cxd5 13. Nb5 {and White is much better.}) 13. Qc2 {[%csl Gc6,Gf5] Attacking [f5] and [c6].} Qe6 14. Rfc1 {A novelty! A strong move. In the only game to reach this position White took the other rook, but that gave Black time to activate the [a8]-rook with [Ra7] because the [c6]-pawn is immune. Now White has strong pressure on the queenside and is much better.} (14. Rfc1 {A sample line goes:} Ra7 15. Rab1 $1 c5 {( Or 15...Bd7 16.b4 . )} 16. Nb5 Re7 17. Bf1 {, followed by [Nd3] and Black can't maintain the tension. ( Not 15.Nxc6? Rc7 . )}) *

