1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Nf3 {I guess in 9 out of 10 games Black will respond automatically with} Nf6 {, but there are some alternatives. Often they will just transpose, but since we generally refrain from an early c2-c4 in this repertoire some lines are quite playable for Black. On the top level, the active move 2...c5 has been very popular lately, but as we will see it is not really a problem for Colle-players!}) 2... c5 3. e3 Nc6 {Black develops sound and active.} (3... Nf6 {transposes to a normal Colle;}) ({And} 3... e6 {can be met by} 4. c3 {or 4.b3 and we will be inside the repertoire as soon as Black plays [Nf6].}) (3... cxd4 4. exd4 {leads to the typical Carlsbad-structure.}) ({See more after} 3... Nc6 4. c3 cxd4 {.}) 4. c3 ({This is the simplest way to stay inside our repertoire. Now it is likely that we will play a reversed Semi-Slav Meran. There are some decent alternatives as well:} 4. Be2 {White just plays a normal QGD with an extra move. The only problem is that we are White and we are supposed to do something!}) (4. dxc5 $5 {is an original attempt to get out of the theory books (or courses!) fast and still play positionally sound chess.} e6 {( Not 4...e5 5.Bb5!)} 5. a3 Bxc5 {( On 5...a5 White can play 6.b3 or 6.c4 . )} 6. b4 {, followed by [Bb2] and [Nbd2] with a very harmonious position. Later White will play [c4] and maybe not be better, but at least be more comfortable.}) 4... cxd4 {This is a very important option and I am sure many Caro-Kann players would go for it.} 5. exd4 {This is a Caro-Kann! In this course, I prefer to call it a Carlsbad structure from the Queen's Gambit Declined with reversed colours. Why all the subtitles? It is just words! Yes, but the way we describe things influences our mindset. And since the Colle is very similar to playing a QGD with an extra move, I think we should stay in that frame of mind. Having made courses about the QGD and the Caro-Kann I should know what I am talking about. However, your sympathies can quickly change. Of course Black must be ok, objectively speaking, but we still have a great version of the Exchange Variation in the Queen's Gambit! Which can be translated to: no problems and pretty easy play.} Bg4 {A good active move with only one drawback.} 6. h3 Bh5 {Taking on [f3] is obviously nice for White.} 7. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Gb7] The bishop no longer protects [b7].} Qd7 8. Ne5 $1 {[%cal Ge5d7] We play very aggressive moves to get the initiative.} Nxe5 9. dxe5 {[%cal Gf1b5] Threatening [Bb5]. Black's reply is forced.} a6 10. c4 {Opening the position.} dxc4 11. Bxc4 e6 12. O-O (12. O-O {White is ahead in development and has good chances. • A sample line goes:} Ne7 13. g4 $1 Bg6 14. Rd1 Qc7 15. Be3 Nc6 16. Nd2 Na5 17. Qc3 Nxc4 18. Nxc4 Be7 19. Nd6+ Bxd6 20. exd6 Qxc3 21. d7+ Ke7 22. bxc3 {, and White was winning with [Bc5]+ and [Bb6] in F. Svane-Ezat, blitz 2022.}) (12. O-O {• In my Caro-Kann course, I gave the novelty} b5 $1 {N as an improvement:} 13. Bd3 Rd8 14. Be4 Bc5 {Black gets the pieces out, next comes [Ne7]. The position is balanced, but White has some initiative.}) *

