1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Nf3 {I guess in 9 out of 10 games Black will respond automatically with} Nf6 {, but there are some alternatives. Often they will just transpose, but since we generally refrain from an early c2-c4 in this repertoire some lines are quite playable for Black. On the top level, the active move 2...c5 has been very popular lately, but as we will see it is not really a problem for Colle-players!}) 2... c5 3. e3 Nc6 {Black develops sound and active.} (3... Nf6 {transposes to a normal Colle;}) ({And} 3... e6 {can be met by} 4. c3 {or 4.b3 and we will be inside the repertoire as soon as Black plays [Nf6].}) (3... cxd4 4. exd4 {leads to the typical Carlsbad-structure.}) ({See more after} 3... Nc6 4. c3 cxd4 {.}) 4. c3 ({This is the simplest way to stay inside our repertoire. Now it is likely that we will play a reversed Semi-Slav Meran. There are some decent alternatives as well:} 4. Be2 {White just plays a normal QGD with an extra move. The only problem is that we are White and we are supposed to do something!}) (4. dxc5 $5 {is an original attempt to get out of the theory books (or courses!) fast and still play positionally sound chess.} e6 {( Not 4...e5 5.Bb5!)} 5. a3 Bxc5 {( On 5...a5 White can play 6.b3 or 6.c4 . )} 6. b4 {, followed by [Bb2] and [Nbd2] with a very harmonious position. Later White will play [c4] and maybe not be better, but at least be more comfortable.}) 4... cxd4 {This is a very important option and I am sure many Caro-Kann players would go for it.} 5. exd4 {This is a Caro-Kann! In this course, I prefer to call it a Carlsbad structure from the Queen's Gambit Declined with reversed colours. Why all the subtitles? It is just words! Yes, but the way we describe things influences our mindset. And since the Colle is very similar to playing a QGD with an extra move, I think we should stay in that frame of mind. Having made courses about the QGD and the Caro-Kann I should know what I am talking about. However, your sympathies can quickly change. Of course Black must be ok, objectively speaking, but we still have a great version of the Exchange Variation in the Queen's Gambit! Which can be translated to: no problems and pretty easy play.} Bf5 6. Qb3 {[%csl Gb7] As soon as the light-squared bishop is developed the [b7]-pawn is a target.} Qd7 7. Nh4 ({The most concrete move. White has also had succes with} 7. Ne5 {, 7.Bb5 or just 7.Bf4 . I prefer to chase the Caro-Kann bishop!}) 7... Be6 $5 {A unique move. If White manages to exchange [Bf5] for a knight it is a success, not that the position is won or anything, but it is pleasant and the game is going in the right direction.} (7... Bg6 8. Nxg6 hxg6 9. Nd2 e6 10. Nf3 {White is slightly better. The bishops!}) (7... Bg4 8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 Bg6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Be3 Nf6 12. Be2 e6 13. Nd2 {again: The bishops!}) 8. Bd3 f6 {Black has to finish development and the bishop on [e6] is clumsy.} 9. O-O Bf7 ({The wild} 9... g5 10. Nf3 Nh6 {has been played in blitz by Keymer but after} 11. Re1 Bf5 12. Bf1 {White had a much more harmonious position in Urazayev-Keymer, blitz 2023.}) 10. f4 e6 11. Nd2 {White has more space and a long-term plan to break with [c3]-[c4].} *

