1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Nf3 {I guess in 9 out of 10 games Black will respond automatically with} Nf6 {, but there are some alternatives. Often they will just transpose, but since we generally refrain from an early c2-c4 in this repertoire some lines are quite playable for Black. On the top level, the active move 2...c5 has been very popular lately, but as we will see it is not really a problem for Colle-players!}) 2... c5 3. e3 Nc6 {Black develops sound and active.} (3... Nf6 {transposes to a normal Colle;}) ({And} 3... e6 {can be met by} 4. c3 {or 4.b3 and we will be inside the repertoire as soon as Black plays [Nf6].}) (3... cxd4 4. exd4 {leads to the typical Carlsbad-structure.}) ({See more after} 3... Nc6 4. c3 cxd4 {.}) 4. c3 ({This is the simplest way to stay inside our repertoire. Now it is likely that we will play a reversed Semi-Slav Meran. There are some decent alternatives as well:} 4. Be2 {White just plays a normal QGD with an extra move. The only problem is that we are White and we are supposed to do something!}) (4. dxc5 $5 {is an original attempt to get out of the theory books (or courses!) fast and still play positionally sound chess.} e6 {( Not 4...e5 5.Bb5!)} 5. a3 Bxc5 {( On 5...a5 White can play 6.b3 or 6.c4 . )} 6. b4 {, followed by [Bb2] and [Nbd2] with a very harmonious position. Later White will play [c4] and maybe not be better, but at least be more comfortable.}) 4... cxd4 {This is a very important option and I am sure many Caro-Kann players would go for it.} 5. exd4 {This is a Caro-Kann! In this course, I prefer to call it a Carlsbad structure from the Queen's Gambit Declined with reversed colours. Why all the subtitles? It is just words! Yes, but the way we describe things influences our mindset. And since the Colle is very similar to playing a QGD with an extra move, I think we should stay in that frame of mind. Having made courses about the QGD and the Caro-Kann I should know what I am talking about. However, your sympathies can quickly change. Of course Black must be ok, objectively speaking, but we still have a great version of the Exchange Variation in the Queen's Gambit! Which can be translated to: no problems and pretty easy play.} g6 {I don't think the bishop is well placed on [g7] in this structure, where the key point [d4] is securely defended by the c-pawn.} 6. Be2 {Simple development. The bishop could also be on [d3], but sooner or later Black will confront it with [Bf5]. I think it is absolutely fine on the modest [e2]-square.} Bg7 7. Bf4 {We could also castle first.} Nh6 {A little artificial, but with a very strong idea behind it.} (7... Bg4 8. Nbd2 {is very much welcomed. If Black will give the bishop pair on f3 we will not prevent it!}) (7... Nf6 {is the most natural. Now after} 8. h3 {we have transposed to the main move 5...Nf6 .}) 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 f6 10. c4 $1 (10. c4 {White comes first and takes the initiative. A game continued} Nf7 11. cxd5 Qxd5 12. Nc3 Qd8 13. d5 {and White was much better in F. Svane-Gonzales Castillo, blitz 2024.}) *

