1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Nf3 {I guess in 9 out of 10 games Black will respond automatically with} Nf6 {, but there are some alternatives. Often they will just transpose, but since we generally refrain from an early c2-c4 in this repertoire some lines are quite playable for Black. On the top level, the active move 2...c5 has been very popular lately, but as we will see it is not really a problem for Colle-players!}) 2... c5 3. e3 Nc6 {Black develops sound and active.} (3... Nf6 {transposes to a normal Colle;}) ({And} 3... e6 {can be met by} 4. c3 {or 4.b3 and we will be inside the repertoire as soon as Black plays [Nf6].}) (3... cxd4 4. exd4 {leads to the typical Carlsbad-structure.}) ({See more after} 3... Nc6 4. c3 cxd4 {.}) 4. c3 ({This is the simplest way to stay inside our repertoire. Now it is likely that we will play a reversed Semi-Slav Meran. There are some decent alternatives as well:} 4. Be2 {White just plays a normal QGD with an extra move. The only problem is that we are White and we are supposed to do something!}) (4. dxc5 $5 {is an original attempt to get out of the theory books (or courses!) fast and still play positionally sound chess.} e6 {( Not 4...e5 5.Bb5!)} 5. a3 Bxc5 {( On 5...a5 White can play 6.b3 or 6.c4 . )} 6. b4 {, followed by [Bb2] and [Nbd2] with a very harmonious position. Later White will play [c4] and maybe not be better, but at least be more comfortable.}) 4... cxd4 {This is a very important option and I am sure many Caro-Kann players would go for it.} 5. exd4 {This is a Caro-Kann! In this course, I prefer to call it a Carlsbad structure from the Queen's Gambit Declined with reversed colours. Why all the subtitles? It is just words! Yes, but the way we describe things influences our mindset. And since the Colle is very similar to playing a QGD with an extra move, I think we should stay in that frame of mind. Having made courses about the QGD and the Caro-Kann I should know what I am talking about. However, your sympathies can quickly change. Of course Black must be ok, objectively speaking, but we still have a great version of the Exchange Variation in the Queen's Gambit! Which can be translated to: no problems and pretty easy play.} Nf6 {The most natural move. Knights out first! There are other options, of course.} 6. Bf4 {This move is hard to achieve in the normal QGD, so already a small victory. White has tried many other moves, but let's stick with this one.} g6 7. h3 {[%cal Gf4h2] Securing our own bishop a retreat square on [h2] and at the same time preventing [Bg4] for good.} Bg7 {The bishop is not really good here. That is why I don't like this [g6]-line for Black, but it is being played a lot.} 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Bf5 10. Nbd2 (10. Nbd2 {White is slightly better. A good plan is to slowly improve the position with Re1 and Bf1 before deciding on any active operations. A sample line goes:} Rc8 11. Re1 Re8 12. Bf1 Ne4 {The only active plan.} 13. Nxe4 {starting some forced play.} Bxe4 14. Ng5 Bf5 15. g4 Bd7 {and now I propose} 16. Bg2 {N} e6 17. Nf3 {White has good potential to build a strong attack. Please notice how the proud Caro-Kann bishop on [f5] now is a passive piece on [d7] locked in behind the [e6]-pawn.}) *

