1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Nf3 {I guess in 9 out of 10 games Black will respond automatically with} Nf6 {, but there are some alternatives. Often they will just transpose, but since we generally refrain from an early c2-c4 in this repertoire some lines are quite playable for Black. On the top level, the active move 2...c5 has been very popular lately, but as we will see it is not really a problem for Colle-players!}) 2... c5 3. e3 Nc6 {Black develops sound and active.} (3... Nf6 {transposes to a normal Colle;}) ({And} 3... e6 {can be met by} 4. c3 {or 4.b3 and we will be inside the repertoire as soon as Black plays [Nf6].}) (3... cxd4 4. exd4 {leads to the typical Carlsbad-structure.}) ({See more after} 3... Nc6 4. c3 cxd4 {.}) 4. c3 ({This is the simplest way to stay inside our repertoire. Now it is likely that we will play a reversed Semi-Slav Meran. There are some decent alternatives as well:} 4. Be2 {White just plays a normal QGD with an extra move. The only problem is that we are White and we are supposed to do something!}) (4. dxc5 $5 {is an original attempt to get out of the theory books (or courses!) fast and still play positionally sound chess.} e6 {( Not 4...e5 5.Bb5!)} 5. a3 Bxc5 {( On 5...a5 White can play 6.b3 or 6.c4 . )} 6. b4 {, followed by [Bb2] and [Nbd2] with a very harmonious position. Later White will play [c4] and maybe not be better, but at least be more comfortable.}) 4... cxd4 {This is a very important option and I am sure many Caro-Kann players would go for it.} 5. exd4 {This is a Caro-Kann! In this course, I prefer to call it a Carlsbad structure from the Queen's Gambit Declined with reversed colours. Why all the subtitles? It is just words! Yes, but the way we describe things influences our mindset. And since the Colle is very similar to playing a QGD with an extra move, I think we should stay in that frame of mind. Having made courses about the QGD and the Caro-Kann I should know what I am talking about. However, your sympathies can quickly change. Of course Black must be ok, objectively speaking, but we still have a great version of the Exchange Variation in the Queen's Gambit! Which can be translated to: no problems and pretty easy play.} Nf6 {The most natural move. Knights out first! There are other options, of course.} 6. Bf4 {This move is hard to achieve in the normal QGD, so already a small victory. White has tried many other moves, but let's stick with this one.} e6 {If all the black pieces had voted, then [Bc8] would have been against this move!} 7. Bd3 Be7 {This is solid, but also a little passive.} 8. Nbd2 O-O ({The wild} 8... Nh5 9. Be3 f5 {backfires after} 10. Ne5 $1) 9. O-O ({Also good is} 9. Ne5 {.}) 9... Nh5 {If Black doesn't play this, White has time to improve the position with [Re1] and [h2]-[h3] with a nice edge based on much more active pieces.} 10. Be3 f5 {Having said 'A', Black should say 'B'.} 11. Ne5 $1 {[%cal Gd1h5] Hitting the knight on the rim.} Nf6 ({After} 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 g6 {Black creates some new weaknesses and doesn't solve the problem with [Nh5]. White is much better after:} 13. f4 {.}) 12. Ndf3 {White coordinates very well. The move [f5] has permanently weakened the [e5]-square and [e6] is a backwards pawn that could be attacked later. White has a static advantage and is in no hurry.} ({Going back with} 12. Bf4 {was also an option.}) 12... Ne4 {The most annoying move for White.} 13. Re1 Bd7 14. Nxc6 {Only one of the white knights can be on [e5], so it makes sense to exchange a key defender.} Bxc6 15. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf2f3] White is much better. Next comes [f2]-[f3] and the [e4]-knight is forced to retreat. Afterwards, the consequences of the [f5]-operation are visible to the World: the nice [e5]-outpost and the weak [e6]-pawn.} *

