1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Nf3 {I guess in 9 out of 10 games Black will respond automatically with} Nf6 {, but there are some alternatives. Often they will just transpose, but since we generally refrain from an early c2-c4 in this repertoire some lines are quite playable for Black. On the top level, the active move 2...c5 has been very popular lately, but as we will see it is not really a problem for Colle-players!}) 2... c5 3. e3 Nc6 {Black develops sound and active.} (3... Nf6 {transposes to a normal Colle;}) ({And} 3... e6 {can be met by} 4. c3 {or 4.b3 and we will be inside the repertoire as soon as Black plays [Nf6].}) (3... cxd4 4. exd4 {leads to the typical Carlsbad-structure.}) ({See more after} 3... Nc6 4. c3 cxd4 {.}) 4. c3 ({This is the simplest way to stay inside our repertoire. Now it is likely that we will play a reversed Semi-Slav Meran. There are some decent alternatives as well:} 4. Be2 {White just plays a normal QGD with an extra move. The only problem is that we are White and we are supposed to do something!}) (4. dxc5 $5 {is an original attempt to get out of the theory books (or courses!) fast and still play positionally sound chess.} e6 {( Not 4...e5 5.Bb5!)} 5. a3 Bxc5 {( On 5...a5 White can play 6.b3 or 6.c4 . )} 6. b4 {, followed by [Bb2] and [Nbd2] with a very harmonious position. Later White will play [c4] and maybe not be better, but at least be more comfortable.}) 4... cxd4 {This is a very important option and I am sure many Caro-Kann players would go for it.} 5. exd4 {This is a Caro-Kann! In this course, I prefer to call it a Carlsbad structure from the Queen's Gambit Declined with reversed colours. Why all the subtitles? It is just words! Yes, but the way we describe things influences our mindset. And since the Colle is very similar to playing a QGD with an extra move, I think we should stay in that frame of mind. Having made courses about the QGD and the Caro-Kann I should know what I am talking about. However, your sympathies can quickly change. Of course Black must be ok, objectively speaking, but we still have a great version of the Exchange Variation in the Queen's Gambit! Which can be translated to: no problems and pretty easy play.} Nf6 {The most natural move. Knights out first! There are other options, of course.} 6. Bf4 {This move is hard to achieve in the normal QGD, so already a small victory. White has tried many other moves, but let's stick with this one.} Qb6 {[%csl Gb2] We have seen White playing [Qb3] against [Bf5] again and again, so why can't Black do the same?} 7. Qb3 {Because of this! White is ready to weaken Black's structure by taking on [b6].} Qxb3 8. axb3 {[%cal Ga1a7,Gb3b4,Gb4b5] And now White's structure is improved because of the open a-file and the potential [b3]-[b4]-[b5] advance.} Bf5 ({White is also much better after} 8... e6 9. b4 {please notice that ...[a7]-[a6] doesn't prevent [b3]-[b4] and [b4]-[b5] because of the pin on the a-file.}) 9. Nbd2 e6 10. b4 (10. b4 {White is much better. A possible continuation is:} Be7 11. Be2 O-O {this was Carlsen-Rees, blitz 2023. Now} 12. b5 Nb8 13. O-O {would have given White a nice ending. Black has no real counterplay and after:} Nbd7 14. Ra2 Nb6 15. Rfa1 Nc8 16. Ne5 {Black is tied up and can only wait while White finds ways to improve the position and create some real threats.}) *

