1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Nf3 {I guess in 9 out of 10 games Black will respond automatically with} Nf6 {, but there are some alternatives. Often they will just transpose, but since we generally refrain from an early c2-c4 in this repertoire some lines are quite playable for Black. On the top level, the active move 2...c5 has been very popular lately, but as we will see it is not really a problem for Colle-players!}) 2... c5 3. e3 Nc6 {Black develops sound and active.} (3... Nf6 {transposes to a normal Colle;}) ({And} 3... e6 {can be met by} 4. c3 {or 4.b3 and we will be inside the repertoire as soon as Black plays [Nf6].}) (3... cxd4 4. exd4 {leads to the typical Carlsbad-structure.}) ({See more after} 3... Nc6 4. c3 cxd4 {.}) 4. c3 ({This is the simplest way to stay inside our repertoire. Now it is likely that we will play a reversed Semi-Slav Meran. There are some decent alternatives as well:} 4. Be2 {White just plays a normal QGD with an extra move. The only problem is that we are White and we are supposed to do something!}) (4. dxc5 $5 {is an original attempt to get out of the theory books (or courses!) fast and still play positionally sound chess.} e6 {( Not 4...e5 5.Bb5!)} 5. a3 Bxc5 {( On 5...a5 White can play 6.b3 or 6.c4 . )} 6. b4 {, followed by [Bb2] and [Nbd2] with a very harmonious position. Later White will play [c4] and maybe not be better, but at least be more comfortable.}) 4... cxd4 {This is a very important option and I am sure many Caro-Kann players would go for it.} 5. exd4 {This is a Caro-Kann! In this course, I prefer to call it a Carlsbad structure from the Queen's Gambit Declined with reversed colours. Why all the subtitles? It is just words! Yes, but the way we describe things influences our mindset. And since the Colle is very similar to playing a QGD with an extra move, I think we should stay in that frame of mind. Having made courses about the QGD and the Caro-Kann I should know what I am talking about. However, your sympathies can quickly change. Of course Black must be ok, objectively speaking, but we still have a great version of the Exchange Variation in the Queen's Gambit! Which can be translated to: no problems and pretty easy play.} Nf6 {The most natural move. Knights out first! There are other options, of course.} 6. Bf4 {This move is hard to achieve in the normal QGD, so already a small victory. White has tried many other moves, but let's stick with this one.} Bf5 ({The main move} 6... Bg4 {has already been covered in the Colle 3...[c5] chapter.}) 7. Qb3 {[%csl Gb7] We immediately attack the weak spot.} Qc8 ({White gets a good ending after} 7... Qb6 8. Qxb6 axb6 9. Na3 {, followed by [Nb5]. The double pawn is a long-term weakness.}) 8. Nbd2 e6 ({With} 8... h6 {Black saves the bishop, but White keeps some pressure after} 9. Ne5 e6 10. Bb5 {.}) 9. Nh4 $1 {Going after the Caro-Kann bishop.} Be4 {Trying to muddle the waters.} ({Instead,} 9... Bg6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Bd3 {is nice for White with the bishops and the better structure.}) 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 {The standard move. White should be better because of the bishops.} 11. Bd3 ({More popular is} 11. Nf3 {but hitting the knight makes sense.}) 11... Bd6 (11... g5 12. Bxe4 {is good for White after} gxf4 13. Bd3 {because of the weakened structure.}) (11... h6 {now ...[g7]-[g5] is a threat, but the simple} 12. Nf3 {is fine for White.}) 12. Be3 ({The most ambitious. White can also reckon with some advantage after} 12. Bxd6 Nxd6 13. O-O {.}) 12... O-O ({The aggressive} 12... f5 {probably weakens more than it helps.} 13. g3 Qc7 14. Ng2 {effectively stopping ...[f5]-[f4] looks good for White.}) 13. O-O ({You could also consider} 13. g3 {.}) 13... Qc7 ({Again} 13... f5 {is too aggressive. A simple answer is} 14. Rae1 {and if} f4 15. Bc1 {, and the [e4]-knight is forced back.}) 14. g3 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Ga1e1,Gh4g2,Ge3f4] White is slightly better. Next a good move could be [Rae1], then maybe [Ng2] and [Bf4]. Exchanging the dark-squared bishops is a good plan in this position. Later we can kick [Ne4] back and start active play on the kingside.} *

