nge. Of course Black must be ok, objectively speaking, but we still have a great version of the Exchange Variation in the Queen's Gambit! Which can be translated to: no problems and pretty easy play.} Nf6 {The most natural move. Knights out first! There are other options, of course.} 6. Bf4 {This move is hard to achieve in the normal QGD, so already a small victory. White has tried many other moves, but let's stick with this one.} Bf5 ({The main move} 6... Bg4 {has already been covered in the Colle 3...[c5] chapter.}) 7. Qb3 {[%csl Gb7] We immediately attack the weak spot.} Qc8 ({White gets a good ending after} 7... Qb6 8. Qxb6 axb6 9. Na3 {, followed by [Nb5]. The double pawn is a long-term weakness.}) 8. Nbd2 e6 ({With} 8... h6 {Black saves the bishop, but White keeps some pressure after} 9. Ne5 e6 10. Bb5 {.}) 9. Nh4 $1 {Going after the Caro-Kann bishop.} Be4 {Trying to muddle the waters.} ({Instead,} 9... Bg6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Bd3 {is nice for White with the bishops and the better structure.}) 10. Nxe4 dxe4 {This leads to more original play.} 11. g3 {[%cal Gh4g2] With a black pawn on [e4] the position is a little tricky. With [g3] we make sure that the knight has a retreat on [g2]. The move can be postponed, because there was no immediate threat, but sooner or later it had to be played anyway.} Be7 12. Ng2 {White regroups. Otherwise, you constantly have to look out for ideas like ...[Nd5].} O-O ({Most likely} 12... Nd5 {will transpose to the mainline.}) 13. Be2 Nd5 {The only active plan for Black.} 14. Bd2 {Saving the bishop gives more chances for an opening edge.} Qd7 15. O-O (15. O-O {White is for preference with the bishop pair. A sample line goes:} a6 16. a4 {, stopping [b5].} Rac8 17. Rad1 Rfd8 18. Ne3 h6 19. Nxd5 exd5 20. f3 {, and White opens the position for the bishops with good play.}) *

