1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 (2. Nf3 {I guess in 9 out of 10 games Black will respond automatically with} Nf6 {, but there are some alternatives. Often they will just transpose, but since we generally refrain from an early c2-c4 in this repertoire some lines are quite playable for Black. On the top level, the active move 2...c5 has been very popular lately, but as we will see it is not really a problem for Colle-players!}) 2... c5 3. e3 Nc6 {Black develops sound and active.} (3... Nf6 {transposes to a normal Colle;}) ({And} 3... e6 {can be met by} 4. c3 {or 4.b3 and we will be inside the repertoire as soon as Black plays [Nf6].}) (3... cxd4 4. exd4 {leads to the typical Carlsbad-structure.}) ({See more after} 3... Nc6 4. c3 cxd4 {.}) 4. c3 ({This is the simplest way to stay inside our repertoire. Now it is likely that we will play a reversed Semi-Slav Meran. There are some decent alternatives as well:} 4. Be2 {White just plays a normal QGD with an extra move. The only problem is that we are White and we are supposed to do something!}) (4. dxc5 $5 {is an original attempt to get out of the theory books (or courses!) fast and still play positionally sound chess.} e6 {( Not 4...e5 5.Bb5!)} 5. a3 Bxc5 {( On 5...a5 White can play 6.b3 or 6.c4 . )} 6. b4 {, followed by [Bb2] and [Nbd2] with a very harmonious position. Later White will play [c4] and maybe not be better, but at least be more comfortable.}) 4... Bg4 {Looks active and attractive. But you shouldn't underestimate the little white move [c3]!} (4... Nf6 {is inaccurate because of} 5. dxc5 $1) ({We already know that} 4... e6 5. Bd3 {should transpose to normal Colle-lines when Black plays [Nf6].}) 5. dxc5 $1 {This is easy to miss.} e5 {The most active response. Black takes the centre.} (5... e6 6. b4 {is no better and 5...a5 to stop [b4] is met by 6.Bb5 .}) 6. b4 {[%csl Gc5] So [c2]-[c3] was a multi-functional move. It doesn't just protect the central [d4]-pawn, but in fact, creates a devious plan to play [dxc5] and protect the gain with [b2]-[b4]!} e4 {[%cal Gg4d1] Winning a piece due to the pin?} 7. h3 {No. White either breaks the pin or win the black bishop.} Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 (8... exf3 9. gxh5 {is even worse.}) 9. Nd4 {[%csl Gc5] Black doesn't have enough for a pawn.} *

