1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 {In this chapter we will meet some of Black's more rare lines.} b6 {This could be a prelude to a Queen's Indian setup.} 3. e3 {We do our usual stuff.} Bb7 4. Bd3 c5 {A reversed Reti.} 5. O-O d5 6. dxc5 {This is a promising change of the structure.} bxc5 7. c4 e6 {Black needs to protect the structure.} 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Bb5+ {A disturbing check.} Bc6 10. Qa4 {White maintains the pressure.} Bxb5 ({Or} 10... Qd7 11. Nc3 {.}) 11. Qxb5+ Qd7 12. Nc3 (12. Nc3 {Black position is unpleasant. The hanging pawns are targets and White is ahead in development. A game continued:} Qxb5 13. Nxb5 Na6 14. Rd1 Be7 15. Ne5 $1 {followed by [Nc6] with a big advantage, Dokutchaev-Kiltti, Finland 2016.}) *

