1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 {In this chapter we will meet some of Black's more rare lines.} b6 {This could be a prelude to a Queen's Indian setup.} 3. e3 {We do our usual stuff.} Bb7 4. Bd3 g6 $5 {An original double fianchetto.} (4... e6 {sends us back to the 2...[e6] chapter.}) 5. O-O Bg7 6. c4 $1 ({The strongest here. Also possible is the flexible} 6. b3 O-O 7. Bb2 {.}) 6... O-O 7. Re1 $1 ({A very precise move. After} 7. Nc3 d5 {Black gets some kind of Grunfeld. It is fine for White, of course, but I prefer to avoid it.}) 7... Ne4 {Black tries to stop White from playing [e3]-[e4].} (7... d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {is no longer good: After} 9. e4 {there is no [Nxc3] so White just got the centre.}) ({Also} 7... d6 8. e4 {is good for White. The [b7]-bishop is generally misplaced in these structures.}) 8. d5 {Now the knight is undermined.} ({White could even consider} 8. Bxe4 {N} Bxe4 9. Nc3 Bb7 10. e4 {with a nice centre.}) 8... Nc5 9. Bc2 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge3e4] Next White will play [e3]-[e4] with a good position. The [d5]-pawn secures extra space and blocks the black bishop on [b7].} *

