1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 {In this chapter we will meet some of Black's more rare lines.} b5 3. e3 {[%cal Gf1b5]} ({It's actually the most played move. If White would play more for initiative than for structure then} 3. e4 $1 Nxe4 4. Bxb5 {is worth investigating.}) 3... a6 {Protecting the pawn.} (3... b4 4. a3 {gives White a superior structure because Black can't protect [b4] with the a-pawn.}) 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. Nbd2 {We postpone castling a little.} d5 6. O-O e6 7. a4 {[%csl Gb5] Hitting away at [b5].} ({Also interesting is the new move} 7. Nb3 {there are some juicy squares on [c5] and [a5].}) 7... c5 {Black tries to defend actively.} 8. dxc5 b4 {The pawn was hanging and [bxa4] would give Black a very weak [a6]-pawn.} 9. Nb3 Nbd7 {Black regains the [c5]-pawn. However the b-pawn is still a target.} 10. Qe1 {[%cal Ge1b4]} Nxc5 11. Qxb4 $1 (11. Qxb4 {A cool move. We just take it. Black doesn't have enough compensation as this sample line illustrates:} Nxd3 12. Qxb7 Nb4 13. Ne5 Be7 14. Nc6 Nxc6 15. Qxc6+ Kf8 16. Nd4 {with a pawn more.}) *

