1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 {In this chapter we will meet some of Black's more rare lines.} b5 3. e3 {[%cal Gf1b5]} ({It's actually the most played move. If White would play more for initiative than for structure then} 3. e4 $1 Nxe4 4. Bxb5 {is worth investigating.}) 3... a6 {Protecting the pawn.} (3... b4 4. a3 {gives White a superior structure because Black can't protect [b4] with the a-pawn.}) 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. Nbd2 {We postpone castling a little.} d5 6. O-O e6 7. a4 {[%csl Gb5] Hitting away at [b5].} ({Also interesting is the new move} 7. Nb3 {there are some juicy squares on [c5] and [a5].}) 7... b4 8. c4 $1 {White takes the initiative on the queenside.} Be7 9. a5 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gc4c5] A classy move. White threatens to play [c4]-[c5] and annihilate the isolated [b4]-pawn.} c5 10. cxd5 {We need to follow up with direct play to fight for the initiative.} exd5 ({Or} 10... Nxd5 11. Nc4 {, followed by [e3]-[e4] with great play.}) 11. dxc5 {We saddle Black with an IQP.} Bxc5 12. Qa4+ ({This check is not necessary, but I like it, because it is made possible by the little move a4-a5. However,} 12. Nb3 {is also good.}) 12... Nbd7 {Or 2...Qd7 13.Nb3 in general, it is not to Black's advantage to get rid of the queens, when there is an isolated pawn, which will be a lasting target in any ending. But here it was perhaps the lesser evil, although White is clearly better.} 13. Nb3 Bd6 14. Bd2 {[%csl Gb4] Gaining a tempo by hitting the b-pawn.} Qe7 15. Nbd4 {[%cal Gd4f5] Gains another tempo because Black must prevent [Nf5].} g6 16. Nc2 {[%csl Gb4] The b-pawn is doomed.} *

