1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 {In this chapter we will meet some of Black's more rare lines.} b5 3. e3 {[%cal Gf1b5]} ({It's actually the most played move. If White would play more for initiative than for structure then} 3. e4 $1 Nxe4 4. Bxb5 {is worth investigating.}) 3... a6 {Protecting the pawn.} (3... b4 4. a3 {gives White a superior structure because Black can't protect [b4] with the a-pawn.}) 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. Nbd2 {We postpone castling a little.} d5 6. O-O e6 7. a4 {[%csl Gb5] Hitting away at [b5].} ({Also interesting is the new move} 7. Nb3 {there are some juicy squares on [c5] and [a5].}) 7... b4 8. c4 $1 {White takes the initiative on the queenside.} bxc3 9. bxc3 Nbd7 10. c4 (10. c4 {White has pressure on the queenside. Next up is Rb1 to annoy Bb7. If Black tries to block the b-file with:} Bb4 {then} 11. c5 {is strong. White will exchange [Bb4] with [Ba3] and leave Black with a bad bishop on [b7] and a very cramped position.}) *

