1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 {In this chapter we will meet some of Black's more rare lines.} b5 3. e3 {[%cal Gf1b5]} ({It's actually the most played move. If White would play more for initiative than for structure then} 3. e4 $1 Nxe4 4. Bxb5 {is worth investigating.}) 3... a6 {Protecting the pawn.} (3... b4 4. a3 {gives White a superior structure because Black can't protect [b4] with the a-pawn.}) 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. Nbd2 {We postpone castling a little.} e6 6. a4 {[%csl Gb5] Weakening Black's structure.} b4 ({Black never wants to play} 6... bxa4 {which gives White good play against the weak [a6]-pawn.}) 7. e4 {White takes the centre.} d5 {Black tries to keep the position closed.} (7... c5 8. e5 $1 Nd5 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Ne4 {is promising for White.}) 8. e5 {White gets a good version of the French.} Nfd7 ({If} 8... Ne4 9. Qe2 {then Black can't keep the knight and} Nxd2 10. Bxd2 {is good for White. A possible plan is to push the h-pawn in AlphaZero style.}) 9. O-O c5 {Black needs to get this break in to free the position.} 10. dxc5 Nxc5 11. Re1 {We are not afraid of [Nxd3].} Nbd7 (11... Nxd3 12. cxd3 Nc6 13. Nb3 {is good for White. The dark-squared bishop can get out, while [Bb7] is doomed to passivity.}) 12. Nb3 ({A dynamic solution. Less clear was} 12. Nd4 Qc7 13. N2b3 Ne4 {although it also looks quite playable after} 14. Bf4 {.}) 12... Ne4 {The most complicated.} (12... Nxb3 13. cxb3 {, followed by [Be3] gives White good piece play.}) 13. Bf4 Be7 {Both sides develop naturally.} 14. Nfd2 {[%csl Ge4] Trying to get rid of the black knight.} Nec5 ({White will get a big attack for free after} 14... Nxd2 15. Bxd2 O-O 16. Qg4 {with the threat [Bh6].}) 15. Qh5 {White has a promising position. Black still can't solve the issues with the king in the centre and taking on [d3] opens the queenside which is to White's advantage.} *

