1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 {In this chapter we will meet some of Black's more rare lines.} d6 3. e3 {It goes without saying that White had a bunch of other good moves!} Bg4 {It makes sense to get the bishop out. However, it doesn't make much sense to give it for the knight on [f3].} 4. Be2 ({This fits best with our repertoire. A very good move is also} 4. c4 {, followed by [Nc3].}) 4... Nbd7 5. h3 Bh5 {Giving the bishop for the knight is just handing White the bishop pair.} 6. c4 {This is the best setup.} e5 7. Nc3 c6 ({Is flexible, but loses time. White can meet it in the same way as after} 7... Be7 {.}) 8. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Gb7]} Qb6 9. g4 {It was also fine just to take on [b6], but this is more forcing.} Bg6 10. Nh4 {If we get the bishop pair, we are just positionally better.} Qxb3 11. axb3 Bc2 {[%csl Gb3] Black tries to keep the bishop with this attack on [b3].} 12. Kd2 $1 Bxb3 13. Ra3 {[%csl Gb3] However it turns out that the bishop is trapped. Black now has to go for:} Bxc4 14. Bxc4 d5 {[%cal Gd5c4,Gf8a3] which regains some material.} 15. Be2 Bxa3 16. bxa3 g6 {Preventing [Nf5].} 17. Kc2 {The two white minor pieces are much better than the rook and two pawns.} *

