1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 {In this chapter we will meet some of Black's more rare lines.} d6 3. e3 {It goes without saying that White had a bunch of other good moves!} Nbd7 {[%cal Ge7e5] Black prepares ...[e5].} ({The most played} 3... g6 {transposes to the King's Indian section.}) 4. Be2 e5 5. O-O Be7 ({Played in the style of the Old Indian.} 5... g6 6. c4 {transposes to the King's Indian Attack.}) 6. c4 O-O 7. Nc3 c6 8. Qc2 {[%csl Ge4] White controls [e4] and prevents the black e-pawn from advancing. Next we will start play on the queenside where we have much more space.} Qc7 9. b3 {White just develops the dark-squared bishop.} Re8 10. Bb2 {White is more comfortable. Black lacks space.} Nf8 {[%cal Gf8g6]} ({A different regrouping. After the more traditional} 10... Bf8 11. h3 {White is also having a good position, for instance,} e4 12. Nd2 d5 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Rfc1 {with good play on the queenside.}) 11. h3 Ng6 12. Bd3 (12. Bd3 {White keeps control over the light squares. A possible continuation is:} Bf8 13. Ne4 $5 {opening for [Bb2].} Nxe4 14. Bxe4 {with some pressure.}) *

