1. d4 ({In this final chapter, we will have a look at all the rest. After} 1. d4 {there are some random moves, some really rare ones but also a few quite decent choices that you are likely to face now and then. My task here has primarily been to try to stay inside our repertoire. Against several of the moves, White has much sharper attempts to refute Black's play, but I stay true to the spirit of this course. There is no reason to learn a lot of difficult lines against something that you will probably never meet over the board in your whole chess career. And if an opponent surprises you, then you will have some sound lines to fall back upon.}) 1... e6 (1... e6 {This is also a decent move, that is if Black is ready to play the French after} 2. e4 {.}) 2. Nf3 b6 ({If Black doesn't play this, we will most likely quickly be in another line, for instance:} 2... f5 3. Bf4 Nf6 {sends us to the Dutch chapter and 2...Nf6 and 2...d5 are clear also.}) 3. e3 $5 {Let's try this!} ({Of course the theoretical most critical is} 3. e4 $1 Bb7 4. Bd3 {which is just good for White.}) 3... Bb7 4. Bd3 f5 {Black avoids an early [Nf6], which would transpose to other lines. With [f5] Black goes for a Dutch, where we already have committed to an [e3]-setup.} 5. O-O Nf6 6. c4 Be7 7. Nbd2 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Gd1c2]} ({The main move is} 7. Nc3 {, but I like [Nbd2]. We protect [Nf3] and prepare to play [Qc2] with control over the important [e4]-square.}) 7... O-O 8. Qc2 {A promising setup. White hopes to expand on the queenside with [a2]-[a3] + [b2]-[b4] or in the centre with [d4]-[d5].} Qe8 {A typical manoeuvre in the e6-Dutch.} 9. a3 Qh5 ({If Black plays} 9... a5 {to stop our expansion we can switch plans with} 10. Re1 {and break in the centre with [e3]-[e4] which looks good.}) 10. b4 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gd2f3] Here we clearly see that it is nice that [Nf3] is protected by the other knight. Next White will play [Bb2] and enjoy a lot of extra space on the queenside.} *

