1. d4 ({In this final chapter, we will have a look at all the rest. After} 1. d4 {there are some random moves, some really rare ones but also a few quite decent choices that you are likely to face now and then. My task here has primarily been to try to stay inside our repertoire. Against several of the moves, White has much sharper attempts to refute Black's play, but I stay true to the spirit of this course. There is no reason to learn a lot of difficult lines against something that you will probably never meet over the board in your whole chess career. And if an opponent surprises you, then you will have some sound lines to fall back upon.}) 1... d6 (1... d6 {This is one of the decent moves! Black threatens to play ...e5. Of course, it allows} 2. e4 {, so Black must be prepared to play the Pirc or Philidor. I think these openings are basically nice for White, but it is clearly outside this repertoire.}) ({•} 1... c5 2. e3 {of course 2.d5! followed by [Nc3] is just good for White, but there is nothing wrong with [e2]-[e3]. Soon, Black will play [d7]-[d5] or [Nf6] and transpose to other lines.}) ({•} 1... Nc6 2. Nf3 {we stay inside our concept. Critical and good is 2.d5! but [Nf3] is also fine.}) ({•} 1... b5 2. Nf3 {again we refrain from the strongest move, which is 2. [e4]!} Bb7 3. e3 a6 {( Or 3...b4 4.Bd3)} 4. Bd3 {and I guess, Black will play [Nf6] and [e7]-[e6] with another transposition.}) ({•} 1... b6 2. Nf3 {also here we could have played 2. [e4]!} Bb7 3. e3 {and after} e6 {we are in the 1.d4 e6 -line.}) 2. Nf3 {We just develop and prevents [e7]-[e5]. Since we have the knight on [f3] throughout the repertoire, so far no need for any alarm.} f5 {The Dutch. We have been kind of move-ordered because of the inclusion of [Nf3] and [d7]-[d6]. Fortunately, there are several good lines to choose from.} 3. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4] Preparing to strike in the centre with [e2]-[e4].} Nf6 ({Here} 3... d5 {makes less sense compared to 1.d4 f5 2.Nc3 d5 , because Black has already moved the d-pawn once. 4.Bf4 White is just better. There is a juicy square on [e5].}) 4. Bg5 {Active development.} Ne4 {This leads to some forcing play that is good for White.} 5. Nxe4 fxe4 6. Nd2 Bf5 {Protecting the pawn.} ({Black has lost all games after} 6... d5 {and you can understand why. After} 7. e3 {White can break with both [c2]-[c4] and [f2]-[f3] and there is still a nice square on [e5].}) 7. f3 {The most forcing.} exf3 8. e4 $1 f2+ {Spoiling White's ability to castle.} ({The line after} 8... Bg6 9. Qxf3 {is really bad for Black.}) 9. Kxf2 Bg6 10. Qf3 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gf3b3,Gb3g8] A new strong move. Often the queen will switch to [b3] from where it attacks [b7] and prevents short castling. The bishop goes to [c4] or [e2], the [h1]-rook can be activated and finally the king will drop back to [g1] with a harmonious position.} *

