 e5 6. Nc3 {will transpose after} Ngf6 {.}) ({The passive} 3... e6 {can be met by} 4. c4 {, followed by [Nc3] with a pleasant position.}) 4. Be2 {Breaking the pin.} e5 {This is actually a mistake because of clever tactics.} ({The more popular} 4... Ngf6 {transposes to 1.d4 Nf6 2.Nf3 d6 .}) 5. dxe5 dxe5 ({If} 5... Nxe5 6. Nxe5 Bxe2 {then} 7. Qxe2 $1 {N This is much better than taking on [f7].} dxe5 8. Qb5+ {picks up a pawn.}) 6. Nxe5 $1 {White wins a pawn with this nice little trick.} Bb4+ {The best chance.} ({If} 6... Nxe5 {, then} 7. Bxg4 {, or 6...Bxe2 7.Qxd7+ Qxd7 8.Nxd7 is just a pawn more for White.}) 7. c3 Nxe5 ({Or} 7... Bxe2 8. Qxd7+ Qxd7 9. Nxd7 {here Black's best is} Bh5 10. cxb4 O-O-O {Black wins the piece back because of back rank issues but after the simple} 11. f3 Rxd7 12. e4 {White is a clear pawn up.}) 8. Bxg4 Nd3+ {At least ruins White's right to castle.} 9. Ke2 Nxc1+ 10. Qxc1 Bd6 11. Bf3 {[%cal Gc1c2,Gb1d2] White is a pawn up. The king is safe on [e2], so we can slowly improve our position with moves like [Qc2] and [Nd2] and then decide where the rooks should be. Black doesn't have any real compensation.} *

